{Perennial Favorite  Back in 1933, when Fred Reinfeld and I were enthusiastically analyzing thousands of master games to find The Fifty Greatest Chess Games Ever Played, one of the undisputed choices on any of the lists (and we made many of them) was the magni ficent game won by Réti from Bogol yubov in 1923. In our introduction to the game, we had this to say of it: “It is well known that an attack undertaken without adequate means must result in loss of the initiative, if parried properly. This is demon strated most convincingly in the present game – the chief interest of which lies in the harmonious simplicity of Réti’s beautifully-timed play. The unusual movements of the Knight add a certain piquancy to Black’s artistic conduct of the game. Réti’s play is versatile: he per forms many tasks here, and per forms them well. He thrusts back a premature attack, he demonstrates the power of a compact center, he steadily cuts down his opponent’s mobility, he maneuvers his Knights with exquisite skill, he obtains and exploits a passed Pawn according to plan.” Today, having played through and analyzed thousands of games in the thirty-year interval, the game be tween Bogolyubov and Réti is still, in my opinion, one of the most beautiful and instructive ever played.} 1. Nf3 {This game appears in both books. I put it here only once (hence the "missing game")} f5 2. e4 d6 (2... fxe4 3. Ng5 Nf6 (3... d5 4. d3) 4. d3 exd3 5. Bxd3) 3. exf5 Bxf5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Bd3 (5. Bc4 d5) 5... Qd7 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc5d4,Yb8c6] Black must attack the center in this line of the French Defense. The immediate threat is 6 … cxd4 7 ♕xd4, ♘c6, winning the e-Pawn.} 6. c4 {In his anxiety to attack, Bogolyubov violates opening principles. Having developed the Queen prematurely, he now moves the Knight twice in the opening.} g6 $1 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 Bg4 $1 {Repulsing the attack} (9... Nc6 10. d5) 10. h3 (10. Be2 Nc6 {and the passed Pawn will become a Queen} 11. d5 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Ne5 13. Be2 Nh5 {[%cal Gd8d1] forcing the promotion of the passed Pawn}) 10... Bxf3 $1 {Saves the Rook, forces an ex change of Queens, and puts an end to the demonstration.} 11. Qxf3 Nc6 12. d5 {White must devote a few moves now to regaining the Pawn he lost.} Ne5 13. Qd1 Rae8 $1 (13... Nh5 {with good drawing chances.} 14. Be2 Nf4 15. Bxf4 Rxf4 {White must give up his Rook for the Pawn.} 16. g3 Rd4) 14. Be2 e6 {Building up a powerful center - Threatens to hold on to the extra Pawn by 15 … e5.} 15. f4 (15. Be3) 15... Nf7 16. Qb3 e5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd5,Ge6,Gf6] The four black Pawns now constitute a compact and powerful center, the Rooks have open files on which to operate, and the King is well posted for the ending – all a consequence of White’s faulty strategy in embarking on an attack without sufficient means. Réti’s play from this point on is as delightful as it is convincing} (16... c6) 17. Qxb7 exf4 {Centralizing the King for the ending - With Queens off the board, the King need not seek safety in Castl ing, as there is little danger of his being mated. At f7, the King supports the center Pawns, and is ready to take active part in the ending.} 18. Bxf4 Rb8 19. Qxa7 {The Bishop is to be developed on the Queen side. An attempt to bring it into play on the Kingside would be rebuffed with loss of time} Rxb2 {The Pawns begin to look formidable.} 20. Qa3 Rbb8 21. Rf1 {Cutting down the scope of the Bishop} Ra8 {[%csl Ra3,Gd7] Placing the Pawns on black squares limits the action of White’s Bishop, while it increases the mobility of Black’s (which travels on white squares).} 22. Qb3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc1d3] The Knight is bound for d3, to get some counter-play by the attack on the c-Pawn.} Qe7 {[%csl Re3][%cal Yc5c4] The Knight gains time by its threat of winning the exchange with 23 … ♘e3. The Knight’s move also unpins the c-Pawn, making the advance … c4 now possible} 23. Rae1 {Establishing an outpost at e3} Ne5 {A fine spot for the Knight. It can either settle down at this ad vanced outpost, or use it as a jumping-off place for further invasion into enemy territory} 24. Qc2 Rfe8 $1 {A powerful move!} 25. Nb5 Nf7 $1 26. Kh2 Qd7 $1 {The galloping Knight - The beginning of some fancy stepping by the Knight.} 27. a4 Re7 28. Bd3 (28. Z0 Nh5) (28. Bf3) 28... Rxe1 $1 {Réti notes that the Knight took ten moves to pay a visit to the home of White’s Knight.} 29. Rxe1 Nh5 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge5,Gf6] The Pawn chain - A thrust at the Bishop, to relegate it to the back rank.} 30. g3 (30. Be3 Be5+ 31. Kg1 Nf4) 30... Nxf4 31. gxf4 Bh6 32. Re4 Qd8 $1 {Control of the vital files} 33. Nd4 (33. Kg3 {If White removes the dangerous Pawn, he loses quickly} Qf6 34. Nxc7) 33... Qf6 $1 {Breakthrough to obtain a passed Pawn} 34. Ne6 Rb8 $1 35. Qg2 Rb2 36. Be2 Ra2 $1 37. Qg4 Qf5 {But this rudely dispels any fond hopes!} 38. Qxf5 (38. Qf3 Ne5) 38... gxf5 39. Re3 Ne5 {The power of the King in the ending} 40. Rg3+ Ng6 $1 {Drives back White’s King, so that his own King may advance.} 41. Rg2 Rxa4 $1 {The aggressive position of Black’s King is decisive!} 42. Bd3 Kf7 $1 {Simplifying to a won ending} 43. Bxf5 {The Knock-out punch!} Nh4 44. Bc2 Rxc4 45. Rf2 Ng6 {and now, so strong is the position of Black’s King, that he can win on either side of the board! Black can move to c3, capture both b-Pawns, and win as he pleases, or he can move to e3 and f2, and capture the King side Pawns to win.} 46. Kg3 0-1


