{Thomas Engqvist: 'Efim Bogoljubow (1889-1952) was born in Kiev, Russia. He is regarded as one of the greatest masters in the history of chess, playing two World Championship matches against Alekhine in 1929 and 1934, and was actually ranked No.1 in the world in early 1927, according to Chessmetrics. His games are characterized by strong dynamics and by play on both sides of the board. Combined with an optimistic attitude this made him a very dangerous opponent indeed. Bogoljubow is famous for saying: "When I am White I win because I am White. When I am Black I win because I am Bogoljubow!" In 'Masters of the Chess Board', Réti mentions that self-confidence is an extremely important asset, since the psychological element plays a more significant part of the game today than it did in the past. From a practical point of view it is better to think that the glass is half full rather than half empty, even if a player's evaluations from time to time as a consequence will be slightly biased. '} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: What is the name of this opening? ANSWER: This is the McCutcheon Variation of the French Defence, named after the American amateur John Lindsay McCutcheon (1857-1905) who played it against Steinitz in a simultaneous display in New York 1885, winning in only 28 moves. His system is still regarded as reliable, though its complicated nature will not suit everyone. It was used occasionally by most of the great players of Réti's day, and was a favourite of Viktor Korchnoi towards the end of his career. Today, its most consistent practitioners are the Russian GMs Igor Glek and Sergey Volkov. Réti and Bogoljubow contested this variation six times from both sides. This was the only game Réti managed to win; he lost all the others. '} 5. Bg2 Bb4+ {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION (candidate moves): What are White's options and best move? ANSWER:'} 6. Bd2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'This solid retreat is regarded as the main line;'} (6. Nbd2 {with}) 6... Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Fischer calls this move "ridiculous", having lost a famous game with it (see the next note).'} (7. Qxd2 {ANSWER: Black has several good moves here; Réti's choice is fine, while R.Spielmann-A.Nimzowitsch, Gothenburg 1920, saw} O-O 8. Nc3 Ne4 9. Qc2 Nxc3 {with comfortable play for Black.} {However, the most flexible equalizer, according to Kasimdzhanov, is} 10. Ng5 $1 Ne4 11. Bxe4 {, intending to recapture on c5 with the knight now that White's f2-f4 has weakened the e4-square. After} Bxe4 12. Qxe4 Qxg5 13. Qxa8 Nc6 14. Qb7 Nxd4 15. Rd1 {, Black has a harmonious position (and} c5 {is met by} 16. e3 {).} {or} Nc2+ $6 17. Kd2 {or} Qf5 18. Qg2 {with convenient play; note that} Nb4 $6 {drops the c2-pawn} {The inferior continuation} 19. e4 $6 Qf6 20. Kc1 Nxa2+ 21. Kb1 $6 Nb4 22. Rxd7 Nc6 23. f4 e5 24. Rhd1 Nd4 {led to an advantage for White in E.Bogoljubow-R.Réti, Baden-Baden 1925.} {Thomas Engqvist: 'White has to give up his dark-squared bishop after all, since '} 25. Rxa7 {Thomas Engqvist: '??' Thomas Engqvist: 'is a grave mistake due to'} exf4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!'} 26. gxf4 Qxf4 $17 27. Re1 Nf3 {, when White has difficulties defending his pawns situated on the now unprotected dark squares.} {Thomas Engqvist: 'In R.J.Fischer-T.V.Petrosian, Curacao Candidates 1962, White played '} 28. Re2 $6 {Fischer-Petrosjan, Curacao 1962/ Fischer-Petrosjan, Curacao 1962/ Thomas Engqvist: ', which was a recommendation by the Russian endgame expert Kopaev. Afterwards, Fischer was very disappointed with the awkward bishop manoeuvre and gave it two question marks in his book. The lesson is perhaps that you should not trust an endgame expert's opening analyses! The idea is to answer '} Nd4 {, with} 29. Re1 {and}) 7... c5 (7... O-O {and ...d5-d4 next move} 8. O-O d6 (8... c5 $2 9. Re1 ({or} 9. Rc1 d6 $1 {Positionally speaking,} 10. Nb1 {is a good move too, but it allows White to solve the main tactical problem, finding safety for his king, by playing} Qe7 {.} {It was better simply to castle with} 11. Nc3 {, though White now stands a little worse after} Nc6 {.} {Thomas Engqvist: 'or'} 12. e3 {Thomas Engqvist: '!?' Thomas Engqvist: 'is reasonable and equal.'} {Either} Rfd8 13. Re1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'is a better alternative, delaying the f1-bishop's development (in Réti style) until it becomes more clear where it should be placed; more likely it belongs on d3.'} {If we look at the "natural" continuation} Rac8 14. b3 Nb4 {, it does not appear logical. What is the logic behind trading queens when you have the French bishop?} {A third option,} 15. a3 {, is fully playable and yet looks neither natural nor logical.} {The Russian theoretician Vasily Panov suggested} Nc6 {and 13 Bd3, but it does not cause Black any problems.} {The alternative is} 16. d5 {so Black might prefer simply} exd5 17. cxd5 Ne5 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. e4 Ne8 {, followed by ...Rhc8 and ...Rxc5 with a decent position} {and if} 20. Bf1 {, Kasimdzhanov recommends} Nd6 21. a4 a6 22. Bd3 g6 23. Qe2 Ra8 {, followed by h2-h4 and Rh3 with attacking chances on the kingside;}) 9... cxd4 {fails to} 10. Nb3 Qc7 11. Qxd4 Nc6 12. Qh4 {and Black should win.} {Thomas Engqvist: 'Of course not '} Ne7 $2 {Thomas Engqvist: '??'} 13. Rac1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'and wins.'} {Rather than preventing ...c6-c5 it was better to allow it, when White at least gains a good blockading square on d4 for his knight. For example, after} d6 14. Nfd4 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 a6 16. Kg1 Rac8 17. Qh3 Qd7 {, White is only slightly worse with three pawns islands versus Black's two.} {or} 18. Nd2 Rc7 {Nevertheless,} 19. b3 $1 {, followed by ...a7-a5, looks a more dangerous way of putting pressure on White's position and trying to open up a file.} {It makes sense to leave the d2-square for the knight; for example, after the useful} Rfc8 {and the obvious (natural)} 20. Red1 {, White has} h6 {. This would be quite okay were not for} 21. Qg2 $1 d5 22. Ra1 e5 23. Nc2 {with a clear advantage for Black, who has a very strong central pawn structure, while White's c3-pawn looks pretty weak.}) 9. Nh4 Bxg2 10. Kxg2 c5 $19 {The most resistant line is} 11. d5 exd5 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Ne4 Nf6 14. Nxd6 Nc6 15. Nb5 Qe7 16. Nc3 {and White has some hopes of surviving, even with his king standing uncomfortably in the middle of the board.} {or} Rad8 17. Qc1 {not} Nd4 $4 {due to} 18. e3 $1 {and if} Ne6 $6 {then} 19. Qc2 g6 20. Rad1 Qb7+ 21. f3 b5 22. Rxd8) 8. dxc5 bxc5 9. O-O Qc7 {Thomas Engqvist: 'It is unclear why Réti elected to change his move here in a later game. '} 10. Qc2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is the strongest continuation for Black? '} O-O 11. Rad1 h6 12. a3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: What is Black's most natural and logical move? ANSWER:'} Nc6 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The idea of exploiting the white queen on d4 with ...Nc6 looks indeed both logical and natural. According to GM Jonathan Tisdall in Improve your Chess NOW, the difference between natural and logical moves is a valid issue. Tisdall means that a natural move is usually obvious, whereas a logical move may not be obvious at all. '} 13. Rfe1 Rab8 14. Rb1 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' Thomas Engqvist: 'The beginning of a flawed strategy.'} a5 15. b3 $2 Rfd8 16. Rb2 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'This was Bogoljubow's plan. He aims to prevent ...c6-c5, cement control of the central light squares, and play with a 'good' knight vs. 'bad' bishop, but he will not be successful. '} {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is the problem with White's move? ANSWER:'} Ne7 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'First of all, Black's bishop is not actually bad at all and takes up a strong diagonal, stopping White from castling. '} 17. e4 d6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Preparing the ...c6-c5 break is logical. '} 18. Nb1 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is the drawback to White's strategy? ANSWER:'} Nc6 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'This is the reason it was more in order to overprotect the important e5-pawn with Rhe1 on the previous move.'} 19. Nc3 Qe7 20. Nb5 Ba6 $1 21. Qe2 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} Nd7 ({or} 21... e5) {Thomas Engqvist: 'Strangely, some sources have White playing '} 22. Rd2 {Thomas Engqvist: '??' Thomas Engqvist: ', which is obviously wrong since it leaves the e5-knight hanging.'} Nde5 $3 23. a4 Nxf3+ $1 24. Qxf3 Rd7 25. Qc3 Qd8 (25... Nb4 {fails to solve the problem, since Black ignores the c5-pawn and plays to enforce the ...d5-d4 break with} 26. Red1 $1 Rb6 27. e5 Bxb5 28. axb5 {, when White's position collapses.}) 26. Red1 Bxb5 27. axb5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How does Black keep the deadly initiative going? ANSWER:'} Nd4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Yes, by hitting the key defender. White cannot hold all the weaknesses in his position. '} 28. Rxd4 (28. Ra2 $1 Ra7 29. Bf3 $19 e5 30. h4 $1 Rba8 31. Ra4 $19) 28... cxd4 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!'} 29. Qxd4 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} Rbb7 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Bogoljubow must have overlooked the double threat to b4 and e2. Now the game is practically over. '} (29... Qc7 30. Bf1 {with a winning position.} {The greedy} Rc8 $4 {is considerably worse: after} 31. e5 (31. Qe3 {, White is fully in the game again.} Kf8) 31... d5) 30. Ra1 Qc7 31. Bf1 Qc5 32. Qe3 (32. Qxc5 dxc5 33. Rxa5 {, White still has a difficult position to defend.} {With the c-file temporarily obstructed, it is now safe and simpler to take the pawn:} Ra7 34. Rxa7 Rxa7) (32. Qd2 Ra7) 32... Kf8 (32... Qxe3 {and Black wins.} {The only move to put up some sort of resistance is} 33. fxe3 {, although after} Kf8 (33... Ra7)) 33. Rxa5 Ra7 (33... Qxe3 34. fxe3 $1 Ke7) 34. b4 Qxe3 (34... Qxb4 35. Rxa7) 35. fxe3 e5 (35... Rab7 36. c5) (35... Ke7 36. Kf2) 36. Bh3 Re7 37. b6 Rab7 {Thomas Engqvist: '. Unfortunately, this was as good as it got for Réti, who only managed one other win in this four-player round robin tournament and finished last on 4½ out of 12, scoring 1½/4 against each of the other participants. Bogoljubow came first on 7½ points, with Brinckmann and Sämisch joint second on 6 points.'} {Komodo prefers} 38. c5 $1 {, followed by ...Rc2+, but the text move is good enough.} {Or} Re8 (38... dxc5 39. bxc5 Re8) 39. Ra6 {.} {Thomas Engqvist: 'Taking the bishop leaves the white king too exposed: '} dxc5 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} 40. bxc5 0-1


