{Paul Motwani: 'G9.17: "Reti repeat of a yeti-like crush!" Scotch Gambit, Code C56. Recently I was studying GM Lasha Janjgava's extremely detailed GAMBIT book, "The Queen's Gambit & Catalan for Black", and I found myself thinking about the enormous increase in chess data that is readily available to competitors nowadays in comparison to the relatively tiny quantity of information which even GMs of the past had to make do with. To take a particularly potent example, if ChessBase had existed in the days of the late great GM Richard Reti (28.5.1889-6.6.1929), then it's unlikely that Dr Max Euwe (World Champion 1935-37) would have been checkmated in a mere 22 moves as White by Reti at Amsterdam in 1920---since ChessBase would have 'told' him that the first 14 moves of the game had already happened six years previously in another yeti-like crush: the encounter P.Kruger-R.Reti, Mannheim 1914!! Let's now do a time warp back to the 20th century to experience that double dose of fighting chess.'} 1. d4 {Das kleine Match zwischen dem jungen Euwe und dem schon erfahrenen Reti hatte es in sich. Sehen Sie z.B. wie die zweite Partie verlief:} Nf6 {Paul Motwani: 'In a sense 1 d4 d5 is a "mirror image", and for lots of information relating to it, I refer you to the aforementioned GAMBIT book, "The Queen's Gambit & Catalan for Black"...or check out GM Ruslan Scherbakov's excellent 1 d4 d5 site within www.chesspublishing.com!'} 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 Nc6 (5... O-O) 6. Nf3 Bxc5 7. Bg5 Nd4 8. Nxd4 Bxd4 9. Nb5 $2 Be5 {Paul Motwani: '!'} (9... Bc5 $3 {in the game A.Pomarleanu-M.Izdebska, 1986 European U-18 Girls Championship.} 10. O-O-O {is much safer for Black} {A few years ago at FM Tim Upton's home in Luxembourg, Tim and I were looking at a game in "Informator" which went} Qa5 11. Bd2 Qb6 12. Bf4 O-O $5 {and after} 13. e3 $2 {we were surprised to learn that} a6 $1 {was a  (rather obvious) "novelty" which leaves White in dire straits because of} 14. Nc3) 10. O-O-O d5 11. f4 Bb8 {Paul Motwani: '!'} 12. cxd5 Bd7 {Paul Motwani: 'OK, so Black's king cannot castle, but being a piece up is more important!'} (12... exd5 {but this backfires on Black because of} 13. Bxf6 gxf6 (13... Bxf4+ $4 14. e3) ({or} 13... Qxf6 14. Qxc8+) 14. e3 $1 a6 15. Nd4 $1 {intending}) (12... O-O {ist der Hauptzug.} 13. dxe6 Qa5 14. exf7+ Kxf7 {after which} 15. Nc3 $2 {allowed}) 13. dxe6 fxe6 14. Kb1 Qa5 $1 15. Bxf6 gxf6 {droht 16...h3} 16. e3 a6 (16... Bxb5 $2 {sets the trap} 17. Qc8+ $4) 17. Nc3 Ke7 $3 {[%mdl 64]} 18. Bc4 {Es ist wirklich unglaublich: Euwe räumt die gegnerischen Türme ab, wobei er die eigenen behält. Und in der zweiten Partie - s.o. - tut er es noch einmal. Allerdings geht es jeweils schief.} b5 (18... Bc6 {immediately take White to a "dead end".}) 19. Qe4 Bd6 $1 {Paul Motwani: 'This final sacrifice quickly forces mate.'} (19... Ra7 20. Rxd7+ {G9.17.2: Even stronger than} Kxd7 {which Reti had played six years before in the game P. Kruger-R.Reti, Mannheim 1914!} (20... Rxd7 {wins easily for Black.} 21. Qxe6+ $4 Kd8 {or} 22. Qxf6+ $4) {If} 21. Qxe6+ {then} Kc7 22. Qe7+) 20. Rxd6 ({or} 20. Nd5+) (20. Bxe6) 20... Kxd6 (20... bxc4 21. Rxd7+ $1 {intending} Kxd7 22. Qb7+ {but he couldn't have been too unhappy with the actual finish in the game!} {Desperation from White, seeing that it's also "curtains" for him after} Kd6 23. Ne4#) 21. Rd1+ Ke7 22. Rxd7+ Kxd7 {Or} 23. Qb7+ (23. Qb7+ {Other ways for White to bow out were} Qc7 ({Reti might have hoped to get the pretty line} 23... Kd6 24. Ne4#) 24. Bxe6+ {or} Kd6 25. Ne4+ Kxe6 26. Qxc7) 0-1


