{Thomas Engqvist: 'Walter Michel (1888-1969) was a Swiss chess master. He won his national Championship in 1926, and represented his country in four Olympiads from 1927-35. He is most famous for the game he lost to Akiba Rubinstein in the 16th round at Semmering (check this out, particularly from move 26 onwards, if you have not seen it before). According to Chessmetrics, his highest estimated rating of 2515 and ranking of 40th in the world came in April 1926, directly after Semmering; in other words Michel was then at his peak, despite finishing second-last with 4½ points. '} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ {Thomas Engqvist: 'The Bogo-Indian Defence is still regarded as a highly respectable opening;'} ({although the Queen's Indian with} 3... b6 {is more common at the highest level.}) 4. Bd2 ({The critical variation, at least in practical play, might be} 4. Nbd2 {, since Black often loses the dark-squared bishop. In the hands of a someone skilful with the bishop pair, and coupled with White's space advantage, this system can turn out to be a dangerous weapon. On the other hand, one must not forget the words from Romanovsky's 'Chess Middlegame Planning': "Thus to the question whether, in evaluating a position, the factor of the presence of the two bishops for one of the opponents should be taken into account as a particular aspect of the advantage, the right reply in our view, will be – no, it should not."}) 4... Bxd2+ {Thomas Engqvist: 'This is a favourite continuation of the Swedish GM Ulf Andersson. The fundamental idea is to follow up with ...0-0 and ...d7-d5, reaching a Queen's Gambit minus the dark-squared bishops, similar to the Lasker Variation where the same trade is effected later on. '} ({More often Black prefers to defend the bishop with one of} 4... a5) (4... c5) ({or} 4... Qe7 {(the most popular), awaiting a more suitable moment to exchange.}) 5. Nbxd2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Taking with the queen is more accurate. The queen is not particularly well placed on d2, but it is preferable to place the knight on c3, where it controls the central d5-square on the fifth rank, whereas on d2 it is actually slightly superfluous since the f3-knight stands in its way. '} d6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Réti changes plans, aiming instead for ...e6-e5, logically putting the pawns on the opposite colour squares to his remaining bishop. '} ({Two rounds earlier, W.Michel-M.Vidmar had seen} 5... d5 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. Qc2 c6 9. O-O Re8 10. e4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 h6 13. Rad1 Qc7 14. Rfe1 b6 15. c5 Bb7 16. b4 {and Black suffered from his lack of space throughout the game, though he managed to draw eventually.}) 6. e4 Qe7 {[%cal Ge6e5]} (6... O-O) 7. Bd3 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'The direct '} 7. e5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'is not as dangerous as it might appear. In fact it is too early to attack, as White's development is far from complete. Play might continue '} dxe5 8. dxe5 Nfd7 9. Bd3 (9. Qa4 O-O 10. O-O-O Nc6 $1 11. Re1 Qc5 (11... Nc5 $5 12. Qa3 b6 13. Nb3 Nxb3+ 14. Qxb3 Bb7 $132) 12. Ne4 Qe7 (12... Qb6) 13. Ned2 Qc5 14. Ne4 {½-½ Lopez Colon,F-Martin Perez,F/Corte Ingles 1998/EXT 2002 (14)}) 9... Nc6 10. Qe2 Qc5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'and now the only way to save the e5-pawn is with'} 11. Nb3 Qb4+ 12. Kf1 {Thomas Engqvist: ', when White loses the right to castle as well as the initiative after, for example, '} b6 $1 $132 {[%cal Rc8b7] ½-½ Parker,J-Arkell,K/Swansea 1995/EXT 1997 (27) ½-½ Parker,J-Arkell,K/Swansea 1995/EXT 1997 (27) Thomas Engqvist: 'is fine too'} (12... a5 13. Re1 a4 14. Nbd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Ra5 {and so forth.})) 7... e5 $132 {If White has played e2-e4 and d3 then this counterblow is good and very effective.  Wenn Weiß e2-e4 und d3 gespielt hat, dann ist dieser Gegenschlag gut und sehr effektiv.} 8. O-O (8. d5 a5 $5 (8... O-O) (8... Na6 9. O-O Nh5) (8... Nh5) 9. h3 $6 (9. O-O) 9... Nbd7 (9... O-O 10. O-O Nh5 $5 $36 11. c5 dxc5 12. Nc4 Nd7 $15) 10. Bc2 Nc5 11. b3 O-O 12. g4 Ne8 13. Nf1 g6 (13... c6 $5) 14. Ne3 Ng7 15. Qb1 Bd7 $15 {0-1 Hoenlinger,B-Engel,J/Trencianske Teplice 1928/EXT 1999 (37)}) 8... O-O 9. Qc2 (9. Re1 Nc6 ({Here Black can fight for the central d4-square with Hier kann Schwarz um das Zentrumsfeld d4 kämpfen mit} 9... c5 $5 {[%cal Rb8c6,Rc6d4]} 10. dxc5 dxc5 11. Nf1 Nc6 12. h3 $132) (9... Re8) 10. d5 Nb4 (10... Nb8) 11. Bf1 a5 12. a3 (12. c5 $5) 12... Na6 13. b4 axb4 14. axb4 Bg4 15. Qa4 {1-0 Gromovs,S-Pace,R/Cesenatico 2003/EXT 2007 (39)} c5 $132) 9... Nc6 (9... Nh5 $5) 10. Qc3 ({Although} 10. d5 {secures a significant space advantage, it is no better in view of} Nb4 11. Qc3 Nxd3 12. Qxd3 Nh5 {and Black has comfortable play nonetheless.}) 10... exd4 $5 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: How should Black continue? ANSWER:'} Qe5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Réti wants to secure the exchange of queens as soon as possible, since it ought to be to Black's advantage. After all, White is sitting with the bad bishop, while the centre loses its value after the exchange of the strongest piece on the board.'} ({Other good alternatives are} 12... Re8 {;}) (12... b6 {, followed by ...Bb7;}) ({and} 12... Bd7 {, followed by ...Bc6. The last two options are logical considering that White is unable to respond with Nd5, as would be the case if the knight was placed on c3. Then again, we have observed from Réti's games that he often postponed the development of this bishop even when it was a perfectly viable move.}) 13. Nf3 ({White cannot avoid the queen exchange with} 13. Qe3 {since the b2-pawn is hanging;}) ({while} 13. Qxe5 dxe5 {only helps Black to improve his position in the centre.}) 13... Qxd4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The most principled and consistent move, especially as Réti loved to play endings. '} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Nevertheless,'} 13... Qf4 $5 $132 {[%cal Rf6g4] Thomas Engqvist: '!?' Thomas Engqvist: 'is an interesting alternative, intending to use the e5-square as a manoeuvring square for the knight via ...Nd7-e5, while the queen is excellently placed on f4. '}) ({Going in another direction with} 13... Qa5 $5 {is also possible, keeping options open for ...Nd7-e5 or even ...c7-c5!? in some instances.}) 14. Nxd4 Re8 15. Nb5 Re7 16. Nc3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'A good manoeuvre by White, since the knight really belongs on this square in this structure. Chigorin said "that the strength of a piece is determined not by its location (static!) but its concrete prospects of action (dynamic!)". But notice that the knight has spent five moves getting here (Nb1-d2-f3-d4-b5-c3) when it could have reached it in one. '} Be6 17. f3 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'The immediate '} 17. Nd5 $6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'is a serious possibility, since '} Bxd5 18. cxd5 Nxe4 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!'} {Thomas Engqvist: ', is answered by '} 19. Rfe1 Rae8 20. Bb5 c6 21. dxc6 a6 22. Bf1 bxc6 $132 23. Rac1 $1 c5 24. b3 {and the bishop is stronger than the knight.}) 17... Nd7 $6 (17... c6 $11) 18. Nd5 $1 Bxd5 19. cxd5 $14 {Thomas Engqvist: 'transposes to the game'} ({Not} 19. exd5 $6 Rae8 {and Black is in full control of the only open file.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: Should Black play the knight to e5 or c5? ANSWER:'} 19... Nc5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'On the surface this is the most logical and natural move, blocking the c-file so that Black does not need to worry about the c7-pawn while he develops counterplay elsewhere. '} ({Nevertheless, when one looks at the concrete variations,} 19... Ne5 $5 {seems playable too; for example, after} 20. Bc2 g5 21. Rac1 Kg7 {, Black has good control of a complex of dark squares, while} 22. g3 Rg8 23. f4 gxf4 24. gxf4 Kh8+ 25. Kh1 Ng4 {just weakens White's centre.}) 20. Bc2 a5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The c5-outpost is secured for the time being.'} 21. b3 (21. Kf2) 21... Rae8 22. a3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Black cannot prevent b3-b4 anymore, but he has gained sufficient time to strike in the centre. '} f5 {Thomas Engqvist: '!'} 23. b4 ({Accepting the offered pawn with} 23. exf5 {looks positionally risky after, for instance,} Re2 24. Rf2 Re1+ 25. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 26. Rf1 Re2 27. Rf2 Re3 28. b4 Na6 $1 {. Although White may achieve a draw after something like} 29. b5 Nc5 30. a4 Ra3 31. g4 Nxa4 32. Bxa4 Rxa4 33. Rc2 Rb4 34. Rxc7 Rxb5 35. g5 Rxd5 36. Rc8+ Kf7 37. Rc7+ Ke8 38. Rxg7 Rxf5 39. Rxb7 Rxg5+ 40. Kf2 Rh5 41. Kg3 Kd8 42. h4 {, considering that the black king is cut-off, Black can always sidestep the rook ending for the time being and look to improve his position first by activating the king and increasing his control of the dark squares.}) 23... axb4 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' Thomas Engqvist: 'This routine exchange is slightly premature. '} ({It is more precise to lure the a1-rook to b1 by playing first} 23... Na6 24. Rab1 ({note that} 24. Rfb1 {leaves the a1-rook looking silly if Black does not exchange on b4}) ({while} 24. bxa5 fxe4 25. Bxe4 Nc5 {followed by ...Ra8 also leads to a good game for Black}) {, and only then} 24... axb4 25. axb4 {, when White does not control the a-file as in the game.}) 24. axb4 Na6 25. Rfb1 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Another way protecting the b4-pawn is '} 25. Ra4 $5 {Thomas Engqvist: ', utilizing the rook in two directions and leaving the other one free to fulfil other duties depending on Black's response.'}) 25... fxe4 26. Bxe4 $14 ({The alternative} 26. fxe4 {closes the e-file more or less permanently, but White has little hope of achieving anything (e.g. with Bxa6) while his e-pawn needs protecting, and Black may later reroute his knight towards the centre with ...Nb8-d7 and so on. Not yet} Nb8 $6 {due to} 27. Ra7 {and it is not easy to attack the e4-pawn.}) 26... Re5 27. Rb2 ({Here too} 27. Bd3 Kf8 $1 ({avoiding} 27... Rxd5 $4 28. Bc4 {and wins}) 28. Bxa6 (28. Bc4 g5 {is fine for Black}) 28... bxa6 29. Rxa6 Rxd5 {leads to a pretty drawish position.}) 27... g6 28. Kf2 Kg7 29. Ra5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Freeing the bishop from its defence of d5.'} Kf6 30. Bd3 R8e7 31. Rb5 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} ({Perhaps in the mistaken belief that he stands better, Michel tries to "make progress" and soon ends up seriously worse. The safer and probably correct course was to secure a half point quickly with} 31. Bxa6 bxa6 32. Rxa6 ({White might even win a pawn by playing} 32. Rd2 {first, but after} Re3 33. Rxa6 Rb3 34. Ra4 g5 {, he has no hope of winning with his passive rooks}) 32... Rxd5 33. b5 {, followed by b5-b6 with a simple draw.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is the problem with White's last move? ANSWER:'} 31... b6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Of course; now the rook is in prison, even if it cannot easily be won.'} 32. Ra2 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'So the rook forces its way in on the a-file, but it cannot accomplish anything there and only helps Black's knight to a better square.'} ({White's best chance here is to try and restrict his opponent with} 32. Be4 {, and if} Nb8 {then} 33. Rc2 {. If Black plays to free his knight by bringing the king to d8 after} Kf7 34. h4 Ke8 {, White has} 35. Rxb6 $1 cxb6 36. Rc8+ {and 37 Rxb8 with reasonable hopes of a draw.}) 32... Nb8 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: Why is White's position uncomfortable? ANSWER: We have already mentioned the problematic rook on b5. Another issue is that the black rooks are now threatening to invade via the e3-square. '} 33. Ra7 {Thomas Engqvist: 'This keeps the knight out of the game but allows the black rook into e3. '} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'If White prevents the rook intrusion with '} 33. Be4 {Thomas Engqvist: ', then '} Rh5 (33... Nd7 34. Rc2 Nf8 {extricates the knight, which can be further improved after ...h7-h5, ...Kg7 and ...Nh7-f6, while White is left with his useless rook.}) ({the tricky} 33... Nc6 $6 {, exploiting the pin on the d5-pawn, offers White more chances after} 34. Rxb6 $1 cxb6 35. dxc6) 34. h3 Nc6 35. Ke3 $14) ({The more active} 33. Ra8 Nd7 34. Rc8 {fails to} Re3 35. Bc4 Ne5 $1 36. Kxe3 Nxc4+ 37. Kd3 Na3 38. Rf8+ Kg7 39. Ra8 ({after} 39. Rxb6 cxb6 40. Rd8 Kf7 {, White does not have enough for the piece, since} 41. Rxd6 {runs into} Re3+ $1) 39... Nxb5 40. Ra6 ({or} 40. Kc4 $6 c6 $1) 40... Re2 {with a winning rook endgame for Black.}) 33... Re3 $1 34. Be4 Rc3 $132 {Thomas Engqvist: 'By defending the c7-pawn one more time the road is prepared for the horse in the stable to make a difference. '} 35. Ke2 Rc2+ ({More accurate than} 35... Nd7 {, which drops the c7-pawn after} 36. Kd2 Rc4 37. Bd3 Rh4 38. Rxc7 $2 {, even if} Rxh2 39. Bf1 Rh1 40. Be2 Rg1 41. Rc6 Rxg2 42. Rxd6+ Kf5 $1 43. Re6 Rxe6 44. dxe6+ Kxe6 {still looks very good for Black.}) 36. Kf1 Rc4 37. Ke2 Nd7 38. Kd2 Ne5 39. Bb1 $2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'White should not have moved the bishop away from the centre; now his position falls apart rapidly.'} (39. Ra2) ({All the same, it is not possible to maintain the bishop there for very long anyway; for instance, after} 39. Ra8 Rd4+ 40. Kc2 Ng4 $1 {;}) ({or} 39. Ra1 g5 40. h3 h5 {, followed by ...g5-g4.}) 39... Rd4+ $6 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Or'} 39... Rh4 $1 $19 40. h3 Nc4+ {.}) 40. Kc2 $2 (40. Kc3) 40... Rh4 41. h3 Nc4 $19 42. Kc3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is the quickest win? '} Ne3 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'ANSWER: The rooks might have finished things off with '} 42... Re3+ {Thomas Engqvist: '!'} 43. Kc2 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} ({but if} 43. Bd3 Ne5 {and the bishop is doomed}) 43... Rd4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: ', followed by ...Rd2 and ...Re1 mate.'} 44. Kc1 Rd2 45. Bc2 Re1+ 46. Bd1 Rexd1#) 43. g4 ({Or} 43. Ra2 Rc4+ 44. Kb3 Rc1 45. Be4 Nd1 $1 {with a family fork on c3; for example,} 46. Rd2 Nc3 47. Kb2 Nxe4 48. Kxc1 ({or} 48. fxe4 Re1) 48... Nxd2 49. Kxd2 {and White is basically a rook down.}) 43... Rxh3 0-1


