{This is a negative example. Master Reti does not succeed in enforcing the interlocking of the pawn formations. When we say negative, we refer merely to the theoretical and didactic value of the play, and we do not mean to infer that the game was badly played.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. b4 {One of the author's innovations which Reti himself adopted upon occasion, as in Rei-Capablanca, New York, 1924.} a5 4. b5 Bg7 5. Bb2 O-O 6. e3 d6 7. d4 Nbd7 8. Be2 e5 {(This move would only be sound if Black were in a position to enforce d5, or at least dxe5, for he would then gain the excellent blockade square at c5.)} (8... e5 9. dxe5 Ng4 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yd7c5]}) 9. O-O exd4 {(And as soon started, the blockading maneuver is already demolished. Theoretically and strategically the only course was 9...Re8, and 10.Nbd2 then c6, and according to circumstances Qc7 or e4, and d5, establishing a chain of pawns.)} (9... Re8 10. Nbd2 c6 11. Z0 Qc7 (11... e4) 12. Z0 d5) 10. exd4 Re8 11. Nbd2 {[%cal Rd6d5] (It is not easy for White to take advantage of his superior pawn position. This move takes too little account of Black's advance d5, and with 11.Nc3 he would have drawn considerably nearer to his goal.)} (11. Nc3) 11... Nf8 12. Re1 Ne6 13. g3 h6 14. Bf1 Ng5 15. Nxg5 hxg5 16. Bg2 {(With the Knight at c3 instead of d2, the pressure brought to bear by White's forces, would give winning chances. As it is, Black can equalize approximately.)} d5 17. Rxe8+ ({The only chance to maintain the fleeting advantage lay in} 17. c5 {With this move White would have obtained a clearly superior position at least on the Queenside. It is very doubtful whether anything could be made of the position after} Bf5 18. Qa4 b6 {It seems that move 11.Nbd2, which must be deprecated from the point of view of centralized development, can no longer be remedied.}) 17... Qxe8 18. cxd5 Qxb5 19. Qb3 Bd7 20. Qxb5 ({Or} 20. Rc1 Ne8 21. Qxb5 Bxb5 22. Ne4 g4 {and eventually} 23. Z0 Rd8) 20... Bxb5 21. Rc1 Re8 ({Playable would also be the simple} 21... Ne8 {e.g.} 22. Ne4 g4 23. h3 gxh3 24. Bxh3 Rd8 {etc.}) 22. Rxc7 Re1+ 23. Nf1 Bxf1 24. Bxf1 Nxd5 25. Rxb7 Rb1 26. Rb8+ Kh7 27. Rb5 Nc7 28. Rb7 Ne6 29. Kg2 Bxd4 30. Rxf7+ Kg8 31. Re7 Rxb2 32. Bc4 Rxf2+ 33. Kh1 Rf6 34. Bxe6+ Kf8 35. Rd7 Rxe6 36. Rxd4 {(After the interesting skirmishing of the last 14 moves, a Rook ending is reached in which White has some advantage without being able to force the win, though the game went on to the 90th move before being drawn.)} 1/2-1/2


