1. d4 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 Qxd1+ 5. Nxd1 Nc6 6. Bf4 Nge7 7. Bb5 (7. Nc3 Ng6 8. Nd5 (8. Bg3 Bb4 9. Nge2 Bg4 10. O-O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 O-O $17 {e5 is doomed anyway.}) 8... Bb4+ $1 9. Bd2 (9. c3 Ba5 10. e6 (10. b4 Be6) 10... Bxe6 11. Nxc7+ Bxc7 12. Bxc7 Rc8 13. Bg3 O-O {Black's lead in development in association with the weakness of a2 and the plan ...f7-f5-f4 ensures him some advantage.}) 9... Bxd2+ 10. Kxd2 O-O 11. Nxc7 Rd8+ 12. Kc3 (12. Ke3 Ngxe5 $1 13. Nxa8 Ng4+ 14. Kxe4 (14. Ke2 Nd4+) 14... Nxf2+ 15. Kf4 Nxh1) 12... Rb8 13. e6 Bxe6 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Re1 Rbc8 16. Rxe4 Nce5+ 17. Kb3 Rd2 18. f4 Nd7 $5 (18... Rcxc2 19. fxe5 Rxb2+ 20. Kc3 Rbc2+ $11) 19. Rc4 Nc5+ 20. Ka3 a5 21. c3 $2 (21. Nf3 Rf2 22. Nd4 Nxf4 23. g3) 21... b5 $1 22. Nf3 b4+ 23. cxb4 axb4+ 24. Kxb4 (24. Rxb4 Ra8+ 25. Ra4 Rxa4#) 24... Rxb2+ {0-1 Kuhne,U-Berger,M corr 1980 Probably there is a long forced win because of the awkward position of the white king after 25.Kc3 Rxa2 or 25...Ba4+ 26.Kd4 Rd8+ since 22...Rf2, with exactly the same idea, forced White to give up the exchange on c5.}) 7... Bd7 8. e6 $6 {White has to play} (8. Nc3 {And then if} Ng6 9. e6 Bxe6 10. Bxc7 Rc8 11. Bg3 a6 12. Bxc6+ Rxc6 13. Nge2 {Which is about equal with White's strong dark-squared bishop and the possession of the open d-file after long castling compensating the opponent's 2 bishops.}) 8... Bxe6 9. Bxc7 Nd5 {Immediately taking the squares from the unfortunate knight on d1.9...a6 with the idea of taking the pair of bishops or 10.Ba4?! b5 11.Bb3 Bxb3 12.axb3 Nb4 looks good too.} (9... a6 10. Ba4 b5 11. Bb3 Bxb3 12. axb3 Nb4) 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Bg3 Bc5 12. Ne2 O-O 13. O-O Rad8 14. a3 a5 $1 15. b3 {Necessary, if White wants to play c4, to protect it and prevent the occurrence of a hole on b3 after ...a4 but there is no good solution anyway, the b-pawn will always be weak.} Rfe8 16. c4 {White not having succeeded in solving the problem of the knight on d1 loses patience 16.Re1 was less compromising.} (16. Ndc3 $2 Nxc3 17. Nxc3 Bd4) 16... Nf6 17. Ndc3 Bg4 $1 18. Bc7 (18. Rfd1 $2 Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Bxa3) 18... Rd2 19. Rfe1 (19. Bxa5 Bxe2 20. Na4 Rc2 21. Nxc5 Bxf1 22. Rxf1 e3) 19... Bxe2 $1 {The square g4 has to be available for the knight.} 20. Rxe2 (20. Nxe2 Ng4 21. Bg3 e3 22. f3 Nf2 23. Kf1 Nd3 24. Red1 Bxa3 $1) 20... e3 21. fxe3 (21. Kf1 Bd4 $1 22. Bxa5 (22. Rxd2 exd2 23. Bxa5 Ng4 24. Rd1 Nxh2+ 25. Kg1 Re1+ 26. Kxh2 Bxc3 27. Rxd2 Bxa5 28. b4 Bc7+) 22... Rxe2 23. Kxe2 exf2+ 24. Kd2 (24. Kd3 Re1) 24... Ng4 25. h3 Nh2) 21... Rxe2 $1 22. Nxe2 Rxe3 23. Kf1 (23. b4 Rxa3+) 23... Rxb3 {The triumph of Black's strategy...} 24. Bxa5 Ng4 $1 {And the final uppercut.} (24... Ng4 25. Bb4 (25. Nc3 Bxa3 26. Ke2 (26. h3 Ne3+ 27. Ke2 Nxc4)) 25... Ne3+ 26. Kf2 Nc2+ 27. Bxc5 Nxa1 $19) 0-1


