{[%evp 18,50,25,14,33,-20,64,21,27,2,16,0,24,0,12,-95,-91,-81,-90,-95,-98,-225,-226,-406,-409,-443,-435,-439,-427,-446,-455,-455,-454,-439,-448] C66: Ruy Lopez: Steinitz Defence Source: Tartakower & du Mont, 500 Master Games of Chess, pp. 71-72. All comments are Tartakower's unless otherwise noted.That it can have serious consequences voluntarily to cede too much territory to an aggressive adversary can be seen in the following lively game.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O d6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. d4 Bd7 7. Re1 exd4 8. Nxd4 O-O 9. b3 {A slow but sound continuation. 9....} Re8 ({If Black resorts to exchanges} 9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Bxb5 11. Nxb5 Nd7 {(threatening 12....f6), then White can create some lasting weaknesses in Black's position after} 12. Qc4 c6 13. Nd4) 10. Bb2 Bf8 {He continues to build up "behind the front" a durable system of defences.} 11. f3 ({Instead of this passive procedure, he could have tried to obtain some initiative by} 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd3 g6 13. f4 {etc.}) 11... g6 {This counter-fianchetto is intended to ease the opposing bishop's pressure on the long black diagonal.} 12. Bf1 Bg7 13. Nde2 {In view of the threat 13....xd4 14.xd4 xe4, etc., White decides on a fresh retrograde manoeuvre. 13....} Nh5 {The beginning of a successful counteroffensive.} 14. Qd2 Qh4 15. Nd1 Ne5 {Avoiding the exchange of bishops and introducing a new fighting unit into the battle zone.} 16. c4 {In order to be able to play 17.f2,} ({which, however, would now be disadvantageous after} 16. Nf2 Nxf3+ 17. gxf3 Bxb2) ({But as Black finds a brilliant refutation of the plausible move in the text, he should have looked for some other means of "patching up" his position, such as, for instance,} 16. Bc3) 16... Nd3 {Emphasising in an artistic manner the weakness of the "ingress square" at d3.} 17. Qxd3 Qxe1 18. Ndc3 Qh4 {Having fairly and squarely won the exchange, the Black queen returns to her post of observation. White's is a lost cause.} 19. c5 Bc6 ({Don't take} 19... Be5 20. g3 Qe7 21. Rd1 $17) 20. Nd4 ({Or} 20. cxd6 Rad8) ({There is no hope of White gaining the initiative, and so} 20. g3 {would have been better.}) 20... Be5 21. g3 Bxg3 {White's fortress is collapsing.} 22. hxg3 Qxg3+ 23. Bg2 ({This gives rise to a fresh and cruel surprise. After} 23. Kh1 Nf4 24. Qd2 Re5 {Black also scores a point.}) 23... Qxg2+ 24. Kxg2 Nf4+ 25. Kg3 Nxd3 {White resigns.} 0-1


