1. b4 e5 2. Bb2 f6 3. e4 Bxb4 4. Bc4 Ne7 5. f4 d5 6. exd5 Bd6 7. fxe5 fxe5 8. Qh5+ Ng6 9. Nf3 Nd7 10. O-O O-O 11. Nc3 Rf4 12. d3 Nf6 13. Qg5 h6 14. Qg3 e4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. dxe4 Bg4 17. Qe1 Bxf3 18. Rxf3 Rxf3 19. gxf3 Qg5+ 20. Kh1 Qh5 21. Qf2 Rf8 22. Be2 Be5 23. Bxe5 Qxe5 24. Rg1 Nf4 25. Bf1 Rf6 26. Qxa7 Rb6 {One of the earliest examples of 1 b4, predating even Sokolsky!  Again it's this crazy line with 2...f6 which I can't believe so many people play. Maybe Reti saw it as a challenge to his manhood!?} {[%tqu "En","At any rate, it's White to play, and more or less win.","","","d5d6","Opening a diagonal for his Bishop.",10,"a7b8","also very strong",10]} 27. d6 $3 {[%csl Yf1][%cal Yf1c4]} (27. Qb8+ Kh7 28. d6 Rxd6 29. Qxc7 Ng6 30. Qxb7 {was also very strong, so full marks for that too.}) 27... Qxd6 28. Bc4+ Kh7 29. Qb8 Ne6 30. Bxe6 $1 Qxe6 31. Qxc7 Qf6 32. Rxg7+ $1 Qxg7 33. Qxb6 {A nice game.} 1-0


