.'} {Rogers: ' '} 9. Ne5 c6 $6 {The '?!' could have gone to any of Black's last three moves. Black's position has become terribly passive and he soon realises his plan to strongpoint ...d5 will merely leave White with a free hand on the kingside.} ({Black should hit out with Rogers: '  The '?!' could have gone to any of Black's last three moves. Black's position has become terribly passive and he soon realises his plan to strongpoint ...d5 will merely leave White with a free hand on the kingside. Black should hit out with '} 9... c5 {and hope for the best - the isolated QP which might result after exchanges in the centre would be a small price to pay for a little space. Rogers: ' and hope for the best - the isolated QP which might result after exchanges in the centre would be a small price to pay for a little space.'}) {Rogers: '  '} 10. f4 dxc4 {Black surrenders the centre and commits himself to a permanent inferiority.} ({Rogers: '  Black surrenders the centre and commits himself to a permanent inferiority. '} 10... c5 {was still worth a try. Rogers: ' was still worth a try.'}) {Rogers: '  '} 11. Bxc4 Nd5 {Correctly aiming to exchange pieces to ease his cramped position. Rogers: ' Correctly aiming to exchange pieces to ease his cramped position. 10...c5 is no longer feasible as 11.Bb5! ties Black in knots.'} (11... c5 {is no longer feasible as} 12. Bb5 $1 {ties Black in knots.}) {Rogers: ' '} 12. Bxe7 {Rogers: ' '} Qxe7 {Rogers: ' '} 13. Qf3 {Rogers: '  It is hard to condemn a move which dislogdes White's powerful knight even though '} f6 {It is hard to condemn a move which dislodges White's powerful knight even though it entails a slight weakening of Black's pawn structure. Rogers: ' entails a slight weakening of Black's pawn structure. Note that '} ({Note that} 13... Nxc3 {Rogers: ').'} {Rogers: ' '} 14. bxc3 {would only be helping White strengthen his centre. Black's main hope must be that when White plays e4 White's queen's pawn will prove weak - a slightly backward queen's pawn on a semi-open file is easier to attack that a backward queen's bishop pawn on a closed file (as would be the case after 13...xc3). Rogers: ' would only be helping White strengthen his centre. Black's main hope must be that when White plays e4 White's queen's pawn will prove weak - a slightly backward queen's pawn on a semi-open file is easier to attack that a backward queen's bishop pawn on a closed file (as would be the case after '}) {Rogers: '  '} 14. Nd3 {Rogers: ' '} Bd7 {Rogers: ' '} 15. e4 {Rogers: ' '} Nb6 {Rogers: ' '} 16. Bb3 {Rogers: ' '} Rad8 {Rogers: ' '} 17. Rad1 {Rogers: ' '} Bc8 {Rogers: ' '} 18. Nc5 {Rogers: ' '} Kh8 {Rogers: ' '} 19. Qf2 {Rogers: ' '} Qc7 20. h3 {White prepares for play on the kingside.} ({This is certainly a powerful plan but my personal preference would be to interpolate the move Rogers: '  White prepares for play on the kingside. This is certainly a powerful plan but my personal preference would be to interpolate the move '} 20. a4 {to soften Black up on the queenside. If Black replied} {Rogers: ' to soften Black up on the queenside. If Black replied '} a5 {the unprotected state of the Black queen's knight could later prevent Black's queen coming to the resuce on the kingside. Wheels within wheels. One should, however, consider the tournament situation when analysing this game. Reti, one of the strongest players in the world, had effortlessly achieved an imposing position against a little known player by the name of Watson (hardly the most chessic of names - compare Dunkelblum or the unpronounceable Euwe). Quite possibly Reti had already earmarked Watson as a tailender for the tournament (he was not wrong). Psychologically it would have been easy for Reti to assume that the remainder of the game would be just as easy as the first twenty moves and therefore Reti might have considered that a good move would do just as well as the best move. Watson sets about correcting that misconception in dogged fashion. Rogers: ' the unprotected state of the Black queen's knight could later prevent Black's queen coming to the resuce on the kingside. Wheels within wheels. One should, however, consider the tournament situation when analysing this game. Reti, one of the strongest players in the world, had effortlessly achieved an imposing position against a little known player by the name of Watson (hardly the most chessic of names - compare Dunkelblum or the unpronounceable Euwe). Quite possibly Reti had already earmarked Watson as a tailender for the tournament (he was not wrong). Psychologically it would have been easy for Reti to assume that the remainder of the game would be just as easy as the first twenty moves and therefore Reti might have considered that a good move would do just as well as the best move. Watson sets about correcting that misconception in dogged fashion.'}) 20... Re7 ({Rogers: '   '} 20... e5 {is still not good:} {Rogers: ' is still not good - '} 21. dxe5 {Rogers: ' '} fxe5 {Rogers: ' 22. Rxd8 Qxd8 23.fxe5 and again White's extra pawn is stronger than it looks.'} (21... Rxd1 {Rogers: ' '} 22. Nxd1 $1 {Rogers: ' '} fxe5 {Rogers: ' '} 23. fxe5) 22. Rxd8 Qxd8 23. fxe5 {and again White's extra pawn is stronger than it looks.}) {Rogers: '   '} 21. Kh1 {Rogers: ' '} Nbd7 22. Nxd7 $6 {Rogers: ' Normally one would expect White to avoid exchanges and leave Black's pieces in a tangle by playing 22.Nd3. Reti was no doubt attracted by the bind which he obtains through his next few moves but logic should have suggested that unless Black could play ...e5 or ...c5, the plan would be even stronger with an extra pair of knights on the board.'} ({Normally one would expect White to avoid exchanges and leave Black's pieces in a tangle by playing} 22. Nd3 {. Reti was no doubt attracted by the bind which he obtains through his next few moves but logic should have suggested that unless Black could play ...e5 or ...c5, the plan would be even stronger with an extra pair of knights on the board.}) {Rogers: '  '} 22... Rexd7 23. e5 $1 {White closes the centre to facilitate his forthcomning kingside attack. Black's next is virtually forced as he cannot allow the White knight to reach d6. White has conceded an outpost on d5 in return for his on d6 but the Black minor pieces have little hope of being able to utilize it in the near future. Rogers: ' White closes the centre to facilitate his forthcomning kingside attack. Black's next is virtually forced as he cannot allow the White knight to reach d6. White has conceded an outpost on d5 in return for his on d6 but the Black minor pieces have little hope of being able to utilize it in the near future.'} {Rogers: '  '} f5 {Rogers: ' '} 24. g4 $1 {Rogers: ' '} g6 {Rogers: ' '} 25. Rg1 {Rogers: ' '} Rg7 {Rogers: ' '} 26. Qh4 {Rogers: ' '} Qe7 27. Qh6 ({Rogers: '  '} 27. Qf6 $5 {was an interesting try. If Black exchanges queens, White will be left with a protected passed pawn in the endgame but without an exchange Black's forces remain severely restricted. Rogers: ' was an interesting try. If Black exchanges queens, White will be left with a protected passed pawn in the endgame but without an exchange Black's forces remain severely restricted.'}) {Rogers: '  '} 27... b6 {Rogers: ' '} 28. Kh2 {Rogers: ' '} Bb7 {Rogers: ' '} 29. Rg3 c5 {Black decides to try for activity at last.} ({Objectively Rogers: '  Black decides to try for acticity at last. Objectively '} 29... Rd7 {might have been more sound but Reti was becoming short of time. Rogers: ' might have been more sound but Reti was becoming short of time.'}) 30. gxf5 {Initiating exchanges which dissipate a large part of White's advantage.} ({The correct line, as Maroczy pointed out in the tournament book, was Rogers: '   Initiating exchanges which dissipate a large part of White's advantage. The correct line, as Maroczy pointed out in the tournament book, was '} 30. Nb5 $1 {Rogers: ' '} cxd4 {Rogers: ' 31.Nd6. White probably feared 31...Rxd6 32.exd6 Qxd6 but Black lacks sufficient compensation for the exchange if White finds 33.Qg5!. '} 31. Nd6 {. White probably feared} Rxd6 32. exd6 Qxd6 {but Black lacks sufficient compensation for the exchange if White finds} 33. Qg5 $1) (30. d5 {Rogers} {is also good but probably too double-edged for Reti's liking - after} exd5 {the Black knight may be also to occupy the blockading square e6 with effect.}) {Rogers: '    '} 30... gxf5 {Rogers: ' '} 31. Rxg7 {Rogers: ' '} Qxg7 {Rogers: ' '} 32. Qxg7+ {Rogers: ' '} Kxg7 33. Nb5 {Better late than never, White may have thought.} ({However, the d6 outpost means less with so few pieces on the board and White should have preferred Rogers: '  Better late than never, White may have thought. However, the d6 outpost means less with so few pieces on the board and White should have preferred '} 33. dxc5 {which at least gives Black a few isolated pawns to worry about. Rogers: ' which at least gives Black a few isolated pawns to worry about.'}) {Rogers: '  '} 33... cxd4 {Rogers: ' '} 34. Nd6 {Rogers: ' '} Rd7 {Rogers: ' '} 35. Rxd4 Re7 {Another trick seen and avoided. How easy it would have been to overlook 36.xe6 xe6 36.xf5+ etc. Rogers: ' Another trick seen and avoided. How easy it would have been to overlook 36.Bxe6 Nxe6 36.Nxf5+ etc.'} 36. Kg3 {A slight inaccuracy which allows Black to activate his rook.} ({Since Rogers: '   A slight inaccuracy which allows Black to activate his rook. Since '} 36. Ra4 {Rogers: ' '} Bc6 $1 {leads nowhere, Rogers: ' leads nowhere White should aim to infiltrate on the c or g file by playing '}) ({White should aim to infiltrate on the c or g file by playing} 36. Rd1 $1 {However, despite a number of second best moves, the position must still be assessed as favourable to White due to the permanent nature of his space advantage. Black lacks scope, so White can try a plan and later abandon it without risking much. Unles White becomes grossly overambitious there is no way he can lose whilst Black has to prepare for a long struggle to obtain the meagre return of a draw. Rogers: ' However, despite a number of second best moves, the position must still be assessed as favourable to White due to the permanent nature of his space advantage. Black lacks scope, so White can try a plan and later abandon it without risking much. Unles White becomes grossly overambitious there is no way he can lose whilst Black has to prepare for a long struggle to obtain the meagre return of a draw.'}) {Rogers: '   '} 36... Kh6 {Rogers: ' '} 37. Kf2 {Rogers: ' '} Rg7 {Rogers: ' '} 38. Ke3 {Rogers: ' '} Ba8 $6 39. Kd2 $2 {A surprising double oversight which leaves Black closer to a draw as he now liquidates rooks.} ({Presumably Reti's mind was set on a king march, for both players have overlooked Rogers: '  A surprising double oversight which leaves Black closer to a draw as he now liquidates rooks. Presumably Reti's mind was set on a king march, for both players have overlooked '} 39. Nxf5+ {Rogers: ' '} exf5 {Rogers: ' '} 40. Rd8 {when White regains the piece while his e pawn becomes a tower of strength. Black's best defence is probably} {Rogers: ' when White regains the piece while his e pawn becomes a tower of strength. Black's best defence is probably '} Rg3+ {but} {Rogers: ' but '} 41. Kf2 {leaves Black in trouble, e.g.} {Rogers: ' leaves Black in trouble, e.g. '} Rf3+ {Rogers: ' '} 42. Ke2 {Rogers: ' '} Ng6 {Rogers: ' '} 43. Rxa8 {Rogers: ' '} Rxf4 {Rogers: ' '} 44. e6 {with a clear advantage. Rogers: ' with a clear advantage.'}) {Rogers: '  '} 39... Rg2+ {Rogers: ' '} 40. Kc3 {Rogers: ' '} Rg3+ {Rogers: ' '} 41. Rd3 {Rogers: ' '} Rxd3+ {Rogers: ' '} 42. Kxd3 {Rogers: ' '} Bg2 {Rogers: ' '} 43. Nf7+ {Rogers: ' '} Kg7 44. Nd8 $1 {The only move to maintain winning chances.} ({Rogers: '  The only move to maintain winning chances. '} 44. Ng5 {Rogers: ' '} h6 $1 {Rogers: ' '} 45. Nxe6+ {Rogers: ' '} Nxe6 {Rogers: ' '} 46. Bxe6 {Rogers: ' '} Bxh3 {is certainly not worse for Black. Rogers: ' is certainly not worse for Black.'}) {Rogers: '  '} 44... Bxh3 {Rogers: ' '} 45. Bxe6 {Rogers: ' '} Ng6 {Rogers: ' '} 46. Ke3 Ne7 {Black has achieved a solid defensive setup and Watson was probably expecting a draw offer reasonable soon. Reti, however, plugs away and goes close to creating serious winning chances. His advantage lies in the fact that Black cannot afford to exchange all the minor pieces as then White's protected passed pawn will be a decisive factor in the pawn ending. Not a great deal to work with, I agree, but the need to avoid exchanges is certainly an inhibiting factor on Black. Rogers: ' Black has achieved a solid defensive setup and Watson was probably expecting a draw offer reasonable soon. Reti, however, plugs away and goes close to creating serious winning chances. His advantage lies in the fact that Black cannot afford to exchange all the minor pieces as then White's protected passed pawn will be a decisive factor in the pawn ending. Not a great deal to work with, I agree, but the need to avoid exchanges is certainly an inhibiting factor on Black.'} {Rogers: '  '} 47. Kf2 {Rogers: ' '} Bg4 {Rogers: ' '} 48. Kg3 {Rogers: ' '} Be2 {Rogers: ' '} 49. Nb7 {Rogers: ' '} Kg6 {Rogers: ' '} 50. Nd6 {Rogers: ' '} Bd3 {Rogers: ' '} 51. a3 {Rogers: ' '} Be2 {Rogers: ' '} 52. b4 Bd3 {White's pieces and pawns have reached their optimum squares and he must now find a plan. White's next few moves indicate either time trouble or a singular lack of ideas. Rogers: ' White's pieces and pawns have reached their optimum squares and he must now find a plan. White's next few moves indicate either time trouble or a singular lack of ideas.'} {Rogers: '  '} 53. Bf7+ {Rogers: ' '} Kg7 {Rogers: ' '} 54. Be8 h6 {Perhaps not immediately necessary, but White was about to force ...h6 by playing h4-g5. The Black pawn is a little more exposed on h6 than on its original square as the game continuation demonstrates. Rogers: ' Perhaps not immediately necessary, but White was about to force 