{Thomas Engqvist: 'Zsigmond Barász (1878-1935) was a strong Hungarian player. He shared first place in the third Hungarian Championship, Budapest 1911, with Zoltán von Balla. According to Chessmetrics he was at his best when he was 34 years old. His highest ranking was 30th in the world with an estimated rating of 2572 on the March 1912 list. ''Zsigmond Barász (1878-1935) was a strong Hungarian player. He shared first place in the third Hungarian Championship, Budapest 1911, with Zoltán von Balla. According to Chessmetrics he was at his best when he was 34 years old. His highest ranking was 30th in the world with an estimated rating of 2572 on the March 1912 list.  Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'Zsigmond Barász (1878-1935) was a strong Hungarian player. He shared first place in the third Hungarian Championship, Budapest 1911, with Zoltán von Balla. According to Chessmetrics he was at his best when he was 34 years old. His highest ranking was 30th in the world with an estimated rating of 2572 on the March 1912 list. '''} 1. d4 {1)Kalendovsky:Richard Reti.1989.Praha. p.10. 2)Di Felice: Chess Results 1901-1920. p.98.3)Matsukevitch: Рихард Рети.2005.Moskau  The Championship with 15 players was won by Leo Fleischmann, (later Leo Forgacs) with 11/14 points (2.-3.) Abonyi and Szekely 10/14 (4).Barasz 9/14 (5.-6.)Foldes and Gajdos 8,5/14 (7.-8.) Exner and Reti 7,5/14.  Reti was 18 years old at the time this game was played, so we can't expect the hypermodern play... Thomas Engqvist: 'The young Réti played 1 e4 almost exclusively, followed by either the Ruy Lopez or the King's Gambit. So it is curious that during the Hungarian National Tournament at Székezfehérvár, he played only Queen's Gambits. ''The young Réti played 1 e4 almost exclusively, followed by either the Ruy Lopez or the King's Gambit. So it is curious that during the Hungarian National Tournament at Székezfehérvár, he played only Queen's Gambits.  Petronijevic,Zoran: '1)Kalendovsky:Richard Reti.1989.Praha. p.10. 2)Di Felice: Chess Results 1901-1920. p.98.3)Matsukevitch: Рихард Рети.2005.Moskau  The Championship with 15 players was won by Leo Fleischmann, (later Leo Forgacs) with 11/14 points (2.-3.) Abonyi and Szekely 10/14 (4).Barasz 9/14 (5.-6.)Foldes and Gajdos 8,5/14 (7.-8.) Exner and Reti 7,5/14.  Reti was 18 years old at the time this game was played, so we can't expect the hypermodern play... Thomas Engqvist: 'The young Réti played 1 e4 almost exclusively, followed by either the Ruy Lopez or the King's Gambit. So it is curious that during the Hungarian National Tournament at Székezfehérvár, he played only Queen's Gambits. '''} d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: What is the name of the opening? ANSWER: Currently we have a Colle formation, signified by the fact that the c1-bishop is shut in behind the pawn chain. On the other hand, if the bishop is later developed to b2, we reach a Zukertort position. ''QUESTION: What is the name of the opening? ANSWER: Currently we have a Colle formation, signified by the fact that the c1-bishop is shut in behind the pawn chain. On the other hand, if the bishop is later developed to b2, we reach a Zukertort position.  Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: What is the name of the opening? ANSWER: Currently we have a Colle formation, signified by the fact that the c1-bishop is shut in behind the pawn chain. On the other hand, if the bishop is later developed to b2, we reach a Zukertort position. '''} c6 ({Alekhine recommended} 3... Bf5 {as a strong antidote to White's aspirations.}) 4. c4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Now it is a Slav by transposition, and Black's next move makes it a Semi-Slav. ''Now it is a Slav by transposition, and Black's next move makes it a Semi-Slav. Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'Now it is a Slav by transposition, and Black's next move makes it a Semi-Slav. '''} ({If White wants to continue with Colle schemes he should play} 4. Bd3 {, securing the b1-h7 diagonal. 4 c3 is possible