 Ke2 Ke6 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: '!''} 45. Kd3 Kd6 46. Kd4 Ke6 $11 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: '=''} 47. c5 bxc5+ 48. bxc5 {. EXERCISE (analysis): How does Black achieve the draw here? ANSWER:} f4 $1 {(the main point of the defence)} 49. gxf4 g3 50. Ke3 Kd5 51. Kf3 Kxc5 52. Kxg3 Kd5 53. Kf3 Kd4 {and despite being a pawn down, Black holds the draw.}) 42. gxh4 $18 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: '+-''} Ke6 43. c5 bxc5+ 44. Kxc5 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: '!''} f4 (44... Ke5 {loses after} 45. b5 f4 46. b6 f3 47. b7 f2 48. b8=Q+ $18 {[%csl Re5][%cal Rb8e5]}) 45. Kd4 Kf5 46. b5 {now everything is clear and no comment is needed. Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'now everything is clear and no comment is needed.''} f3 47. Ke3 f2 48. Kxf2 Ke5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: Can you work the forced variation out to its conclusion? ANSWER:''EXERCISE: Can you work the forced variation out to its conclusion? ANSWER: Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: Can you work the forced variation out to its conclusion? ANSWER:'''} 49. Kf3 Kd5 50. Kf4 Kc5 51. Kg5 Kxb5 52. Kxh5 Kc4 53. Kg4 Kb3 54. h5 Kxa3 55. h6 Kb2 56. h7 a3 57. h8=Q+ {Thomas Engqvist: 'With the pawn on a2 the position is an easy draw, but with the pawn on a3 it is a win.''With the pawn on a2 the position is an easy draw, but with the pawn on a3 it is a win. Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'With the pawn on a2 the position is an easy draw, but with the pawn on a3 it is a win.'''} Kb1 58. Qb8+ Ka1 59. Qe5+ ({Technically,} 59. Qf4 $1 {is the most precise move, leading to mate in nine. Note that} a2 {fails to} 60. Qc1# {.}) 59... Kb1 60. Qe1+ Kb2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'after ''after Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'after '''} 61. Qb4+ {Thomas Engqvist: 'This is the key squa'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'This is the key square for the white queen, putting pressure on the a3-pawn; ''' re for the white queen, putting pressure on the a3-pawn; '} Ka2 62. Kf4 {, Black loses the pawn, since he is forced to make a move. To win by zugzwang is one of the main methods in theoretical endgames. A well-played game by the young Réti, showing his fondness for endings.} 1-0


