{This game was a bit of a tragedy from Reti's point of view. After obtaining an excellent position from the opening and even winning a pawn, he lets slip what should have been a really excellent endgame.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 e6 3. g3 dxc4 4. Qa4+ Nd7 5. Bg2 Ngf6 6. O-O Bd6 (6... c5 {is the modern preference and frankly I doubt that White can hope for too much there.}) 7. Na3 Bxa3 ({After} 7... O-O 8. Nxc4 {White has to be better because of his harmonious development and central pawn majority. So Bogoljubow's plan is critical.}) 8. bxa3 (8. Qxa3 Nb6 {would make it difficult for White to recover the c4 pawn.}) 8... O-O 9. Qxc4 Nb6 10. Qc2 Bd7 11. Bb2 Ba4 12. Qb1 Bc6 $6 ({Presumably Black didn't like} 12... h6 {because of} 13. Ne5 {but then} Qxd2 {isn't clear.}) 13. Ng5 $1 {This is very strong now, the threat being to take the knight on f6 when h7 hangs.} Nbd7 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Rc1 c5 $6 ({And here} 15... Rb8 {was better.}) 16. Rxc5 $1 Rb8 ({Of course} 16... Nxc5 {would lose on the spot to} 17. Bxf6 {.}) 17. Rc4 h6 18. Ne4 Nd5 19. Qc2 N7b6 20. Rc6 Qc8 21. d3 Qb7 22. Be5 Qa6 23. Bxc7 (23. Qc1 {might have been better, simply protecting the a3 pawn. In any case White is better but this might have clamped down better on any counterplay.}) 23... Rbc8 24. Bxb6 Rxc6 25. Qxc6 Rc8 26. Nc5 Rxc6 27. Nxa6 Rxb6 28. Nb4 Nc3 (28... Nxb4 29. axb4 {would give White all the chances in a simple endgame, so Bogoljubow keeps more pieces on the board.}) 29. e3 a5 30. Nc2 Rb2 31. Nd4 Nxa2 32. Re1 $2 {After Black's reply White has to go back when he might even be somewhat worse.} (32. Kg2 {was a better chance.}) 32... Rd2 33. Ra1 a4 34. Nb5 g5 35. Kg2 g4 36. Nd6 Nc3 37. Ne4 $6 {It looks as if Reti was blind to the dangers inherent in this position.} (37. Nc4 {was a better chance though after} Rxd3 38. Ne5 Rd2 39. Nxg4 Ne4 {he's still struggling to draw.}) 37... Rxd3 38. Nf6+ Kg7 39. Nxg4 ({Or} 39. Nh5+ Kf8 40. Nf6 h5 41. Nxh5 Ne4 {, tying White up.}) 39... f6 40. h4 h5 41. Nh2 Nb5 42. Nf3 Rxa3 43. Rxa3 $2 {Black's outside passed pawn is especially dangerous in the knight endgame. White should have kept rooks on.} Nxa3 44. Nd4 Kf7 45. Kf3 e5 46. Ne2 Nb1 47. Ke4 ({Or} 47. e4 a3 48. Nc1 Nc3 {etc.}) 47... a3 48. Nc1 Nc3+ 49. Kd3 a2 50. Nb3 Na4 51. Na1 ({Or} 51. Ke2 Nc5 $1 52. Na1 Ne4 {, leaving White completely tied up.}) 51... Nc5+ 52. Ke2 Ne4 53. Kf3 f5 54. Kg2 Nd2 55. f3 e4 56. fxe4 Nxe4 57. Kf3 Kf6 58. Kf4 Nc5 59. Nc2 Nd3+ 0-1


