{Thomas Engqvist: 'The Viennese master Rudolf Spielmann (1883-1942) was a professional chess player and spent most of his mature life in Germany. He is said to have competed in more than 100 tournaments and 50 matches and was one of the hardest-working players. During the 1927 New York tournament he came to the conclusion that he needed to improve his rook endings – by the time he competed at Bad Kissingen in 1928 he was already a first-class specialist! In 1928/29 he did the same thing with positional play by studying the classic works of Nimzowitsch. Before this period Spielmann was mainly a dangerous attacking player, especially in open positions, and an intuitive one regarding combinations. He was regarded as the upholder of the romantic tradition, following in the footsteps of Anderssen and Chigorin. He might be regarded as a forerunner of Mikhail Tal in that he believed sacrifices should be judged according to the problems they set the opponent rather than whether they are objectively correct. Another similarity regarding their personalities is that both had a very friendly disposition. Spielmann himself wrote a classic book entitled 'The Art of Sacrifice' ('Richtig Opfern!') published in 1935, which it is necessary to assimilate in order to understand the art of combinations at a deeper level. '} 1. e4 {[%mdl 1]} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The main line of the Four Knights has some similarities with the Ruy Lopez (or Spanish Opening) considering the pressure on the important central e5-pawn. In the 1990s the English grandmasters Nigel Short and John Nunn were successful with it, while today it is the Chinese young genius GM Wei Yi who has revitalized it and made it into a potent weapon. Tarrasch in fact wrote that "The Four Knights Game leads to a very animated play, rich in chances for both sides", whereas Keres said that "The Four Knights Game is one of the best proven systems of avoiding all complications in the opening and it is therefore regarded by masters as a drawish opening." Who is right? Whether you are White or Black in this opening (or perhaps both!), you will have to find out for yourself and form your own opinion. '} a6 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' Thomas Engqvist: 'While 3...a6 is historically the main reply to 3 Bb5, with the two knight moves inserted, ...a7-a6 is regarded as inferior. That is because, in order to justify his play tactically, Black has to lose time with his queen, as we will see.'} ({The main reason the Four Knights went out of fashion was Rubinstein's energetic} 4... Nd4 {. We will see an example of this continuation (with Réti on the black side) in Game 15.}) ({However, such sharp variations are not to everyone's taste, so the solid symmetrical} 4... Bb4 {is actually more popular;}) ({as well as the rather passive} 4... d6 {which transposes to the Steinitz Defence.}) ({Other moves, such as} 4... Bc5 {and even the crazy looking but fully playable}) ({and the crazy-looking yet fully playable} 4... Bd6 $5 {(Cohen's Defence) are also seen regularly.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: How should White proceed? ANSWER:'} 5. Bxc6 ({Retreating with} 5. Ba4 {transposes to a minor variation of the Ruy Lopez which is considered harmless.}) 5... dxc6 ({Not} 5... bxc6 $2 6. Nxe5 {and Black loses the central pawn without any compensation.}) 6. Nxe5 Nxe4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'This is the tactical justification of Black's fourth move.'} 7. Nxe4 Qd4 (7... Qd5 {comes to the same thing, but why not move as deep into enemy territory as possible?}) 8. O-O Qxe5 9. d4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'It is useful to ask the question of the black queen before committing to Re1.'} Qd5 ({Rubinstein tried} 9... Qf5 {against Kuczynski at Lodz 1907, but in that case White can respond} 10. Ng3 $1 Qd5 11. Bf4 Bd6 12. Nh5 $1 {with advantage, as in A.Motylev-A.Kharlov, European Club Cup, Izmir 2004.}) 10. Re1 Be6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is White's strongest continuation? '} 11. Ng5 ({ANSWER: Taimanov analysed} 11. Bg5 $1 {, preventing castling queenside, while planning b2-b3 and c2-c4;} {On the other hand, if Black tries to drive the g5-bishop away with} h6 $6 {, White can respond} ({for example,} 11... Bd6 12. b3 b5 13. Rc1 b4 14. Qf3 O-O 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. c3 bxc3 17. Qxc3 {with a slight structural advantage, even if a draw is the most likely result.} (17. Z0)) 12. Bf6 $3 ({rather than Taimanov's} 12. Bh4) {, the idea being that the natural} 12... Qf5 {is met by} 13. Qd3 $1 {and the bishop is still taboo in view of Nd6+. Securing the queen with} Qg6 {does not solve the problem either, because} 14. Bh4 {then threatens 15 d5! cxd5 16 Nf6+ gxf6 17 Rxe6+ and wins. Black has to attempt artificial castling with} Kd7 {, followed by ...Re8 and Kc8, but then} 15. Rad1 Re8 16. d5 $1 cxd5 17. Qc3 Kc8 18. Bg3 Kb8 19. Nc5 $3 {(even stronger than taking on c7)} Bxc5 20. Qxc5 Rc8 21. b4 {, intending b4-b5, leads to a dangerous initiative for White.}) 11... O-O-O 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Qg4 Qxd4 ({A.Alekhine-D.Van Foreest, Bussum (simul) 1933, continued more passively with} 13... Re8 $6 14. Bf4 $6 (14. Re4 {secures a slight advantage}) 14... h5 $1 15. Qg6 Bd6 16. Bxd6 cxd6 {(now Black has equalized)} 17. Rad1 Qf5 18. Qxf5 exf5 19. Kf1 Kd7 20. h4 Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Rh6 22. Re3 Re6 23. Rg3 g6 24. Rb3 ({I do not believe for a second that Alekhine played} 24. Rh3 {as in the source}) 24... Kc7 25. f3 d5 {and a draw was agreed.}) 14. Qxe6+ Qd7 (14... Rd7 {is playable too, with the point} 15. Qe8+ Rd8 16. Bg5 $1 Bd6 $1 {.}) 15. Qxd7+ (15. Bg5 {leads to nothing substantial after} Qxe6 16. Rxe6 Rd5 $1 {.}) 15... Rxd7 16. Re8+ Rd8 17. Rxd8+ Kxd8 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: How would you evaluate this position? ANSWER: White has a small but distinct advantage. Three pawns versus two on the kingside is an significant factor when the opponent has more difficulties creating a passed pawn on the other side. '} 18. b3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Now Black gets the opportunity to place his pieces on optimal squares.'} (18. Be3 {is more active.}) 18... Bc5 19. Bb2 Rf8 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Threatening f2, so White does not have time to take on g7. '} 20. Rd1+ (20. Bxg7 $4 {would be a grave error since Black will get too much activity after} Rxf2 {as well as the pawn on c2.}) 20... Kc8 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!'} ({A good rule when playing against an opposing pawn majority is to place the king on the same side of the board. This will make it more difficult for the adversary to create a passed pawn, and if one does somehow appear the king stands ready to help restrain it. Therefore} 20... Ke8) ({or} 20... Ke7 {looks more logical, whereas after the text move it is cut off by the white rook.}) 21. Rd2 g6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How does White deal with the f2-weakness? ANSWER:'} 22. Kf1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Réti plans to place his pawn on f3, according to the famous rule by Capablanca.'} ({Presumably he did not want to weaken the f3-square with} 22. g3 {unnecessarily, since Black might exploit it with} g5 23. Kg2 g4 {, practically forcing} 24. Bd4 {, when Black can choose between 24...Bd6 and} Rd8 {. After the latter move,} 25. c3 {looks best, since White would be happy for all the pieces to be exchanged.} ({Instead,} 25. Bc3 Re8 $1 {gets nowhere}) ({while} 25. Be3 {leads to a draw by force after the surprising} Bxe3 $1 26. Rxd8+ Kxd8 27. fxe3 {; for example,} Ke7 28. Kf2 Ke6 29. e4 Ke5 30. Ke3 c5 31. Kd3 Ke6 {, when it easily visible that there is no possibility of zugzwang, and as a consequence the passed pawn is without venom.})) 22... Rf5 23. f3 Bd6 24. Kf2 Ra5 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'The Fischer-like '} 24... Bxh2 $2 {Thomas Engqvist: '??' Thomas Engqvist: 'loses to '} 25. g3 Rg5 26. Rd8+ {Thomas Engqvist: '!'} (26. Bf6 Bxg3+ 27. Kg2 Bf4+ 28. Bxg5 Bxg5 {prolongs the game considerably}) 26... Kxd8 27. Bf6+ Kd7 28. Bxg5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'and the bishop remains trapped. '}) 25. a4 Rh5 ({Black could have played} 25... b5 $1 {at once, aiming to get rid of his doubled pawn and balance the game. It works tactically because of the following variation:} 26. Bc3 (26. axb5 cxb5 {is completely equal; the rook comes to a2 next move}) 26... b4 27. Bg7 Bxh2 $1 {. In this position the Fischer move works, since} 28. g3 Rg5 29. Rd8+ {fails to} Kb7 {and the bishop escapes.}) 26. h3 b5 27. Bc3 Rh4 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Spielmann tries to encourage his opponent to capture on b5, but Réti does not oblige. '} ({Instead,} 27... bxa4 28. bxa4 Rc5 {is a fairly easy way to draw; e.g.} 29. Rd3 ({or} 29. Bb4 Rc4 30. Bxd6 cxd6 31. Rxd6 Rxc2+) 29... Rc4 30. a5 Ra4 {, followed by ...Bb4.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is the drawback to Black's last move? ANSWER:'} 28. g4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Shutting the rook in as well as blocking the fourth rank. '} Bf4 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Black cannot play'} 28... Rxh3 {Thomas Engqvist: '??' Thomas Engqvist: 'because of '} 29. Rxd6 {Thomas Engqvist: '!'} cxd6 30. Kg2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'and the rook is trapped; i.e. '} Rh6 31. Bg7 Rh4 32. Bf6 Rh6 33. Bg5 {.}) ({Black can liberate his rook with} 28... h5 29. Kg2 hxg4 30. fxg4 Rh7 {, but White still has a symbolic extra pawn after} 31. Bf6 {.}) 29. Rd8+ {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} ({It is better to play} 29. Kg2 {, rather than help Black exchange his problem rook. Obviously he cannot take on d2, since his rook gets trapped again.}) 29... Kxd8 30. Bf6+ Kd7 31. Bxh4 c5 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'A serious mistake. '} (31... Ke6 {should have been played. If Spielmann was worried about a possible pawn ending after} 32. Bg3 {, there was no need:} Ke5 $1 {cements the f4-square and Black has nothing to fear. It would now be suicide to play} 33. Bxf4+ $4 Kxf4 {, when White even loses due to the enormous activity of the black king.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: Why is Black's move a mistake? ANSWER: Because it allows White to fix the queenside pawns. '} 32. axb5 ({The immediate} 32. c4 $1 {is the most principled move, fixing the weakness on c5; but Réti's continuation is convincing too.}) 32... axb5 33. Bg3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Now Black must withdraw his bishop from the strong post on f4, since exchanging bishops leads to a hopeless pawn endgame.'} Bc1 (33... Bd6 {would have been answered the same way.}) 34. c4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!'} c6 35. Ke2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'White's king heads to e4 before starting the advance of the kingside pawns.'} Ke6 36. Kd3 Bg5 37. Ke4 Bf6 38. Bf2 Kd6 39. f4 Bc3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Black can only wait while the white pawns march forward.'} 40. h4 Bf6 41. f5 gxf5+ {Thomas Engqvist: 'Otherwise White plays 42 fxg6 hxg6 43 h5. '} 42. Kxf5 Bd4 43. Bg3+ Ke7 44. h5 Kf7 45. g5 bxc4 46. bxc4 Be3 47. g6+ hxg6+ 48. hxg6+ Kg8 $11 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Making things more difficult for himself. '} ({After} 48... Kg7 49. Be5+ Kf8 $1 50. Ke6 Bd4 {, White cannot control the long dark diagonal while taking the c6-pawn. Black places his bishop on d4 and goes back and forth with his king.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How can White make progress? ANSWER:'} 49. Bf4 Bd4 50. Bh6 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'This is the point. Black's king is trapped in a prison so White can go across and collect the c6-pawn. Nevertheless, Black is not losing yet.'} Bg1 51. Ke6 Bf2 52. Kd7 Bd4 53. Kxc6 Bf2 54. Kd5 Bg1 {Thomas Engqvist: '??' Thomas Engqvist: 'The fatal error. '} ({The bishop had to return to d4, after which White cannot win:} 54... Bd4 55. Bf4 ({or similarly} 55. Ke4 Bc3 56. Be3 Bb4 57. Kd5 Kg7 {etc}) 55... Bf2 ({not} 55... Kg7 $4 56. Be5+) 56. Bd6 Kg7 57. Bxc5 Be1 $1 {and draws, since the g6-pawn falls at once and the c-pawn will not get past c5 without the bishop taking it off.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: Now White wins very easily, but how? ANSWER:'} 55. Ke4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Threatening 56 Be3 while the black bishop cannot get to the other side of the c5-pawn.'} Bh2 56. Bf4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!'} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Black resigned in view of '} 56. Bf4 Bg1 57. Be3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'or'} Bh2 (57... Bxe3 58. Kxe3 Kg7 59. Ke4 Kxg6 60. Kd5 Kf6 61. Kxc5 {and his king is too far away to stop the c-pawn.}) 58. Bxc5 Kg7 59. Kf5 $18) 1-0


