1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 d6 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O e5 8. d3 Nh5 9. Nc3 f5 10. e3 Bd7 11. Qd2 {This developing move is the most flexible and possibly best. Reti surely understood the spirit of his most famous opening invention! In recent games White's play was less convincing.} (11. Ne1 {releases the control over the d4-square too soon allowing:} f4 $5 12. Nd5 ({The main problem is that after} 12. exf4 exf4 {the knight will eventually have to move again in order to control d4.}) 12... fxe3 13. fxe3 Rxf1+ 14. Kxf1 Ne7 15. Nc2 c6 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Kg1 Nf6 18. e4 Rf8 $11 {Kalinin,O (2395)-Miroshnichenko,E (2538) Alushta 2003 (½-½, 67)}) (11. Nd5 {is a premature display of activity as Black can exchange the active knight:} Ne7 12. b4 {Singh,P (2305)-Conquest,S (2495) Kolkata 1994 (0-1, 35)} Nxd5 $5 13. cxd5 a5 $5 $132 {This justifies the bishop's development to d7 since White does not have b4-b5.}) 11... Be8 $6 {Clearly a passive move, but White is well prepared against all sort of other plans.} (11... f4 12. exf4 exf4 13. d4 {The queen and knight stand much better in this position than in the similar subline from the game Kalinin,O (2395)-Miroshnichenko,E (2538) above.} Bg4 {The most active move, which, however, implies a loss of a tempo. It is useful to compare with Pedersen-Anderssen below.} 14. Rae1 Qd7 15. Ne4 Rae8 16. d5 Ne5 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Nc5 $1 Qf7 (18... Qc8 19. Bxe5 dxe5 20. f3 Bd7 21. g4 Nf6 22. Nd3 $16 {[%csl Ge5]}) (18... Qd8 19. Bxe5 dxe5 20. Nxb7 {[%csl Gd8]} Qc8 21. Nc5 f3 22. Bh1 Bh3 23. Re3 Bxf1 24. Kxf1 Qg4 25. Ne4 $44 {/}) 19. Bxe5 dxe5 (19... f3 20. Bh1 dxe5 21. Re3 $16) 20. f3 Bc8 21. g4 Nf6 22. Nd3 Nd7 23. Qa5 $16 {[%csl Ga7,Gc7]}) (11... Nf6 12. Ne1 $5 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) (11... a5 12. a3 {leaves the situation very much unchanged.}) 12. Nd5 Bh6 (12... Ne7 13. Ng5 Bd7 14. f4 $14) 13. Ne1 g5 (13... f4 14. exf4 exf4 15. Nf3) 14. f4 gxf4 15. gxf4 Bg6 16. Nf3 Re8 17. b4 Bg7 18. b5 Ne7 19. Ng5 $16 {White has carried out all the typical ideas of this setup and enjoys an advantage on practically all the sectors of the board.} Qc8 20. Nxe7+ Rxe7 21. Bd5+ Kh8 22. Qg2 Rb8 23. fxe5 dxe5 24. Ba3 Qe8 25. Bxe7 Qxe7 26. Rxf5 Nf6 27. Raf1 c6 28. bxc6 bxc6 29. Bxc6 Bxf5 30. Rxf5 h6 31. Ne4 Qe6 32. Ng3 Qd6 33. Bd5 Rb1+ 34. Rf1 Qb6 35. Nf5 Bf8 36. Rxb1 Qxb1+ 37. Qf1 Qb6 38. h3 Bc5 39. Qe2 Qb1+ 40. Kh2 Qb8 41. Be4 Nxe4 42. dxe4 Bf8 43. Qd2 Qb1 44. Ng3 Be7 45. c5 Qb5 46. Nf5 Bf8 47. Qc3 Kh7 48. c6 Qe2+ 49. Kg1 Qd1+ 50. Kf2 Bc5 51. Qb3 Qd2+ 52. Kf3 Kh8 53. Qb8+ 1-0


