{Thomas Engqvist: '"Réti brought back not only a 'beauty prize' for his game against Romanovsky but also a beautiful young Russian as his wife." – Hans Kmoch (1926)  Peter Arsenievich Romanovsky (1892-1964) was one of the strongest Russian players in the 1920s and '30s, with a peak rank of 12th in the world according to Chessmetrics, and was awarded the IM title in 1950. One reason he did not achieve the grandmaster title was that he had many other interests, such as music and literature. When asked why he did not put the required effort into the game he answered: "Oh, because in life there are many attractions which I did not want to pass by..." After WWII Romanovsky withdrew from competitive chess and focused on training and writing. He is probably most familiar to English readers for his book 'Chess Middlegame Planning', first published in Moscow 1960 and translated into English by Jimmy Adams in 1990. GM Alexander Kotov called it "one of the best books in the world's chess literature". There are not that many works on planning and Romanovsky was a good writer, both chesswise and pedagogically. He wrote 16 books and several further manuscripts were discovered amongst his archives, after his death. Unfortunately, a significant part of his work remains unpublished. ' 2.Schönheitspreis:} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. g3 e6 ({Another healthy scheme of development is} 3... b6 {, immediately neutralizing White's fianchetto.}) 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 Nc6 7. Bb2 d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 ({Instead,} 8... exd5 9. d4 {leads to the Tarrasch Variation of the Queen's Gambit, but it is not to everyone's taste to accept a vulnerable pawn structure in return for piece activity.}) 9. Nc3 ({The classical approach} 9. d4 {leads to a more simplified game after} b6 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Bb7 {. Black has no problems since all his pieces, including his majors, will easily find convenient squares on e7, c8 and d8. The only reasonable way to try and disturb Black's development is} 13. Ne5 {, but then} Qc7 (13... Qc8 $5 {is also playable}) 14. Qd7 Rac8 15. Rfd1 Nxe5 16. Qxc7 Nf3+ 17. Bxf3 Rxc7 18. Be5 Re7 19. Bxb7 Rxb7 20. Rac1 f6 21. Bd6 Bxd6 22. Rxd6 e5 {leads to a rather equal game. White's more active rooks are not a relevant factor since Black controls the vital seventh rank.}) 9... Bf6 10. Rc1 ({Alternatively,} 10. Qc2 {connects the rooks at once and defends the bishop. White does not need to worry about either} Ncb4 ({or} 10... Ndb4 {since, after} 11. Qb1 {, he will regain the tempo with the useful move a2-a3.})) 10... Nxc3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'There is no reason to exchange the knights immediately, as the b2-bishop is unprotected. '} ({Instead,} 10... b6 {keeps the tension between the minor pieces a little longer.}) 11. Bxc3 e5 (11... Bxc3 $6 12. Rxc3 {xc5}) 12. Bb2 $6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Understandably, White wants to put pressure on the c5-pawn, but the bishop is again left undefended on this square. '} (12. d3) ({Either} 12. Ba1) ({or} 12. Ne1 {deserves consideration.}) 12... Qd6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: Black's last move creates a deadly threat; how to parry it? ANSWER:'} 13. Ne1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The most logical move, defending against the threat of ...e5-e4, winning a piece, while preparing a knight manoeuvre to d3 or with c2-e3-c4 in the near future.'} (13. d3 $2 e4 $1 $19) ({Instead,} 13. Ba3 {is a step in the wrong direction. The one-move threat does not serve White's strategic plan as a whole and is answered simply by} b6 {, when it is unclear what the bishop is doing on a3. If White goes for} 14. b4 $6 cxb4 15. Rxc6 Qxc6 16. Bxb4 ({after} 16. Nxe5 $2 Qb5 17. Bxb4 Qxb4 18. Nd3 Qa5 19. Bxa8 Bf5 $1 20. Bc6 Bxd3 21. exd3 Qxa2 {, Black is clearly better}) {, then} 16... Bb7 17. Bxf8 Rxf8 {leaves Black with the slightly preferable position.}) 13... Bf5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Presumably Romanovsky wants to forestall Nd3, but otherwise the bishop is not particularly effective here. '} (13... Bg4 $1 {is a more active approach; if White plays} 14. Nd3 (14. Nc2 Rad8 15. Ne3 {is answered by} Be6) 14... b6 15. b4 {, Black has the strong exchange sacrifice} Nxb4 16. Nxb4 cxb4 17. Bxa8 Rxa8 {with good compensation on the light squares.}) 14. d3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'A standard, human move. '} (14. f4 $5 {is an interesting non-standard possibility; this double-edged move is assessed by the computer as completely equal.}) 14... Rad8 15. Nc2 b6 16. Ne3 Be6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: Black has equalized without any problems, so how does White continue? '} 17. f4 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' Thomas Engqvist: 'This is mistimed in view of Black's reply.'} ({ANSWER: In a hedgehog structure the normal move is} 17. a3 {, preparing b3-b4;}) ({but if White wants to play f2-f4, he should prepare it with} 17. Nc4 {first.}) 17... Nd4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The fundamental defect in White's structure is the weak d4-square which is promptly exploited by Romanovsky. In other positions White might simply respond with e2-e3, but here his own knight is in the way. '} 18. f5 ({It is no good playing} 18. Nc4 $2 {now, in view of} Bxc4 19. Rxc4 exf4 20. gxf4 Nf5 $1 {and White has serious weaknesses on the dark squares; for example,} 21. Bxf6 ({not} 21. Bc1 $4 Bd4+ 22. Kh1 $2 Ng3+ 23. hxg3 Qh6+ 24. Bh3 Qxh3# {and mates}) 21... Qxf6 22. Re4 Rfe8 23. Qc1 Rxe4 24. Bxe4 Nd4 25. Qe3 g6 26. Qf2 Nb5 27. f5 g5 {and so forth. Black is in full control of the game, particularly the dark squares, and can improve his position move by move, while White can only sit and watch.}) 18... Bg5 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'A nice intermediate move. If Black retreats the e6-bishop, White continues 19 Nc4 and 20 Be4. '} 19. Nc4 Bxc4 20. Rxc4 Be3+ $2 (20... b5 21. Rc3 c4 22. Kh1 $1 (22. dxc4 Nf3+) (22. bxc4 b4 $1 23. c5 bxc3 24. cxd6 cxb2) (22. Bc1 $2 Bxc1 23. Rxc1 Qa3) 22... cxb3 23. axb3 Rc8 $17) ({Another active idea is} 20... g6 {practically forcing an immediate exchange on d4. After} 21. Bxd4 ({opening the f-file with} 21. fxg6 fxg6 {is in Black's favour considering the stranded rook on c4}) ({while} 21. Be4 {is answered by} b5 22. Rc3 gxf5 23. Bxf5 Be3+ 24. Kg2 Nxf5 25. Rxf5 Qc6+ 26. Rf3 Bd4 {, and} 27. Rc2 e4 {wins on the spot}) 21... exd4 {, Black has a pronounced control of the dark squares, whereas the corresponding light squares are less important.}) 21. Kh1 Qh6 ({Inserting} 21... b5 22. Rc3 {before} Qh6 {preserves the d4-knight for the moment but obviously weakens the queenside pawns. Romanovsky probably did the right thing to avoid this, since complications arise after} 23. f6 $1 ({not yet} 23. Rxc5 $2 Nxe2 {, threatening ...Nxg3 mate as well as ...Bxc5, winning material}) 23... gxf6 ({or} 23... g6 24. Rxc5 Nxe2 25. Qxe2 Bxc5 26. Bc1 $1 Qh5 27. Qxh5 gxh5 28. Rf5 {etc}) 24. Rxc5 $1 Nxe2 25. Qxe2 Bxc5 26. Be4 {and White has good compensation.}) 22. Bxd4 Rxd4 ({On the surface} 22... exd4 {looks more convincing, but after} 23. a3 $1 {and b3-b4, the c4-rook will become quite active. One illustrative line is} Rd6 24. b4 cxb4 25. axb4 Qg5 26. Qc2 Rh6 27. Rc8 Qxg3 28. Rxf8+ Kxf8 29. Qc8+ Ke7 30. Qb7+ {with perpetual check.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: Should White play Be4 immediately or exchange rooks first? '} 23. Rxd4 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!'} ({ANSWER:} 23. Be4 {is correct, not helping Black to improve his position.}) 23... Bxd4 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'The worst of the three possible recaptures, since the d-file is the least useful for Black. '} ({He would prefer to play} 23... cxd4 {and utilize the c-file with ...Rc8, but that is not easily achieved after} 24. Qc2 {.}) ({Therefore} 23... exd4 $1 {is the best option, opening the e-file, and restricting White's counterplay.}) 24. Be4 Rd8 25. Kg2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'White improves his position on the light squares, while Black strives for consolidation of the dark squares.'} b5 26. Qc1 Qxc1 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'It is important for Black to keep the queens on the board, in order to prevent White working on his own plans, such as preparing e2-e3, undisturbed. For instance, ' Schwarz hatte friedliche Absichten und traute scheinbar seinem Gegner nichts Böses zu, sonst hätte er} 26... Be3 27. Qa3 (27. Qc3 {the most cunning try;} Bd4 28. Qa5 Rf8 $1 {(the only safe square from the white queen)} 29. Qxb5 (29. Qxa7 $4 {even leads to a win for Black after} c4 $1 {with ...c4-c3 and ...Qd2 to follow}) 29... Qd2 30. Bf3 Qxa2 {ensures Black of counterplay and an equal game.}) 27... Qb6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'gets nowhere' gezogen.}) 27. Rxc1 b4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!?' Thomas Engqvist: 'In 'Masters of the Chess Board', Réti uses this position as the starting point when discussing the theme "The centre pawn as an obstruction to its own pieces". This made a very deep impression on me when I read the book for the first time. Réti writes that if White's e2-pawn was placed on e4 and the bishop on c4 the position would be absolutely even. The difference here is that the bishop is very comfortably placed on the e4-square. "Then it will be used by the rook as a thoroughfare, and finally it will constitute a strong post for White's king." EXERCISE: How does White respond to Black's last move? ANSWER:'} 28. Rc4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'This is an excellent outpost for the white rook, as will be visibly clearer in connection with an eventual Kf3 and e2-e3, forcing the black bishop off the fourth rank.  '} Kf8 {Thomas Engqvist: 'This move is not necessary at this moment and makes White's plan slightly easier to carry out.'} (28... Rc8 29. Kf3 h6 {more precise.}) 29. Kf3 Rc8 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Black must defend the c5-pawn before the defending bishop is driven away. '} 30. e3 Bc3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How does White make progress in the most efficient manner? ' Der schwarze Läufer steht jetzt sehr unglücklich.} 31. a4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Taking the chance to improve the a2-pawn.'} ({ANSWER: However,} 31. f6 $1 {is even stronger, exploiting the tactical weakness of the h7-pawn;} {or} h6 ({since} 31... gxf6 32. Bxh7 {produces a passed h-pawn as well as a beautiful square for the bishop on f5. These variations show why it was important for Black to place the pawn on h6 earlier.}) ({Instead,} 31... g6 32. g4 h6 33. h4 Be1 34. g5 $1 h5 (34... Bxh4 $2 35. Bb7 Rc7 36. Rxh4 Rxb7 37. Rxh6 {leads to an easily winning rook ending}) 35. Bb7 Rc7 36. Ba6 {improves White's position considerably, with ideas of both d3-d4 and Ke4-d5}) 32. fxg7+ Kxg7 33. Bf5 Rc7 34. Ke4 Kf6 35. Bh3 {, intending Kd5.}) 31... Ke7 32. Bd5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'White clears the fourth rank for the rook as well as the e4-square for the king. Observe the difference between the bishops: White's pressurizes the f7-pawn while the black bishop cannot do anything useful. Preventing the white rook from dropping back on the c-file has no meaning considering its potential activity at g4 or h4. '} Rc7 33. Rh4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'At the last moment the rook moves away, evacuating the c4-square for the bishop and preparing Ke4 as well. White has anticipated ...Kd6 in the most efficient way. '} h6 34. Ke4 Kf6 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!'} ({It is better to play} 34... Rd7 {at once, followed by ...Rd6, defending the sixth rank.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How can White improve his position further? ANSWER:'} 35. Rh5 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'A beautiful rook manoeuvre from c4 to h5 has taken place. The rook's function is obviously to prepare h2-h4 and g4-g5, gaining space as well as creating weaknesses on the kingside.  '} Rd7 (35... g6 36. fxg6) ({It seems more logical to admit the mistake with} 35... Ke7 {, intending} 36. g4 f6 {in order to make the kingside breakthrough as hard as possible to carry out.} {However, after} 37. Be6 {, Black will soon be in zugzwang as the following variations show:} ({Then} 37. h4 $2 Rc8 38. g5 Rh8 {leads to a draw, since the white rook remains shuts in.} (38... Z0)) 37... Rb7 (37... Kd6 $6 {, preventing the white king from entering d5, can now be met by} 38. h4 $1 {since the black rook cannot manoeuvre to h8. After} Be1 39. g5 hxg5 40. hxg5 fxg5 41. Rxg5 Bh4 42. Rh5 Bf6 43. Rh8 {, White is winning; for example,} g6 44. Rh6 gxf5+ 45. Kxf5 Bg7 46. Rg6 Bh8 47. Bc4+ Ke7 48. Rg8 Bf6 49. e4 {and Black is in zugzwang, losing material by force.} (49. Z0)) 38. Kd5 Bd2 39. Rh3 Rc7 40. Rg3 $1 {creates a subtle zugzwang. Black can only move his bishop and White manoeuvres accordingly. For example} Be1 (40... Bc1 {allows} 41. h4 {and g4-g5 next move}) 41. Rg2 $1 {(this quiet move controls the second rank and eliminates the pressure on the e3-pawn from the rear)} Bh4 42. Re2 {(preventing the bishop from going back to e1)} Bg5 43. a5 $1 a6 {(otherwise White plays 44 a6, followed by e3-e4 and Ra2-a5-b5)} 44. Re1 $1 {an important waiting move;} (44. h3 $1 {has the same purpose}) 44... Bh4 45. Rc1 Bg5 46. Rxc5 Rxc5+ 47. Kxc5 Bxe3+ 48. Kxb4 {and the bishop endgame is easily winning for White due to the weak pawn on a6.}) 36. g4 $1 {h4,g5} g6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'If Black sits and waits, then h2-h4 and g4-g5 decides. '} 37. Rxh6 Kg5 38. Rh7 Kxg4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: Can you spot White's next move? ANSWER:'} 39. Be6 $3 {Thomas Engqvist: '!'} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'while after '} 39. f6 $2 Kg5 40. Bxf7 Kxf6 41. Bxg6 {, the game is considerably prolonged.}) ({Of course not} 39. fxg6 $4 f5#) 39... fxe6 40. fxg6 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'This is the tactical point. One wonders how many moves ahead Réti actually spotted this beautiful combination. '} (40. Rxd7 $4 gxf5# {Thomas Engqvist: 'is another way to commit suicide.'}) (40. h3+ $1 {Fruth}) 40... Rd8 41. Rxa7 {Der schwarze Läufer ist selten hilflos!} ({The methodical} 41. g7 Rg8 42. h4 Bb2 43. h5 Kg5 44. h6 Kg6 45. Rh8 Kf7 46. h7 Rxg7 47. Rf8+ Kxf8 48. h8=Q+ {is another, slower way to win.}) 41... Kg5 42. g7 Kh6 43. a5 ({Here} 43. Rf7 Rg8 44. a5 Kg6 45. Rb7 Ra8 46. a6 Kh7 47. a7 {and 48 Rb8 is quicker. Note that the bishop does not participate at all in the defence against the passed pawns.}) 43... Kh7 44. a6 Rd6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How does White finish the game? ANSWER:'} 45. h4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!'} Be1 46. h5 Bh4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'After'} 47. h6 {Thomas Engqvist: ', Black resigned in view of 48 Ra8, or if'} Rd8 {then} 48. Rf7 $1 {and 49 Rf8 decides the issue. A very typical game by Réti, showing his fondness for hypermodern ideas, and one of his very best efforts. Notice that in the final position, the white d- and e-pawns are still located on the third rank!} 1-0


