{Lasker and Réti share the lead by 6½/8. The decisive game begins.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 b5 6. a4 b4 7. Na2 e6 8. Bxc4 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Qe2 Nbd7 $5 {They play a quiet Slav Defence.} 11. b3 a5 12. Bb2 c5 13. Rfd1 Qb6 14. Nc1 Ba6 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Ne5 Bxc4 17. Nxc4 Qa6 18. Bd4 Rfc8 $5 {Lasker discontinues the exchanges.} 19. Bxc5 Bxc5 20. Qf3 Be7 21. Nd3 Nd5 22. Nde5 Bf6 23. e4 Nc3 $1 {A battle begins.} 24. Rd6 Qb7 25. Re1 Bxe5 26. Nxe5 Qc7 27. Nc4 e5 $6 {Emanuel starts a "Schwindel".} 28. Qf5 $1 {Lasker likes to smoke cigars full of opium during a game. About this time, his wife Martha prepares one. White threatens 29. Rd7. She has heard rumours and worries. He says it's alright.} Ne2+ $5 {Lasker plays fast under time pressure.} 29. Kf1 $2 ({Tartakower analyses} 29. Rxe2 Qxd6 30. Qxf7+ $1 Kh8 $1 31. Qd5 $1) ({Best is} 29. Kh1 $1 Nd4 30. Qxe5 Nxb3 31. Nb6 Qc3 32. Qxc3 bxc3 33. Nxa8 c2 34. h3 {and White gains a pawn (Tarrasch).}) 29... Nd4 $1 30. Qxe5 Nxb3 31. Nb6 Nd2+ $1 32. Kg1 Nc4 $1 33. Nxc4 Qxc4 34. Qf5 Rab8 35. e5 $2 (35. Qxa5 Qxe4 $1 36. Rdd1 $1 {shapes a firm defensive screen against the b-pawn.}) 35... b3 36. e6 fxe6 37. Rdxe6 Rf8 38. Qe5 Qc2 39. f4 b2 40. Re7 Qg6 41. f5 Qf6 42. Qd5+ Kh8 43. Rb7 Qc3 $1 {Lasker had won the crucial game of the tournament.} 0-1


