{The opening moves lead through hyper-modern looking byways to a pawn formation well known in the exchange variation of the French Defense.} 1. c4 e5 2. Nf3 e4 3. Nd4 Nc6 4. Nc2 Bc5 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. d4 exd3 7. exd3 d5 8. d4 Be7 9. c5 {(Played in enterprising blockade style.)} Bf5 ({Attempts to break the blockade with} 9... b6 {would have been premature, e.g.} 10. b4 a5 11. b5 Na7 12. c6 Bd6) 10. Bd3 ({Here the natural combination would have been} 10. Bb5 {followed by} Z0 11. Bxc6+) 10... Bxd3 11. Qxd3 b6 {(Here this move is in order.)} 12. O-O ({Now} 12. b4 a5 13. b5 {fails on account of} Nb4 {with the gain of a tempo.}) 12... O-O 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bh4 bxc5 15. dxc5 Ne5 16. Qd4 Ng6 17. Bg3 c6 {[%csl Rd4,Gd5][%cal Gg3b8,Yc2b4,Rb4c6] (Black has a good d-pawn [poorly blockaded] and the possibility of attacking the White c-pawn. Against this, White's control of the g3-b8 diagonal does not seem to afford an equivalent. White should clearly have played 10.Bb5.)} 18. Nb4 Rc8 19. h3 Re8 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Yg6f8,Yf8e6,Ge8e1] (Making room for the Knight and at the same time preparing for the occupation of the central file, which White can't dispute because of his difficulties at c5.)} 20. Rad1 Nf8 21. Nd3 Qa5 {(Black saw that 22.Qa4 is now forced and prepared a highly original centralization maneuver in reply.)} 22. Qa4 ({Bad would be} 22. b4 Qa3 23. Rb1 Ne6 24. Qe5 Nd7 25. Qe1 Nexc5 26. bxc5 Bf6) 22... Qxa4 23. Nxa4 Ne4 {[%csl Yd5,Ye4] (Now the Knight occupies the center, which has become free after the defelction of the defending forces.)} 24. Bh2 Ne6 {(What can the Knight want? The c-pawn is easy to defend.)} 25. b4 Nd4 {[%csl Yd4,Yd5,Ye4] (A quite rather extraordinary cooperation! Two Knights, of which one can easily be driven away by f3 and the other is undefended and yet they control the whole board.)} 26. Rfe1 ({If} 26. f3 {then} Ne2+ 27. Kh1 N4g3+ 28. Bxg3 Nxg3+ 29. Kg1 Nxf1) 26... Bh4 {(The third ally)} 27. Be5 {(White was in difficulties. This move loses a pawn.)} Rxe5 28. Nxe5 Bxf2+ 29. Kf1 Bxe1 30. Rxd4 Bg3 31. Nf3 Re8 32. Rd1 Re6 33. Rc1 Kf8 {(The King goes to the threatened wing.)} 34. Nc3 Nxc3 35. Rxc3 Re4 36. a3 Ke8 37. Rd3 ({Fine move.} 37. Rd3 Kd7 38. b5) 37... a6 38. Rd4 f5 39. a4 Kd7 40. b5 {(This fails now on account of a finesse worthy of an endgame study.)} axb5 41. axb5 cxb5 42. Rxd5+ Kc6 {(As in Game No. 1, the extra material is returned with thanks.)} 43. Rd4 ({If} 43. Rxf5 b4) 43... Kxc5 {And Black won.} 0-1


