was presumably worried about weakening his king's position, and especially the f3-square, but this is balanced by the greater central control, which makes it harder for Black to bring his pieces to the kingside.'}) 23... hxg3 24. hxg3 Qc7 {Kasparov: 'Forced to fight against Reti's special weapon Alekhine has almost equalized, but his opponent, playing with ongoing inventiveness, has managed to retain the initiative. He has a positional edge because of his superiority in the centre and on the queenside, with Alekhine obviously looking for counterchances on the kingside. ' Kasparov: 'Aljechin ist gezwungen, gegen Retis Spezialwaffe anzutreten, hat aber fast gleichgezogen. Aber der Gegner hat es mit anhaltendem Einfallsreichtum geschafft, die Initiative zu behalten. Er hat einen positionellen Vorteil im Zentrum und am Damenflügel, während Aljechin offensichtlich Gegenspiel am Königsflügel sucht. ' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Aljechin ist gezwungen, gegen Retis Spezialwaffe anzutreten, hat aber fast gleichgezogen. Aber der Gegner hat es mit anhaltendem Einfallsreichtum geschafft, die Initiative zu behalten. Er hat einen positionellen Vorteil im Zentrum und am Damenflügel, während Aljechin offensichtlich Gegenspiel am Königsflügel sucht. '} 25. b5 {Steve Giddins: ''Garry Kasparov: ''Consequent, but very risky to say the least.' (Alekhine)'' ?!' Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: Still pursuing the queenside attack! ANSWER: Yes, he is nothing if not consistent; but as we will see, it was now time to take Black's kingside attacking chances more seriously.' Kasparov/Alekhine: '?!' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Aljechin'} ({Kasparov: 'Eine solide positionelle Alternative war'} 25. e4 {'Garry Kasparov: 'was much safer, when Black was intending'' Kasparov/Alekhine: ''} Ne7 (25... Nb6 {Kasparov: 'and ...Nbd7! with sufficient counterplay. But Réti, of course, did not want to block the h1-a8 diagonal of his favourite bishop.'} 26. Qb3 {Kasparov/Alekhine: ''} ({but} 26. Qd3 Nbd7 27. f4 {still looks better for White to me}) (26. Qc3 Rad8 27. Ndb3 Rxd2 (27... Nbd7 28. f3 Qxg3+) 28. Qxd2 Rd8 29. Qf4 Qc8 30. a5 $36 {Lasker}) 26... Nbd7 {would give Black sufficient counterplay. Admittedly, Réti can hardly be blamed for not seeing Alekhine's extraordinary 26th move.} (26... Rad8 $11 {Alekhine})) 26. a5 {would strengthen the position of the knight on c5 but Reti wanted to attack c6. In retrospect this was a fateful decision. Kasparov: 'strengthening the knight on c5 was a solid positional alternative, but Reti wanted to create weaknesses on c6. ' Kasparov: ', wonach der Springer auf c5 verstärkt wird. Aber Reti wollte eine Schwäche auf c6 erzeugen. ' Kasparov/Alekhine: ', wonach der Springer auf c5 verstärkt wird. Aber Reti wollte eine Schwäche auf c6 erzeugen.'}) 25... axb5 26. axb5 {'Garry Kasparov: 'It appears that White's strategy has triumphed: he is about to give the opponent a weak pawn, which will be bound to fall. But Alekhine finds a resource that radically changes the picture.'' Kasparov: 'White's strategy seems to be working very nicely. The isolated black pawn is doomed to fall within a few moves. But Alekhine wasn't going to passively wait for destruction. He finds a way to completely change the unwanted course of the game. ' Kasparov: 'Die weiße Strategie scheint sehr gut zu funktionieren, zumal der schwarze Isolani in wenigen Zügen verlorengehen wird. Aber Aljechin hatte nicht vor, passiv auf seine eigene Vernichtung zu warten. Er findet einen Weg, um den Charakter der Partie völlig umzukehren. '} {'Garry Kasparov: 'His king suddenly finds itself in difficulties:''} Re3 $1 {Just when it was'Garry Kasparov: '??' ''It seems almost incredible that this spectacular move not only stops White's attack but even brings him serious trouble.' (Alekhine)'' starting to look as if Black's strategy was not succeeding Black launches this stunning combinative blow. The position is unclear after this but Alekhine succeeds in confusing his opponent. Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: Wow! Lightning from a clear sky! ANSWER: Alekhine was not short on imagination when it came to finding ways of attacking enemy kings! This move is the start of a famous and fabulous combinative assault, although, in itself, it does not guarantee Black any advantage. ' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Alekhine: !!. Kasparov:' Kasparov: 'All of a sudden the white king feels insecure. The audacious rook cannot be taken: ' Kasparov: 'Auf einmal ist es der weiße König, der sich nun unsicher fühlt.' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Auf einmal ist es der weiße König, der sich nun unsicher fühlt.'} 27. Nf3 $4 {Steve Giddins: ''Garry Kasparov: '?' 'Strangely enough, this is already an irreparable mistake.'' ?' Steve Giddins: 'This move turns out to be a serious mistake.' Kasparov: '?' Kasparov/Alekhine: '?' Kasparov: 'From now on Alekhine makes a series of moves that sweep White off the board. ' Kasparov: 'Von nun an führt Aljechin eine Reihe von Zügen aus, die Weiß förmlich vom Brett fegen.'} ({Kasparov: 'The impudent rook cannot be taken:' Kasparov: 'Der freche Turm kann nicht geschlagen werden:'} 27. fxe3 $4 {Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Alekhine: '?''} Qxg3+ {obviously leads to mate Kasparov: 'with mate; and even after ' Kasparov: 'nebst Matt;'} 28. Bg2 Nxe3 {, and 27...Rxg3+ is threatened. And Réti, unable to withstand Alekhine's pressure, flinches... fortunately for the chess world! Kasparov/Alekhine: '-+'}) ({but Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Alas Alekhine's original attempt to complicate the position could have been met by simply' Kasparov: 'Leider konnte Aljechins origineller Versuch, die Stellung zu verkomplizieren, ganz einfach durch'} 27. Bf3 {deserved attention. After} Rea3 (27... Bxf3 28. exf3 {Kasparov: 'ending Black's activity; or even by the cold-blooded ' Kasparov: 'abgewehrt werden, wonach die schwarze Aktivität zum erliegen kommt.'} cxb5 29. Nxb5 Qa5 {, considering that Kasparov: '!' Kasparov: 'still with advantage for Black, as' Kasparov/Alekhine: ''} 30. Rxd5 $2 {"would lose immediately after} (