though it looks as if we have a "simple" ending with two pawns vs. one on the same side, Black is actually winning the white g-pawn, because the only attempt to defend it with' Kasparov: 'etc. White's position has lost its attraction, but how can Black make something serious out of that? Both 31...xc1... (see below) '} 35. Rd8+ Kh7 36. Rh1+ Kg6 37. Rh3 {runs into the elegant trick} Rfb3 $1 {and White is losing a piece, in view of the mate threat from the black rooks! QUESTION: If Alekhine saw that, it is amazing! ANSWER: I think he did. And as we will see, it was not the only remarkably deep variation he calculated in this game. Kasparov: 'winning.' Kasparov/Alekhine: '-+'}) {Kasparov/Alekhine: 'White's position has lost its attraction, but how can Black make something serious out of that? ' Kasparov: 'Die weiße Stellung ist wenig attraktiv, aber wie kann Schwarz das zum vollen Punkt verwerten? ' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Die weiße Stellung ist wenig attraktiv, aber wie kann Schwarz das zum vollen Punkt verwerten? '} 31... Ne4 $3 {A fantastic move'Garry Kasparov: ''The beginning of a new combination – which, however, is the absolutely logical consequence of the previous manoeuvres – aiming, after a series of twelve practically forced moves, at the capture of White's exposed knight at b7.' (Alekhine) But what a knight move! The audacious black rook has already been en prise for six moves! 'It was Alekhine's stamina that carried him to victory. It was in the most complicated positions that Alekhine found his greatest concepts.' (Fischer).'' from Alekhine, wasting no time in closing in on White's position. Steve Giddins: 'The computer confirms that this is the only move to win. QUESTION: What is the point? ANSWER: Well, we will see in a minute, but I can reveal at this stage that the whole point of the combination is the vulnerable knight on b7. QUESTION: You are kidding? ANSWER: Nope! ' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Alekhine: '!'' Kasparov: 'What a move! This new member of the cavalry regiment will turn White's defence lines into dust. Now White's best chance was 32.d8... (see below) ' Kasparov: 'Was für einen Zug! Das neue Mitglied der schwarzen Kavallerie wird die weiße Verteidigungslinie in Staub auflösen. ' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Was für einen Zug! Das neue Mitglied der schwarzen Kavallerie wird die weiße Verteidigungslinie in Staub auflösen. '} ({After Steve Giddins: 'and' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Both' Kasparov: 'Sowohl'} 31... Nxc1 {Kasparov: 'and'} 32. fxe3 Ra3 33. Ng5) ({and Kasparov/Alekhine: 'and' Kasparov: 'wie auch'} 31... Rxf3 32. Rxe2 Rf5 (32... Rxg3 33. Kxg3 Bxe2 {will only leave Black with an extra pawn with all pawns on one side, endings which should be easily drawn. But Alekhine had foreseen a stunning further blow.}) 33. Rb2 {White would save the draw. Kasparov: 'lead to an obvious draw.' Kasparov: 'führen offensichtlich zum Remis.'}) 32. Rc4 {Reti is trying t'Garry Kasparov: '!?' Garry Kasparov: 'A desperate tactical trick! Alekhine and Kotov attach an exclamation mark to this move, calling it the best defence.'' o exchange some pieces via tactical means. Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Alekhine: '!'' Kasparov: 'Reti, using nice tactical attempts, desperately hopes he will be able to exchange the terrifying black pieces. 32...xf3... (see below) ' Kasparov: 'Mit netten taktischen Finessen versucht Reti verzweifelt, die furchterregenden schwarzen Figuren abzutauschen. '} ({'Garry Kasparov: 'while after'' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Now White's best chance was' Kasparov: 'Jetzt war die beste Chance für Reti' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Jetzt war die beste Chance für Reti'} 32. Rd8+ Rxd8 33. fxe3 {Kasparov: 'although after' Kasparov: 'obwohl nach'} Rd5 $1 {and Kasparov: 'Black wins the pawn while his pieces still dominate the board. ' Kasparov: 'Schwarz den Bauern erobert, während seine Figuren immer noch das Brett beherrschen.'} 34. Rc4 N2xg3 {Black is a pawn up with a decisive attack, for example:} 35. Bg2 Nf1+ $1 36. Kh1 Rd1 37. Rd4 Neg3+ 38. Kg1 Nd2+ {etc.}) ({and Steve Giddins: 'After'} 32. fxe3 $2 Nxd2 {Steve Giddins: ''Garry Kasparov: 'is clearly bad'' , both the c1-rook and f3-knight are hanging.' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Alekhine: '-+' Lasker' Kasparov: 'loses right away.' Kasparov: 'verliert sofort'} 33. Nxd2 Nxc1 {are good for Black.}) ({QUESTION: I cannot see how you are going to exploit the undefended knight on b7, but you seem like an honest chap, so I will take your word for it and therefore suggest} 32. Rc7 {, defending it!   ANSWER: A nice try, but that loses most simply to} Nxd2 33. Nxd2 Re5 {, simply leaving Black an exchange up; although all the remaining pawns are on one flank, the fact that several extra pairs of pieces are on the board means that White should have no real hope of holding this position (if it were just a single rook vs. a single white minor piece, then he might have some chances).}) 32... Nxf2 $1 {'Garry Kasparov: 'A simple refutation: Black picks up the key f2-pawn and maintains all his threats.'' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Alekhine: '!' Kasparov:' Kasparov: 'The simple refutation - Black takes the key pawn on f2 and keeps all threats alive. ' Kasparov: 'Die einfache Widerlegung – Schwarz nimmt den wichtigen Bauern auf f2 und hält alle Drohungen aufrecht.' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Die einfache Widerlegung – Schwarz nimmt den wichtigen Bauern auf f2 und hält alle Drohungen aufrecht.'} ({After'Garry Kasparov: 'or at least'' Kasparov: 'Nach'} 32... Bxf3 {White can play'Garry Kasparov: '?!'' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Alekhine: '?'' Kasparov: 'is met by' Kasparov: 'kommt'} 33. Rxe4 $1 {Kasparov: '!!' '!!' Kasparov/Alekhine: '!!'} Bxe4 ({or} 33... Rxe4 34. Bxf3) 34. fxe3 Bxh1 35. Kxh1 {'Garry Kasparov: 'with drawing chances.''} Nxg3+ 36. Kg2 {with good drawing chances.} Ne4 37. Rd8+ Rxd8 38. Nxd8 {with good drawing chances. mit guten Remischancen.}) ({And Steve Giddin'Garry Kasparov: 'Réti was cherishing hopes of'' s: 'Not'} 32... Nxd2 {doesn't work be'Garry Kasparov: '?'' cause of Steve Giddins: '?' Steve Giddins: 'due to' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Alekhine: '?'' Kasparov: 'also doesn't work' Kasparov: 'geht auch nicht:'} 33. Nxd2 {Steve Giddins: ''Garry Kasparov: '!'' !' Steve Giddins: '(Alekhine) and White is saved, since Black has two pieces hanging.'} Rd3 34. Nc5 $1 {.'Garry Kasparov: 'equalising'' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Lasker'}) {Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: This is a bit head-spinning! What is going on here? Materially, White seems only to be a pawn down, and as you have pointed out already, the fact that we have so few pawns, and all on one flank, should mean he can draw the ending. ANSWER: I agree in principle; the problem here is that White's pieces are tactically insecure. In fact, it is a classic case of Nunn's Law: Loose Pieces Drop Off. For the moment, the f3-knight is hanging. '} 33. Bg2 {Steve Giddins: ''Garry Kasparov: 'Black is now obviously winning, but see how he does this:'' does not defend the Nf3 per se, but Black cannot now win a piece with' Kasparov: 'Black is clearly winning, but Alekhine's final combination makes this game a true masterpiece.' Kasparov: 'Schwarz war klar auf der Siegerstraße, aber Aljechins Schlußkombination macht aus der Partie ein Meisterwerk.'} (33. Nc5 {was a slightly better chance but is still winning for Black after} Rae8 34. Ng5 Nxh1 35. Kxh1 Nxg3+ {etc.}) ({QUESTION: Okay, say I move the knight, with} 33. Nd4 {for example...? ANSWER: Then we see for the first time that the b7-knight is also a loose piece:} Nxh1 34. Kxh1 Nxd4 35. Rcxd4 Bf3+ {and the LP duly DOs.}) 33... Be6 $1 {Steve Giddins: ''Garry Kasparov: 'An essential link of the combination! It is easy to see that White has no choice.'' Another attack on a loose piece, this time the c4-rook. '} (33... Bxf3 34. Bxf3 Rxf3 {because of} 35. Rxe2 {.}) 34. Rcc2 $2 (34. Rb4 Ng4+ 35. Kh3 {would have been the best chance.}) ({If the rook moves away at random, such as} 34. Rc7 {, there follows} Ng4+ 35. Kh3 Raa3 {and White will lose the g3-pawn and further material thereafter (including possibly his king). QUESTION: Even in such a simplified position, Black has a raging attack? ANSWER: Yes, that is the other reason he is winning. The text tries to defend by counter-attacking against the e2-knight.}) 34... Ng4+ 35. Kh3 ({Stepping into the discovered check is highly unpleasant, but there is no choice at all, since} 35. Kh1 Ra1+ {forces mate.}) 35... Ne5+ 36. Kh2 ({Again,} 36. Kh4 Re4+ {forces mate.} (36... Ra4+ {.})) 36... Rxf3 $1 {Steve Giddins: 'The final combinative blow.' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Alekhine: '!!''} (36... Nxf3+ $6 37. Bxf3 Rxf3 38. Rxe2 {is also better for Black but much less clear than the game.}) 37. Rxe2 ({Here} 37. Bxf3 Nxf3+ 38. Kg2 Nxd2 39. Rxd2 Nc3 {just leaves Black a piece up.}) 37... Ng4+ 38. Kh3 {Neither now nor before could the white king move to the first rank because of the deadly check on a1 Kasparov: 'Neither now nor before could the white king move to the first rank because of the deadly check on a1' Kasparov: 'Weder jetzt noch früher konnte der weiße König auf die erste Reihe ziehen, wegen des tödlichen Schachs auf a1.'} ({And again after} 38. Kh1 {there would have followed a deadly rook check.}) 38... Ne3+ {Steve Giddins: 'It has long been assumed by commentators that this final, beautiful combination is the only way to win.'} ({Sadly, the computer points out another, slightly more prosaic finish in} 38... Rf6 {. White cannot hold the ending after} 39. Rxe6 fxe6 40. Kxg4 {with two pieces for a rook, because of the sting in the tail:} Ra4+ $1 {, when White's king is caught in a mating net and he would have to surrender a piece after all with} 41. Be4 {;} ({e.g.} 41. Kh3 Rh6#) ({or} 41. Kg5 Rf5+ 42. Kg6 Rg4# {.})) 39. Kh2 ({Once again,} 39. Kh4 Ra4+ {is forced mate.}) 39... Nxc2 40. Bxf3 {Steve Giddins: ''Garry Kasparov: 'After'' After'} Nd4 {Steve Giddins: ''Garry Kasparov: '!'' !' Steve Giddins: 'An exquisite final position, and the endpoint of Alekhine's breathtakingly deep combination.' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Alekhine: 'Ich halte diese und meine Partie gegen Bogoljubow, Hastings, 1922 für die brillantesten Turnierpartien meiner Schachkarriere. ''} 41. Rf2 ({or} 41. Re3) 41... Nxf3+ 42. Rxf3 Bd5 {Either the knigh'Garry Kasparov: '!' Garry Kasparov: '– the final blow! – he loses his errant knight.'' t or rook will be lost. Steve Giddins: ', the loose colt on b7 drops off, since' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'Alekhine: '-+' Kasparov:' Kasparov: 'and the abandoned knight on b7 is lost. The endgame with a piece less is hopeless, so Reti resigned. I think there is reason to nominate this game the most beautiful ever played in the history of chess. ' Kasparov: 'und der verlassene Springer auf b7 geht verloren. Das Endspiel mit einer Minusfigur ist verloren, also hat Reti die Partie aufgegeben. Es überrascht mich nicht, daß diese Partie damals zu den schönsten der ganzen Schachgeschichte gezählt wurde. ' Kasparov/Alekhine: 'und der verlassene Springer auf b7 geht verloren. Das Endspiel mit einer Minusfigur ist verloren, also hat Reti die Partie aufgegeben. Es überrascht mich nicht, daß diese Partie damals zu den schönsten der ganzen Schachgeschichte gezählt wurde.'} 43. Rb3 {is impossible! QUESTION: You mean Alekhine saw that when he sacrificed his rook on e3? ANSWER: It is not clear. He does not say so, but I think he must have seen it at least when playing 31...Ne4!. Given the complexity of the position, even that is a remarkable piece of combinative vision.} 0-1


