1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 c6 5. cxd5 {Christoph Scheerer: '?!' Christoph Scheerer: 'Relieving the tension this early turns out to be premature, but given that Réti was employing his new system for the first time in this game, he should not be heavily criticized.'} ({The move} 5. b3 {, which Réti later employed with great success, has become standard in various set-ups in the Réti Opening. White should retain a small plus after the common continuation} Bg7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O Bg4 8. d3 Nbd7 9. Nbd2 Re8 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 {, although there are plenty of other options too.}) 5... cxd5 6. O-O Bg7 7. d3 Nc6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Qb3 (9. Bf4 {scores surprisingly well in the few games that the 'Mega Database 2008' has to offer. However, after the forceful} d4 $1 10. Na4 Nd5 11. Bd2 b6 12. Rc1 Bb7 13. a3 Qd7 14. b4 Rac8 {(M.Stryjecki-P.Harikrishna, online blitz 2005), it is actually Black who has the better prospects.}) 9... b6 10. Bg5 Na5 11. Qa3 Bb7 12. Rac1 h6 13. Bf4 Nh5 14. Bd2 Nc6 15. Rc2 Qd7 16. Rfc1 Rfc8 17. Qa4 Nf6 {Christoph Scheerer: 'The crucial position of the game. The opening phase is complete and Black has comfortably equalized. With his next move, Réti decides to initiate an attack on the kingside, but it turns out that Black can defend quite easily.'} 18. Qh4 g5 19. Nxg5 $2 ({Christoph Scheerer: 'It would have been better to meekly return to the queenside with'} 19. Qa4 $14 {Christoph Scheerer: '.'}) 19... hxg5 20. Bxg5 Nd8 $1 {Christoph Scheerer: 'An excellent resource. Black transfers his knight to the kingside and manages to reduce the remaining material significantly.'} 21. Bh3 Ne6 22. Bf5 d4 $1 23. Ne4 (23. Bxf6 Bxf6 24. Qh7+ Kf8 $19) 23... Rxc2 24. Rxc2 Rc8 $1 25. Rxc8+ Qxc8 26. Bh6 (26. Nxf6+ exf6 $19) 26... Qc2 27. f3 Bxe4 28. fxe4 Qxe2 29. Bxe6 fxe6 30. Qg5 Qg4 31. Qxg7+ Qxg7 32. Bxg7 Kxg7 {Christoph Scheerer: 'The smoke has cleared and Black is a piece up in an endgame.'} 33. h3 Nd7 34. Kf2 Nc5 35. Ke2 Na4 {Christoph Scheerer: '. Thus the Réti Opening's debut wasn't too successful. Furthermore, the critics weren't afraid to voice their opinion: Tarrasch, for instance, described the opening as 'a profound but completely faulty system', while Emanuel Lasker named it a 'spiritual opening'. However, Réti wasn't taken aback by his setback, and eventually he was rewarded at the famous 1924 New York tournament, where he not only beat José Capablanca, but also Frederick Yates, Edward Lasker and Efim Bogoljubow with his system! The game against the Bogoljubow, which also brought Réti the brilliancy prize, will conclude this chapter (see the following game).'} 0-1


