{This game was played a year after Capablanca's stunning defeat by Reti in the New York 1924 tournament. This time he plays a set-up that would become recognised as one of the most solid and reliable defences to the Reti.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 c6 3. b3 ({Of course} 3. d4 {would bring about a Slav Defence which Black must also be prepared for.}) ({If, on the other hand, White wants to fianchetto his king's bishop then he should do this now with} 3. g3 {. But in this case White has to reckon with} dxc4 {.}) 3... Bg4 4. Bb2 (4. Ne5 Bf5 5. Bb2 e6 6. e3 f6 7. Nf3 e5 8. Be2 Bd6 9. Nc3 Be6 10. O-O Ne7 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Nb5 $14 {Keres - Pachman, Baden, 1957}) 4... Nf6 (4... Bxf3 5. gxf3 $14) 5. Ne5 ({One of the advantages of Capablanca's early ...Bc8-g4 is that after} 5. g3 {he can mangle White's pawn structure with} Bxf3 {.}) 5... Bh5 6. g3 e6 7. Bg2 Be7 (7... Bd6 {!?}) 8. O-O Nbd7 {Exchanging off White's advanced knight. It could go back of course, but that would represent a loss of two tempi.} 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. d3 O-O 11. Nd2 Qc7 12. Rc1 Rfd8 13. Nf3 Ne8 {Preparing to exchange more pieces with .. .Be7-f6. This time round it's evident that Capablanca is treating his opponent with far more caution.} (13... Qa5 14. Bc3 {!?} Qxa2 {??} 15. Ra1 $18) 14. Rc2 Bf6 15. Qa1 $5 {Reti really loved putting his queen on this square!} Bxb2 16. Qxb2 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Qe7 18. Rd1 a6 {There's not much in it now.} 19. Bg2 g6 20. e3 h5 21. cxd5 exd5 22. b4 {!} h4 23. a4 Nd6 (23... hxg3 24. hxg3 Nf6 25. Rdc1 Ng4 26. d4 $14) 24. e4 {!} dxe4 (24... h3 {?!} 25. Bxh3 dxe4 26. dxe4 Qxe4 27. Rcd2) 25. dxe4 Ne8 (25... Nxe4 {?} 26. Re1 f5 27. f3 {would win the knight.}) (25... a5 {?!} 26. bxa5 Rxa5 27. Rcd2) 26. Rcd2 hxg3 27. hxg3 Rxd2 28. Qxd2 Nf6 29. Qd4 Re8 30. Qb6 Kg7 31. e5 Qxe5 (31... Nh5 {!?}) 32. Qxb7 Ng4 33. Qb6 ({And not} 33. Qxc6 {because of ?} Nxf2 {!} 34. Kxf2 Qe2+ 35. Kg1 Qxd1+ {etc.}) ({whilst} 33. Bxc6 $2 {is bad because of} Qh5 34. Bg2 ({Or} 34. Qa7 Re2) 34... Re2 {etc.}) 33... Qh5 {?} (33... Qh5 34. Qd4+ Kg8 (34... Kh7 35. Bf3 (35. Bxc6 {?} Rd8 $19 {!}) 35... Qh2+ 36. Kf1 Ne5 (36... Qh3+ 37. Bg2 Qh5 38. Bxc6) 37. Bg2 $16) 35. Qd2 Re5 {gives Black adequate counterplay.}) (33... Qc3 34. Bxc6 Nxf2 35. Qd4+ Qxd4 36. Rxd4 $16) (33... Qf6 {!} 34. Bf1 (34. Rf1 Ne5 35. Qxa6 Nf3+ 36. Bxf3 Qxf3 37. Qc4 Rh8 38. Qd4+ Kg8 39. Qd8+ {=}) 34... Rb8 {!?} (34... Re3 {?} 35. Qd4 Re4 36. Qxf6+ Nxf6 37. Bxa6 Rxb4 38. Ra1 $16) (34... Ne5 35. Bg2 {=}) 35. Qc5 Rxb4 36. Rd6 Qf3 37. Rd8 Kh7 $13) 1/2-1/2


