1. d4 {1)Kagan:Turnierpartien des Jahres 1919. S.4 Cyrus Lakdawala: 'ChessBase: '1)Kagan:Turnierpartien des Jahres 1919. S.4''} d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 Nbd7 4. f3 {Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Who would have guessed that it was Réti, godfather of the hypermoderns, who employed the very first pure Veresov? ''Who would have guessed that it was Réti, godfather of the hypermoderns, who employed the very first pure Veresov?  ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Who would have guessed that it was Réti, godfather of the hypermoderns, who employed the very first pure Veresov? '''} h6 5. Bh4 ({I recently tested the rarely-played} 5. Bf4 $5 {in an ICC blitz game, which continued} c5 6. e4 cxd4 7. Qxd4 e5 $6 {(unsound, but very difficult to meet in a blitz game)} 8. Bxe5 Bc5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Qxd5 ({the safer} 10. Qd2 $5 {also denies Black full compensation since} Qb6 $2 {is met by the simple} 11. Na4 $1) 10... Qb6 11. Nge2 $2 (11. O-O-O $3 {refutes Black's sac after} Bxg1 12. Bb5 Be3+ 13. Kb1 O-O 14. Bxd7 Rd8 15. Bxc8 $3 Rxd5 16. Nxd5 Qc5 17. Bxb7 Rf8 18. Nxf6+ {and White's knight, rook and four pawns outweigh Black's lone queen}) 11... Bf2+ 12. Kd1 O-O {and in C.Lakdawala-'Zq', Internet blitz 2010, Black had full compensation in the form of his lead in development, White's harassed king, and his domination of the dark squares.}) 5... e6 6. e4 Be7 {Cyrus Lakdawala: '?!' '?!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'This move is played all the time by Black, but it simply leads to a rotten French Defence, with his knight m'This move is played all the time by Black, but it simply leads to a rotten French Defence, with his knight misplaced on d7. ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '?!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'This move is played all the time by Black, but it simply leads to a rotten French Defence, with his knight misplaced on d7.''' isplaced on d7.'} ({Perhaps Black should risk} 6... dxe4 $5 7. fxe4 Bb4 8. e5 g5 9. Bg3 Nd5 10. Nge2 c5 11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. Nxc3 Ne3 13. Qd2 cxd4 14. Nb5 Qb6 15. Nd6+ Kf8 {and now, instead of} 16. Rc1 $5 {as in F.Cottegnie-R.Cardoso, correspondence 2004,} ({White might play the safer} 16. c3 $1 dxc3 17. Qxc3 Nd5 18. Qd2 Qe3+ 19. Qxe3 Nxe3 20. Rc1 {when his development lead and open files give him more than enough compensation for the pawn in the queenless middlegame.})) 7. e5 Nh5 (7... Ng8 8. Bf2 Bb4 9. f4 Ne7 10. Nf3 {leaves Black tangled.}) 8. Bxe7 Qxe7 9. g3 {Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Preparing to build his centre with f4. Meanwhile, Black's knight floats in outer space on h5. ''Preparing to build his centre with f4. Meanwhile, Black's knight floats in outer space on h5.  ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Preparing to build his centre with f4. Meanwhile, Black's knight floats in outer space on h5. '''} O-O 10. f4 g6 11. Qd2 {Cyrus Lakdawala: 'White has achieved a wonderful version of the French Defence. ''White has achieved a wonderful version of the French Defence.  ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'White has achieved a wonderful version of the French Defence. '''} Ng7 12. Nf3 c5 13. Bh3 {Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Playing for the f5 pawn break. ''Playing for the f5 pawn break.  ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Playing for the f5 pawn break. '''} Kh7 14. O-O (14. O-O-O $1 {and then continuing as he did in the game looks grim for Black.}) 14... cxd4 15. Nxd4 a6 16. Rae1 b5 (16... h5 {only stalls White's plan of g4:} 17. Bg2 b5 18. h3 {and g4 follows.}) 17. g4 {Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'The breakthrough f5'The breakthrough f5 is coming.  ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'The breakthrough f5 is coming. ''' is coming. '} Bb7 18. f5 $14 {Cyrus Lakdawala: 'ChessBase: '''} Qg5 {Cyrus Lakdawala: '?!' '?!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Fearing for his king, Black bails out into a'Fearing for his king, Black bails out into a rancid ending. ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '?!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Fearing for his king, Black bails out into a rancid ending.''' rancid ending.'} ({Cyrus Lakdawala: 'He probably should have taken his chances in the line''He probably should have taken his chances in the line ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'He probably should have taken his chances in the line'''} 18... Qh4 19. Rf3 gxf5 20. gxf5 Rg8 21. Kh1 Nc5 {. Even here though, White's attacking chances clearly trump Black's ability to counterattack against the somewhat exposed position of White's king.}) 19. Qxg5 hxg5 20. f6 Ne8 21. Re3 (21. Rf3) (21. Nb1 b4 22. Nd2 $16 {z.B.} Nc7 23. N2f3 Kh6 24. Re3 Nb5 25. Nxb5 axb5 26. Ra1 Ra4 27. b3 Ra3 28. Bg2 Rfa8 29. Nd4 $16) 21... Rh8 (21... b4) 22. Rd1 ({Retaining the bind over the materialistic} 22. Nf3 $5 Kg8 23. Nxg5 d4 24. Rd3 Nxe5 25. Rxd4 Rc8 {which offers Black some counterplay for the pawn.}) 22... Kg8 23. a3 $2 {Cyrus Lakdawala: '??' '??' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Careless.'Careless. ChessBase: '?' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '??' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Careless.''' '} (23. Bg2) (23. Bf1 {keeps Black totally tied up.}) 23... Rc8 $2 {Cyrus Lakdawala: '??' '??' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Laissez faire?'Laissez faire? ChessBase: '?' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '??' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Laissez faire?''' '} ({Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Both Grandmasters overlook the simple''Both Grandmasters overlook the simple ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Both Grandmasters overlook the simple'''} 23... Nxe5 {Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' '!''ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!'''} 24. Rxe5 Rxh3 $17 {Cyrus Lakdawala: 'which leaves White down a pawn and overextended.''which leaves White down a pawn and overextended. ChessBase: '' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'which leaves White down a pawn and overextended.'''}) 24. Bf1 $16 {Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Now he sees the threat. ''Now he sees the threat.  ChessBase: '' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'Now he sees the threat. '''} Nexf6 {Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'A temporary piece sac to mix it up. Possibly Réti, a habitual time trouble addict, may have been low on the clock at this point. Tartakower's sac gives him practic'A temporary piece sac to mix it up. Possibly Réti, a habitual time trouble addict, may have been low on the clock at this point. Tartakower's sac gives him practical chances.  ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' Cyrus Lakdawala: 'A temporary piece sac to mix it up. Possibly Réti, a habitual time trouble addict, may have been low on the clock at this point. Tartakower's sac gives him practical chances. ''' al chances. '} 25. exf6 e5 26. Nf3 {Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' '!''ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!'''} (26. Ndxb5 $6 {allows Black back into the game after} axb5 27. Bxb5 Nxf6 28. Rxe5 Rh4 $1 {and Black is still kicking.}) 26... d4 27. Nxd4 {Cyrus Lakdawala: '?' '?''ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '?'''} (27. Nxe5 $142 {Cyrus Lakdawala: '!' '!''ChessBase: '' ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '!'''} Nxe5 (27... dxe3 28. Rxd7 $18) 28. Rxe5 dxc3 29. bxc3 Bf3 30. Rd4 (30. Rd6 Rxc3 31. Bd3 Rxa3 32. Bxg6 $1 {and Fritz announces a forced mate in 21 moves, while Rybka disputes this and claims a mate in 10. Obviously someone is not telling the truth here!}) 30... Rc6 (30... Rxc3 31. Re7 Rc8 32. c4 $18) 31. c4 $16) 27... exd4 28. Rxd4 Nxf6 $11 {Cyrus Lakdawala: 'ChessBase: '=''} 29. h3 Kg7 30. Bg2 {Cyrus Lakdawala: '?!' '?!''ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: '?!'''} (30. a4 $1 {was White's last chance to continue the pressure.}) 30... Bxg2 31. Kxg2 Rhd8 {Cyrus Lakdawala: 'A lucky escape for Black. Summary: One of the great trade secrets of Veresov practitioners is to con unsuspecting opponents into bad versions of the French Defence. You will see this pattern over and over again in this book.''A lucky escape for Black. Summary: One of the great trade secrets of Veresov practitioners is to con unsuspecting opponents into bad versions of the French Defence. You will see this pattern over and over again in this book. ChessBase: 'Cyrus Lakdawala: 'A lucky escape for Black. Summary: One of the great trade secrets of Veresov practitioners is to con unsuspecting opponents into bad versions of the French Defence. You will see this pattern over and over again in 