1. e4 {1)Tenner,O in den Münchner Neuesten Nachrichten 2)DWS 1915,S.10,13(Tablle). 8Spieler. Doppelrundig. 1.Spielmann 11,5/14 2.Kaufmann 11,0/14 3.-4.Reti und Spielmann je 8,5/14 5.Albin 7/14} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 ({The pure Berlin approach, although} 4... Bc5 {is a major alternative which can also be reached via the Classical Defence (1 e4 e5 2 Nf3 Nc6 3 Bb5 Bc5 4 0-0 Nf6); hence it is often called the Classical Berlin. Then} 5. c3 {is the most popular move, intending to build a powerful centre. Naturally} Nxe4 {must be the critical response after which White has to make a choice:} 6. Z0 ({. Emms's main recommendation in his generally excellent 'Easy Guide to the Ruy Lopez' is} 6. Qe2 Bxf2+ 7. Kh1 (7. Rxf2 Nxf2 8. Kxf2 f6 {is not to be recommended: for example, D.Wood-D.McMahon, London 1995, continued} 9. d4 O-O 10. Bxc6 dxc6 11. dxe5 fxe5 12. Qxe5 Bg4 {when Black had a decisive lead in development and the position of the white king was not at all safe}) 7... d5 8. c4 {'which is a direct attempt at a refutation of Black's play' (Emms). The problem that I have with this recommendation is that while Emms does analyse all kind of moves, he does not examine the critical} Be6 $5 {. After} 9. d3 Ng3+ 10. hxg3 Bxg3 11. Bg5 f6 12. Bh4 Bxh4 13. Nxh4 O-O 14. Bxc6 bxc6 {Black had a decent position and good compensation in A.Kuthan-W.Krpelan, Austrian League 2005.}) (6. d4 {seems more challenging. In return for the pawn, White will get a long lasting initiative: for example,} exd4 7. cxd4 Be7 8. d5 Nb8 ({or} 8... Nd6 9. Ba4 Na5 10. Bc2 b6 11. Qd3 Nab7 12. Re1 {and Black could hardly move in M.Kaminski-D.McMahon, London 1994}) 9. Re1 Nd6 10. Bg5 f6 11. Bd3 $1 fxg5 12. Nxg5 g6 13. Qf3 Rf8 14. Qh3 c6 15. Nxh7 Qa5 {and now in D.Bellizzi-V.Levenson, New York 1991, the fastest win was} 16. Qe3 $1 {.})) 5. d4 Be7 ({Should Black detest the main lines of the Berlin Defence he could play} 5... a6 {, after which play most likely transposes to the Open Spanish, which is examined in some detail in Chapter 39.}) ({However, Black's main move is} 5... Nd6 {, as we will see in our next game.}) 6. Qe2 {Christoph Scheerer: '!' Christoph Scheerer: 'Alternatively:'} (6. d5 {is premature:} Nd6 7. Nc3 ({'NCO' claims a slight edge for White after} 7. Be2 e4 8. dxc6 exf3 9. cxb7 Bxb7 10. Bxf3 {, but I'm not particularly impressed}) 7... Nxb5 $1 8. Nxb5 a6 9. dxc6 ({better is} 9. Nc3 {, even though after} Nb8 10. Nxe5 d6 11. Nf3 O-O 12. Bf4 Bg4 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Nd7 15. Rfe1 Bf6 {Black has solved nearly all of his problems}) 9... axb5 10. cxb7 Bxb7 11. Nxe5 d6 12. Nf3 O-O {and it is Black who is better due to his pair of bishops.}) (6. Re1 Nd6 7. Bxc6 dxc6 8. dxe5 Nf5 {is an improved version of the Berlin Endgame for Black as he has not lost the right to castle.}) 6... Nd6 ({Instead} 6... d5 $6 {tries to maintain the knight in the centre, but White's slight lead in development enables him to create nasty threats after} 7. Nxe5 Bd7 8. Bxc6 {and now:} Z0 ({. After} 8... bxc6 9. Re1 {Black cannot castle in view of 10 f3 followed by 11 Nxd7 winning a piece. That leaves} Kf8 (9... Nf6 10. Bg5 Ng8 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 13. Nc3 f6 14. Na4 {was considered to be the refutation of 6...d5 by Curt von Bardeleben and Jacques Mieses in their 1894 'Lehrbuch des Schachspiels'}) 10. Nc3 {, but after} Nxc3 11. bxc3 Be8 12. Qa6 {White was clearly better in E.Lasker-T.Scheve, Berlin (simul) 1891.}) (8... Bxc6 9. Re1 Bd7 (9... O-O $2 10. f3 {followed by 11 Nxc6 and 12 Qxe7 again wins a piece}) 10. Bf4 c6 ({or} 10... O-O $5 11. Nd2 $1 ({this time Black can respond to} 11. f3 {with} Bg5 {when things are not so clear}) 11... Nxd2 12. Nxd7 $1 Re8 13. Qb5 Nc4 14. Qxd5 Nxb2 15. Rab1 c6 16. Qf5 {is good for White according to Emms}) 11. Nd2 Nxd2 12. Bxd2 {and Black has problems completing his development, such as after} Be6 13. Nxf7 $1 Bxf7 14. Bb4 {.})) 7. Bxc6 bxc6 ({No better is} 7... dxc6 $2 {on account of} 8. dxe5 Nf5 9. Rd1 Bd7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Ne4 {when White enjoyed a commanding position in F.Gheorghiu-T.Ujtumen, Sochi 1964.}) 8. dxe5 Nb7 ({After} 8... Nf5 {, White has} 9. Qe4 $1 {when Black has to make at least some positional concessions. T.Zatulovskaya-S.Kruchonok, Moscow 1979, continued} g6 10. Nd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 O-O (11... d5 12. Bh6 $1 {keeps the black king in the centre; in the game P.Schlosser-L.Keitlinghaus, Münster 1992, the king went to the queenside with} Be6 13. Nd2 c5 14. Qa4+ Qd7 15. Qa6 c6 16. Rad1 Qc7 17. b3 Qb6 18. Qe2 O-O-O {, but} 19. Nf3 Rhe8 20. Ng5 Rd7 21. Nxf7 $1 {gave White a significant advantage}) 12. Bh6 Re8 13. Nc3 d5 14. exd6 Bf6 15. Qc4 {with an edge.}) 9. Nc3 O-O (9... Nc5 {is also playable, but} 10. Nd4 O-O ({inadvisable is} 10... Ba6 $2 11. Qg4 $1 Bxf1 12. Qxg7 Rf8 13. Kxf1 Ne6 14. Nf5 {and the black position was a complete mess in J.Showalter-S.Tarrasch, Vienna 1898}) 11. Rd1 Qe8 12. Nf5 f6 13. Qg4 Ne6 14. Bh6 {left White with the initiative in S.Winawer-J.Zukertort, Paris 1878.}) 10. Nd4 {Christoph Scheerer: 'This move is aimed at preventing the liberating ...d7-d5. As Reuben Fine noted in his 'Ideas behind the Chess Openings', 'White has a tangible advantage because of Black's development'.'} Bc5 11. Rd1 Bxd4 12. Rxd4 d5 13. exd6 cxd6 14. b4 $1 {Christoph Scheerer: '. This is the key move in White's strategy, which leaves Black's knight suffering on b7. The game eventually ended in a draw after Schlechter made a grave mistake in the endgame, but nevertheless the Berlin Defence soon went out of fashion for a long time. The only subsequent game in the 'Mega Database 2008' which features this position was P.Keres-W.Unzicker, Hamburg 1956; suffice to say that Unzicker was soundly defeated in that game.'} Qf6 15. Be3 Bf5 16. Rad1 a6 17. g4 Qg6 18. Kh1 Bd7 19. h3 f5 20. Qd3 Qf7 21. Rf4 Qe6 (21... g5 22. Rg1 $1 gxf4 23. gxf5+ Kh8 (23... Qg7 24. Rxg7+ Kxg7 25. Bd4+ Kf7 26. f6 $18) 24. Bd4+ $18) (21... a5 22. a3 axb4 23. axb4 Qg6) (21... Qe8 22. g5 a5) 22. g5 Rfe8 (22... a5) 23. a3 Re7 (23... a5) 24. Kh2 $14 Qg6 25. h4 Be6 26. Ne2 c5 27. c4 cxb4 28. axb4 Rc7 29. Nc3 Qf7 30. Nd5 Bxd5 31. Rxf5 Qe6 32. Rxd5 Rf8 33. Kg3 h5 $1 34. gxh6 gxh6 35. Kh2 Rg7 36. Rg1 Rff7 37. Rxg7+ Rxg7 38. Qf5 Qxf5 39. Rxf5 Rg4 40. Rf4 Rxf4 41. Bxf4 a5 42. bxa5 $2 (42. b5 $18) (42. Bd2 $18) 42... Nxa5 43. Bxh6 Nxc4 44. Kg3 Kh7 45. Bf4 d5 46. Kf3 Kg6 47. Ke2 $14 Na5 1/2-1/2


