{[%evp 20,61,-29,-24,0,0,4,0,13,0,0,0,0,0,87,94,79,91,85,90,84,56,102,104,108,108,102,102,114,102,391,391,391,360,388,388,406,367,496,507,1706,1681,1583,1582] C55: Two Knights: 4 d3, 4 d4 exd4 5 e5 and Max Lange Attack Sources: Tartakower & du Mont, 500 Master Games of Chess, pp. 53-54; Tartakower, My Best Games of Chess: 1905-1954 pp. 77-80. All comments are Tartakower's unless otherwise noted. The well-known sacrifice at f-7 has won many games. The combination in the following game contains some special finesses.A match extending to 6 points took place between Réti and myself at Vienna in October, 1920. This amtch was won by me with 4 wins, no losses and 4 draws (i.e. 6 points to 2), and the events leading to it were quite intriguing.  Radiant victor in the first great international tournament after the war, at Goeteborg (Sweden) in 1920, Réti deemed he could, at length, take substantial revenge against me since he had previously, in 1919, lost a short match (+3,-2,=5 in my favor) and drawn a second one (+2, -2, =2).  How can one explain that, this time, he had to see his hopes fly away and, once again, admit defeat -- and this even without having succeeded in winning a single game? This enigma can be solved by saying that (1) psychologically, one can never trust in the appearances of chess form, which can change from one moment to another; and that (2), technically, Réti was much less a match player, which requires a steady and resolute temperament, and more a brilliant tournament player, in which the theoretical investigation often procured him precious points.  Here, then is the first game of our 1920 match:} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Nc3 {Although this move, because of the following reply, is in bad odor with omniscient theory, it is quite playable.} ({Another move that has "bad press," in a rather ill-deserved way, is} 4. Ng5 {1-0 Tartakower,S-Bogoljubow,E Bad Homburg 1927 (1.2) (emn Stumperzug! — a beginner's move — according to Dr. Tarrasch's dogmatic assessment). In reality, the skirmishes it provokes are still far from completely explored by theory, and I will return to it when dealing with a later game.}) 4... Nxe4 5. Nxe4 ({After} 5. Bxf7+ Kxf7 6. Nxe4 d5 7. Neg5+ Kg8 {White's chances of getting anything out of the position are negligible.}) 5... d5 6. Bd3 {Still retaining this most valuable bishop.} ({Less good is} 6. Bb5 {because of 6....} dxe4 7. Nxe5 Qg5 {with many possibilities such as} 8. Nxc6 ({or} 8. d4 Qxg2) 8... Qxb5 {with advantage to Black.}) 6... dxe4 ({Better than complicating matters by} 6... f5 {although it wins back the piece, because after} 7. Nc3 e4 8. Bb5 exf3 9. Qxf3 {, etc., the disposition of White's forces is greatly superior.}) 7. Bxe4 Bd6 ({The logical development. If} 7... Bc5 8. O-O f6 9. c3 O-O 10. Qc2 Kh8 {(Also to respond to 11.xh7 with 11....f5)} 11. d4 $1 {and White has the attack.}) 8. d4 ({White must hasten to disturb the central zone for, if he still plays a waiting game by} 8. O-O {there follows} Bg4 {with the threat of 9....f5, when Black has seized the initiative.}) 8... exd4 ({Inferior is} 8... Nxd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Qxd4 O-O 11. Be3 Qe7 12. O-O-O Be5 13. Qd3 ({if} 13. Qc4 Qf6 {with counter-attack}) 13... f5 14. Bd5+ Be6 15. Rhe1 Kh8 16. Bxe6 Qxe6 17. Kb1 $1 ({better than the precipitate continuation in Chigorin-Forgacs, Nuremberg 1906:} 17. Bc5 Rfe8 18. Kb1 Qc6 {0-1 Chigorin,M-Forgacs,L DSB Kongress-15 Meisterturnier 1906 (10) when Black wins a pawn.}) 17... Qf6 18. Qb3 {and White has rather the better game. Therefore, the text move is superior to 8...xd4, though the latter is recommended by many a theorist as leading to equality.}) 9. Bxc6+ {This exchange is the only continuation that assures White the domination of the center for some time. 9....} bxc6 10. Qxd4 {"Here I am, and here I'll stay" would seem to be the white queen's motto.} ({If} 10. Nxd4 O-O {and Black goes over to the attack.}) 10... O-O 11. O-O ({A more solid line than} 11. Be3 {which would have, in view of castling queenside, ignored the danger of the open b-file.}) 11... Bf5 ({Black can trouble his adversary more by} 11... c5 12. Qc3 Bb7 $1 13. b3 Qd7 14. Bb2 f6 15. Rad1 Qf5 16. Qc4+ Kh8 17. Nh4 Qf4 ({if} 17... Qh5 18. h3 Rae8 19. Rde1 Bd5 20. Qg4 Qxg4 21. hxg4 Re4 22. f3 Rxe1 23. Rxe1 Bg3 24. Rd1 Bxb3 25. cxb3 Bxh4 26. Ba3 {and White regains his pawn while maintaining a practically decisive advantage in the structure of the queenside pawns.}) 18. Qxf4 Bxf4 19. Rd2 {and the activity of Black's two bishops compensate somewhat for the weak points in his position.}) 12. b3 c5 ({Liquidation of the position by} 12... Bxc2 13. Bb2 Qf6 14. Qxf6 gxf6 15. Bxf6 {would hardly be desirable for Black.}) 13. Qc3 Qd7 14. Ba3 {The versatility of this bishop (which seemed rather intended for development on the long a1-h8 diagonal), renders great service to White.} ({In fact,} 14. Bb2 {is useless because of 14....} f6) 14... Qb5 15. Rfe1 Rfe8 16. Ne5 {Taking possession of the important strong post. 16....} Re6 {A trap (which hopes for 17.f3? ae8 18.xf5 xe5 when Black wins) which, nevertheless, ensnares Black himself!} ({Relatively best was} 16... Re7 17. Nc4 (17. Qf3 Rae8 18. Nd3 {achieves little}) 17... Rae8 {and Black can still put up a fight.}) 17. Nxf7 {White has scarcely entered (by means of the outpost maneuver of the previous move) the phase of the real middlegame (for all the previous moves merely served to mobilize his forces), when suddenly he wins a pawn in surprising fashion! Moral: you can never sufficiently protect the ominous f7 square! 17....} ({Incidentally, White avoids a trap:} 17. Qf3 {(attacking rook and bishop) 17....} Rae8 18. Qxf5 Bxe5 {and the tables are turned.}) 17... Rae8 ({There is no satisfactory move for, if} 17... Kxf7 18. Qf3 {this time genuinely attacking both the queen's rook and queen's bishop.}) ({And, if} 17... Rxe1+ 18. Rxe1 Re8 19. Ng5 ({better than} 19. Ne5 Bxc2 {though even then the continuation} 20. Qxc2 Bxe5 21. g3 Bd4 22. Qc4+ Qxc4 23. Rxe8+ Kf7 24. bxc4 Kxe8 25. Kg2 {would assure White an advantage}) 19... h6 ({or} 19... Bxc2 20. Qc4+ {with sudden death for Black}) 20. Nf3 {preserving his extra pawn, not to mention the compromised position of Black's king.}) 18. Rxe6 Rxe6 19. Bb2 {cf. the note to White's 14th move. 19....} Bf8 ({(1) No move is adequate, to wit:} 19... Kxf7 20. Qxg7+ Ke8 21. Qg8+ Bf8 (21... Kd7 22. Qf7+) (21... Ke7 22. Qg5+ {followed by xf5}) 22. Bg7 {and wins.}) ({(2)} 19... Rf6 20. Nh6+ $1 Kf8 21. Nxf5 {winning.}) ({(3)} 19... Rg6 20. Ne5 $1 ({here} 20. Nh6+ gxh6 21. Qh8+ Kf7 22. Re1 Qd7 {would lead only to a draw.}) 20... Rf6 ({or} 20... Bxe5 21. Qxe5 {dominating the board}) 21. Nc4 {and White maintains both his material and positional advantage.}) 20. Ng5 Rg6 21. Qf3 ({This confirms White's superiority because all strategic points are under control, whereas neither} 21. Qe5 {(or 21.d2)} Qd7) ({nor} 21. h4 Qc6 {would lead to much.}) 21... Qd7 {Warding off, at any rate, the enemy attack on the f7 and f5 squares.} ({There is no saving the game by} 21... Rxg5 22. Qd5+ Kh8 23. Qd8 h6 24. Qxf8+ Kh7 25. h4) ({Or by} 21... c4 {(relatively best)} 22. a4 Qc5 ({or} 22... Qa5 23. Bc3) ({or} 22... Qd7 23. Rd1 Rd6 24. Rxd6 Qxd6 25. Qe2 cxb3) 23. g4 Qe7 24. Qd5+ Be6 25. Nxe6 Qxe6 26. Qxe6+ Rxe6 27. Bc3 Re2 28. Rc1 g6 29. Kf1 {etc.}) 22. Rd1 Rd6 23. Rxd6 Qxd6 ({Evidently not} 23... cxd6 24. Qd5+ {etc.}) ({nor} 23... Bxd6 24. Qd5+ Kf8 25. Qa8+ Ke7 ({or} 25... Qe8 26. Bxg7+) ({or} 25... Qc8 26. Nxh7+) 26. Bxg7 {and White's material advantage is decisive.}) 24. h4 h6 ({Not} 24... Bxc2 25. Qb7 Kh8 26. Ne6 {and wins;}) ({nor} 24... Bg6 25. h5 Be8 26. Qe2 Bc6 27. Qc4+ ({and not} 27. Qe6+ Qxe6 28. Nxe6 Be8 29. Nxc7 Bxh5 {=}) 27... Qd5 ({if} 27... Bd5 28. Qd3) 28. Qxd5+ Bxd5 29. c4 {(preventing Black from undoubling his pawns) 29....} Bc6 30. f3 Be7 31. Ne4 {and the ending is automatically won for White.}) ({The lesser evil is, however,} 24... Qd7 {(so as to retain the good observation post on f5), but, even then, the continuation} 25. Qe2 h6 26. Nf3 Bd6 27. Ne5 Bxe5 28. Bxe5 ({if} 28. Qxe5 Qd1+ 29. Kh2 Qd6) 28... Qe7 29. Qc4+ Kh7 30. Bg3 {would assure White, despite the bishops of opposite colors, the domination of the field of battle.}) 25. Qxf5 hxg5 26. hxg5 Qd1+ 27. Kh2 Qh5+ 28. Kg3 {Black's faint hope of obtaining perpetual check vanishes. 28....} Bd6+ 29. Be5 Qe2 30. Bxd6 cxd6 31. g6 {Black resigns.} 1-0


