{Thomas Engqvist: '"He forgot everything, stick, hat, umbrella; above all, however, he would always leave behind him his traditional yellow leather briefcase, so that it was said of him: wherever Réti's briefcase is, there he himself is no longer to be found. It is therefore evidence of Réti's pre-existence." – Savielly Tartakower (Vienna 1924)  Savielly Tartakower (1887-1956) was born in Rostov-on-Don, the largest city in the south of Russia. After WWI he became a Polish citizen. He had a brilliant intellect and was not only a great chess player (ranked 3rd in the world in 1921, according to Chessmetrics) and a prolific writer of chess books; he was also a Doctor at Law, a screen writer, and a very well-known translator of Russian poetry into German and French. Like Réti he was representative of the hypermodern movement. His greatest contribution, 'The Hypermodern Game of Chess' ('Die hypermoderne Schachpartie'), contains 108 very well, originally annotated games. With impressive chapters like "The Doctrine of Weaknesses", many other insightful writings about the great players, and systematically covering a whole range of openings from the hypermodern era, it is just as important as Réti's and Nimzowitsch's classics and should be studied from cover to cover to gain the right feeling for the kind of chess that was played during this period of chess history. '} 1. e4 {1)Kagan:Turnierpartien des Jahres 1919. S.5 2)DSZ 1919,S.31 Thomas Engqvist: 'The most suitable move according to Tartakower, since it: (i) Enters the centre of battle without delay; (ii) Mobilizes the maximum of pieces (bishop, knight and queen); (iii) provides well-defined targets; and (iv) has therefore been subjected to thorough research since time immemorial. Fischer concurred, writing more succinctly: 'Best by test."'} c5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Tartakower opts for the Sicilian Defence, an opening with a good reputation. Sometimes, despite the fact that he knew everything, Tartakower did not play the openings that were considered the best. According to Réti, "it gives him pleasure to choose those that are considered weaker, so that he can reveal the shortcomings of the recognized theories wherever that is possible. Indeed, he has in this way contributed much to the revision of old dogmas."  '} 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 a6 4. g3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'White's game plan is the "accumulation of latent power", to use an expression from Tartakower. '} Nc6 ({N.Short-G.Kasparov, Tilburg 1991, continued with the logical} 4... b5 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. d3 d6 7. O-O Nd7 8. a3 Rc8 9. Bd2 Ngf6 10. Nh4 {and now} {and now} Qc7 {, defending the b7-bishop before playing ...Be7, was correct with a balanced game.} ({The immediate} 10... Be7 $2 {allowed the tactical trick} 11. e5 {with advantage to White, although Short did not subsequently play in the strongest way and the game was drawn after 25 moves.})) 5. Bg2 Nf6 ({I.Glek-N.Miezis, Porto San Giorgio 2000, saw the enterprising continuation} 5... g5 6. d3 h6 7. Be3 d6 8. h4 g4 {and here} 9. Nd2 {is best with an edge.}) 6. O-O Be7 7. e5 ({Objectively, the best course for White is probably} 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qc7 {, transposing to an Open Sicilian, specifically a standard line of the Kan Variation. After the text move, the game takes on an independent character while keeping the game closed.}) ({Alternatively,} 7. d3 {still emphasizes the accumulation of latent energy.}) 7... Ng4 8. Qe2 Qc7 9. Re1 d6 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} ({The correct way to attack the white centre is} 9... f6 10. exf6 Nxf6 {with an even game.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: What is the drawback to using the d-pawn? ANSWER:'} 10. exd6 Qxd6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The drawback is clearly seen here. The black queen is on an exposed square, so White can activate a knight on e4 or c4 for free.'} ({If Black instead replies} 10... Bxd6 {, it is possible to go for an immediate} 11. d4 $1 {and in some variations exploit the hanging knight on g4:} (11. Ne4 Be7 12. c3 {and d2-d4 is good too}) {Or if} 11... O-O {then} ({For example,} 11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 $2 13. Qxg4 Nxc2 {fails to} 14. Qa4+ b5 15. Qxc2 {and Black cannot regain the piece with} b4 {since the a8-rook is hanging.} (15... Z0)) 12. d5 $1 {and White has a clear advantage in all variations:} Nd4 (12... exd5 13. Nxd5) ({or} 12... Nb4 13. Ng5 $1) 13. Qd1 {.}) 11. d3 O-O 12. Ng5 ({The alternative manoeuvre} 12. Nd2 Nf6 13. Nc4 {is more precise, intending} Qd8 ({or} 13... Qc7 14. Bf4) ({Black can counter with} 13... Nd4 {, but after} 14. Qd1 Qd8 15. Bf4 {, White might follow with Na4 or a4-a5 on his next move, pressurizing the b6-square}) 14. Bxc6 {.}) 12... Nf6 13. Nce4 Qd8 {Thomas Engqvist: '!?' Thomas Engqvist: 'This is a little passive considering that Black has three more active options.'} ({a)} 13... Qc7 {looks more natural, but perhaps Tartakower wanted to prevent} 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Qe4 {which would not be playable with a queen on d8. After the forced} g6 {, White should be happy with the positional} 16. c3 {, claiming a slight advantage.} ({Note that the primitive attack} 16. Qh4 h5 17. g4 $2 {is easily countered by} Nd4 18. gxh5 Nxc2 19. hxg6 fxg6 {and the black queen defends the h7-square.})) ({b)} 13... Nd4 {might lead to} 14. Nxd6 (14. Qd1 $5 {keeps more pieces on the board with a slight advantage}) 14... Nxe2+ 15. Rxe2 Bxd6 16. b3 {and 17 Bb2 with a rather nagging edge for White in view of the fianchettoed bishops raking the long diagonals.}) ({c)} 13... Nxe4 14. Qxe4 $1 {is a little annoying; for example,} g6 ({giving the two bishops away with} 14... Bxg5 15. Bxg5 {is comfortable for White}) 15. Qh4 h5 16. g4 f6 (16... Qd4 {is answered by the cool} 17. h3 $1 {, followed by c2-c3 or Be3, driving the black queen to an awkward position}) 17. Ne4 Qd8 18. gxh5 $1 g5 19. Qg3 Nd4 20. f4 Nxc2 {and now the incredible quiet move in the middle of the combination, reminiscent of Rubinstein or Alekhine:} 21. Bd2 $3 Nxa1 22. Rxa1 {and White has a very strong attack, which can be developed with moves like f4xg5, Bc3 and h2-h4. A remarkable position. When you look at such variations it is more easily understandable why Tartakower preferred to put pressure on the g5-knight by withdrawing the queen to its original square.}) 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: Is it possible for White to turn his slight initiative into something tangible? '} 15. Qh5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'ANSWER: Before playing the knight to e4 Réti wants to provoke ...h7-h6. Whether this is to White's advantage, when looking at the concrete variations, is not clear. It is generally in the attacker's interest to provoke a weakening of the defensive pawn structure, and here it might enable a future sacrifice on h6 or even a g2-g4-g5 break in some positions. On the other hand, the white queen has moved already and was fulfilling a function on e2, as we will see.'} ({Instead,} 15. Ne4 Be7 ({there is no reason for Black to give up the bishop pair via} 15... Nd4 $6 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. Qd1) 16. c3 {leads a similar position, and without the drawback that occurs in the game, but of course without the provoked ...h7-h6 as well. It is a matter of taste whether one prefers to play this position or the actual one.}) ({Another option is} 15. Bxc6 Bxg5 16. Bxg5 Qxg5 17. Be4 {, removing two pairs of minor pieces from the board. In this case too White has a slight advantage: he can still use one outpost for his bishop, while Black's bishop has a harder time becoming active. White can improve his position with moves like f2-f4 and c2-c3, followed by doubling the rooks on the d-file, and a timely opening of the game with d3-d4.}) 15... h6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Practically forced.'} ({Giving up the bishop pair with} 15... Bxg5 16. Bxg5 Qb6 17. Rab1 {is far less appetizing, when attacking manoeuvres like Re4-h4 are in the air.}) 16. Ne4 ({Here} 16. Bxc6 hxg5 17. Be4 g6 {is nothing special for White.}) 16... Be7 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: How does White proceed? '} 17. c3 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'With the queen on h5 this is illogical, since the d3-pawn becomes a target.'} ({ANSWER: It is better to put pressure on the c5-pawn with} 17. Be3 {.} Nb4 {is probably best, forcing the queen back to defend the c2-pawn. Nevertheless, after} ({Then} 17... f5 $5 {is answered by} 18. Nd2 {and a timely Nc4} ({not} 18. Nxc5 $2 {since} f4 19. Bxf4 Rf5 {wins a piece})) ({and} 17... Nd4 18. Rac1 {does not solve Black's problems either.}) 18. Qe2 Qc7 19. c4 $1 {, preventing ...Nd5, White's pieces are more active and the pressure on the c5-pawn remains. The raking bishops are tremendous in this position. It is not clear why Réti refrained from this set-up, but we have seen this peculiar trait before. He sometimes delayed the development of his queen's bishop even when it was more logical to develop it!}) 17... f5 {Thomas Engqvist: '!'} ({The immediate} 17... Qxd3 $2 {runs into} 18. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 19. Rad1 $1 {a strong intermezzo;} ({compare} 19. Qxh6 Rd8 20. Nf6+ Bxf6 21. Be4 Qd2 22. Bh7+ Kh8 23. Qxf6+ Kxh7 24. Qxf7+ Kh8 25. Qf6+ Kh7 26. Re4 Qh6 27. Rh4 Qxh4 28. Qxh4+ {, which prolongs the game unnecessarily}) 19... Qb5 20. Qxh6 Ne5 21. Nd6 Bxd6 22. Rxd6 Ng6 23. Be4 Qe8 ({or} 23... Qxb2 24. Rd3 $1 {and Black's queen cannot defend the kingside}) 24. Bxg6 $1 fxg6 25. Re4 {and White wins by transferring the rook along the fourth rank to g4 or h4.}) 18. Nd2 ({Note that} 18. Bxh6 $2 {is met by the zwischenzug} Qe8 $1 {, when two white pieces are hanging.}) 18... Qxd3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is White's strongest continuation here? '} 19. Nf3 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} ({ANSWER: To strengthen the grip on e5 it is more logical to play} 19. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 20. Nf3 {, followed by Bf4 or Ne5. Nevertheless, it is not to everyone's taste to surrender a fianchettoed bishop even when it is objectively good!}) 19... Qc4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!?' Thomas Engqvist: 'This just wastes time, since the queen was better where it was. '} ({Developing with} 19... Bd7 {is more natural. We do not know Réti's intention, but} 20. Nh4 $1 Be8 21. Ng6 {appears to offer White just about enough compensation for the pawn deficit.}) 20. Bf4 ({Tartakower was obviously hoping for} 20. Bxh6 $4 {, when} Qg4 $1 {would have decided the game in a swift manner.}) 20... Bd7 21. Bf1 ({Another possibility is} 21. Nd2 Qb5 22. a4 Qxb2 23. Rab1 Qa2 24. Rxb7 Be8 25. Qe2 {with advantage to White, whose pieces are far more active than his opponent's. The immediate threats are Rxe7, Bxc6, Rc7, and Qxe6+.}) 21... Qa4 ({Worse is} 21... Be8 22. Bxc4 Bxh5 23. Bxe6+ Kh8 24. Nd2 {, when White has regained the pawn with a tremendous bishop on e6.}) 22. b3 Qa5 ({Instead,} 22... Qa3 {just puts the queen out of play. After} 23. Bc4 Rf6 24. Ne5 Be8 25. Qh3 Nd8 26. Be2 Qa5 27. Nc4 Qb5 28. Rad1 ({better than} 28. Nd6 $6 Qc6 29. Nxe8 Qxe8 {, when White is only slightly better}) 28... Qc6 29. Rd3 {, planning Bf3, White has more than sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 23. Bc4 Rf6 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} ({The seemingly greedy} 23... Qxc3 {is best. After} 24. Be5 (24. Ne5 Nxe5 25. Bxe5 Qa5 26. Re3 {also gives White enough compensation for the pawns}) 24... Nxe5 25. Nxe5 Be8 (25... Bc8 $2 {is too passive; Black has no development and is clearly worse after} 26. Ng6 Rf7 27. Rad1) 26. Bxe6+ Kh8 27. Bf7 Bxf7 28. Nxf7+ Kg8 29. Nxh6+ gxh6 30. Qg6+ Qg7 31. Qxg7+ Kxg7 32. Rxe7+ Rf7 33. Re5 {, White has regained the material with the superior position, and has some slight chances to convert the rook ending into a win.}) 24. Ne5 Be8 (24... Nxe5 25. Bxe5 Rf7 26. Rad1 Bc8 27. Qg6 {does not solve Black's problems at all.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is the problem with Black's last move? ANSWER:'} 25. Nxc6 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'With his queen also en prise on a5, there is no time for Black to capture the white queen. '} bxc6 ({Unfortunately,} 25... Bxc6 {fails to} 26. Rxe6 {with a decisive attack; for example,} Rxe6 27. Bxe6+ Kh7 ({or} 27... Kh8 28. Be5 $1) 28. Qxf5+ Kh8 29. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 30. Qe5+ {and so on.}) 26. Qf3 Bd7 27. Rad1 Ra7 28. Be5 Rf7 29. Rxd7 Rxd7 30. Bxe6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Black's position collapses.'} Bf8 31. Qxf5 ({One can imagine how much Réti must have enjoyed deciding whether to play the text move or} 31. Qxc6 {.}) 31... Qxa2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'This is a normal case of desperation.'} 32. Re3 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: '. Black resigned, since 33 Rf3 cannot be prevented.'} 1-0


