{[%evp 13,108,-27,13,0,0,-7,0,-41,-19,-29,-22,-32,15,28,38,21,56,38,36,0,0,0,0,-37,-50,-32,-27,-39,-35,-158,-166,-157,-162,-144,-164,-137,-145,-148,-198,-157,-169,-198,-193,-526,-559,-566,-597,-591,-587,-543,-553,-602,-603,-594,-599,-589,-586,-667,-542,-535,-535,-553,-492,-486,-492,-492,-490,-485,-467,-448,-413,-492,-492,-515,-507,-508,-505,-508,-501,-489,-472,-4927,-4918,-4914,-4910,-2465,-1860,-5085,-4798,-29984,-29985,-29985,-29986,-29986,-29987,-29985,-29986] C50: Hungarian Defence and Giuoco Pianissimo Source: Tartakower & du Mont, 500 Master Games of Chess, pp. 25-26. All comments are Tartakower's unless otherwise noted. It will be seen in the following game that Black, by measures both wise and patient, throws off the hostile yoke (12 ....h8 ; and 14 ....g8), himself gains territory (13 ....c4 and 22 ....c4), and finally takes up the offensive (27 ....f5). It is, therefore, the power of sound manceuvring which we shall see illustrated.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Bb6 7. h3 {Instead of this waiting move, the most effective plan here is 7.d2, in preparation for 0-0-0. 7....} Be6 8. Bb5 {Leads to greater complications than 8.b3. 8....} O-O 9. Bxc6 {This exchange makes the black centre more compact. White should have delayed it by first playing 9.g5. 9....} bxc6 10. Bg5 Qe7 11. O-O h6 12. Bh4 Kh8 {Methodically preparing the unpinning of the knight by ....g8 and then g5. At this stage 12 .... g5 would have been premature, because of 13.xg5.} 13. d4 Bc4 14. Re1 Rg8 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Bg3 Rad8 17. Qc1 Nd7 18. Nd1 f6 19. Ne3 Bf7 ({A sound manoeuvre. For after,} 19... Be6 20. Nf5 Bxf5 21. exf5 {the games would tend to equalise, whereas now Black can rely on his bishops. (An old motto says: "The future belongs to him who has the bishops.")}) 20. Nf5 {Although this move maintains White's initiative for some time to come, certain strategic weaknesses in his position will gradually make themselves felt, namely, the restricted bishop, his weak f2 square, the queen forced back behind the lines, and his adversary's control of the open d-file. 20....} Qf8 {The queen escapes whilst parrying the threat 21.xh6.} 21. c3 {As this move—intending to prepare a demonstration on the queen side—weakens the position in the centre (d3),} ({it would have been preferable to play} 21. b4 c5 22. c3 {(preventing 21 ....c5), although even then Black would obtain the better game by 21....c5 (not 21....xb4, on account of 22.xh6); 22.c3 h6, followed by .... g6.} Kh7) 21... Nc5 {This threatens 22 ....d3, and at the same time ties the adverse  at e1 to the protection of the pawn on e4.} 22. Qc2 ({White assumes the defensive. The violent attempt} 22. Nxe5 fxe5 23. Bxe5 {(threatening 24.xh6#) would fail because Black would reply, not 23....h7 24.xg7 xg7 25.xh6 g8 26.h4, etc. but 23....} Bg6 24. Qxh6+ Bh7 {etc., a sufficient defence.}) 22... Bc4 23. Nd2 ({The only way of guarding the pawn, for if} 23. Red1 Rxd1+ {, winning either the pawn on e4} 24. Qxd1 Nxe4 {or the pawn on a2, 24.xd1 xa2.}) 23... Bd3 24. Qc1 g6 {At the right moment the opponent's only active piece is driven back.} 25. Nh4 Ba6 {A vacating manoeuvre: the knight is enabled to settle on the dominant square at d3.} 26. Qc2 Nd3 27. Red1 {[#]} f5 {With the persuasive threat 28 ....f4.} 28. a4 ({A desperate attempt at salvation, for if} 28. Rf1 {there follows} f4 29. Bh2 Nxf2 30. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 31. Kxf2 Qc5+ 32. Ke1 Qe3+ 33. Kd1 Qf2 34. Nhf3 Be2+ 35. Kc1 Bxf3 36. gxf3 Qxh2 {and wins}) 28... f4 29. a5 Bc5 30. Kh2 ({The loss of a piece cannot be avoided: 30 P-Kt4, B-K2.} 30. b4 Be7) 30... fxg3+ 31. fxg3 Qf2 {The threat is 32....e1; 33.xe1 xd3 34.xe1.} 32. Rf1 Ne1 {Embarras de richesses Black wins the exchange as well: 33.xf2 xc2; and both the White rooks are attacked.} 33. Raxe1 Bxf1 34. Rxf1 Qxd2 {And wins. (Editor's note: Tartakower ends his comments here but the game went on for another 20 moves.)} 35. Qb3 Rdf8 36. Rxf8 Bxf8 37. Qb7 Bc5 38. Qxc7 Qd6 39. Qf7 Rg7 40. Qc4 Be3 41. Nf3 Re7 42. h4 h5 43. b3 Kg7 44. Qe2 Bh6 45. b4 Rd7 46. Qc4 Rf7 47. Qa6 Qd1 48. Ng5 Bxg5 49. hxg5 Qg4 50. Qxc6 Qxg5 51. b5 h4 52. gxh4 Qxh4+ 53. Kg1 Qf2+ 54. Kh2 Rf4 {White resigns.} 0-1


