{Perennial Favorite  Back in 1933, when Fred Reinfeld and I were enthusiastically analyzing thousands of master games to find The Fifty Greatest Chess Games Ever Played, one of the undisputed choices on any of the lists (and we made many of them) was the magni ficent game won by Réti from Bogol yubov in 1923. In our introduction to the game, we had this to say of it: “It is well known that an attack undertaken without adequate means must result in loss of the initiative, if parried properly. This is demon strated most convincingly in the present game – the chief interest of which lies in the harmonious simplicity of Réti’s beautifully-timed play. The unusual movements of the Knight add a certain piquancy to Black’s artistic conduct of the game. Réti’s play is versatile: he per forms many tasks here, and per forms them well. He thrusts back a premature attack, he demonstrates the power of a compact center, he steadily cuts down his opponent’s mobility, he maneuvers his Knights with exquisite skill, he obtains and exploits a passed Pawn according to plan.” Today, having played through and analyzed thousands of games in the thirty-year interval, the game be tween Bogolyubov and Réti is still, in my opinion, one of the most beautiful and instructive ever played.} 1. e4 {This game appears in both books. I put it here only once (hence the "missing game")} e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 ({One would expect Bogolyubov to adopt the Alekhine attack, with which he has won some brilliant games} 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 Bxg5 7. hxg5 Qxg5 8. Nh3 Qe7 9. Qg4 g6 10. Nf4) 4... Nfd7 5. Qg4 c5 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc5d4,Yb8c6] Black must attack the center in this line of the French Defense. The immediate threat is 6 … cxd4 7 ♕xd4, ♘c6, winning the e-Pawn.} 6. Nb5 {In his anxiety to attack, Bogolyubov violates opening principles. Having developed the Queen prematurely, he now moves the Knight twice in the opening.} cxd4 $1 7. Nf3 (7. Nd6+ Bxd6 8. Qxg7 Bxe5 {protects the Rook, and wins a piece for Black.}) 7... Nc6 8. Nd6+ Bxd6 9. Qxg7 Bxe5 $1 {Repulsing the attack} 10. Nxe5 Qf6 $1 {Saves the Rook, forces an ex change of Queens, and puts an end to the demonstration.} 11. Qxf6 Nxf6 12. Bb5 {White must devote a few moves now to regaining the Pawn he lost.} Bd7 13. Nf3 Ne4 $1 14. O-O f6 {Building up a powerful center - Threatens to hold on to the extra Pawn by 15 … e5.} 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Nxd4 c5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd5,Ge6,Gf6] The four black Pawns now constitute a compact and powerful center, the Rooks have open files on which to operate, and the King is well posted for the ending – all a consequence of White’s faulty strategy in embarking on an attack without sufficient means. Réti’s play from this point on is as delightful as it is convincing} 17. Ne2 Kf7 {Centralizing the King for the ending - With Queens off the board, the King need not seek safety in Castl ing, as there is little danger of his being mated. At f7, the King supports the center Pawns, and is ready to take active part in the ending.} 18. f3 Nd6 19. b3 {The Bishop is to be developed on the Queen side. An attempt to bring it into play on the Kingside would be rebuffed with loss of time} (19. Bf4 e5 {and the Bishop must retreat.}) (19. Be3 d4 {and the Bishop is driven off}) (19. Bd2 Nc4 {and the Bishop must return.}) 19... e5 {The Pawns begin to look formidable.} 20. Ba3 Rac8 21. Rad1 {Cutting down the scope of the Bishop} d4 {[%csl Ra3,Gd7] Placing the Pawns on black squares limits the action of White’s Bishop, while it increases the mobility of Black’s (which travels on white squares).} 22. Nc1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc1d3] The Knight is bound for d3, to get some counter-play by the attack on the c-Pawn.} Nf5 {[%csl Re3][%cal Yc5c4] The Knight gains time by its threat of winning the exchange with 23 … ♘e3. The Knight’s move also unpins the c-Pawn, making the advance … c4 now possible} 23. Rf2 {Establishing an outpost at e3} Ne3 {A fine spot for the Knight. It can either settle down at this ad vanced outpost, or use it as a jumping-off place for further invasion into enemy territory} 24. Re1 c4 $1 {A powerful move!} 25. b4 (25. Z0 cxb3 26. cxb3 Nc2 {and the attack on Rook and Bishop will force White to give up the exchange.}) (25. bxc4 Rxc4 26. Ree2 Rhc8 {[%csl Rc2] and Black wins the c-Pawn.}) 25... Ba4 $1 26. Ree2 ({White cannot save the Pawn by} 26. c3 Nc2 {[%csl Ra3,Re1]}) 26... Nd1 $1 {The galloping Knight - The beginning of some fancy stepping by the Knight.} 27. Rf1 Nc3 28. Ref2 Nb1 $1 {Réti notes that the Knight took ten moves to pay a visit to the home of White’s Knight.} 29. Bb2 c3 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge5,Gf6] The Pawn chain - A thrust at the Bishop, to relegate it to the back rank.} 30. Nb3 (30. Ba1 Nd2 31. Re1 Bxc2 {and Black is not only a Pawn ahead, but has two wicked-looking connected passed Pawns.}) 30... Bxb3 31. axb3 (31. Rxb1 Bxa2 32. Ra1 cxb2) (31. cxb3 c2 (31... cxb2 32. Rxb1 Rc1+ 33. Rf1) 32. Bc1 d3 33. Z0 d2 34. Bxd2 Nxd2 35. Rxd2 c1=Q {and White must give up his Rook for the newly-crowned Queen.}) 31... Nd2 32. Re1 Rhd8 $1 {Control of the vital files} 33. Bc1 d3 $1 {Breakthrough to obtain a passed Pawn} 34. cxd3 (34. Bxd2 cxd2 35. Rxd2 dxc2 (35... Rxc2) 36. Rxd8 Rxd8 {[%cal Gd8d1] forcing the promotion of the passed Pawn}) 34... Rxd3 $1 35. Bxd2 (35. Rxd2 cxd2 36. Rd1 Rxc1 {and the passed Pawn will become a Queen}) 35... Rxd2 36. Ra1 Ke6 $1 37. Kf1 (37. Rxa7 Rxf2 38. Kxf2 c2 {White must give up his Rook for the Pawn.}) 37... Rxf2+ {But this rudely dispels any fond hopes!} (37... Z0 38. Rxd2 cxd2 39. Rd1 Rc1 40. Ke2 {with good drawing chances.}) 38. Kxf2 c2 39. Rc1 Kd5 {The power of the King in the ending} 40. Ke3 Rc3+ $1 {Drives back White’s King, so that his own King may advance.} 41. Kd2 Kd4 $1 {The aggressive position of Black’s King is decisive!} 42. h4 ({If White removes the dangerous Pawn, he loses quickly} 42. Rxc2 Rxc2+ 43. Kxc2 Ke3 44. Kc3 Kf2) 42... Rd3+ $1 {Simplifying to a won ending} (42... Rd3+ {The Knock-out punch!} 43. Kxc2 (43. Ke2 Kc3) 43... Rc3+ 44. Kd2 Rxc1 45. Kxc1 {and now, so strong is the position of Black’s King, that he can win on either side of the board! Black can move to c3, capture both b-Pawns, and win as he pleases, or he can move to e3 and f2, and capture the King side Pawns to win.} Kc3 (45... Ke3)) 0-1


