{Paul Motwani: 'G9.17: "Reti repeat of a yeti-like crush!" Scotch Gambit, Code C56. Recently I was studying GM Lasha Janjgava's extremely detailed GAMBIT book, "The Queen's Gambit & Catalan for Black", and I found myself thinking about the enormous increase in chess data that is readily available to competitors nowadays in comparison to the relatively tiny quantity of information which even GMs of the past had to make do with. To take a particularly potent example, if ChessBase had existed in the days of the late great GM Richard Reti (28.5.1889-6.6.1929), then it's unlikely that Dr Max Euwe (World Champion 1935-37) would have been checkmated in a mere 22 moves as White by Reti at Amsterdam in 1920---since ChessBase would have 'told' him that the first 14 moves of the game had already happened six years previously in another yeti-like crush: the encounter P.Kruger-R.Reti, Mannheim 1914!! Let's now do a time warp back to the 20th century to experience that double dose of fighting chess.'} 1. e4 {Das kleine Match zwischen dem jungen Euwe und dem schon erfahrenen Reti hatte es in sich. Sehen Sie z.B. wie die zweite Partie verlief:} (1. d4 f5 2. e4 fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 g6 5. f3 exf3 6. Nxf3 Bg7 7. Bd3 c5 8. d5 Qb6 $2 {Unsolide.} 9. Qd2 Qxb2 10. Rb1 $1 Nxd5 {Hat Weiß nicht etwas übersehen?} (10... Qa3 11. Nb5 Qxa2 12. O-O) 11. Nxd5 $1 Qxb1+ 12. Kf2 Qxh1 {Erinnerungen an die "Unsterbliche" von Anderssen werden wach.} 13. Bxe7 {Der Angriff ist tödlich.} d6 14. Bxd6 Nc6 15. Bb5 Bd7 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Qe2+ {1-0 Reti,R-Euwe,M/Amsterdam 1920/HCL (17)}) 1... e5 {Paul Motwani: 'In a sense 1 d4 d5 is a "mirror image", and for lots of information relating to it, I refer you to the aforementioned GAMBIT book, "The Queen's Gambit & Catalan for Black"...or check out GM Ruslan Scherbakov's excellent 1 d4 d5 site within www.chesspublishing.com!'} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4 ({Anyone going in for} 4. Ng5 d5 ({or the ultra-wild} 4... Bc5 $5 {should first do a great deal of analysis at home!})) 4... exd4 ({The opening has transposed to the Scotch Gambit, since the same position can also be reached via the move-order 1 e4 e5 2 Nf3 Nc6 3 d4 exd4 4 Bc4 Nf6. Note that in the game Reti was right to stay clear of} 4... Nxe4 $6 5. dxe5 {which gets really black for Black after} Bc5 $4 6. Qd5 $1) 5. O-O ({If} 5. e5 {then Black's reasonable response-options include} d5 ({or} 5... Ne4) ({or} 5... Ng4)) 5... Nxe4 (5... Bc5 6. e5 d5 7. exf6 dxc4 8. Re1+ Be6 9. Ng5 {is the tricky Max-Lange Attack, in which one of many pitfalls to avoid is} Qxf6 $4 10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. Qh5+ {winning the loose c5-bishop.}) 6. Re1 d5 7. Bxd5 ({After} 7. Nc3 dxc3 8. Bxd5 {if Black is at all fearful for his king on the e-file, then an ultra-safe answer is} Be6 {intending} 9. Rxe4 $4 Ne7 $1 {and White can already resign without waiting for his pinned d5-bishop to be devoured.}) 7... Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qa5 ({A few years ago at FM Tim Upton's home in Luxembourg, Tim and I were looking at a game in "Informator" which went} 8... Qh5 9. Nxe4 Be6 10. Bg5 Bd6 $5 {and after} 11. Bf6 $2 {we were surprised to learn that} Bxh2+ $1 {was a  (rather obvious) "novelty" which leaves White in dire straits because of} 12. Nxh2 Qxd1 13. Raxd1 gxf6) 9. Nxd4 $2 (9. Nxe4 {ist der Hauptzug.} Be6 10. Bd2 Qd5 (10... Bb4 {is much safer for Black}) 11. Bg5 {after which} Bc5 $2 {allowed} 12. c4 $3 {in the game A.Pomarleanu-M.Izdebska, 1986 European U-18 Girls Championship.}) 9... Nxd4 {Paul Motwani: '!'} (9... f5 $2 {sets the trap} 10. f3 $4 ({but this backfires on Black because of} 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qh5+ $1 g6 12. Rxe4+ $1 {intending} fxe4 $4 ({or} 12... Be7 13. Qg5) 13. Qxa5) 10... Nxd4) 10. Qxd4 f5 11. Bg5 (11. Nxe4 $4 Qxe1#) ({or} 11. f3 $4 Bc5 {immediately take White to a "dead end".}) 11... Qc5 {Paul Motwani: '!'} 12. Qd8+ Kf7 {Paul Motwani: 'OK, so Black's king cannot castle, but being a piece up is more important!'} 13. Nxe4 fxe4 14. Rad1 ({If} 14. Rxe4 {then} Bf5 15. Qxa8 Bxe4 {wins easily for Black.}) 14... Bd6 $1 ({G9.17.2: Even stronger than} 14... Bg4 {which Reti had played six years before in the game P. Kruger-R.Reti, Mannheim 1914!}) 15. Qxh8 Qxg5 {droht 16...h3} 16. f4 ({Desperation from White, seeing that it's also "curtains" for him after} 16. Rxe4 Bh3) ({or} 16. Qxh7 Bf5 17. h4 Qg4) 16... Qh4 17. Rxe4 ({Reti might have hoped to get the pretty line} 17. g3 Bc5+ 18. Kh1 Bg4 $1 {intending} 19. Qxa8 Bf3# {but he couldn't have been too unhappy with the actual finish in the game!}) 17... Bh3 $3 {[%mdl 64]} 18. Qxa8 {Es ist wirklich unglaublich: Euwe räumt die gegnerischen Türme ab, wobei er die eigenen behält. Und in der zweiten Partie - s.o. - tut er es noch einmal. Allerdings geht es jeweils schief.} Bc5+ 19. Kh1 ({Other ways for White to bow out were} 19. Kf1 Qf2#) ({or} 19. Rdd4 Bxd4+ 20. Rxd4 Qe1#) 19... Bxg2+ $1 {Paul Motwani: 'This final sacrifice quickly forces mate.'} 20. Kxg2 Qg4+ 21. Kf1 ({Or} 21. Kh1 Qf3#) 21... Qf3+ 22. Ke1 Qf2# 0-1


