1. Nf3 {ChessBase Schulz,Andre JvR Garry Kasparov: 'JvR JvR JvR: 'Lopez Lopez : 'Reti opens the game in hypermodern style by developing from the flank.''''JvR JvR JvR: 'Lopez Lopez : 'Reti opens the game in hypermodern style by developing from the flank.'' Schulz,Andre: 'Garry Kasparov: 'JvR JvR JvR: 'Lopez Lopez : 'Reti opens the game in hypermodern style by developing from the flank.''''' Garry Kasparov: 'Schulz,Andre: 'Retis Erfindung: die nach ihm benannte Reti-Eröffnung. Die Idee ist, daß man auch mit Figuren um das Zentrum kämpfen kann.''} (1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. h3 (4. Nbd2 c5 5. e3 d6 6. c3 Nc6 7. h3 O-O 8. Bc4 {Alekhine-Euwe, London 1922}) 4... O-O ({or} 4... c5 5. e3 b6 6. Nbd2 Bb7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O d6 9. c3 Nbd7 10. Qe2 Rc8 11. a4 {(Réti-Alekhine, New York 1924, 13th round)}) 5. Nbd2 d6 6. e3 Nbd7 7. c3 c5 8. Bc4 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Qe2 Qc7 11. Bh2 Rae8 12. e4 {(Capablanca-Réti, London 1922).}) 1... d5 2. c4 {Garry Kasparov: 'JvR: 'Lopez : 'Immediately challenging the center.''''JvR: 'Lopez : 'Immediately challenging the center.'' Schulz,Andre: 'Garry Kasparov: 'JvR: 'Lopez : 'Immediately challenging the center.'''''} c6 {Garry Kasparov: '!?' '!?''Schulz,Andre: 'Garry Kasparov: '!?'''} ({Before this In the sixth round of the tournament Yates had opted for} 2... e6 {was tried against Réti – Game No.98 , although the game developed in similar fashion to this one, since Black subsequently played ...e5 and was able to develop his bishop outside the pawn chain.}) ({for} 2... d4 {cf. Game No.146.}) 3. b3 {Garry Kasparov: 'JvR: 'Lopez : 'Reti is just supporting the c-pawn before continuing his development.''''JvR: 'Lopez : 'Reti is just supporting the c-pawn before continuing his development.'' Schulz,Andre: 'Garry Kasparov: 'JvR: 'Lopez : 'Reti is just supporting the c-pawn before continuing his development.'''''} ({Avoiding the questionable Varying from} 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 b5 {<xml:>, as played in R.Réti-Em.Lasker, MÃ<sym>N</sym>hrisch-Ostrau 1923 (Game 39).</:/xml>} 6. a4 b4 7. Na2 e6 {(Réti-Lasker, Mährisch-Ostrau 1923). This theme was later developed in the game Reshevsky-Smyslov (USSR-USA radio match 1945), which is examined in the second volume.}) 3... Bf5 {Garry Kasparov: '!?' '!?' Garry Kasparov: ''With this move Dr Lasker as second player applies the London system of development, which, with colours transposed, has several times stood the test against the double fianchetto,' writes Alekhine, having in mind the 1 d4 variat''With this move Dr Lasker as second player applies the London system of development, which, with colours transposed, has several times stood the test against the double fianchetto,' writes Alekhine, having in mind the 1 d4 variation, above. Schulz,Andre: 'Garry Kasparov: '!?' Garry Kasparov: ''With this move Dr Lasker as second player applies the London system of development, which, with colours transposed, has several times stood the test against the double fianchetto,' writes Alekhine, having in mind the 1 d4 variation, above.''' ion, above.' Alekhine commented in the tournament book: “With this move Dr. Lasker as second player applies the London system of development, which, with colours transposed, has several times stood the test against the double fianchetto”, referring to the London System, played with White after 1 d4, which has been revived in recent years, having been employed by world champion Magnus Carlsen among others.} ({A modern variation is The set-up adopted here by Lasker is now known as the New York System, or Lasker's System. Capablanca preferred} 3... Bg4 {, which, as it happens, has also been played by me: against Gulko (46th USSR Championship, Tbilisi 1978) and Leko (Wijk aan Zee 2001). In any case, Black's main idea is to develop his c8-bishop outside the pawn chain and only then set up the defensive wall c6-d5-e6. against Réti in Moscow 1925; both possibilities, developing the bishop outside the pawn chain, either to f5 or g4, are still regarded as completely sound.}) 4. g3 Nf6 5. Bg2 Nbd7 ({Garry Kasparov: ''More cautious would have been first '} 5... e6 {Garry Kasparov: ', as White might assure himself of a positional advantage, even if microscopical, by means of'} 6. cxd5 $1 cxd5 7. Bb2 {followed by Nc3 etc. (compare the game Dr Lasker-Alekhine from the 18th round, wherein, with colours transposed, this method was adopted successfully).' (Alekhine)}) 6. Bb2 {Garry Kasparov: 'JvR: 'Lopez : 'Notice how each move by both players is one that exerts some measure of control over the center squares. The White Bishops cut scissors-like across the center.''''JvR: 'Lopez : 'Notice how each move by both players is one that exerts some measure of control over the center squares. The White Bishops cut scissors-like across the center.'' Schulz,Andre: 'Garry Kasparov: 'JvR: 'Lopez : 'Notice how each move by both players is one that exerts some measure of control over the center squares. The White Bishops cut scissors-like across the center.'''''} (6. cxd5 $5 {!?} cxd5 7. Bb2 {c3,d3,b1-a2,b4,ac1d5 Alekhine}) 6... e6 7. O-O Bd6 {'?!' JvR: 'Euwe calls this variation the First New Yorker after this game.' Garry Kasparov: ''?!' JvR: 'Euwe calls this var''?!' JvR: 'Euwe calls this variation the First New Yorker after this game.' ChessBase: '?!' '?!' Schulz,Andre: 'Garry Kasparov: ''?!' JvR: 'Euwe calls this variation the First New Yorker after this game.'''' iation the First New Yorker after this game.' ChessBase: '?!''} ({Garry Kasparov: 'A good alternative was '} 7... Be7 $142 {Garry Kasparov: ''' ChessBase: ''' %03'better is' is also played; on d6 the bishop allows a later ...Qe7, creating the possibility of ...Ba3. Black mustn't forget that the bishop is undefended on d6, so a possible e4 by White, after the moves} 8. d3 {and 9 Nbd2, must be taken into account.} O-O 9. Nbd2 a5 $5 ({managing without} 9... h6 {– Game No.108}) {, and if} 10. Nh4 {, then} Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. g4 Bg6 {with equality.}) ({He names} 7... h6 {(JvR) the Second New Yorker.}) 8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2 {JvR: '?!' Garry Kasparov: 'JvR: '?!' '?!'''JvR: '?!' '?!' Schulz,Andre: 'Garry Kasparov: 'JvR: '?!' '?!'''' This line was still in its infancy, so it's understandable that at first the masters failed to grasp all the details of the position. Réti repeats the plan that had been successful against Yates, without deviating, even though there were better options. Nunn made a instructive comment: “Réti tended to play this system with the idea of delaying any action in the centre for a considerable time, but these days players are aware that central activity by e4 is often an effective strategy.”} ({JvR: 'Euwe prefers'} 9. Nc3 $5 {Garry Kasparov: ''!?' ChessBase: '!?''} Qe7 {equalises.} 10. Re1 e5 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. e4) 9... e5 {JvR: '!' Garry Kasparov: '?!' '?!' Garry Kasparov: 'Rather premature activity. JvR: '!' '!' JvR: 'Lopez : 'Lasker's idea is to play ...Re8 (to back up the e-pawn) and then advance the two center pawns to sweep Wh'Rather premature activity. JvR: '!' '!' JvR: 'Lopez : 'Lasker's idea is to play ...Re8 (to back up the e-pawn) and then advance the two center pawns to sweep White's forces away.'' Schulz,Andre: 'Garry Kasparov: '?!' Garry Kasparov: 'Rather premature activity. JvR: '!' '!' JvR: 'Lopez : 'Lasker's idea is to play ...Re8 (to back up the e-pawn) and then advance the two center pawns to sweep White's forces away.''' Garry Kasparov: 'Alekhine attaches an exclamation mark to this move, ignoring the possible reply''' ite's forces away.''' Garry Kasparov: 'Alekhine attaches an exclamation mark to this move, ignoring the possible reply' '?!' '?!'} ({Garry Kasparov: 'but the most logical is ''but the most logical is Schulz,Andre: 'Garry Kasparov: 'but the most logical is ''' As Kasparov pointed out, the most logical continuation was the aforementioned} 9... Qe7 $5 {Garry Kasparov: '!' '!' Garry Kasparov: ''!?' ChessBase: '!?''''!?' ChessBase: '!?' Schulz,Andre: '!?' Schulz,Andre: 'Garry Kasparov: '!' G