{Lasker and Réti share the lead by 6½/8. The decisive game begins.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 c6 {Lasker plays the Slav Defence once again after an interval of no less than 33 years. In total there were only seven such occasions (+3 -2 =2); his two losses were against Horatio Caro, in Berlin in 1890, in only 14 moves, and later against Capablanca in New York in 1924. Those defeats did not prevent Lasker from winning both tournaments (he tied with his brother Berthold in Berlin).} 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 {The main line;} ({but} 5. a4 {is almost exclusively played these days.}) 5... b5 6. a4 b4 7. Na2 ({This retreat, immediately regaining the pawn, is more popular than} 7. Nb1 {, which allows} Ba6 {, delaying the recovery of the pawn, although this move is also playable.}) 7... e6 8. Bxc4 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Qe2 Nbd7 $5 {They play a quiet Slav Defence.} 11. b3 {Alekhine was very critical of this idea. Commenting on his game against Tarrasch, from Hastings 1922, he said: “It's surprising that in an identical position Réti continued here against Lasker with b3 and Bb2, which dangerously weakens the square c3. But in this variation the square b3 should be reserved for the queen knight”. In that game Tarrasch had played 10...Bb7 and the game continued 11 Rd1 Nbd7 12 e4; Alekhine developed his queen's bishop to g5, followed by playing Nc1-b3.} a5 12. Bb2 c5 13. Rfd1 Qb6 14. Nc1 Ba6 {This is the reason why Lasker held back from playing ...Bb7 earlier; with the exchange of the light-squared bishops, Black solves his mobility problems and seeks to exploit, in the long run, the weakness of the b3-pawn.} 15. dxc5 {'?!' '?!'} ({Here} 15. Bxa6 Qxa6 16. Qxa6 Rxa6 17. Nd3 {has been suggested, and “White has the somewhat better endgame”, but after} cxd4 18. Nxd4 {Black can play} Ne4 {in preparation for ...Ndc5, taking aim at the weakness of b3, no white advantage is visible.}) ({Although with the move played White plans to occupy c4 with a good knight, this exchange also facilitates the attack on b3, so it isn't the most precise. Instead,} 15. Nd2 $1 {seems better, with the idea of 16 Nd3, and after} cxd4 16. Bxd4 Bc5 {White simply retreats with} 17. Bb2 $1 {.}) 15... Nxc5 16. Ne5 {EXERCISE: The position is close to equality, but Black has a slight initiative. What do you think Lasker played now? ANSWER:} Bxc4 {'!' This will allow Black to continue to put pressure on the b3-pawn. Although he has to move the queen on the next move, this is no hardship for him. '!'} ({On the other hand, a natural move such as} 16... Rfc8 {would allow} 17. Ncd3 $1 {, and the white pieces start to come to life.}) 17. Nxc4 Qa6 18. Bd4 Rfc8 $5 {Lasker discontinues the exchanges. A natural move, which includes an inactive piece in the struggle, but it's not the most incisive move.} (18... Nfe4 $1 {was better; at first sight it looks much less logical than Lasker's move, but with the possibility of...Nc3, among other ideas, it hinders White's regrouping. Let's investigate this a little further: Best seems} 19. Ra2 $1 {, when a possible continuation is} ({If} 19. Bxc5 $2 {, Black renews the pressure on b3 with} Nxc5 {, and after} 20. Rb1 Rfd8 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 {Black takes control of the d-file.} 22. Z0 (22. Z0)) 19... Nc3 20. Bxc3 bxc3 21. Rc2 Bf6 {, with the idea of ...Rab8; then} 22. e4 {can be answered with} Rfd8 $1 {, and the weakness of White's back rank prevents} 23. e5 $2 {on account of} Bxe5 $1 {, so that Black has time to play ...Bd4.}) 19. Bxc5 {'!' Eliminating the pressure on b3 and now the white pieces can emerge from their prison. '!'} Bxc5 ({If} 19... Rxc5 {then} 20. e4 $1 {, limiting the mobility of the f6-knight.}) 20. Qf3 {'!' '!'} ({QUESTION: Why not play} 20. e4 {here too? ANSWER: With the bishop on c5, 20 e4 isn't so good; Black can} Qb7 $1 21. Re1 Rd8 {, threatening 22...Nxe4, followed by ...Rd4.}) 20... Be7 ({QUESTION: Isn't it more logical to play} 20... Nd5 {, aiming at the c3-square? ANSWER: The move played represents a notable decision on Lasker's part. He rejected 20...Nd5 possibly in view of the response} 21. Ne2 ({or possibly because} 21. e4 Nc3 {(21...Nb6 is also an option)} 22. Rd7 Rf8 23. Nd3 Qc8 24. Nxc5 Qxc5 25. Qd3 Rac8 {(to have ...Nxa4 available if the rook moves from a1) would lead to balanced play. Shereshevsky made this comment on the move chosen: “Lasker provokes his opponent to play a more active manoeuvre with the knight, Ncl-d3-e5, after which White seizes all the central squares. In return the black knight gets the chance to come to c3. Lasker's enormous experience of defending strategically difficult situations probably prompted the idea that the favourable placement of just one piece may prove to be his sheet anchor, by utilising which he will be able to neutralise the menacing-looking offensive of the large army of white pieces.”})) 21. Nd3 ({The passive} 21. Ne2 {was also possible, of course, but why renounce a more active plan?}) 21... Nd5 22. Nde5 Bf6 ({Lasker didn't expel the invading knight with} 22... f6 $2 {, because this loses to} 23. Rxd5 $1 {, since if} exd5 {there is a smothered mate with} 24. Qxd5+ Kh8 25. Nf7+ Kg8 26. Nh6+ {and Qg8+, while other moves just lose material.}) 23. e4 Nc3 $1 {A battle begins. The strong knight on c3 is a good antidote, neutralizing the activity of the other white pieces, meaning that for now the position is balanced.} 24. Rd6 {'?!' '?!'} ({If} 24. Rd7 {then} Ra7 {, so Réti 'gains a tempo' by attacking the black queen but, just as with 17 Nxc4, the queen improves its position, in this case even more so.}) ({It's understandable that for Réti it was very difficult psychologically to conclude that despite all his recent activity, his position is in danger, and the safest plan was to head for a draw. This could have been achieved with} 24. Nd7 $1 Nxd1 25. Rxd1 Rd8 ({if} 25... Rxc4 {then} 26. Nxf6+ {leaves the black king weak, so this isn't an improvement}) 26. Rd6 Qa7 27. Nxf6+ gxf6 28. Qxf6 Rxd6 29. Nxd6 Qc7 30. Qg5+ {and it ends in a draw after} Kf8 31. Qh6+ Ke7 32. e5 {.}) 24... Qb7 25. Re1 {White has defended his pawn and all he needs now, before resuming his active play, is to make an escape square for his king.} Bxe5 {'!' Exchanging this bishop is done only for a specific reason; it's the first step in Lasker's grand plan. '!'} 26. Nxe5 {EXERCISE: What was the reason behind Lasker's last move? ANSWER:} Qc7 {'!' '!'} (26... Rd8 {gives no more than comfortable equality after} 27. Nc4 e5 28. Rxd8+ Rxd8 {and now, for example,} 29. Nxa5 Qc7 30. Nc4 Nxa4 31. Rd1 {.}) 27. Nc4 {Forced.} ({Lasker sets White problems, exploiting the weakness of White's back rank, which prevents} 27. Qd3 $2 {due to} Nxe4 $1 28. Rxe4 $2 Qxd6 $1 {.}) 27... e5 $6 {Emanuel starts a "Schwindel". '?' This prevents White from advancing with e5, which would provide him with an outpost on d6, but isn't the most effective move. Lasker fails to play the third key move. '?'} ({It was necessary to cold-bloodedly calculate the consequences of} 27... Nxa4 $1 {. If, instead,} 28. e5 {, with the idea of 29 Red1 and 30 Rd7 (as well as 30 bxa4 Qxc4 31 Qxa8! followed by mate), the knight is unable to move from a4 due to 29 Nb6, but Black has time to play} ({Then} 28. Red1 {would threaten to win with Rd7, but Black can defend with} Rf8 29. Rd7 Qc5 {.} (29... Z0)) 28... Ra7 $1 {, escaping the influence of the white queen on f3 and also evading the possible fork on b6. Then after} 29. Red1 {Black can play} Nc3 {, since} 30. Rd7 ({while if} 30. R1d2 {then simply} h6 {, with the idea of ...a4, or even 30...a4 right away}) 30... Qxd7 {leads a lost endgame for White. QUESTION: OK, you've convinced me, but in that case why didn't Lasker play 27...Nxa4 - ? ANSWER: That we don't know. Maybe he was short of time or maybe he made a miscalculation; we've got no firm information.}) 28. Qf5 $1 {Lasker likes to smoke cigars full of opium during a game. About this time, his wife Martha prepares one. White threatens 29. Rd7. She has heard rumours and worries. He says it's alright. Réti replies forcefully, threatening to win with 29 Rd7, as well as to capture the e5-pawn. Now the white position is preferable.} Ne2+ $5 {Lasker plays fast under time pressure. QUESTION: Now this is a surprise, isn't it? What is Lasker hoping to achieve? Wasn't it better to defend with 28...Ra7 - ?} ({ANSWER:} 28... Ra7 {would have been answered with} 29. h4 Re8 ({not} 29... Nxa4 $4 {because then White wins with} 30. Red1 {, threatening Rd7, and if} Nc5 31. Qxc8+ $1 {, forcing mate}) 30. h5 {, and Black is under unpleasant pressure. Nunn explains Lasker's decision like this: “A typical Lasker move. Seeing that there is no really satisfactory continuation, Lasker chooses a move which at least creates complications and gives White the chance to go wrong.”}) {EXERCISE: What does your intuition tell you? Which way should the white king go?} 29. Kf1 $2 {This looks obvious; it eliminates any problems of back-rank mate, it attacks the knight, the king looks safe, etc.} ({Tartakower analyses Now} 29. Rxe2 {'?!' would run into '?!'} Qxd6 {'!' , when the only way to avoid loss is '!'} 30. Qxf7+ $1 {, but after} Kh8 $1 {White has no advantage.} 31. Qd5 $1) ({Best is ANSWER: Who would even have considered such an absurd-seeming move as} 29. Kh1 $1 {'?' . And yet the text move, which intuitively seems the better of the two, is in reality worse, for tactical reasons, naturally. In this case, as in other similar ones, where the position is untypical, to quote Nunn: “One should be aware that intuition can lead one badly astray in situations which don't fit standard patterns.” The best defence is} {29 Kh1! is, indeed, better, when} Nd4 {fails to} (29... Rd8 30. Qxe5 Rxd6 31. Qxd6 Qxd6 32. Nxd6 Nd4 33. Re3 Rd8 34. Nb7 Rd7 35. Rd3 ({not} 35. Nxa5 $2 Nxb3 $1) 35... Rxb7 36. Rxd4 {and now, for instance,} g6 {, followed by 37...Rc7-c3, when it's likely to end up as a rook ending with four pawns against three, where there are practical chances of a win, but it's a theoretical draw.}) 30. Qxe5 Nxb3 31. Nb6 {, since after} Qc3 32. Qxc3 bxc3 {, Black's passed pawn can be stopped this time by exploiting the weakness of Black's back rank with} 33. Nxa8 (33. Nxc8 $1 Rxc8 34. Red1 Nd2 35. f3 c2 36. Rc1 {followed by Kg1-f1, etc.} (36. Z0)) 33... c2 34. h3 {and White gains a pawn (Tarrasch).}) 29... Nd4 $1 30. Qxe5 Nxb3 31. Nb6 {EXERCISE: How can Black show that 29 Kf1 was an error? ANSWER:} Nd2+ $1 {This check wouldn't exist after 29 Kh1. Now the knight reaches c4 and Black has the advantage.} 32. Kg1 ({Not} 32. Ke2 $4 Nxe4 33. Nxc8 Qc2+ 34. Kf3 Qxf2+ {, forcing a winning simplification.}) 32... Nc4 $1 {Following the exchange of knights Black's passed b-pawn gives him a clear advantage.} 33. Nxc4 Qxc4 34. Qf5 {'?' The imprecise play by both sides in the final stage of the game was probably due to time pressure. White's plan is to play e5-e6, seeking counterplay, but it's inadequate. '?'} ({It was rather more tenacious to give the white king some luft with} 34. h4) ({or} 34. g3) ({or else enter a worse endgame with} 34. Qd5 Qxd5 35. exd5 {.}) 34... Rab8 (34... b3 {was slightly quicker, but this move is also effective.}) 35. e5 $2 (35. Qxa5 Qxe4 $1 36. Rdd1 $1 {shapes a firm defensive screen against the b-pawn.}) ({Here} 35. Qd5 {has been suggested, but it doesn't change much after} Qc3 36. Qd2 {when exchanging queens is good for Black, but it seems even better to play} Qa3 {, followed by 37...Qxa4 or 37...b3.}) 35... b3 36. e6 fxe6 37. Rdxe6 Rf8 ({There was a quicker win with} 37... b2 38. Re7 b1=Q 39. Rxb1 g6 $1 {, and the queen is unable to defend the rook on b1.}) 38. Qe5 Qc2 39. f4 b2 {The passed pawn is decisive; the black queen can easily rush back to the defence of its monarch.} 40. Re7 Qg6 41. f5 Qf6 {'?' A strange mistake by Lasker in this phase of the game; with this move he squanders at least two winning continuations and puts the victory at risk. '?'} ({It was much better to drive the white king to a worse square with} 41... Qb6+ $1 {and after} 42. Kh1 ({or} 42. Kf1 {, and the f5-pawn later falls with check}) {, only now} 42... Qf6 {, and White is unable to regroup in the way that was possible in the game.} 43. Rb1 Qxe5 44. Rxe5 Rfc8 45. Ree1 Rc2 {, followed by ...Rb4, or ...Kf7 first.}) (41... Qh6 $1 {was also winning: for instance,} 42. Rb1 Qc1+ 43. Kf2 ({or} 43. Qe1 Rfc8) 43... Qc2+ 44. Kg3 Rb3+ {.}) 42. Qd5+ {'?' Returning the favour. '?'} ({White could have offered much greater resistance with} 42. Rb1 $1 Qxe5 43. Rxe5 Rfc8 44. Kf2 Rc1 45. Re1 Rc4 46. Re2 Rcb4 47. Ke1 {. If Black had interpolated the check 41...Qb6+! then after 42 Kh1 Qf6 the white king would have been unable to arrive in time to defend against Black's invasion.}) 42... Kh8 43. Rb7 {If now} Qc3 $1 {Lasker had won the crucial game of the tournament.} 44. Rf1 {the quickest and simplest way to exploit the passed pawn is by playing} Rxb7 ({but there are several other ways, such as} 44... Qe3+ 45. Kh1 Qf4 $1 46. Kg1 Rxb7 47. Qxb7 Rb8) 45. Qxb7 Qe5 46. Rd1 Rb8 {followed by 47...h6.} 0-1


