{Thomas Engqvist: 'Zsigmond Barász (1878-1935) was a strong Hungarian player. He shared first place in the third Hungarian Championship, Budapest 1911, with Zoltán von Balla. According to Chessmetrics he was at his best when he was 34 years old. His highest ranking was 30th in the world with an estimated rating of 2572 on the March 1912 list. ''Zsigmond Barász (1878-1935) was a strong Hungarian player. He shared first place in the third Hungarian Championship, Budapest 1911, with Zoltán von Balla. According to Chessmetrics he was at his best when he was 34 years old. His highest ranking was 30th in the world with an estimated rating of 2572 on the March 1912 list.  Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'Zsigmond Barász (1878-1935) was a strong Hungarian player. He shared first place in the third Hungarian Championship, Budapest 1911, with Zoltán von Balla. According to Chessmetrics he was at his best when he was 34 years old. His highest ranking was 30th in the world with an estimated rating of 2572 on the March 1912 list. '''} 1. d4 {1)Kalendovsky:Richard Reti.1989.Praha. p.10. 2)Di Felice: Chess Results 1901-1920. p.98.3)Matsukevitch: Рихард Рети.2005.Moskau  The Championship with 15 players was won by Leo Fleischmann, (later Leo Forgacs) with 11/14 points (2.-3.) Abonyi and Szekely 10/14 (4).Barasz 9/14 (5.-6.)Foldes and Gajdos 8,5/14 (7.-8.) Exner and Reti 7,5/14.  Reti was 18 years old at the time this game was played, so we can't expect the hypermodern play... Thomas Engqvist: 'The young Réti played 1 e4 almost exclusively, followed by either the Ruy Lopez or the King's Gambit. So it is curious that during the Hungarian National Tournament at Székezfehérvár, he played only Queen's Gambits. ''The young Réti played 1 e4 almost exclusively, followed by either the Ruy Lopez or the King's Gambit. So it is curious that during the Hungarian National Tournament at Székezfehérvár, he played only Queen's Gambits.  Petronijevic,Zoran: '1)Kalendovsky:Richard Reti.1989.Praha. p.10. 2)Di Felice: Chess Results 1901-1920. p.98.3)Matsukevitch: Рихард Рети.2005.Moskau  The Championship with 15 players was won by Leo Fleischmann, (later Leo Forgacs) with 11/14 points (2.-3.) Abonyi and Szekely 10/14 (4).Barasz 9/14 (5.-6.)Foldes and Gajdos 8,5/14 (7.-8.) Exner and Reti 7,5/14.  Reti was 18 years old at the time this game was played, so we can't expect the hypermodern play... Thomas Engqvist: 'The young Réti played 1 e4 almost exclusively, followed by either the Ruy Lopez or the King's Gambit. So it is curious that during the Hungarian National Tournament at Székezfehérvár, he played only Queen's Gambits. '''} d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: What is the name of the opening? ANSWER: Currently we have a Colle formation, signified by the fact that the c1-bishop is shut in behind the pawn chain. On the other hand, if the bishop is later developed to b2, we reach a Zukertort position. ''QUESTION: What is the name of the opening? ANSWER: Currently we have a Colle formation, signified by the fact that the c1-bishop is shut in behind the pawn chain. On the other hand, if the bishop is later developed to b2, we reach a Zukertort position.  Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: What is the name of the opening? ANSWER: Currently we have a Colle formation, signified by the fact that the c1-bishop is shut in behind the pawn chain. On the other hand, if the bishop is later developed to b2, we reach a Zukertort position. '''} c6 ({Alekhine recommended} 3... Bf5 {as a strong antidote to White's aspirations.}) 4. c4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Now it is a Slav by transposition, and Black's next move makes it a Semi-Slav. ''Now it is a Slav by transposition, and Black's next move makes it a Semi-Slav. Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'Now it is a Slav by transposition, and Black's next move makes it a Semi-Slav. '''} ({If White wants to continue with Colle schemes he should play} 4. Bd3 {, securing the b1-h7 diagonal. 4 c3 is possible too, but in that case Black again has the option of placing his bishop on the h7-b1 diagonal as per Alekhine's recommendation above.}) 4... e6 5. Bd3 Nbd7 6. O-O {Thomas Engqvist: 'The best move order,''The best move order, Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'The best move order,'''} ({avoiding the Meran Variation which arises after} 6. Nc3 dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 {. Black plans the liberation of the queen's bishop as well as pressure on the centre via ...Bb7, ...a7-a6 and ...c7-c5. This plan is less effective without the white knight on c3, since Black lacks the useful tempo-gaining resource ...b5-b4 in key positions.}) 6... Bd6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. e4 dxe4 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'After losing to Steinitz in their 1889 match, Chigorin later fixed on ''After losing to Steinitz in their 1889 match, Chigorin later fixed on Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'After losing to Steinitz in their 1889 match, Chigorin later fixed on '''} 8... dxc4 {is an alternative. Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'is an alternative.''} 9. Bxc4 e5 {, followed by ...Qe7 or ...Qc7, as the correct handling in Black's quest for equality.}) 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Although this position is still being played regularly (MegaBase lists over 3000 games), it seems to me that White has achieved a comfortable edge. ''Although this position is still being played regularly (MegaBase lists over 3000 games), it seems to me that White has achieved a comfortable edge.  Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'Although this position is still being played regularly (MegaBase lists over 3000 games), it seems to me that White has achieved a comfortable edge. '''} f5 {the game move is also played nowadays. Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'the game move is also played nowadays.''} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'd)' Though it is considered that better is Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Though it is considered that better is''} 10... h6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'is the most popular choice, forestalling any sacrifices and preparing ...e7-e5. Nevertheless, after'} 11. Bc2 e5 12. b3 Re8 ({or} 12... f5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Bb2) 13. Re1 exd4 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. Qxd4 Bc5 16. Qc3 {, followed by 17 Bb2, White keeps an edge with positional pressure on the black kingside.}) ({Thomas Engqvist: 'c)''c) Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'c)''' or Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'or''} 10... Nf6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'can again be answered by ''can again be answered by Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'can again be answered by '''   Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: ' ''} 11. Bc2 {,} ({or else the sharper} 11. Bg5 {, when} h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. c5 $1 Bc7 14. Re1 {leaves Black with difficulties developing the c8-bishop.})) ({Other moves: a)} 10... e5 $2 {is an elementary mistake, due to} 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Bxh7+ ({not} 13. Qh5 $2 f5) 13... Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Qxe5 {, winning a pawn.}) ({b)} 10... Re8 {hopes for the impatient} 11. Bxh7+ $2 Kxh7 12. Ng5+ Kg6 $1 (12... Kg8 13. Qh5 Nf6 14. Qxf7+ Kh8 15. f4 $1 {intending Rf3 is dangerous}) 13. h4 Rh8 14. g3 Nf8 {and Black is better; but simply 11 Bc2 maintains White's options and advantage.}) 11. Bc2 Nf6 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'The seemingly liberating ''The seemingly liberating Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'The seemingly liberating ''' Black is not developed enough for opening up the play Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Black is not developed enough for opening up the play''} 11... e5 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' '?' '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'is an illusion a'is an illusion after Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'is an illusion after ''' fter '} 12. Bg5 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!' '!''Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: '!'''} Be7 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Nxe5 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!' '!''Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: '!'''} Nxe5 15. Re1 Rd8 (15... Qb4 {Thomas Engqvist: '(otherwise Black loses a pawn) ''(otherwise Black loses a pawn) Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: '(otherwise Black loses a pawn) ''' loses Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'loses''} 16. Rxe5 Qxb2 17. Rb1 (17. c5 $1 {(opening the a2-g8 diagonal while limiting the black queen's retreat squares)} Kh8 18. Re3 Qb4 19. Qd3 b6 20. a3 $1 Qa5 21. Re7 bxc5 22. Qg3 Rg8 23. Bb3 {and White won in V.Korchnoi-Zhu Chen, Bad Homburg 1998.}) 17... Qa3 18. c5 $18 {Black has serious problems due to his undeveloped queenside}) 16. Rxe5 Qxe5 17. dxe5 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 $16 {White is a pawn up and so he has a good winning chances.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: How might White continue his development? ANSWER:''QUESTION: How might White continue his development? ANSWER: Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: How might White continue his development? ANSWER:'''} 12. b3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Réti intends to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop, increasing his control over the weak e5-square. ''Réti intends to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop, increasing his control over the weak e5-square. Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'Réti intends to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop, increasing his control over the weak e5-square. '''} ({The logical} 12. Re1) ({and} 12. Qe2 {support that aim too, while putting pressure on the backward e6-pawn – Réti in fact plays Qe2 next move.}) ({Other alternatives which spring to mind are} 12. Be3) ({and} 12. c5 {, playing against Black's liberating ...c6-c5 break.}) 12... Qc7 13. Qe2 Re8 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: What is White's most principled continuation? ''QUESTION: What is White's most principled continuation?  Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: What is White's most principled continuation? '''} 14. Ne5 $2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'It seems Réti is fully content with exploiting the e5-square, but he undervalues the weakness of the e6-pawn. In particular, by blocking the e-file he allows Black to develop his bishop to b7.''It seems Réti is fully content with exploiting the e5-square, but he undervalues the weakness of the e6-pawn. In particular, by blocking the e-file he allows Black to develop his bishop to b7. Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'It seems Réti is fully content with exploiting the e5-square, but he undervalues the weakness of the e6-pawn. In particular, by blocking the e-file he allows Black to develop his bishop to b7.'''} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'and ''and Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'and ''' White plays naturally but not good. After Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'White plays naturally but not good. After''} 14. c5 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: '!'' White has a clear advantage Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'White has a clear advantage''} Be7 15. b4 $16 (15. Bd2 $16 {Thomas Engqvist: 'would be more logical.''would be more logical. Petronijevic,Zoran: '' Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'would be more logical.''' is also good enough for getting an advantage. Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'is also good enough for getting an advantage.''})) ({ANSWER: It seems better to leave the e-file open and keep the option of increasing the pressure on e6 with a knight move to g5. To this end, any of} 14. Bb2) (14. Re1) 14... b6 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'A good alternative is ''A good alternative is Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'A good alternative is '''} 14... c5 $11 {was a good alternative for equal play. Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: '=' Petronijevic,Zoran: 'was a good alternative for equal play.''} 15. Bb2 cxd4 16. Bxd4 b6 {, followed by ...Bb7, with equality.}) 15. f4 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Here ''Here Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'Here ''' More natural was: Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'More natural was:''} 15. Bb2 $11 {Thomas Engqvist: 'makes more sense. The knight did not require further reinforcement, so there is no reason to weaken the light squares at this moment.''makes more sense. The knight did not require further reinforcement, so there is no reason to weaken the light squares at this moment. Petronijevic,Zoran: '='