was: Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Better was:''} 18... cxd4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!' '!''Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: '!'''} 19. Bxd4 {Thomas Engqvist: ', and only then continue with '', and only then continue with Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: ', and only then continue with '''} Be4 $15 {Thomas Engqvist: '.''. Petronijevic,Zoran: '' Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: '.''' Black has a small advantage. Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Black has a small advantage.''}) 19. Bxe4 Nxe4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How does White exploit Black's inaccurate move order? ANSWER:''EXERCISE: How does White exploit Black's inaccurate move order? ANSWER: Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How does White exploit Black's inaccurate move order? ANSWER:'''} 20. d5 $11 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!' '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Now White manages to turn the position to his advantage.''Now White manages to turn the position to his advantage. Petronijevic,Zoran: '=' Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Now White manages to turn the position to his advantage.'''} exd5 21. Rxd5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The rook move from d1 to d5 will always be associated with Réti, since it was this particular manoeuvre which concluded his wins against Capablanca and Alekhine (see Games 30 and 33). ''The rook move from d1 to d5 will always be associated with Réti, since it was this particular manoeuvre which concluded his wins against Capablanca and Alekhine (see Games 30 and 33).  Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'The rook move from d1 to d5 will always be associated with Réti, since it was this particular manoeuvre which concluded his wins against Capablanca and Alekhine (see Games 30 and 33). '''} Nf6 ({This is simplest. It is more complicated to get an equal play by} 21... Bxe5 22. fxe5 (22. Bxe5 $6 Qf7 {gives Black small advantage.}) 22... Rxd5 23. cxd5 c4 (23... Rxe5 $5 24. Bxe5 Qxe5 25. Qd1 g6 $13) 24. bxc4 Qc5+ 25. Kh1 g6 26. Qe2 b5 27. cxb5 Qxd5 $13 {leads to an irrational position in which Black's chances are not inferior.}) 22. Rd2 Ng4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The knight belongs on e4 really, but the text turns out okay.''The knight belongs on e4 really, but the text turns out okay. Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'The knight belongs on e4 really, but the text turns out okay.'''} (22... Ne4 {leads to completely equal play.}) 23. Qg3 ({Equal play also gives} 23. h3 Nf6 24. Qe3 $11) (23. Re2 $5 {also leads to equal position} Nf6 $11) 23... Bxe5 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Black could have changed his mind and returned the knight with ''Black could have changed his mind and returned the knight with Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'Black could have changed his mind and returned the knight with '''} 23... Nf6 $11 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!' '!' Thomas Engqvist: ', followed by ...Ne4, not caring about the lost tempi. Centralization is worth more than time in this position!'', followed by ...Ne4, not caring about the lost tempi. Centralization is worth more than time in this position! Petronijevic,Zoran: '=' Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: ', followed by ...Ne4, not caring about the lost tempi. Centralization is worth more than time in this position!''' led to equal play simpler than the game move. Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'led to equal play simpler than the game move.''}) 24. Rxd8 Qxd8 25. fxe5 g6 26. h3 ({Better was} 26. Qf4 Qc7 (26... Qd3 27. Re1 Qc2 28. Ba1 $14) 27. Bc3 $14 {White has a small advantage.}) ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Or if ''Or if Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'Or if '''} 26. Re1 $5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'then ''then Petronijevic,Zoran: '!?' Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'then ''' is also an interesting possibility. Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'is also an interesting possibility.''} Re6 27. h3 Nh6 {.}) ({White could have prevented the immediate infiltration of the enemy queen with} 26. Bc3 {, but then simply} Nh6 {is solid enough.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How does Black deal with this situation? ANSWER:''EXERCISE: How does Black deal with this situation? ANSWER: Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How does Black deal with this situation? ANSWER:'''} 26... Qd2 $1 {Excellent move which gives Black equal play. Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Excellent move which gives Black equal play.''} ({Retreating the knight would be disastrous:} 26... Nh6 $2 27. Qe3 Nf7 28. e6 Kf8 29. Re1 Qd6 30. Bf6 $1 {with a decisive bind. White threatens 31 Qf3 Rxe6 32 Qb8+ and wins, while} Qc6 {fails to} 31. Qg3 Rxe6 32. Qb8+ Re8 33. Rxe8+ Qxe8 34. Bg7+ {etc.}) 27. Bc3 Qe3+ 28. Qxe3 Nxe3 29. Rf3 Nc2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The natural move, manoeuvring to the d4-outpost. ''The natural move, manoeuvring to the d4-outpost. Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'The natural move, manoeuvring to the d4-outpost. '''} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'The slightly awkward-looking ''The slightly awkward-looking Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'The slightly awkward-looking '''} 29... Nd1 {also leads to equal play though it creates a complicated position unnecessarily. Thomas Engqvist: 'keeps the balance too, after either ''keeps the balance too, after either Petronijevic,Zoran: 'also leads to equal play though it creates a complicated position unnecessarily. Thomas Engqvist: 'keeps the balance too, after either '''} 30. Bd2 ({or} 30. Ba1 Rd8) 30... Rxe5 {Thomas Engqvist: '.''. Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: '.'''} 31. Rd3 Re4 32. Kf1 f4 $11) 30. Rd3 Kf7 ({To equal play, also leads} 30... Nd4 31. Bxd4 Rd8 32. Kf2 cxd4 $11) 31. Kf2 Nd4 32. Bxd4 cxd4 33. Rxd4 Rxe5 {The rook ending is completely equal. Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'The rook ending is completely equal.''} 34. Rd7+ Re7 35. Rxe7+ Kxe7 {Also pawn ending is completely equal. Old books give a small advantage to White though it's not clear why. Thomas Engqvist: 'The position is obviously a draw but Réti manages to fool his opponent. It is interesting to see how he achieved the impossible.  ''The position is obviously a draw but Réti manages to fool his opponent. It is interesting to see how he achieved the impossible.  Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Also pawn ending is completely equal. Old books give a small advantage to White though it's not clear why. Thomas Engqvist: 'The position is obviously a draw but Réti manages to fool his opponent. It is interesting to see how he achieved the impossible.  '''} 36. Ke3 g5 37. b4 {Both sides prepare for pushing their passed pawns. Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Both sides prepare for pushing their passed pawns.''} Kd6 38. Kd4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'White has the more active king, so Black needs to be careful in his defence.''White has the more active king, so Black needs to be careful in his defence. Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'White has the more active king, so Black needs to be careful in his defence.'''} a5 39. a3 ({In his book, "Richard Reti" by Matcukevich, Moscow 2005, the following variation is given as a draw} 39. bxa5 bxa5 40. a4 $4 ({To draw leads only} 40. c5+ $1 Kc6 41. Ke5 f4 42. Kf6 Kxc5 43. Kxg5 Kb4 44. Kxf4 Ka3 45. g4 $11) {In fact, White is lost here after} 40... f4 41. Kd3 Kc5 42. Kc3 h5 $19) 39... a4 40. g3 h5 $5 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' '?!' '?!''Petronijevic,Zoran: '!?' Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: '?!'''} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'or more picturesquely, ' In the above mentioned book, it is considered that this move is a decisive mistake and that to draw leads only Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'In the above mentioned book, it is considered that this move is a decisive mistake and that to draw leads only''} 40... h6 41. h4 Ke6 42. hxg5 ({ili Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'ili''} 42. h5 Kd6 43. c5+ bxc5+ 44. bxc5+ Kc6 (44... Ke6 45. c6 Kd6 46. c7 Kxc7 47. Ke5 f4 48. gxf4 g4 (48... gxf4 {draws as well}) 49. Ke4 Kd6 50. Ke3 Ke6 51. Kf2 Kf6 52. Kg3 Kf5 53. Kh4 Kxf4 {stalemate!}) 45. Ke5 f4 46. gxf4 gxf4 47. Kxf4 Kxc5 $11) 42... hxg5 43. c5 b5 (43... bxc5+ {also leads to draw} 44. Kxc5 f4 45. gxf4 gxf4 46. Kd4 Kf5 $11) 44. c6 Kd6 45. c7 Kxc7 46. Ke5 f4 47. gxf4 gxf4 48. Kxf4 Kd6 $11) ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Either 40...Ke6 or 40...h6 leads to a draw; for example, ''Either 40...Ke6 or 40...h6 leads to a draw; for example, Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'Either 40...Ke6 or 40...h6 leads to a draw; for example, ''' In fact, neither after the game move Black loses, and to draw also leads Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'In fact, neither after the game move Black loses, and to draw also leads''} 40... Ke6 41. h4 (41. c5 bxc5+ 42. Kxc5 g4 43. hxg4 fxg4 44. Kc6 h5 45. b5 h4 46. gxh4 g3 47. b6 g2 48. b7 g1=Q 49. b8=Q Qc1+ {and so forth}) 41... h6 42. c5 bxc5+ 43. bxc5 f4 44. gxf4 gxh4 $11) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How can White profit from Black's inaccuracy? ANSWER:''EXERCISE: How can White profit from Black's inaccuracy? ANSWER: Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How can White profit from Black's inaccuracy? ANSWER:'''} 41. h4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!' '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Forcing a breach in Black's pawn wall, though he is not lost ye'Forcing a breach in Black's pawn wall, though he is not lost yet.  Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Forcing a breach in Black's pawn wall, though he is not lost yet. ''' t. '} gxh4 $4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The fatal mistake.''The fatal mistake. Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'The fatal mistake.'''} ({This move leads to defeat. After Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'This move leads to defeat. After''} 41... g4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'is the only way to hold on: ''is the only way to hold on: Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'is the only way to hold on: ''' the position is draw, for instance: Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'the position is draw, for instance:''} 42. Kd3 ({not} 42. c5+ $4 bxc5+ 43. bxc5+ Kc6 44. Ke5 Kxc5 45. Kxf5 Kc4 {and Black wins}) 42... Ke6 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: '!''} 43. Kd2 Kf6 44. Ke2 Ke6 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: '!''} 45. Kd3 Kd6 46. Kd4 Ke6 $11 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: '=''} 47. c5 bxc5+ 48. bxc5 {. EXERCISE (analysis): How does Black achieve the draw here? ANSWER:} f4 $1 {(the main point of the defence)} 49. gxf4 g3 50. Ke3 Kd5 51. Kf3 Kxc5 52. Kxg3 Kd5 53. Kf3 Kd4 {and despite being a pawn down, Black holds the draw.}) 42. gxh4 $18 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: '+-''} Ke6 43. c5 bxc5+ 44. Kxc5 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: '!''} f4 (44... Ke5 {loses after} 45. b5 f4 46. b6 f3 47. b7 f2 48. b8=Q+ $18 {[%csl Re5][%cal Rb8e5]}) 45. Kd4 Kf5 46. b5 {now everything is clear and no comment is needed. Thomas Engqvist: 'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'now everything is clear and no comment is needed.''} f3 47. Ke3 f2 48. Kxf2 Ke5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: Can you work the forced variation out to its conclusion? ANSWER:''EXERCISE: Can you work the forced variation out to its conclusion? ANSWER: Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: Can you work the forced variation out to its conclusion? ANSWER:'''} 49. Kf3 Kd5 50. Kf4 Kc5 51. Kg5 Kxb5 52. Kxh5 Kc4 53. Kg4 Kb3 54. h5 Kxa3 55. h6 Kb2 56. h7 a3 57. h8=Q+ {Thomas Engqvist: 'With the pawn on a2 the position is an easy draw, but with the pawn on a3 it is a win.''With the pawn on a2 the position is an easy draw, but with the pawn on a3 it is a win. Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'With the pawn on a2 the position is an easy draw, but with the pawn on a3 it is a win.'''} Kb1 58. Qb8+ Ka1 59. Qe5+ ({Technically,} 59. Qf4 $1 {is the most precise move, leading to mate in nine. Note that} a2 {fails to} 60. Qc1# {.}) 59... Kb1 60. Qe1+ Kb2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'after ''after Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'after '''} 61. Qb4+ {Thomas Engqvist: 'This is the key squa'Petronijevic,Zoran: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'This is the key square for the white queen, putting pressure on the a3-pawn; ''' re for the white queen, putting pressure on the a3-pawn; '} Ka2 62. Kf4 {, Black loses the pawn, since he is forced to make a move. To win by zugzwang is one of the main methods in theoretical endgames. A well-played game by the young Réti, showing his fondness for endings.} 1-0


