{Thomas Engqvist: 'The Hungarian master Gyula Breyer (1893-1921) is regarded as one of the pioneers of the hypermodern school. Sadly, he died of heart failure at the young age of 28. He has probably affected more chess players than most are aware of. In my own chess life, I have included Breyer’s Defence to the Ruy Lopez (9...Nb8 in the closed variation) in my opening repertoire; and, in honour of this imaginative player, I also tried 1 d4 Nf6 2 Nd2 in a serious game against Jonathan Tisdall in Oslo 1992. The main idea is to avoid the early exchange of the queen’s bishop, as in the French Defence or the Stonewall Dutch. According to Chessmetrics, Breyer highest ranking was 9th in the world in December 1917 with an estimated rating of 2630. At the time of the current game he was ranked equal 10th with Réti, but in fact Breyer found Réti to be a difficult opponent, and only beat him once in their 16 games together while losing on nine occasions. '} 1. e4 {ChessBase} e5 2. f4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The King's Gambit is the oldest known gambit in chess history. It has been ventured not only by pronounced romantic players such as Anderssen, Chigorin, Kolisch, Morphy and Spielmann, but also by those of a different style, like Rubinstein, Spassky and Bronstein. '} exf4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'This is absolutely the best continuation for Black, either to reach an early equalization or even try for more. Do not be deterred, when you are preparing for a game, by the fact that your opponent might be a King's Gambit expert and therefore ready for this move. Learn some variations and there is virtually nothing for Black to worry about. The Soviet GM Ratmir Kholmov (1925-2006) once said, after losses to Bronstein and Spassky: "Make sure that you always have a solid system against the King's Gambit at your disposal." '} 3. Qf3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'This line is in fact known as the Breyer Gambit. White's idea is rather crude: ignoring the development of the king's knight for the moment, White plans to recapture the gambit pawn with the queen, and then follow up with Bc4, Nf3, and 0-0. The result is that strong pressure is established on the half-open f-file, particularly the f7-square. Coupled with the fundamental idea of setting up a classical centre with pawns on e4 and d4, the two chief aims of the opening are thus achieved. In that sense Breyer's move is both logical and in the spirit of King's Gambit. QUESTION: So, what is your answer to the Breyer Gambit? ANSWER:'} {Thomas Engqvist: 'Note that the direct threat after'} d5 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'It is logical to strike at the centre pawn, while opening up the game to exploit the suspicious position of the white queen.'} ({Another reasonable alternative is} 3... Nc6 {, preventing White from playing an immediate d2-d4, while again eyeing the queen on f3.}) ({On the other hand,} 3... Qh4+ $6 4. g3 fxg3 5. hxg3 {shows one of the points behind the Breyer: the h1-rook is now defended by the queen. After} Qd8 ({or} 5... Qf6 $5 6. Nc3 {, White has definite compensation for the pawn}) 6. d4 {.}) 4. exd5 ({Not} 4. Qxf4 $2 {, which fails to either} dxe4 ({or} 4... Bd6 5. e5 {(otherwise ...Qh4+ and ...Qxe4 follows)} Qe7 6. d4 f6 {with a huge advantage to Black}) 5. Nc3 ({after} 5. Qxe4+ Be7 {, White's queen is seriously misplaced on the open e-file}) 5... f5 {.}) (4. Z0 Qh4+ 5. g3 fxg3 6. hxg3 Qxe4+ {.}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 ({The immediate} 5. Bb5+ {can be met by} c6 $1 (5... Bd7 6. Nc3 Bb4 7. Nge2 O-O 8. Bxd7 Nbxd7 9. O-O Nb6 10. Nxf4 {gave White comfortable play in R.Réti-A.Rubinstein, Stockholm 1919}) 6. dxc6 Nxc6 {, transposing to R.Spielmann-A.Nimzowitsch, Munich 1906. Now after} 7. d4 (7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Qxc6+ Bd7 {is far too greedy}) {, Black should have played} 7... Bb4+ $1 ({instead of the passive} 7... Bd7 $2) 8. c3 O-O $1 {with a winning position. Note that the b4-bishop is taboo in view of} 9. cxb4 ({or} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. cxb4 Re8+ {is no better}) 9... Re8+ {and 10...Nxd4, when White's position is in ruins.}) 5... Bd6 ({Rapid development with} 5... Bg4 6. Qxf4 Bd6 {leads to nothing substantial after} 7. Qe3+ Kd7 $6 ({but} 7... Be7 $1 {keeps the balance}) 8. Nge2 $1 {.}) 6. Bb5+ {Thomas Engqvist: 'The only logical continuation.'} (6. Bc4 {transposes to H.Ree-S.Gligoric, Teesside 1972, where} O-O 7. Nge2 Bg4 8. Qf2 Nbd7 {gave Black a clear advantage, which he converted to a win in 46 moves.}) 6... Bd7 ({Here} 6... c6 {is not quite as attractive, since} 7. dxc6 Nxc6 $4 ({though} 7... O-O $1 8. cxb7 Qe7+ 9. Qe2 Qxb7 {still offers Black decent compensation for the pawn}) 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Qxc6+ {wins material.}) ({Alternatively, S.Winawer-V.Knorre, Wiesbaden 1880, continued} 6... Nbd7 7. d4 O-O 8. Nge2 Nb6 9. Bxf4 {and now} Bg4 {was correct with a slight advantage to Black. A free development move like this highlights one of the fundamental defects with the Breyer Gambit.}) 7. Bxd7+ {Thomas Engqvist: 'Breyer prefers to eliminate Black's light-squared bishop. '} ({For instance, after} 7. Nge2 O-O 8. d4 Bg4 9. Qf2 Bf5 {, the bishop would certainly show its teeth;} ({or Black might again play} 9... c6 10. dxc6 Nxc6 {, accelerating his development.})) 7... Nbxd7 8. d4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The most natural move, opening a path for the c1-bishop while keeping the d7-knight at bay. '} ({After} 8. Nge2 Ne5 9. Qh3 Neg4 $1 {, this knight would have become pretty active.}) 8... Nb6 ({The immediate} 8... O-O {looks more logical and limits White's options; then} 9. Nge2 Nb6) 9. Bd2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'There is no need to prevent the pseudo-sacrifice on d5. '} ({An interesting deployment is to start with} 9. Nh3 {, preventing a later ...g7-g5, and after the strongest reply} Qe7+ $1 ({now if} 9... Nbxd5 $2 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. O-O {, White gets one of those positions you dream about when playing the King's Gambit}) {, go for artificial castling with} 10. Kf2 O-O 11. Nxf4 Rfe8 12. Rf1 Rad8 13. Kg1 {and so on with about equal play.}) ({But not} 9. Bxf4 $2 Bxf4 10. Qxf4 O-O {, followed by ...Re8 and ...Nbxd5 or ...Nfxd5 with a problematic position for White; note especially the exposed queen on f4.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: Should Black castle short or prepare to go long? '} 9... O-O ({ANSWER: Having declined to castle kingside on the previous move, it was better now to play} 9... Qe7+ $1 10. Nge2 O-O-O 11. O-O-O g5 {, showing the main idea behind castling queenside.}) 10. Nge2 Bb4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!?' Thomas Engqvist: 'Réti wants to use his queen when he eventually recaptures on d5. '} ({The natural} 10... Re8 {might have been answered by} 11. O-O-O Nc4 12. Nxf4 $1 (12. Bxf4 {allows the clever} Qe7 $1 {, threatening ...Ba3!}) 12... Nxd2 13. Rxd2 Bxf4 14. Qxf4 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. b3 {and White has a rather safe position after, for example,} Re7 17. Rf1 Rae8 18. Kb2 {and so forth.}) 11. O-O ({Castling long was an option for White too:} 11. O-O-O Nbxd5 ({or} 11... Bxc3 12. Nxc3 Nbxd5 13. Rhe1 Qd6 14. Re5 {and White is fine}) 12. Nxd5 Bxd2+ 13. Rxd2 Qxd5 14. Qxd5 Nxd5 15. c4 Ne3 16. Nxf4 Nxc4 17. Rc2 Nb6 18. Rxc7 Rac8 19. Rxc8 Rxc8+ 20. Kd2 {with full equality.}) 11... Bxc3 ({Réti tries to upset the balance, since after} 11... Nfxd5 12. Nxd5 (12. Nxf4 Nxf4 13. Qxf4 Nc4 14. Be1 Bd6 {offers Black a slight initiative,} ({whereas pawn-grabbing with} 14... Nxb2 $6 {is not so palatable after} 15. Rb1 Bd6 16. Qf3 Nc4 17. Rxb7 {and White has good counterplay})) 12... Bxd2 13. Ndxf4 Qe8 {, the position is rather simplified. The white bishop looks a bit awkward on d2, but it actually helps to control the weak e3-square.}) 12. bxc3 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'This is the worst recapture. '} ({Any of the others was preferable:} 12. Bxc3 Nbxd5 13. Nxf4 c6 {with equality;}) ({or} 12. Nxc3 Nbxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Qxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxf4 {with a level endgame;}) ({or even} 12. Qxc3 $5 Ne4 13. Qd3 Nxd2 14. Qxd2 {and if} g5 {then} 15. g3 $1 {.}) 12... Qxd5 (12... Nc4 13. Bxf4 Qxd5 {was good too.}) 13. Bxf4 (13. Qxf4 Qe4 {also forces the exchange of queens.}) ({If White wants to avoid a queen trade, he has to resort to} 13. Qd3 {, but then} Qc6 14. Rxf4 Nfd5 15. Rf3 Nc4 {highlights the weak light squares and Black's super knights secure a large advantage.}) 13... Qxf3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'It will be easier for Black to exploit the opposing pawn weaknesses without the queens, since White will find it more difficult to generate counterplay. '} 14. Rxf3 Rfe8 15. Ng3 Nfd5 16. Rb1 Rab8 17. Kf2 Re6 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'A rook lift with dual purpose: Black can either double on the e-file or swing the e6-rook across to c6 attacking the c3-pawn. '} (17... Nc4 $2 18. Rb5 $1) ({Another good move is} 17... g6 {, taking squares away from the white knight, as well as giving the black king some air.}) 18. Rb5 Rc6 19. Ne4 Rc4 20. Nd2 $1 ({It makes sense to exchange the annoying rook with} 20. Rc5 {, but then Black activates the other one with} Re8 21. Rxc4 Nxc4 22. Nd2 Nb2 $1 23. c4 Nxf4 24. Rxf4 Nd1+ 25. Kf1 f5 $1 {with a clear advantage. The black knight is doing a terrific job!}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How should Black meet the threat to his rook? '} 20... Rxc3 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'Grabbing the c3-pawn releases the pressure.'} ({ANSWER: Correct is} 20... Ra4 $1 21. Rb2 f6 22. Bg3 Re8 {, when Black's pieces are more active than their opposing counterparts, yielding a clear advantage. It is difficult to find a constructive plan for White, whereas it is easy for Black to improve his position move by move; for example, with ...Kf7, ...h7-h5, ...g7-g5 (if the opponent allows it!), ...Kg6 etc. Black can also consider ...Re6-c6 with his second rook, forcing White to put his knight in an even more passive position on b1, protecting c3 and a3.}) 21. Rxc3 Nxc3 22. Rc5 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} ({Breyer misses a chance to equalize with} 22. Rb3 $1 {and then:} Nbd5 $1 {is stronger, although White has his share of the chances in the rather hair-raising variation} (22... Ncd5 23. Bg3 {(intending to harass the centralized knight with c2-c4)} {Black can counter with} f5 24. Kf3 g5 25. c4 g4+ 26. Kf2 f4 27. cxd5 (27. Bh4 Ne3 $1) 27... fxg3+ 28. Kxg3 Nxd5 29. Kxg4 {, when White's activity compensates for Black's more compact position}) 23. Bxc7 Re8 24. Rxb7 Re2+ 25. Kf3 Re3+ (25... h5 $5) 26. Kf2 g5 27. Nb1 Re2+ 28. Kf3 g4+ 29. Kxg4 Nxb1 30. Be5 f6 31. c4 $1 Ne3+ $1 ({after} 31... fxe5 $2 32. cxd5 {, it is suddenly Black fighting for a draw!}) 32. Kf3 Nc3 33. Bxf6 Nxc4 34. Rg7+ Kf8 35. Rxa7 h5 36. a4 {, when a draw is the most likely outcome.}) 22... Nbd5 23. Bxc7 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: Where should Black put his rook? '} Rc8 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'This pseudo-pin should not achieve anything.'} ({ANSWER:} 23... Re8 $1 {is more dangerous. One plausible variation is} 24. Ba5 Nd1+ 25. Kg1 N1e3 26. c4 Nf4 {, when Black's enormous activity is too much for the white position to deal with in a proper way.}) 24. Bd6 {Thomas Engqvist: '??' Thomas Engqvist: 'The wrong direction.'} (24. Ba5 $1 {forces the exchange of rooks with} Rxc5 25. dxc5 {, when} Nxa2 {might be met by} 26. Ne4 Nab4 27. c4 Nf4 $1 28. Nd6 Nc6 29. Nxb7 Ne6 30. Bc3 {with good drawing chances.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How does Black exploit White's mistake? '} 24... Rxc5 {Thomas Engqvist: '??' Thomas Engqvist: 'Swapping the rooks off seriously jeopardizes Black's prospects of winning.'} ({ANSWER:} 24... Re8 $1 {is now even stronger than on the previous move, since the c3-knight can no longer be challenged, so Black can play ...f7-f6 and penetrate with the rook on the e-file; for example,} 25. Kf3 b6 26. Rc6 f6 27. Bg3 ({or} 27. Nf1 Nb5) 27... Re3+ 28. Kg4 Re2 {and so forth.}) 25. Bxc5 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Taking with the d-pawn is better as it makes the b7-pawn a target for the knight. '} ({After} 25. dxc5 Nxa2 26. Nb3 {(stopping Black from advancing his a-pawn)} f5 ({or similarly} 26... Nac3 27. Kf3 f6 28. Na5) 27. Na5 b6 28. Nb7 bxc5 29. Bxc5 {, White's strong bishop and the elimination of his doubled pawn means he has reasonably good drawing chances.}) 25... b6 26. Bd6 Nxa2 $2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Grabbing the a-pawn is too greedy. '} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'or'} 26... f6 $17 {Thomas Engqvist: ', followed by ...Kf7-e6, is the correct course.'}) (26... f5) 27. c4 Ndb4 28. d5 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!'} ({It is better to centralize the king first. A possible variation is} 28. Ke3 f6 29. Ne4 Kf7 30. d5 Ke8 31. g4 {and White has sufficient compensation for the pawn, with a space advantage in the centre and on the kingside.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: Why was White's move not the best? ANSWER:'} 28... b5 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Undermining White's central pawns before his king is ready to support them. '} 29. c5 $2 (29. cxb5 Nxd5 30. Bb8 $11) ({The logical continuation is} 29. Bc7 Kf8 30. d6 Ke8 31. cxb5 Nd5 32. Bb8 Nac3 33. Bxa7 Nxb5 34. Bc5 Kd7 35. Nc4 {and although Black will pick up the d6-pawn, it should not be too difficult to hold the draw with three versus two on the kingside, as long as White avoids the pawn ending.}) 29... Nxd5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Now it's a different story because Black has two connected distant passed pawns. '} 30. c6 Nac3 $1 ({Preparing to activate the king with} 30... f5 $1 {is more precise; for example} 31. c7 Nb6 32. Ke3 Kf7 33. Kd4 Ke6 34. Kc5 Kd7 35. Be5 g6 36. Kxb5 Nc1 {and Black has good winning chances.}) 31. c7 Nb6 32. Ke3 Nc8 33. Bg3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is Black's best continuation? '} Nd5+ {Thomas Engqvist: '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'This check only drives the white king further forward.'} ({ANSWER: Black needs to bring his own king into the game with} 33... Kf8 {, although White's activity should be sufficient to hold after} 34. Kd4 b4 35. Kc5 Ke8 36. Kc6 ({not} 36. Kxb4 $2 Ne2 37. Bf2 Nf4 38. Bg3 Nh5 39. Bf2 Kd7 {and the c7-pawn falls}) 36... Ne7+ 37. Kb7 Kd7 38. Kxa7 Kc8 39. Kb6 Ncd5+ 40. Kc5 Kd7 41. c8=Q+ $1 Kxc8 42. Bd6 Kd7 43. Bxe7 Nxe7 44. Kxb4 Nd5+ 45. Kc5 Ne3 46. g3 Ke6 47. Kd4 Ng4 48. Nf3 {and so forth.}) 34. Kd4 Nde7 35. Ne4 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} ({It was important to control the b-pawn with} 35. Kc5 {before centralizing the knight. If Black defends the pawn with} {If Black defends the pawn with} a6 {, the most likely result is a draw. Look at the following variation:} 36. Ne4 Kf8 37. Nd6 {(Black can hardly move his pieces so he has to advance his kingside pawns)} f6 38. h4 g5 39. hxg5 fxg5 40. Bh2 h5 41. Be5 h4 42. Bf6 {(now it is a forced draw)} b4 43. Nxc8 Nxc8 44. Kxb4 Ke8 45. Bxg5 Kd7 {etc.}) 35... b4 36. Kc4 f5 37. Nd6 g5 ({Seeing no prospect of holding onto his queenside pawns (e.g. after} 37... a5 38. Kb5 b3 39. Nxc8 Nxc8 40. Be5 {etc), Réti gets his kingside pawns moving.}) 38. Kxb4 f4 39. Nxc8 Nxc8 40. Be1 Kf7 41. Bd2 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'Breyer forgets to use his king.'} ({Correct is} 41. Kc5 Ke6 42. Kc6 g4 43. Kc5 $1 {with sufficient counterplay after the further 44 Kd4. White can pick off the kingside pawns and leave the a-pawn to the bishop.}) 41... Ke6 42. h4 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'Trying to undermine the kingside pawns.'} (42. Kc5 {is again a better try, although White will now have a tough time after} Kd7 {; for example,} 43. Bc3 Nd6 44. Kd5 Nb5 45. c8=Q+ Kxc8 46. Be1 Nc7+ 47. Kd6 h6 48. Ke5 Kd7 49. Kf5 Ne6 50. Kg6 Nc5 51. Kxh6 Nd3 52. Bc3 g4 {and wins.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is the problem with White's move? '} 42... h6 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} ({ANSWER: Black has a smooth win after} 42... f3 $1 43. gxf3 gxh4 {. White faces outside passed pawns on both sides of the board. If he goes for the a-pawn with his king, Black will force the front h-pawn through by manoeuvring his knight to f3; e.g.} 44. Ka5 Kd7 45. Bf4 h3 46. Ka6 Ne7 47. Kxa7 Kc8 {, followed by ...Ng6-h4 etc. If the white king goes the other way, Black will push his a-pawn down the board, pick up the c7-pawn, and then transfer his king to the kingside where he has another h-pawn in reserve.}) 43. Kc5 Kd7 44. Kd5 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} ({Here} 44. hxg5 hxg5 45. Kd5 Kxc7 46. Bb4 {, preventing ...Nd6, was the correct course} ({but not} 46. Ke5 Kc6 47. Kf5 $2 {due to} Nd6+ $1 {and wins in view of} 48. Kxg5 Ne4+ {.})) 44... Kxc7 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} ({Again missing} 44... f3 $1 45. gxf3 ({after the text, White can return to the previous note with} 45. hxg5 hxg5 46. Bb4) 45... gxh4 {and Black wins after} 46. Bxh6 Ne7+ 47. Ke4 a5 {and so on.}) 45. Ke6 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!'} Nd6 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} (45... Kc6 {is the best try. One fascinating, long line runs} 46. hxg5 hxg5 47. Bb4 ({not} 47. Kf5 $2 Nd6+ 48. Kxg5 Ne4+ {etc}) 47... g4 48. Kf5 f3 49. gxf3 g3 $1 50. Be1 g2 51. Bf2 a5 52. Kg4 a4 53. Kh3 a3 54. Kxg2 Kd5 $1 55. Bh4 Ke5 56. Be1 Kd4 57. Bh4 Nd6 58. Bf6+ Kd3 59. f4 a2 60. Kf3 Nc4 61. Ba1 ({not} 61. f5 $2 Ne3 $1) 61... Kc2 62. f5 Kb1 63. Bg7 $1 Nb2 64. f6 a1=Q 65. f7 {and surprisingly the game is a draw.}) 46. Bc3 {Thomas Engqvist: '??' Thomas Engqvist: 'A huge blunder. '} ({After the natural continuation} 46. hxg5 hxg5 47. Bb4 Nc4 48. Kf5 Ne3+ 49. Kxg5 Nxg2 {, Black cannot win.}) 46... Kc6 47. hxg5 hxg5 {Thomas Engqvist: '. White is two pawns down for nothing, so Breyer resigned. A game full of errors, but it was really exciting with an interesting ending. What the student can learn from the game is the enormous agility of the knight. It's easy to underestimate the knight when it struggles against a bishop, but here White's dark-squared bishop had a really hard time keeping pace with the black knight!'} 0-1


