{Martin Lokander: 'In our next game we will start covering 3 Nf3, and I think it's quite fascinating that a game played 94 years ago is still theoretically relevant today.' Martin Lokander: 'In our next game we will start covering 3 Nf3, and I think it's quite fascinating that a game played 94 years ago is still theoretically relevant today. '} 1. e4 {Bangiev Bangiev} e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 Nf6 {Martin Lokander: '!' '!' Martin Lokander: 'Nowadays most of the fuss is about 3...g5 and there is lots of analysis showing that perhaps Black is better. Still, White gets typical King's Gambit play which might be difficult to deal with practically, so why not pick something lesser known but still good for Black? After all, 3...Nf6 is a very logical move in all types of Open Games.' Martin Lokander: 'Nowadays most of the fuss is about 3...g5 and there is lots of analysis showing that perhaps Black is better. Still, White gets typical King's Gambit play which might be difficult to deal with practically, so why not pick something lesser known but still good for Black? After all, 3...Nf6 is a very logical move in all types of Open Games. '} 4. Nc3 ({The critical move is Martin Lokander: 'The critical move is '} 4. e5 {, as we will see, but John Shaw mentioned 4 Nc3 as a decent alternative in his recent book. Martin Lokander: ', as we will see, but John Shaw mentioned 4 Nc3 as a decent alternative in his recent book. '}) ({Alternatives like Martin Lokander: 'Alternatives like '} 4. d3) ({and Martin Lokander: 'and '} 4. Qe2 {will be covered in our next game.}) 4... d5 5. exd5 ({White could play Martin Lokander: 'White could play '} 5. e5 {, but Black just seems to obtain a very good position after Martin Lokander: ', but Black just seems to obtain a very good position after '} Nh5 $1 6. d4 {and now we have the important Martin Lokander: 'and now we have the important '} Nc6 $1 {. White's idea is generally to play Be2 and get to the knight on h5, but Black's clever ...Nc6 makes sure that this position works well for Black. Not only does the knight put pressure on d4, but Black could definitely use the option of castling long:} 7. Z0 (7. g3 {is a strange computer idea, but after Martin Lokander: 'is a strange computer idea, but after '} Bg4 $1 (7... fxg3 8. Ng5 $1 {actually gives White a decent attack}) 8. Bxf4 Nxf4 9. gxf4 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Bxf3 11. Rg1 c6 {there's no doubt that Black is much better with an extra pawn and the bishop pair. Martin Lokander: 'there's no doubt that Black is much better with an extra pawn and the bishop-pair.'}) (7. Be2 g5 $1 {(there's no reason to shy away from this now; White can't challenge the kingside with h2-h4 and the h5-knight can always spring to life on f5 via g7) Martin Lokander: '(there's no reason to shy away from this now; White can't challenge the kingside with h2-h4 and the h5-knight can always spring to life on f5 via g7) '} 8. Nxg5 Qxg5 9. Bxh5 Qh4+ $1 (9... Qxg2 $2 10. Bf3 {is not to be recommended, as the white knight on d5 will cause all kind of havoc in Black's position}) 10. Kf1 Be6 11. Bf3 f6 $1 {and Black successfully challenges White's centre in time. Indeed,} ({However, the immediate Martin Lokander: 'However, the immediate '} 11... O-O-O $2 12. Ne2 $1 {would allow White to consolidate his centre and put pressure on f4}) {Martin Lokander: '. Indeed,'} 12. Nxd5 O-O-O $1 {opens up the centre when the weakness of the king on f1 will become apparent. Martin Lokander: 'opens up the centre when the weakness of the king on f1 will become apparent. '})) 5... Nxd5 6. Nxd5 ({Shaw gives some very good and interesting analysis on the move Martin Lokander: 'Shaw gives some very good and interesting analysis on the move '} 6. Bc4 {, but he himself doesn't believe it holds up if Black plays accurately:} Nxc3 $1 7. dxc3 (7. bxc3 $6 Bd6 {will most likely lead to an endgame after Martin Lokander: 'will most likely lead to an endgame after '} 8. Qe2+ Qe7 9. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {where White seems to be struggling for compensation, as Shaw points out}) 7... Bd6 $1 {. This is a risky strategy which leads to double-edged complications according to Shaw. After looking through his excellent analysis of the alternatives, I felt that even though Black can get a better position, White isn't far from a draw. Eventually I managed to find an improvement on Shaw's analysis: Martin Lokander: '. This is a risky strategy which leads to double-edged complications according to Shaw. After looking through his excellent analysis of the alternatives, I felt that even though Black can get a better position, White isn't far from a draw. Eventually I managed to find an improvement on Shaw's analysis: '} 8. O-O O-O 9. Nd4 Qg5 $1 {. This move doesn't look like the most logical one, walking straight into a pin along the c1-h6 diagonal. However, Black has a clever idea in mind: Martin Lokander: '. This move doesn't look like the most logical one, walking straight into a pin along the c1-h6 diagonal. However, Black has a clever idea in mind: '} 10. Qf3 Qc5 $1 {. This is where Black's queen was heading. Black gains a tempo attacking c4 while also planning to utilize a pin himself. --- Now after Martin Lokander: '. This is where Black's queen was heading. Black gains a tempo attacking c4 while also planning to utilize a pin himself. Now after'} 11. Bd5 (11. Bb3 Nc6 {puts pressure on d4 and makes sure that White won't get his pawn back}) 11... Nd7 {Black is threatening ...Ne5 so White is pretty much forced to play Martin Lokander: 'Black is threatening ...Ne5 so White is pretty much forced to play '} 12. b4 Qb6 13. Bxf4 Bxf4 14. Qxf4 Nf6 {. White has managed to regain his f4-pawn, but the weaknesses created with b2-b4 are permanent and Black will enjoy a good game with ...a5 and perhaps ...c5.}) 6... Qxd5 7. d4 Be7 $1 {Martin Lokander: 'The best square for the bishop.'} ({Martin Lokander: 'It can help prepare ...g5, which is more useful than playing it to d6:'} 7... Bd6 8. c4 Qe4+ 9. Kf2 {has scored incredibly well for White, who will develop quickly with Bd3 and Re1.}) 8. c4 ({Otherwise,} 8. Bxf4 $4 {immediately drops a piece to Martin Lokander: 'immediately drops a piece to '} Qe4+ {;}) ({while Martin Lokander: 'while '} 8. Be2 g5 $1 {leaves White short of ideas on how to regain the f4-pawn.}) 8... Qd6 {Martin Lokander: '!' '!' Martin Lokander: 'This move is omitted in Shaw's analysis, but it looks very good for Black. Basically Black intends to hang on to his pawn on f4 and on d6 the queen is flexibly placed.'} ({Shaw only analyzes} 8... Qe4+ {, when White gains a lot of time attacking the queen further on.}) 9. Bd3 ({Martin Lokander: 'Alternatively: White could try to regain the pawn on f4 with' Martin Lokander: 'Alternatively: White could try to regain the pawn on f4 with '} 9. c5 $5 {Bangiev} Qd5 (9... Qf6 10. Bb5+ (10. Qa4+ $5) (10. Qd2 {, but playing c4-c5 is terrible positionally. Black is simply better after} Be6 11. Qxf4 Bd5 {.}) 10... c6 11. Be2 Be6 $13 { Kortschnoj,V-Borisenko,G/Tula 1950}) 10. Be2 g5 11. O-O Nc6 $36 { Shipman,W-Friedman,L/USA jr 1947}) ({The immediate Martin Lokander: 'The immediate '} 9. Qd2 g5 {is nothing to worry about either.}) 9... g5 ({Brinckmann's move is very sensible, protecting his extra pawn and maintaining a good position, but I'd be interested in playing Martin Lokander: 'Brinckmann's move is very sensible, protecting his extra pawn and maintaining a good position, but I'd be interested in playing '} 9... Nc6 $5 {as well, putting pressure on the d4-pawn. After Martin Lokander: 'as well, putting pressure on the d4-pawn. After '} 10. d5 Ne5 11. Nxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Qe2 f6 {we will get an endgame and following ...g5 Black seems to be a clean pawn up.}) 10. Qe2 Bg4 (10... g4 $5 {Bangiev} 11. c5 $5 $13) 11. Bd2 (11. Qe5 $5 {Bangiev} Qxe5+ 12. Nxe5 Be6 13. O-O $13) 11... Nc6 {Bangiev: '' '' Martin Lokander: '!' '!'} 12. Bc3 O-O-O (12... Nxd4 {Bangiev} 13. Bxd4 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Qxd4 15. Qxb7 O-O $17) 13. O-O-O Bf6 $13 {Bangiev: '' '' Martin Lokander: 'Some annotator at ChessBase gives the evaluation as unclear at this point, but I don't think it's that unclear. White lacks serious compensation for his pawn.' Martin Lokander: 'Some annotator at ChessBase gives the evaluation as unclear at this point, but I don't think it's that unclear. White lacks serious compensation for his pawn. '} 14. Rhe1 Ne7 {Martin Lokander: '?' '?' Martin Lokander: 'This doesn't look right.' Martin Lokander: 'This doesn't look right. '} ({Martin Lokander: 'I don't see what's wrong with' Martin Lokander: 'I don't see what's wrong with '} 14... Nxd4 $1 {Bangiev Martin Lokander: ', grabbing a second pawn. Moreover, I thought it was still the custom for players in the early 20th Century to accept sacrifices.'} 15. Bf5+ $1 Bxf5 16. Nxd4 (16. Bxd4 Qa6 $17) 16... Bxd4 17. Bxd4 f6 $17) 15. Qf2 Bf5 16. Qc2 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Qd7 {Martin Lokander: '?!' '?!'} 18. Nd2 $1 {Bangiev: '?!' '?!' Martin Lokander: '?!' '?!'} ({Martin Lokander: 'White could have grabbed the initiative with' Martin Lokander: 'White could have grabbed the initiative with '} 18. d5 $1 $36 {Bangiev Martin Lokander: '!' '!'} Bxc3 19. Qxc3 {when Black has to consider Nxg5, Ne5 and Qf6. Black's kingside is quite weak.}) 18... Nf5 19. Ne4 Be7 (19... Bxd4 $1 {Bangiev} 20. Nc5 Bxc5 21. Qxd7+ Rxd7 22. Rxd7 Kxd7 23. Bxh8 Ne3 $36) 20. d5 {Bangiev: '!?' '!?'} Rhg8 21. c5 {Bangiev: '!?' '!?'} (21. Nf6 {Bangiev} Bxf6 22. Bxf6 $44) 21... Ne3 $1 {Martin Lokander: '?' '?'} 22. Rxe3 {Bangiev: '!' '!' Martin Lokander: '!' '!' Martin Lokander: 'A strong exchange sacrifice, not losing any time and eliminating Black's best piece. White's attack should now be decisive.'} (22. c6 Qxd5 23. Rxe3 Qxc6 $19) 22... fxe3 23. c6 {Bangiev: '!' '!'} bxc6 24. Qa6+ Kb8 25. Bd4 {Bangiev: '!' '!'} c5 26. Bxc5 (26. Nxc5 $2 Bxc5 27. Bxc5 c6 28. Rd3 Rc8 $1 29. d6 e2 $19) 26... c6 27. Rd3 Ka8 28. dxc6 $2 {Martin Lokander: 'Spoiling a beautiful attack.' Martin Lokander: 'Spoiling a beautiful attack. '} (28. d6