{Thomas Engqvist: 'Efim Bogoljubow (1889-1952) was born in Kiev, Russia. He is regarded as one of the greatest masters in the history of chess, playing two World Championship matches against Alekhine in 1929 and 1934, and was actually ranked No.1 in the world in early 1927, according to Chessmetrics. His games are characterized by strong dynamics and by play on both sides of the board. Combined with an optimistic attitude this made him a very dangerous opponent indeed. Bogoljubow is famous for saying: "When I am White I win because I am White. When I am Black I win because I am Bogoljubow!" In 'Masters of the Chess Board', Réti mentions that self-confidence is an extremely important asset, since the psychological element plays a more significant part of the game today than it did in the past. From a practical point of view it is better to think that the glass is half full rather than half empty, even if a player's evaluations from time to time as a consequence will be slightly biased. '} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: What is the name of this opening? ANSWER: This is the McCutcheon Variation of the French Defence, named after the American amateur John Lindsay McCutcheon (1857-1905) who played it against Steinitz in a simultaneous display in New York 1885, winning in only 28 moves. His system is still regarded as reliable, though its complicated nature will not suit everyone. It was used occasionally by most of the great players of Réti's day, and was a favourite of Viktor Korchnoi towards the end of his career. Today, its most consistent practitioners are the Russian GMs Igor Glek and Sergey Volkov. Réti and Bogoljubow contested this variation six times from both sides. This was the only game Réti managed to win; he lost all the others. '} 5. e5 h6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION (candidate moves): What are White's options and best move? ANSWER:'} 6. Bd2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'This solid retreat is regarded as the main line;'} ({though} 6. Be3 Ne4 7. Qg4 g6 ({or} 7... Kf8) 8. a3 {is a critical alternative, sacrificing a pawn for development.}) ({Staying on the h4-d8 diagonal, on the other hand, is ineffective:} 6. Bh4 g5 7. Bg3 Ne4 8. Nge2 c5 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. Nxc3 Qa5 11. Qd3 Nc6 {led to mutual chances in O.Bernstein-R.Swiderski, Coburg 1904.}) ({In the aforementioned simultaneous Steinitz played the harmless} 6. Bxf6 $6 gxf6 {, which gave Black the bishop pair as well as additional pressure on the centre. The game continued} 7. Nf3 f5 $6 ({one of} 7... fxe5) (7... Nd7) ({and} 7... c5 {is better}) 8. Bd3 c5 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. O-O Nc6 11. Qd2 Qe7 12. Qf4 Bd7 13. Nb5 O-O-O 14. c4 Be8 15. Rfc1 Kb8 16. a3 a6 17. Nc3 dxc4 18. Bxc4 Nd4 19. Ne2 Nxf3+ 20. Qxf3 Bc6 21. Qh3 Ka7 22. b4 Bb6 23. Nc3 Rhg8 24. Bf1 Rd2 25. Nd1 Qg5 26. Rxc6 bxc6 27. Qc3 Qf4 28. Qxc6 Rxd1 {0-1. It has to be said that this was a pretty good marketing game for the McCutcheon's opening!}) ({The sharp variation} 6. exf6 hxg5 7. fxg7 Rg8 {"leads to nothing", according to Fischer in 'My 60 Memorable Games'; for example, after} 8. a3 ({or} 8. h4 gxh4 9. Qg4 Qf6) {In the latter line, it is also possible to give up the bishop pair and destroy White's pawn formation with} 8... Bxc3+ (8... Be7 $1 9. Qh5 Rxg7 {, the position is fairly equal.} (9... Z0)) 9. bxc3 {and then continue} Qf6 {. Here the 2004 FIDE World Champion, Rustam Kasimdzhanov, recommends} 10. Qd3 Qxg7 11. Qg3 {. Black's best response may be} f6 12. O-O-O Qe7 13. Kb2 Nd7 $1 {, intending} 14. Qxc7 $6 ({nevertheless, after} 14. h4 Nb6 15. hxg5 Bd7 16. gxf6 Na4+ 17. Kb1 Rxg3 18. fxe7 Nxc3+ 19. Kc1 Rg8 20. Re1 Kxe7 21. Nf3 {, White has a small but clearly visible advantage since the e5-square is weak}) 14... Nb6 15. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {with sufficient compensation for the pawn due to White's weaknesses on the queenside.}) 6... Bxc3 7. Bxc3 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' '?!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Fischer calls this move "ridiculous", having lost a famous game with it (see the next note).'} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'The main variation goes '} 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Bc1 $1 (8. Qg4 g6 9. Bd3 Nxd2 10. Kxd2 c5 {. See, for example, the hard-fought game R.J.Fischer-N.Rossolimo, US Championship, New York 1965, which Fischer won after only 32 moves; or indeed E.Bogoljubow-R.Réti, Breslau 1925, which White won in 29 moves.})) 7... Ne4 8. Bb4 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'In R.J.Fischer-T.V.Petrosian, Curacao Candidates 1962, White played '} 8. Ba5 $6 {Fischer-Petrosjan, Curacao 1962/ Fischer-Petrosjan, Curacao 1962/ Thomas Engqvist: ', which was a recommendation by the Russian endgame expert Kopaev. Afterwards, Fischer was very disappointed with the awkward bishop manoeuvre and gave it two question marks in his book. The lesson is perhaps that you should not trust an endgame expert's opening analyses! The idea is to answer '} b6 ({after} 8... O-O 9. Bd3 Nc6 10. Bc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 f6 $5 {, White was already slightly worse and eventually lost in 43 moves}) {, with} 9. Bb4 {and} c5 {with} 10. Ba3 {, creating positional pressure on the a3-f8 diagonal. However, the whole plan backfires if Black postpones any threat to the bishop until castling has been made.}) 8... c5 9. Bxc5 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'White has to give up his dark-squared bishop after all, since '} 9. dxc5 {Thomas Engqvist: '??' '??' Thomas Engqvist: 'is a grave mistake due to'} Nxf2 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!'} 10. Kxf2 Qh4+ $17 11. g3 Qxb4 {, when White has difficulties defending his pawns situated on the now unprotected dark squares.}) 9... Nxc5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'It is unclear why Réti elected to change his move here in a later game. '} ({The inferior continuation} 9... Nc6 $6 10. Ba3 Qa5+ 11. c3 Nxc3 $6 12. Qd2 Na4 13. Qxa5 Nxa5 14. b3 Nb6 15. Nf3 {led to an advantage for White in E.Bogoljubow-R.Réti, Baden-Baden 1925.}) 10. dxc5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is the strongest continuation for Black? '} Qa5+ ({ANSWER: Black has several good moves here; Réti's choice is fine, while R.Spielmann-A.Nimzowitsch, Gothenburg 1920, saw} 10... Nd7 11. Qd4 Qc7 12. Nf3 Nxc5 {with comfortable play for Black.}) ({However, the most flexible equalizer, according to Kasimdzhanov, is} 10... Qc7 $1 11. f4 ({or} 11. Nf3 Qxc5 {with convenient play; note that} 12. Qd4 $6 {drops the c2-pawn}) 11... Nd7 {, intending to recapture on c5 with the knight now that White's f2-f4 has weakened the e4-square. After} 12. Nf3 ({or} 12. b4 $6 b6) 12... Nxc5 13. Qd4 Bd7 14. O-O-O Rc8 15. Kb1 O-O {, Black has a harmonious position (and} 16. g4 {is met by} f6 {).}) 11. c3 ({The alternative is} 11. Qd2 {so Black might prefer simply} Qxd2+ ({and if} 11... Qxc5 {, Kasimdzhanov recommends} 12. f4 O-O 13. Nf3 Nc6 14. O-O-O Bd7 15. Kb1 {, followed by h2-h4 and Rh3 with attacking chances on the kingside;} (15. Z0)) 12. Kxd2 Nd7 13. Bb5 Ke7 14. Bxd7 Bxd7 {, followed by ...Rhc8 and ...Rxc5 with a decent position}) 11... Qxc5 12. Qd4 ({The Russian theoretician Vasily Panov suggested} 12. Nf3 {and 13 Bd3, but it does not cause Black any problems.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: What is Black's most natural and logical move? ANSWER:'} 12... Qc7 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The idea of exploiting the white queen on d4 with ...Nc6 looks indeed both logical and natural. According to GM Jonathan Tisdall in Improve your Chess NOW, the difference between natural and logical moves is a valid issue. Tisdall means that a natural move is usually obvious, whereas a logical move may not be obvious at all. '} ({If we look at the "natural" continuation} 12... Qxd4 13. cxd4 Nc6 {, it does not appear logical. What is the logic behind trading queens when you have the French bishop?}) ({A third option,} 12... b6 {, is fully playable and yet looks neither natural nor logical.}) 13. Nf3 Nc6 14. Bb5 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' '?!' Thomas Engqvist: 'The beginning of a flawed strategy.'} (14. Qe3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'is a better alternative, delaying the f1-bishop's development (in Réti style) until it becomes more clear where it should be placed; more likely it belongs on d3.'}) 14... O-O 15. Bxc6 $2 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'or'} 15. Qc5 {Thomas Engqvist: '!?' '!?' Thomas Engqvist: 'is reasonable and equal.'}) ({Either} 15. Qe3) 15... bxc6 16. b4 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'This was Bogoljubow's plan. He aims to prevent ...c6-c5, cement control of the central light squares, and play with a 'good' knight vs. 'bad' bishop, but he will not be successful. '} ({It was better simply to castle with} 16. O-O {, though White now stands a little worse after} c5 {.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is the problem with White's move? ANSWER:'} 16... Ba6 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'First of all, Black's bishop is not actually bad at all and takes up a strong diagonal, stopping White from castling. '} ({Positionally speaking,} 16... a5 {is a good move too, but it allows White to solve the main tactical problem, finding safety for his king, by playing} 17. O-O {.}) 17. Kd2 ({It makes sense to leave the d2-square for the knight; for example, after the useful} 17. a4 {and the obvious (natural)} Bc4 {, White has} 18. Nd2 {. This would be quite okay were not for} c5 $1 19. Qxc5 ({or} 19. bxc5 Ba6 $1) 19... Qxe5+ 20. Qe3 Qc7 {with a clear advantage for Black, who has a very strong central pawn structure, while White's c3-pawn looks pretty weak.}) 17... Rac8 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Preparing the ...c6-c5 break is logical. '} ({Nevertheless,} 17... Bc4 $1 {, followed by ...a7-a5, looks a more dangerous way of putting pressure on White's position and trying to open up a file.}) 18. Qc5 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' '?'} ({Rather than preventing ...c6-c5 it was better to allow it, when White at least gains a good blockading square on d4 for his knight. For example, after} 18. Rhe1 c5 19. Qxc5 Qxc5 ({or} 19... Qd7 20. Qe3) 20. bxc5 Rxc5 21. Nd4 Rfc8 22. Rec1 {, White is only slightly worse with three pawns islands versus Black's two.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is the drawback to White's strategy? ANSWER:'} 18... f6 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'This is the reason it was more in order to overprotect the important e5-pawn with Rhe1 on the previous move.'} 19. Rhe1 fxe5 20. Nxe5 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Of course not '} 20. Rxe5 $2 {Thomas Engqvist: '??' '??'} Rxf3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'and wins.'}) 20... Rf5 $1 21. Qe3 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' '?'} (21. Nf3 e5 22. h3 Rcf8 23. Kd1 Bd3 $19) ({The most resistant line is} 21. Qd4 c5 22. bxc5 ({not} 22. Qxc5 $4 {due to} Rxf2+ $1 {and if} 23. Qxf2 $6 {then} Qxc3+ 24. Kd1 Qxa1+ 25. Kd2 Qc3+ 26. Kd1 Qc1#) 22... Rcf8 23. f3 Rf4 24. Qe3 Ra4 25. Red1 Rf5 ({or} 25... Ra3 26. Ke1) 26. Nd3 {and White has some hopes of surviving, even with his king standing uncomfortably in the middle of the board.}) (21. Ng6 $2 Re8 22. f4 {fails to} Rf6 23. Ne5 Rxf4 24. Kc2 Rf5 {and Black should win.}) 21... c5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Strangely, some sources have White playing '} 22. Rec1 {Thomas Engqvist: '??' '??' Thomas Engqvist: ', which is obviously wrong since it leaves the e5-knight hanging.'} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'The difference from the previous note, where White played the queen to d4, is that Black can now meet '} 22. bxc5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'with the strong '} Qa5 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: ', threatening 23...d4! and wins. The 'correction' '} 23. Nd3 (23. Qd4 {fails to solve the problem, since Black ignores the c5-pawn and plays to enforce the ...d5-d4 break with} Rcf8 $1 24. Nf3 ({or} 24. f3 Rf4 {and ...d5-d4 next move}) 24... Rf4 25. Qe5 d4 {, when White's position collapses.}) 23... Rf6 $19) (22. Rac1 {EXERCISE: Black already has a winning position. How does he proceed? ANSWER:} cxb4 $1 ({Or} 22... d4 $1 23. cxd4 cxd4 {, which leads to the same position.}) 23. cxb4 d4 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: ', which leads to the same position.'} 24. Qg3 {The only move;} (24. Qxd4 $2 {again runs into} Rxf2+ $1 25. Qxf2 (25. Ke3 Rc2 {wins as well}) 25... Rd8+ {and the white king is trapped in the centre. Komodo declares mate in eight.}) 24... Qd6 $2 ({More precise is} 24... Qb7 $1 {, leaving the bishop on the a6-f1 diagonal. After} 25. Rxc8+ Qxc8 26. f4 ({or} 26. Rc1 Qf8 27. Nd3 Bxd3 28. Kxd3 Qxb4 {, White will not survive for long}) 26... d3 27. Rc1 Qb7 28. Nc6 e5 $1 {(this second breakthrough decides)} 29. fxe5 Qf7 {, the white king is too exposed with so many entries for Black's major pieces.}) 25. Rxc8+ Bxc8 26. Nd3 $2 ({The best defence is} 26. a3 a5 27. Ng4 {, when Black must find the spectacular} e5 $1 28. Rxe5 ({or} 28. bxa5 Qe6 $1) 28... Rf8 $1 29. Rxa5 Qe6 {, threatening ...Qa2+. A truly amazing formation! Play might continue} 30. Rc5 $1 d3 $1 ({after} 30... Qxg4 $2 31. Qxg4 Bxg4 32. f3 Bd7 33. Kd3 {, the d4-pawn falls and White has realistic drawing chances with three pawns for the piece}) 31. Qxd3 ({or} 31. Nxh6+ Qxh6+ 32. Qg5 Qxh2) 31... Qxg4 32. Qc4+ Qxc4 33. Rxc4 Be6 ({or} 33... Ba6 $5) 34. Rc2 Rxf2+ 35. Kc3 Rf4 {, when White is fighting hard for a draw but, with only two pawns for the bishop here, the chances of succeeding look slim indeed.}) 26... Qd5 {0-1 (37) Bogoljubow,E-Reti,R 19: Kiel 1921 MBM: Réti [Thomas Engqvist]}) 22... cxb4 $3 23. cxb4 d4 $1 24. Qg3 (24. Qxd4 Rxf2+ $1 25. Ke3 Rc2 $19) 24... Qd6 25. Rxc8+ Bxc8 26. Nd3 Qd5 27. Rc1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How does Black keep the deadly initiative going? ANSWER:'} Ba6 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Yes, by hitting the key defender. White cannot hold all the weaknesses in his position. '} ({The greedy} 27... Qxa2+ $4 {is considerably worse: after} 28. Rc2 Qa6 29. Rc7 {, White is fully in the game again.}) 28. Nc5 d3 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!'} ({With the c-file temporarily obstructed, it is now safe and simpler to take the pawn:} 28... Qxa2+ 29. Rc2 Qa1 30. Nxa6 Qxa6 31. Rc7 Qa2+ {with a winning position.}) 29. Nb3 {Thomas Engqvist: '?'} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Taking the bishop leaves the white king too exposed: '} 29. Nxa6 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' '?'} Qxa2+ 30. Kxd3 Qxa6+ (30... Rd5+ 31. Ke4 Qe2+ 32. Qe3 Qg4+ 33. f4 Qxg2+ 34. Qf3 Qg6+ $1 35. f5 Rxf5 {and Black wins.})) ({The only move to put up some sort of resistance is} 29. Nxd3 {, although after} Bxd3 30. Rc8+ Kh7 31. Qxd3 Qxg2 {, White still has a difficult position to defend.}) 29... Qe4 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Bogoljubow must have overlooked the double threat to b4 and e2. Now the game is practically over. '} 30. Qb8+ Rf8 31. Qxa7 Qe2+ 32. Kc3 d2 33. Rg1 ({Or} 33. Nxd2 Rc8+ {.}) 33... Rc8+ 34. Nc5 Qc4+ 35. Kb2 Qxb4+ 36. Nb3 Qc3+ ({Komodo prefers} 36... Bd3 $1 {, followed by ...Rc2+, but the text move is good enough.}) 37. Ka3 Be2 {Thomas Engqvist: '. Unfortunately, this was as good as it got for Réti, who only managed one other win in this four-player round robin tournament and finished last on 4½ out of 12, scoring 1½/4 against each of the other participants. Bogoljubow came first on 7½ points, with Brinckmann and Sämisch joint second on 6 points.'} 0-1


