{Thomas Engqvist: 'The German grandmaster Friedrich "Fritz" Sämisch (1896-1975) was a professional chess player. His highest ranking was 10th in the world, in 1929, with an estimated rating of 2665, according to Chessmetrics. He is perhaps most famous nowadays for his systems against the King's Indian and Nimzo-Indian Defences, being mainly a 1 d4 player as White, though he seemed happy to play either side of any reputable opening. 'The Oxford Companion to Chess' states that "his most notable match victory was against Réti in 1922", which he won by the score of 5½-2½. The game below is the only one he lost. ''The German grandmaster Friedrich "Fritz" Sämisch (1896-1975) was a professional chess player. His highest ranking was 10th in the world, in 1929, with an estimated rating of 2665, according to Chessmetrics. He is perhaps most famous nowadays for his systems against the King's Indian and Nimzo-Indian Defences, being mainly a 1 d4 player as White, though he seemed happy to play either side of any reputable opening. 'The Oxford Companion to Chess' states that "his most notable match victory was against Réti in 1922", which he won by the score of 5½-2½. The game below is the only one he lost.  Reti,Richard: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'The German grandmaster Friedrich "Fritz" Sämisch (1896-1975) was a professional chess player. His highest ranking was 10th in the world, in 1929, with an estimated rating of 2665, according to Chessmetrics. He is perhaps most famous nowadays for his systems against the King's Indian and Nimzo-Indian Defences, being mainly a 1 d4 player as White, though he seemed happy to play either side of any reputable opening. 'The Oxford Companion to Chess' states that "his most notable match victory was against Réti in 1922", which he won by the score of 5½-2½. The game below is the only one he lost. '''} 1. d4 {1)Het Vaderland 1922 APR 08/ 2)Kagans Neueste Schachnachrichten 1923, S.4} Nf6 2. Nf3 b6 3. c4 Bb7 ({Playing} 3... e6 {straight away is more flexible, keeping options open for both bishops; for instance, the c8-bishop sometimes develops at a6, while the f8-bishop can go to b4, taking the game into the Nimzo- or Bogo-Indian Defences.}) 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 ({More common today is} 5. a3 {, preventing ...Bb4 and preparing d4-d5 as well as Qc2 and e2-e4}) ({or else} 5. Bg5 {, trying to do without a2-a3 while fighting for the same squares.}) 5... Bxf3 $1 ({Normal continuations are either} 5... Bb4 {, leading to the Nimzo-Indian (a good choice for Black);}) ({or the more restrained but fully viable} 5... Be7 {, followed by ...Ne4, which is one of the main lines of the Queen's Indian. On the other hand, Sämisch knew those defences from both sides of the board; the text does at least change the character of the game.}) 6. exf3 d5 ({Here too} 6... Bb4 {is a decent choice, not disclosing the pawn formation too early in the game.}) 7. cxd5 Nxd5 ({Otherwise,} 7... exd5 {is a serious alternative, keeping the knights on the board.}) 8. Bg2 ({Completing the fianchetto is natural enough, but} 8. Nxd5 $1 Qxd5 9. Bd3 {looks more convincing if White wants to appreciate the value of the light-squared bishop both in the short and long terms.}) 8... Be7 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'In a later game Réti tried ' Reti; Viel besser war Thomas Engqvist: 'Reti,Richard: 'Reti; Viel besser war''} 8... g6 $142 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Reti,Richard: ''' nebst g7, zumal g6 auch den evet. Vorstoß f4-f5 verhindert hätte. Thomas Engqvist: 'Reti,Richard: 'nebst g7, zumal g6 auch den evet. Vorstoß f4-f5 verhindert hätte.''} {Taking on d5 is critical; for example,} 9. Nxd5 $1 (9. f4 $6 c6 10. O-O Bg7 11. Ne2 O-O {and equalized in E.Grünfeld-R.Réti, Breslau 1925.} (11... Z0)) 9... Qxd5 10. O-O c6 11. f4 Qd7 12. Re1 Na6 ({not} 12... Bg7 $2 13. d5 $1) 13. Bd2 Nc7 14. Qa4 Nd5 15. Rac1 {and White wins a pawn, although} Bg7 16. Qxc6 Qxc6 17. Rxc6 Kd7 {does offer Black reasonable drawing chances.}) ({Therefore} 8... c6 $1 {is probably necessary, so that Nxd5 can be answered ...c6xd5, removing a potential weak pawn on the c-file, even if it means Black giving up on his plan.}) 9. f4 ({Again,} 9. Nxd5 $1 {is the critical test, intending after} exd5 ({while} 9... Qxd5 $6 10. O-O {and f3-f4 gives strong White pressure on the long light diagonal. Note that} c6 11. f4 Qd7 {fails to} 12. f5 $1 exf5 13. d5 {, and was perhaps the justification for Réti's early ...g7-g6 in the previous note}) 10. Be3 ({or} 10. Bf4 {to organize pressure on the c-file.})) 9... c6 10. O-O ({Reti: Hier kam} 10. f5 {sehr in Betracht.}) 10... O-O 11. Qe2 ({Another possibility is} 11. f5 exf5 12. Qf3 Na6 (12... Nxc3 13. bxc3 g6 {is met by} 14. d5 {with a clear advantage}) 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Qxf5 Nc7 15. Be3 {, when White is at least slightly better owing to the bishop pair and more active pieces, while Black's c7-knight, defending the d5-pawn, is rather unstable.}) 11... Bf6 ({The immediate} 11... g6 {is more precise, consolidating the light squares before deciding upon the arrangement of his pieces.}) 12. Rd1 ({Similarly,} 12. Be3 {might be played first, followed by Rc1 and perhaps doubling on the c-file, with a more active treatment of the rooks; for example,} g6 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Rfc1 {.}) 12... g6 {cf 8...g6} 13. Be3 a6 $1 ({ANSWER: A more reliable set-up is} 13... Bg7 14. Rac1 Nd7 {, with the idea of ...N7f6, ...Ne7, ...Nfd5 and ...Nf5. The b8-knight would be most happy if placed on the f5 outpost, and the outlined move order seems to be the best way to achieve this.}) ({The alternative} 13... a5 $2 {, planning ...Na6-c7-e8-d6-f5, does not work because of Black's weaknesses on the queenside, particularly b5 and c6, as the following variation illustrates:} 14. Nxd5 cxd5 ({or} 14... exd5 15. Rac1 {with pressure on the weak c6-pawn}) 15. Rac1 Bg7 16. Qb5 Nd7 17. Rc6 {and White is in control of the queenside, while the weakness of the b6-pawn prevents the black knight from moving any further.}) 14. Rac1 Ra7 15. a3 ({Another option is to change the pawn structure with} 15. Nxd5 cxd5 {and then continue} 16. g4 {, preparing the break f4-f5, although after} Qd7 17. Qc2 Be7 18. f5 Bd6 {, Black seems only to be slightly worse.}) 15... Ne7 {Reti: Nun droht Schwarz bereits Eroberung des Bauern d4.} 16. Ne4 $1 {Weiß gewinnt Zeit, um diesen Springer rechtzeitig nach f3 zu überführen.} Bg7 17. Ng5 ({The continuation} 17. b4 $5 Rd7 18. a4 Nf5 19. a5 Nxd4 20. Qf1 {or 20 Qa2 suggests itself, followed by a5xb6 and Nc5, when White's tremendous piece activity promises more than enough compensation for the pawn. Note that} bxa5 $4 {loses to} 21. Nc5 Rd6 22. Nb7 {, so Black must defend passively. This would be a more active way for White to handle the position, while showing that the isolated queen's pawn can often be sacrificed for dynamic opportunities. This is logical as eventually everything is about having more activity than the opposing army.}) 17... Rd7 18. Nf3 Nf5 19. Ne5 Bxe5 ({The passive} 19... Rd6 $6 {is no better; White improves his rooks with} 20. Rd2 {keeping a clear edge.}) ({ANSWER: The correct and consistent continuation is} 19... Nxd4 $1 20. Bxd4 ({or if} 20. Qe1 {only then} Bxe5 21. fxe5 c5 {, keeping the extra pawn, although White has sufficient compensation with his bishop pair}) 20... Rxd4 21. Rxd4 Qxd4 22. Rc4 Qd6 23. Nxc6 b5 24. Rc1 Nxc6 25. Rxc6 Qd4 {with an equal game. The dark-squared bishop in particular might be troublesome for Black if he does not play actively enough.}) 20. dxe5 ({This is obviously stronger than} 20. fxe5 {, when Black can just take on d4 again with balanced play.}) 20... c5 ({Neither} 20... Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 Qc7 22. b4) ({nor} 20... Nxe3 21. Rxd7 Qxd7 22. Qxe3 Qc7 23. b4 {alters the assessment that White is now clearly better. The queenside pawns are a supreme target for White's forces.}) 21. Rxd7 Qxd7 22. Rd1 (22. b4 {looks critical, concentrating on the main weaknesses in Black's position. One plausible variation is} Nxe3 23. Qxe3 cxb4 24. axb4 a5 {probably best;} (24... Qb5 $6 {can be met by} 25. f5 $1 gxf5 26. Bf1 {, intending Rc4 with threats on both flanks}) 25. Qxb6 axb4 26. Qxb4 Rc8 27. Rxc8+ Qxc8 28. h4 {with a definite advantage; the position is unpleasant for Black with his remaining knight lacking a reliable outpost, even if he has reasonable chances to hold with all the pawns on the same side.}) 22... Nd4 ({Sidestepping with} 22... Qc7 {is a more resilient defence.}) 23. Bxd4 ({Another way to work on the centralized knight is shown by} 23. Qc4 Rd8 24. Rd2 a5 25. b4 $1 {, when Black should play} axb4 26. axb4 Qa4 27. Bxd4 Rxd4 ({not} 27... cxd4 $2 28. Qc7 {, winning both the b6- and d4-pawns}) 28. Rxd4 cxd4 29. Qxd4 Nc6 30. Qxb6 Qd1+ $1 (30... Nxb4 $6 31. Qd4 Qa5 32. h4 {gives White a similar advantage to that after 22 b4 above}) 31. Bf1 Nd4 {with sufficient counterplay against the white king; for example,} 32. Qb7 ({or} 32. h4 Nf3+ 33. Kg2 Ne1+ 34. Kh3 Qd5) 32... Nf3+ 33. Kg2 Ne1+ 34. Kh1 Nd3 35. Kg1 Qe1 36. Qb6 Nxb4 {and Black has much better drawing chances, having managed to activate his pieces.}) 23... Rd8 24. Be4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'But the text move creates new dark square weaknesses in his position, which White can exploit with '} b5 ({Presumably Réti refrained from} 24... cxd4 {because he did not like} 25. Qc4 {.}) 25. Rd3 (25. Qd2 $1 cxd4 26. Qa5 {, followed by Qb6, when the queen penetrates even deeper into Black's position than after Qc4.}) 25... cxd4 26. Qd2 {Reti: Es ist eine schwer zu beurteilende Stellung entstanden. Schwarz aht den Bauern d4 gewissermaßen mehr, da der weiße Doppelbauer keine Kompensation dafür ist. Dagegen laboriert das schwarze Spiel an der Schwierigkeit, den b8 ins Spiel zu bringen.} Qa7 {Reti: Droht mit a6-a5 nebst b6 und a6 den Springer ins Spiel zu führen, worauf die Partie für Schwarz leicht gewonnen wäre.} ({ANSWER: The best and most obvious move is} 26... Nc6 $1 {. Réti probably misjudged the position after} 27. Bxc6 Qxc6 28. Rxd4 Rxd4 29. Qxd4 Qc1+ 30. Kg2 {, when Black is a pawn down. As a matter of fact this queen ending is a fairly easy draw:} Qc6+ 31. f3 ({or} 31. Kh3 Qh1) 31... Qc2+ 32. Qf2 Qd1 {and it is not possible for White to improve his position substantially in view of Black's active queen; for example,} 33. g4 Qc1 34. Kg3 Kg7 {and Black can simply wait until White does something drastic.}) 27. b4 ({The immediate} 27. g4 {is better, with ideas of f4-f5, Qh6 and Rh3, exploiting the miserable state of Black's pieces located on the other flank.}) 27... Qb6 28. g4 {Weiß will am Königsflügel angreifen, aber dieser Zug gibt dem Schwarzen eine andere Chance.} Qc7 $1 ({Once again Black should have played} 28... Nc6 {, not fearing} 29. Bxc6 $6 (29. h4 $1 {keeps the edge}) 29... Qxc6 30. Rxd4 Rxd4 31. Qxd4 {, since either} Qf3 ({or} 31... Qc1+ {and ...Qxa3 secures equality.})) 29. Rxd4 $2 {Reti: Damit geht Weiß in dei Falle} (29. h3 $142) (29. Kg2 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'is the appropriate course, with the following plausible variation: Reti,Richard: '!''} Nc6 30. Qc1 Rc8 31. Rd2 ({or} 31. Qc5) 31... Qb8 32. Rc2 Na7 33. Rxc8+ Nxc8 34. Qc5 Nb6 35. Qxd4 Nc4 36. a4 {and White is clearly better.}) 29... Rxd4 30. Qxd4 Qc1+ 31. Kg2 Qxf4 32. f3 $2 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Safer is ''Safer is Reti,Richard: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'Safer is '''} 32. Qd8+ Kg7 33. f3 ({or} 33. Bf3) 33... Qxe5 34. g5 $11 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!' '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'with a positional draw. Black's knight has no squares so his queen cannot leave the b8-h2 diagonal either. Note that ''with a positional draw. Black's knight has no squares so his queen cannot leave the b8-h2 diagonal either. Note that Reti,Richard: '=' Reti,Richard: 'Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'with a positional draw. Black's knight has no squares so his queen cannot leave the b8-h2 diagonal either. Note that '''} h6 ({while} 34... a5 $4 35. bxa5 Na6 {even loses after} 36. Qf6+ Qxf6 37. gxf6+ Kxf6 38. Bb7 Nc7 39. a6 {and so on}) 35. h4 $1 {does not help.}) 32... Nc6 {Das hatte Weiß übersehen. Der e4 ist gefesselt} (32... Kg7 33. Qd6 $11 {So hatte Weiß gerechnet}) 33. Qd6 Nxe5 $15 34. Qxa6 Qd2+ ({Not} 34... Nxg4 $2 35. Qa8+ Kg7 36. fxg4 Qxg4+ 37. Kf2 {, when Black has to be content with perpetual check.} Qf4+) ({ANSWER: The best move is} 34... Kg7 $1 {, stepping off the exposed back rank and maintaining the threat of ...Nxg4;} {while} 35. Qd6 {is answered by} ({for instance,} 35. Qxb5 $6 Nxg4 $1 36. fxg4 Qxg4+ 37. Kf2 Qxe4 {gives Black all the chances in the queen endgame.} (37... Z0)) ({Preventing this with} 35. h3 $2 {runs into} Qd2+) 35... g5 $1 {, intending 36...h5 37 gxh5 g4 or 37 h3 h4. White can meet that threat by stabilizing the g4-pawn with} {White can meet this threat by stabilizing g4 with} 36. h3 {, now that ...Qd2+ is no longer possible, but then the quiet move} h6 $3 {puts him in a very unusual zugzwang.} {while if} 37. Qd4 {then} ({For example,} 37. Qd1 {allows} Qe3 {, entering the heart of White's position;} (37... Z0)) 37... f5 38. Qa7+ Kf6 39. gxf5 exf5 40. Qb6+ Kg7 41. Qc7+ Kg6 42. Qd6+ Kh5 43. Bb7 Nc4 44. Qxf4 ({not} 44. Qd3 $2 {due to} Kh4 {, introducing the king into the attack}) 44... gxf4 {and the exchange of queens gives Black excellent winning chances due to White's pawn weaknesses. Black will win a pawn on the queenside and most probably the f3-pawn as well by combining an attack with king and knight.}) 35. Kg3 $2 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'It is better to play ''It is better to play Reti,Richard: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'It is better to play '''} 35. Kh3 $142 {Thomas Engqvist: ', and if Black attempts to repeat the position with '', and if Black attempts to repeat the position with Reti,Richard: '' Reti,Richard: 'Thomas Engqvist: ', and if Black attempts to repeat the position with '''} Qe3 (35... Qf4 {(intending 36 Kg2 Kg7! again), White can defend with} 36. Qc8+ Kg7 37. Qc3 {, followed by Bc6.}) 36. Qxb5 Nxf3 37. Qb8+ Kg7 38. Bxf3 Qxf3+ 39. Qg3 Qf1+ 40. Qg2 Qc4 $15) 35... Qe1+ $17 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'ANSWER: ''ANSWER: Reti,Richard: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'ANSWER: '''} 35... h5 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!' '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'is the most dangerous move, threatening 36...Qe1+ 37 Kg2 Qe2+ 38 Kg3 h4+! and wins; w'is the most dangerous move, threatening 36...Qe1+ 37 Kg2 Qe2+ 38 Kg3 h4+! and wins; while after Reti,Richard: 'Thomas Engqvist: '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'is the most dangerous move, threatening 36...Qe1+ 37 Kg2 Qe2+ 38 Kg3 h4+! and wins; while after''' hile after'} 36. gxh5 Qg5+ 37. Kf2 Qxh5 38. Kg3 Qg5+ 39. Kf2 Nc4 {, Black has good chances of a successful attack against White's primary weaknesses: the king, the a3-pawn and the h2-pawn.}) 36. Kg2 (36. Kh3 {is also fine for White:} Qf1+ 37. Kg3 Qg1+ 38. Kh3 Kg7 39. Qxb5 Nxg4 40. fxg4 Qe3+ 41. Kg2 Qxe4+) 36... Qe2+ 37. Kg3 Kg7 38. a4 $4 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Much better is '} 38. Qb6 $142 {Thomas Engqvist: ', planning centralization with Qd4, while '} Nxg4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'is answered by '} 39. fxg4 ({not} 39. Kxg4 $4 Qg2+ 40. Kf4 Qxh2+ {and White gets mated or loses his queen}) 39... Qxe4 40. Qxb5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'is the same drawn position as in t'and so forth, since Reti,Richard: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'is the same drawn position as in the previous note.' Thomas Engqvist: 'and so forth, since ''' he previous note.'} Qe3+ 41. Kg2 $15 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Reti,Richard: ''' Und Schwarz hat noch eine Menge Arbeit vor sich. Thomas Engqvist: 'Reti,Richard: 'Und Schwarz hat noch eine Menge Arbeit vor sich.''} Qxa3 42. Qe5+ {draws at once.}) 38... Qe1+ {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' '?!'} 39. Kh3 $2 (39. Kg2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'loses too after ''loses too after Reti,Richard: 'Thomas Engqvist: 'loses too after '''} Nxg4 40. fxg4 Qxe4+ 41. Kg3 Qd3+ 42. Kf2 Qc2+ {and 43...bxa4. Even mutual promotion will just leave White two pawns down.}) 39... Qf1+ 40. Kg3 Qg1+ 41. Kh3 h5 42. g5 Ng4 $1 43. Qd6 e5 {and mate comes swiftly even if White gives up his queen; so Sämisch resigned.} 0-1


