{Rubinstein's 4...d4 is not a move that many modern players would venture. But at the time this game was played Benoni type positions were thought to confer a huge advantage on the player taking the space. 49: Personal Style: '28. RETI (1889-1929) During and after World War I there emerged a group of young players who attempted to break completely with accepted opinion. Foremost among them was Reti. Instead of occupying the centre with pawns these hypermoderns, with Reti as their leader, preferred to control the central territory by the action of their pieces. They developed their Bishops on the flanks and held back the centre pawns as long as possible. In his innovations Reti eventually went too far. He overpressed his theories, as inexperienced players sometimes do, and was often the victim of practical difficulties' 49: Personal Style: '28. RETI (1889-1929) During and after World War I there emerged a group of young players who attempted to break completely with accepted opinion. Foremost among them was Reti. Instead of occupying the centre with pawns these hypermoderns, with Reti as their leader, preferred to control the central territory by the action of their pieces. They developed their Bishops on the flanks and held back the centre pawns as long as possible. In his innovations Reti eventually went too far. He overpressed his theories, as inexperienced players sometimes do, and was often the victim of practical difficulties '} 1. Nf3 {49: Personal Style: 'Zukertort also frequently opened with this Knight move, but the system White used here was worked out by Reti, and is quite rightly known as Reti's opening' 49: Personal Style: 'Zukertort also frequently opened with this Knight move, but the system White used here was worked out by Reti, and is quite rightly known as Reti's opening '} d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 d4 {49: Personal Style: 'This ambitious space gaining move is virtually an attempt at refutation' 49: Personal Style: 'This ambitious space gaining move is virtually an attempt at refutation '} ({In my own games I've noticed that} 4... c6 {tends to be the most popular reply when I've played either 5.b3 or 5.Qa4. 49: Personal Style: 'more prudent' 49: Personal Style: 'more prudent'}) 5. d3 Bg7 6. b4 {49: Personal Style: 'A sophisticated strategem; White anticipates the reinforcing move ... Pc5, undermining it in advance' 49: Personal Style: 'A sophisticated strategem; White anticipates the reinforcing move ... c5, undermining it in advance'} O-O 7. Nbd2 {I've always liked the smooth harmony that you find in Reti's games by delaying the development of his queen's bishop White has extra options available, such as the a3 square.} ({After the more forceful} 7. Bb2 {Black can play} a5 (7... c5 8. bxc5 Nc6 9. Nbd2 Nd7 10. Nb3 Nxc5 11. Nxc5 Qa5+ 12. Nd2 Qxc5 13. O-O Qh5 14. Re1 Bh3 15. Bh1 Rab8 16. Rb1 {was very pleasant for White in Geller, E-Novopashin, A, Kiev 1963.}) {, for example} 8. b5 c5 9. bxc6 Nxc6 10. Na3 e5 11. Nb5 Re8 12. O-O Bf8 13. Nd2 Bf5 14. Rc1 Qd7 15. c5 Bh3 {was not bad for Black in Larsen, B (2625)-Pfleger, H (2540), Manila 1975.}) 7... c5 8. Nb3 (8. bxc5 {is also better for White, for example} Nfd7 9. Nb3 Nxc5 10. Nxc5 Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Qxc5 12. Rb1 {gives definite pressure. But Reti may have preferred to avoid this because of the resultant simplification.}) 8... cxb4 9. Bb2 Nc6 10. Nbxd4 {Gaining a central pawn for a flank one is one of the major themes of the Reti Opening. Now it will be White who gains a major share of the centre, despite the fact that he did not stake an early claim to this part of the board.} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 {49: Personal Style: 'White's strategy has been completely successful. The centre is under control by White's pieces - not pawns. Note that White has made no automatic developing moves; he has not yet castled. The hypermodern player does this only after some sophisticated preliminary strategical skirmishing' 49: Personal Style: 'White's strategy has been completely successful. The centre is under control by White's pieces - not pawns. Note that White has made no automatic developing moves; he has not yet castled. The hypermodern player does this only after some sophisticated preliminary strategical skirmishing'} b6 {Contesting the h1-a8 diagonal.} 12. a3 {Getting rid of the annoying b4 pawn and setting up a position in which White has a single pawn island (c4 to h2) against Black's two.} ({Note that} 12. Nd2 $2 {is bad because of} Qxd4 13. Bxa8 Ng4 14. O-O Nxf2 $1 {etc.}) 12... Bb7 {Threatening 13...Bxf3.} 13. Bb2 bxa3 14. Rxa3 Qc7 15. Qa1 $1 {These days there is nothing strange about this development of the queen. But in Reti's time it was highly original and raised more than a few eyebrows. 49: Personal Style: 'The doubling on the diagonal is an invention of Reti; it may be regarded as analogous to doubling heavy pieces on a file' 49: Personal Style: 'The doubling on the diagonal is an invention of Reti; it may be regarded as analogous to doubling heavy pieces on a file'} Ne8 16. Bxg7 Nxg7 17. O-O (17. Rxa7 $2 Rxa7 18. Qxa7 Ra8 {trapping White's Queen 49: Personal Style: 'trapping White's Queen'}) 17... Ne6 18. Rb1 ({And not} 18. Rxa7 $4 Rxa7 19. Qxa7 Ra8 {, winning the queen.}) 18... Bc6 (18... Z0 19. Rxa7 Rxa7 20. Qxa7 Ra8 21. Qxb6) 19. d4 {So now it is White who gains control of the centre. And this spatial control will allow White to put his pieces on big squares. 49: Personal Style: 'Only now do the centre pawns come into action' 49: Personal Style: 'Only now do the centre pawns come into action'} Be4 20. Rd1 a5 ({And not} 20... Qxc4 $2 {because of} 21. Nd2 {.}) 21. d5 Nc5 22. Nd4 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 Rfd8 24. Nc6 Rd6 25. Re3 Re8 26. Qe5 f6 ({On} 26... Rd7 {there follows} 27. Nxe7+ Rexe7 28. Qxc7 Rxc7 29. d6 {as after} Rxe3 30. dxc7 Re8 31. Rd8 {the passed c-pawn will promote. 49: Personal Style: '+-' '+-'}) (26... Z0 27. Nxe7+ {49: Personal Style: ''}) 27. Qb2 {With the mission accomplished (creation of further weaknesses in Black's camp) the queen latches on to a new target, the weak pawn on b6.} (27. Nxe7+ $2 {is bad because of} Kf7 {by the way.}) 27... e5 28. Qb5 Kf7 29. Rb1 Nd7 30. f3 Rc8 31. Rd3 e4 {With his position held in a vice like grip, Rubinstein makes a desperate bid for some counterplay. 49: Personal Style: 'A last try' 49: Personal Style: 'A last try'} (31... Nb8 32. c5 $1) 32. fxe4 Ne5 33. Qxb6 {49: Personal Style: '!' '!'} Nxc6 (33... Nxd3 34. exd3 {would be hopeless for Black because of White powerful clump of pawns.}) 34. c5 {49: Personal Style: '!' '!' 49: Personal Style: 'The point of White's previous move' 49: Personal Style: 'The point of White's previous move'} Rd7 35. dxc6 Rxd3 36. Qxc7+ Rxc7 37. exd3 Rxc6 38. Rb7+ Ke8 39. d4 {49: Personal Style: 'White has acquired complete central domination. The following endgame is expertly handled by Reti, who was a noted composer of many fine endgame studies' 49: Personal Style: 'White has acquired complete central domination. The following endgame is expertly handled by Reti, who was a noted composer of many fine endgame studies'} Ra6 {Getting his rook behind the passed pawn. But this rook endgame proves to be too much for even Rubinstein.} 40. Rb6 {49: Personal Style: '!' '!'} ({And not} 40. Rxh7 $6 {because of} a4 {.}) 40... Ra8 (40... Rxb6 41. cxb6 Kd7 42. e5 fxe5 43. dxe5 a4 44. e6+ $1 Kxe6 45. b7 $18) 41. Rxf6 a4 42. Rf2 a3 43. Ra2 Kd7 44. d5 g5 45. Kf3 Ra4 46. Ke3 h5 47. h4 {49: Personal Style: 'Preparing decisive pentration of the White King' 49: Personal Style: 'Preparing decisive pentration of the White King'} gxh4 48. gxh4 Ke7 49. Kf4 Kd7 50. Kf5 1-0


