dre: 'Garry Kasparov: 'JvR: 'Lopez : 'Reti is just supporting the c-pawn before continuing his development.'''''} ({Avoiding the questionable Varying from} 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 b5 {<xml:>, as played in R.Réti-Em.Lasker, MÃ<sym>N</sym>hrisch-Ostrau 1923 (Game 39).</:/xml>} 6. a4 b4 7. Na2 e6 {(Réti-Lasker, Mährisch-Ostrau 1923). This theme was later developed in the game Reshevsky-Smyslov (USSR-USA radio match 1945), which is examined in the second volume. Garry Kasparov: '(Réti-Lasker, Mährisch-Ostrau 1923). This theme was later developed in the game Reshevsky-Smyslov (USSR-USA radio match 1945), which is examined in the second volume.'}) 3... Bf5 {Garry Kasparov: '!?' '!?' '!?' Garry Kasparov: ''With this move Dr Lasker as second player applies the London system of development, which, with colours transposed, has several times stood the test against the double fianchetto,' writes Alekhine, having in mind the 1 d4 variat''With this move Dr Lasker as second player applies the London system of development, which, with colours transposed, has several times stood the test against the double fianchetto,' writes Alekhine, having in mind the 1 d4 variation, above. Schulz,Andre: 'Garry Kasparov: '!?' Garry Kasparov: ''With this move Dr Lasker as second player applies the London system of development, which, with colours transposed, has several times stood the test against the double fianchetto,' writes Alekhine, having in mind the 1 d4 variation, above.''' ion, above.' Alekhine commented in the tournament book: “With this move Dr. Lasker as second player applies the London system of development, which, with colours transposed, has several times stood the test against the double fianchetto”, referring to the London System, played with White after 1 d4, which has been revived in recent years, having been employed by world champion Magnus Carlsen among others. Garry Kasparov: ''With this move Dr Lasker as second player applies the London system of development, which, 