wn, which should generally lead to a closed position.''Alekhine opens with his d-pawn, which should generally lead to a closed position. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 's.a. Best Games 1924-37, 1.  Nunn: A.'s Best, 33. Oertmann: Schach für Fortgeschrittene, S. 130-36.  Müller, 21. Aljechin: New York 1924, 38. (A)  Linder, 23.  Fiala II, 344.  Rubinstein in: Kagans Neueste Schachnachrichten 1924, Nr. 73. (R)  Varnusz: Aljechin, der Größte <1924/08>   Haas: Alexander Aljechin, S. 65.   Skinner/Verhoeven: Alexander Alekhine's Chess Games, 794.  La Stratégie 1924, S. 111f. Lopez : 'Alekhine opens with his d-pawn, which should generally lead to a closed position.''' Ribli s.a. Best Games 1924-37, 1.  Nunn: A.'s Best, 33. Oertmann: Schach für Fortgeschrittene, S. 130-36.  Müller, 21. Aljechin: New York 1924, 38. (A)  Linder, 23.  Fiala II, 344.  Rubinstein in: Kagans Neueste Schachnachrichten 1924, Nr. 73. (R)  Varnusz: Aljechin, der Größte <1924/08>   Haas: Alexander Aljechin, S. 65.   Skinner/Verhoeven: Alexander Alekhine's Chess Games, 794.  La Stratégie 1924, S. 111f. Lopez : 'Alekhine opens with his d-pawn, which should generally lead to a closed position.''Alekhine opens with his d-pawn, which should generally lead to a closed position. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 's.a. Best Games 1924-37, 1.  Nunn: A.'s Best, 33. Oertmann: Schach für Fortgeschrittene, S. 130-36.  Müller, 21. Aljechin: New York 1924, 38. (A)  Linder, 23.  Fiala II, 344.  Rubinstein in: Kagans Neueste Schachnachrichten 1924, Nr. 73. (R)  Varnusz: Aljechin, der Größte <1924/08>   Haas: Alexander Aljechin, S. 65.   Skinner/Verhoeven: Alexander Alekhine's Chess Games, 794.  La Stratégie 1924, S. 111f. Lopez : 'Alekhine opens with his d-pawn, which should generally lead to a closed position.'''} Nf6 {Lopez : 'Reti's Knight leaps toward the center where, as you know, it will be well placed to take part in the action to come.''Reti's Knight leaps toward the center where, as you know, it will be well placed to take part in the action to come. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti's Knight leaps toward the center where, as you know, it will be well placed to take part in the action to come.'''} 2. c4 {Lopez : 'By moving the c-pawn before playing Nc3, Alekhine ensures that the pawn's advance won't be blocked by the Knight.''By moving the c-pawn before playing Nc3, Alekhine ensures that the pawn's advance won't be blocked by the Knight. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'By moving the c-pawn before playing Nc3, Alekhine ensures that the pawn's advance won't be blocked by the Knight.'''} g6 {Lopez : 'Reti advances the pawn to prepare a Bishop fianchetto (...Bg7).''Reti advances the pawn to prepare a Bishop fianchetto (...Bg7). Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti advances the pawn to prepare a Bishop fianchetto (...Bg7).'''} 3. g3 {Damit sucht Aljechin die Grünfeld-Variante, welche hier nach 3.c3 entstehen könnte, zu umgehen. Ob jedoch dieser Zug eine Verstärkung des weißen Spiels bedeutet, scheint recht fraglich zu sein. Grünfeld pflegte nun in ähnlichen Stellungen mit c7-c6 nabst d7-d5 fortzusetzen, was auch wohl besser ist, als die in dieser Partie gewählte Entwicklungsweise. (R, (A)) Lopez : 'Alekhine will also fianchetto his Kingside Bishop.''Alekhine will also fianchetto his Kingside Bishop. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Damit sucht Aljechin die Grünfeld-Variante, welche hier nach 3.c3 entstehen könnte, zu umgehen. Ob jedoch dieser Zug eine Verstärkung des weißen Spiels bedeutet, scheint recht fraglich zu sein. Grünfeld pflegte nun in ähnlichen Stellungen mit c7-c6 nabst d7-d5 fortzusetzen, was auch wohl besser ist, als die in dieser Partie gewählte Entwicklungsweise. (R, (A)) Lopez : 'Alekhine will also fianchetto his Kingside Bishop.'''} Bg7 {Lopez : 'The Bishop moves to the long a1-h8 diagonal, from which it can easily influence the center.''The Bishop moves to the long a1-h8 diagonal, from which it can easily influence the center. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'The Bishop moves to the long a1-h8 diagonal, from which it can easily influence the center.'''} (3... c6 $142 4. Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Nf3 Bg7 7. O-O {Obwohl Weiß auch in diesem Falle noch eine Zeitlang den Vorteil des Anzugs (im engeren Sinne - d.h. das Tempo) behaupten kann. (A)}) 4. Bg2 {Lopez : 'The White Bishop's move is the counterpart to Black's; White's Bishop now dominates the a8-h1 diagonal.''The White Bishop's move is the counterpart to Black's; White's Bishop now dominates the a8-h1 diagonal. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'The White Bishop's move is the counterpart to Black's; White's Bishop now dominates the a8-h1 diagonal.'''} O-O {Lopez : 'Reti completes his Kingside development by castling, though it's not strictly necessary here (as the center pawns have not developed).''Reti completes his Kingside development by castling, though it's not strictly necessary here (as the center pawns have not developed). Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti completes his Kingside development by castling, though it's not strictly necessary here (as the center pawns have not developed).'''} 5. Nc3 {Lopez : 'Alekhine advances his Knight, a move he planned as far back as Move 2.''Alekhine advances his Knight, a move he planned as far back as Move 2. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine advances his Knight, a move he planned as far back as Move 2.'''} d6 {Damit lenkt Schwarz in die Indische Verteidigung ein, bei welcher aber die Fianchettierung des f1 sich als durchaus sachgemäß erweist. (A) Lopez : 'By advancing the d-pawna single square, Reti paves the way for his c-pawn or e-pawn to advance two squares, possibly breaking up White's pawn center.''By advancing the d-pawna single square, Reti paves the way for his c-pawn or e-pawn to advance two squares, possibly breaking up White's pawn center. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Damit lenkt Schwarz in die Indische Verteidigung ein, bei welcher aber die Fianchettierung des f1 sich als durchaus sachgemäß erweist. (A) Lopez : 'By advancing the d-pawna single square, Reti paves the way for his c-pawn or e-pawn to advance two squares, possibly breaking up White's pawn center.'''} 6. Nf3 {Lopez : 'Alekhine continues to develop usefully, moving his Kingside Knight toward the center.''Alekhine continues to develop usefully, moving his Kingside Knight toward the center. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine continues to develop usefully, moving his Kingside Knight toward the center.'''} Nc6 {Ein hypermoderner Zug. Zwar muß der  sofort den Rückzug antreten, aber ähnliche Tempoverluste sind eben nur scheinbar; sie bilden vielmehr ein Stück der modernen Schachstrategie. (R) Falls Schwarz nichts Besseres hat - und dies scheint der Fall zu sein - als durch solche Anstrengungen den weißen  nach d5 zu provozieren (wo er zwar momentan die Diagonale des g2 verkürzt, dafür aber einen selbständigen Druck auf die feindliche Stellung ausübt) - so ist seine Partieanlage sicher nicht empfehlenswert. (A) Lopez : 'All of the Knights are now developed to their natural center-controlling squares.''All of the Knights are now developed to their natural center-controlling squares. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Ein hypermoderner Zug. Zwar muß der  sofort den Rückzug antreten, aber ähnliche Tempoverluste sind eben nur scheinbar; sie bilden vielmehr ein Stück der modernen Schachstrategie. (R) Falls Schwarz nichts Besseres hat - und dies scheint der Fall zu sein - als durch solche Anstrengungen den weißen  nach d5 zu provozieren (wo er zwar momentan die Diagonale des g2 verkürzt, dafür aber einen selbständigen Druck auf die feindliche Stellung ausübt) - so ist seine Partieanlage sicher nicht empfehlenswert. (A) Lopez : 'All of the Knights are now developed to their natural center-controlling squares.'''} 7. d5 {Lopez : 'Alekhine plays a move with several purposes: the pawn advance attacks the c6-Knight, it controls two squares deep in Black's territory, and it makes it harder for Black to break the center by advancing the c- or e-pawn.''Alekhine plays a move with several purposes: the pawn advance attacks the c6-Knight, it controls two squares deep in Black's territory, and it makes it harder for Black to break the center by advancing the c- or e-pawn. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine plays a move with several purposes: the pawn advance attacks the c6-Knight, it controls two squares deep in Black's territory, and it makes it harder for Black to break the center by advancing the c- or e-pawn.'''} Nb8 $2 {Lopez : 'If Reti plays ...Ne5, Alekhine would counter with Nxe5. After ...dxe5, the doubled e5-pawn becomes a weak target. The move ...Na5 is possible, but encourages White to harass the Knight by advancing the Queenside pawns.''If Reti plays ...Ne5, Alekhine would counter with Nxe5. After ...dxe5, the doubled e5-pawn becomes a weak target. The move ...Na5 is possible, but encourages White to harass the Knight by advancing the Queenside pawns. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '?' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'If Reti plays ...Ne5, Alekhine would counter with Nxe5. After ...dxe5, the doubled e5-pawn becomes a weak target. The move ...Na5 is possible, but encourages White to harass the Knight by advancing the Queenside pawns.''' Lopez : 'If Reti plays ...Ne5, Alekhine would counter with Nxe5. After ...dxe5, the doubled e5-pawn becomes a weak target. The move ...Na5 is possible, but encourages White to harass the Knight by advancing the Queenside pawns.''If Reti plays ...Ne5, Alekhine would counter with Nxe5. After ...dxe5, the doubled e5-pawn becomes a weak target. The move ...Na5 is possible, but encourages White to harass the Knight by advancing the Queenside pawns. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '?' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'If Reti plays ...Ne5, Alekhine would counter with Nxe5. After ...dxe5, the doubled e5-pawn becomes a weak target. The move ...Na5 is possible, but encourages White to harass the Knight by advancing the Queenside pawns.''' Lopez : 'If Reti plays ...Ne5, Alekhine would counter with Nxe5. After ...dxe5, the doubled e5-pawn becomes a weak target. The move ...Na5 is possible, but encourages White to harass the Knight by advancing the Queenside pawns.''If Reti plays ...Ne5, Alekhine would counter with Nxe5. After ...dxe5, the doubled e5-pawn becomes a weak target. The move ...Na5 is possible, but encourages White to harass the Knight by advancing the Queenside pawns. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '?' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'If Reti plays ...Ne5, Alekhine would counter with Nxe5. After ...dxe5, the doubled e5-pawn becomes a weak target. The move ...Na5 is possible, but encourages White to harass the Knight by advancing the Queenside pawns.''' Ribli: '?!'} (7... Na5 { -c5}) 8. O-O {Lopez : 'Satisfied with his space advantage and with Black's lack of immediate threats, Alekhine takes time to castle his King out of the center.''Satisfied with his space advantage and with Black's lack of immediate threats, Alekhine takes time to castle his King out of the center. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Satisfied with his space advantage and with Black's lack of immediate threats, Alekhine takes time to castle his King out of the center.'''} Bg4 $6 {Da der folgende Abtausch des g4 gegen f3 für Schwarz unvorteilhaft ist, wäre es hier besser gewesen, den Zug zu unterlassen und sofort e7-e5 zu spielen. (R) Der damit beabsichtigte Abtausch dieses  ist unmotiviert und vermindert nur die Verteidigungskraft der Stellung von Schwarz. (A) Lopez : 'Reti advances the Bishop, looking to trade it for White's Knight.''Reti advances the Bishop, looking to trade it for White's Knight. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '?!' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Da der folgende Abtausch des g4 gegen f3 für Schwarz unvorteilhaft ist, wäre es hier besser gewesen, den Zug zu unterlassen und sofort e7-e5 zu spielen. (R) Der damit beabsichtigte Abtausch dieses  ist unmotiviert und vermindert nur die Verteidigungskraft der Stellung von Schwarz. (A) Lopez : 'Reti advances the Bishop, looking to trade it for White's Knight.'''} (8... a5 {Käme in Betracht, um eine Zeitlang den Punkt c5 dem  zu sichern; aber auch in diesem Falle würde Weiß durch die Verwirklichung des naheliegenden Gegenplanes h3, e3, c2, b3, a3 und schließlich b4 seinen Positionsvorteil behaupten. (A)  d7/c5}) (8... e5 $6 {gleichfalls ungenügend.} 9. dxe6 fxe6 10. Bg5 {Al.-Thomas, Karlsbad 1923. (A)}) 9. h3 {Es war wichtig, die Lage zu klären, bevor der Gegner seine Entwicklung beendet hat. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine "puts the question" to the Bishop: either capture or retreat!''Alekhine "puts the question" to the Bishop: either capture or retreat! Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Es war wichtig, die Lage zu klären, bevor der Gegner seine Entwicklung beendet hat. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine "puts the question" to the Bishop: either capture or retreat!'''} Bxf3 {Lopez : 'Reti swaps his Bishop for a Knight. But this exchange seems a little premature. With many pieces undeveloped and the position still somewhat unclear, it's a good idea to hang onto both Bishops until the position becomes better defined.''Reti swaps his Bishop for a Knight. But this exchange seems a little premature. With many pieces undeveloped and the position still somewhat unclear, it's a good idea to hang onto both Bishops until the position becomes better defined. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti swaps his Bishop for a Knight. But this exchange seems a little premature. With many pieces undeveloped and the position still somewhat unclear, it's a good idea to hang onto both Bishops until the position becomes better defined.'''} 10. exf3 $1 {Wohl besser als f3:. Weiß erhält danach die offene e-Linie, auch wirkt später dieser  von f4 aus für den Schwarzen störend. (R) Viel besser, als mit dem  wiederzunehmen, bei welcher Spielweise der e2 entweder eine lange Zeit tatenlos geblieben wäre, oder durch sein Vorgehen den Wirkungskreis der eigenen Figuren beschränkt hätte. Nach dem Textzuge wird er aber die Bewachung des wichtigen Punktes e5 übernehmen, und außerdem wird Schwarz mit einer eventuellen gegnerischen Aktion auf der hiermit geöffneten e-Linie rechnen müssen. (A) Lopez : 'At first glance, this looks like it blocks the light-squared Bishop. But Alekhine has an idea...''At first glance, this looks like it blocks the light-squared Bishop. But Alekhine has an idea... Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '!' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Wohl besser als f3:. Weiß erhält danach die offene e-Linie, auch wirkt später dieser  von f4 aus für den Schwarzen störend. (R) Viel besser, als mit dem  wiederzunehmen, bei welcher Spielweise der e2 entweder eine lange Zeit tatenlos geblieben wäre, oder durch sein Vorgehen den Wirkungskreis der eigenen Figuren beschränkt hätte. Nach dem Textzuge wird er aber die Bewachung des wichtigen Punktes e5 übernehmen, und außerdem wird Schwarz mit einer eventuellen gegnerischen Aktion auf der hiermit geöffneten e-Linie rechnen müssen. (A) Lopez : 'At first glance, this looks like it blocks the light-squared Bishop. But Alekhine has an idea...'''} e6 {Besser wäre es, diesen  2 Schritte vorzurücken. (R) Lopez : 'The old chess maxim says "When your position is cramped, free it by exchanging", which is exactly what Reti seeks to do here.''The old chess maxim says "When your position is cramped, free it by exchanging", which is exactly what Reti seeks to do here. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Besser wäre es, diesen  2 Schritte vorzurücken. (R) Lopez : 'The old chess maxim says "When your position is cramped, free it by exchanging", which is exactly what Reti seeks to do here.'''} (10... e5 $142 {Der e-Bauer mußte abgetauscht werden; aber verhältnismäßig besser war dies hiermit zu erreichen. Weiß hätte nämlich darauf nur eine günstige Antwort:} 11. dxe6 $8 (11. f4 $6 exf4 12. Bxf4 Nbd7 {was für den Nachziehenden offenbar ganz gut erträglich wäre. Nach dem geschehenen Zuge hat Weiß dagegen die angenehme Wahl zwische zwei guten Fortsetzungen. (A)})) 11. f4 $1 {Lopez : 'Now we see the idea behind 10.exf3. The f4-pawn carves out space on the Kingside, the f1-Rook can slide over to e1 to command the e-file, and the light-squared Bishop on g2 once again controls the long diagonal.''Now we see the idea behind 10.exf3. The f4-pawn carves out space on the Kingside, the f1-Rook can slide over to e1 to command the e-file, and the light-squared Bishop on g2 once again controls the long diagonal. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '!' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Now we see the idea behind 10.exf3. The f4-pawn carves out space on the Kingside, the f1-Rook can slide over to e1 to command the e-file, and the light-squared Bishop on g2 once again controls the long diagonal.'''} (11. dxe6 fxe6 12. Re1 Qd7 {und die schwarzen Zentrumsschwächen sind nicht so leicht zu nutzen. (A)}) 11... exd5 {Lopez : 'Reti clears some space by swapping center pawns. His eventual goal is to plant a Knight on c6.''Reti clears some space by swapping center pawns. His eventual goal is to plant a Knight on c6. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti clears some space by swapping center pawns. His eventual goal is to plant a Knight on c6.'''} 12. cxd5 {Jetzt hat Schwarz dagegen zwischen drei bestimmten Übeln zu wählen: 1. Schwäche von c7, falls er die Bauernstellung intakt läßt. 2. Schwäche von c6, falls er nach c7-c5 dc6:/ep mit dem  wiedernimmt und dann erzwungenermaßen d6-d5 spielt. 3. Und schließlich die von ihm tatsächlich gewählte Spielweise, bei welcher er einen isolierten d6 bekommt, dessen Verteidigung, erschwert durch das wuchtige Zusammenwirken der gegnerischen , zu einer entscheidenden Schwächung seines Damenflügels bald führen wird. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine, of course, completes the swap, leaving him with an isolated pawn on d5.''Alekhine, of course, completes the swap, leaving him with an isolated pawn on d5. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Jetzt hat Schwarz dagegen zwischen drei bestimmten Übeln zu wählen: 1. Schwäche von c7, falls er die Bauernstellung intakt läßt. 2. Schwäche von c6, falls er nach c7-c5 dc6:/ep mit dem  wiedernimmt und dann erzwungenermaßen d6-d5 spielt. 3. Und schließlich die von ihm tatsächlich gewählte Spielweise, bei welcher er einen isolierten d6 bekommt, dessen Verteidigung, erschwert durch das wuchtige Zusammenwirken der gegnerischen , zu einer entscheidenden Schwächung seines Damenflügels bald führen wird. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine, of course, completes the swap, leaving him with an isolated pawn on d5.'''} c5 {Dieser und der folgende Zug von Schwarz ist als der entscheidende Fehler zu betrachten, denn nun wird d6 vereinzelt und in dieser Stellung ist derselbe wirklich schwach. (R) Lopez : 'Reti really isn't too concerned with making the d5-pawn a target. The fact that he has a pawn on d6, directly in front of the isolated White pawn, means that the White pawn will be hard to attack anyway (the Rooks and Queen can't get at it along the d-file). So Reti advances his c-pawn, inviting White to capture en passant.''Reti really isn't too concerned with making the d5-pawn a target. The fact that he has a pawn on d6, directly in front of the isolated White pawn, means that the White pawn will be hard to attack anyway (the Rooks and Queen can't get at it along the d-file). So Reti advances his c-pawn, inviting White to capture en passant. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Dieser und der folgende Zug von Schwarz ist als der entscheidende Fehler zu betrachten, denn nun wird d6 vereinzelt und in dieser Stellung ist derselbe wirklich schwach. (R) Lopez : 'Reti really isn't too concerned with making the d5-pawn a target. The fact that he has a pawn on d6, directly in front of the isolated White pawn, means that the White pawn will be hard to attack anyway (the Rooks and Queen can't get at it along the d-file). So Reti advances his c-pawn, inviting White to capture en passant.'''} 13. dxc6 {Lopez : 'The rules for en passant capture state that it must be done immediately or not at all, so Alekhine snaps up the pawn.''The rules for en passant capture state that it must be done immediately or not at all, so Alekhine snaps up the pawn. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'The rules for en passant capture state that it must be done immediately or not at all, so Alekhine snaps up the pawn.'''} Nxc6 {Lopez : 'And Reti has his second Knight out. But his d-pawn is now isolated (plus it's advanced only one square), so it may become a liability later.''And Reti has his second Knight out. But his d-pawn is now isolated (plus it's advanced only one square), so it may become a liability later. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'And Reti has his second Knight out. But his d-pawn is now isolated (plus it's advanced only one square), so it may become a liability later.'''} 14. Be3 {Lopez : 'Alekhine develops his last minor piece. 14.Bd2 was out of the question, as the Bishop would then block the Queen's influence along the d-file.''Alekhine develops his last minor piece. 14.Bd2 was out of the question, as the Bishop would then block the Queen's influence along the d-file. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine develops his last minor piece. 14.Bd2 was out of the question, as the Bishop would then block the Queen's influence along the d-file.''' Lopez : 'Alekhine develops his last minor piece. 14.Bd2 was out of the question, as the Bishop would then block the Queen's influence along the d-file.''Alekhine develops his last minor piece. 14.Bd2 was out of the question, as the Bishop would then block the Queen's influence along the d-file. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine develops his last minor piece. 14.Bd2 was out of the question, as the Bishop would then block the Queen's influence along the d-file.''' Lopez : 'Alekhine develops his last minor piece. 14.Bd2 was out of the question, as the Bishop would then block the Queen's influence along the d-file.''Alekhine develops his last minor piece. 14.Bd2 was out of the question, as the Bishop would then block the Queen's influence along the d-file. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine develops his last minor piece. 14.Bd2 was out of the question, as the Bishop would then block the Queen's influence along the d-file.''' Ribli: ''} Qd7 {Lopez : 'Reti pushes the Queen forward. This gets the Queen a bit more play along the c8-h3 diagonal, as well as opens up the square d8 for occupation by a Rook (adding to the defense of the isolated d6-pawn).''Reti pushes the Queen forward. This gets the Queen a bit more play along the c8-h3 diagonal, as well as opens up the square d8 for occupation by a Rook (adding to the defense of the isolated d6-pawn). Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti pushes the Queen forward. This gets the Queen a bit more play along the c8-h3 diagonal, as well as opens up the square d8 for occupation by a Rook (adding to the defense of the isolated d6-pawn).'''} 15. Qa4 $1 {Ein sehr wirksames Feld für die , von welchem sie einen lästigen Druck auf den schwarzen Damenflügel ausübt. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine completes his development by pinning the c6-Knight (should the Knight move, the Black Queen is hanging undefended. Notice, though, that the c3-Knight guards the White Queen).''Alekhine completes his development by pinning the c6-Knight (should the Knight move, the Black Queen is hanging undefended. Notice, though, that the c3-Knight guards the White Queen). Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '!' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Ein sehr wirksames Feld für die , von welchem sie einen lästigen Druck auf den schwarzen Damenflügel ausübt. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine completes his development by pinning the c6-Knight (should the Knight move, the Black Queen is hanging undefended. Notice, though, that the c3-Knight guards the White Queen).'''} Rac8 {Lopez : 'Rooks belong on open files, as the old adage says.''Rooks belong on open files, as the old adage says. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Rooks belong on open files, as the old adage says.'''} 16. Rad1 {Beide Gegner verfolgen dieselbe Idee: die b-Bauer sollen der indirekten Wirkung der feindlichen  entzogen werden. (A) Lopez : 'White puts pressure on the d6-pawn as well as indirectly attacks the Black Queen (by pinning the pawn). Alekhine is planning Bc5, piling up on the d6-pawn (...dxc5 would be impossible due to the reply Rxd7).''White puts pressure on the d6-pawn as well as indirectly attacks the Black Queen (by pinning the pawn). Alekhine is planning Bc5, piling up on the d6-pawn (...dxc5 would be impossible due to the reply Rxd7). Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Beide Gegner verfolgen dieselbe Idee: die b-Bauer sollen der indirekten Wirkung der feindlichen  entzogen werden. (A) Lopez : 'White puts pressure on the d6-pawn as well as indirectly attacks the Black Queen (by pinning the pawn). Alekhine is planning Bc5, piling up on the d6-pawn (...dxc5 would be impossible due to the reply Rxd7).'''} (16. Bxa7 $2 Ra8 {(A)}) 16... b6 {Lopez : 'Reti keeps the White Bishop off of c5 by controlling the square with a pawn.''Reti keeps the White Bishop off of c5 by controlling the square with a pawn. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti keeps the White Bishop off of c5 by controlling the square with a pawn.'''} 17. b3 {Außerdem hat dieser Zug noch den Zweck, in Voraussicht der folgenden Verwicklungen die a4 nochmals zu decken. Wie wichtig dies ist, wird sich sehr bald zeigen. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine overprotects the Queen. Both the b3-pawn and the c3-Knight defend the Queen; now either one of them is free for another duty should the need arise.''Alekhine overprotects the Queen. Both the b3-pawn and the c3-Knight defend the Queen; now either one of them is free for another duty should the need arise. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Außerdem hat dieser Zug noch den Zweck, in Voraussicht der folgenden Verwicklungen die a4 nochmals zu decken. Wie wichtig dies ist, wird sich sehr bald zeigen. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine overprotects the Queen. Both the b3-pawn and the c3-Knight defend the Queen; now either one of them is free for another duty should the need arise.'''} Rfd8 {Lopez : 'Reti adds another defender to the d6-pawn, in anticipation of White's Nb5 (which would attack the pawn).''Reti adds another defender to the d6-pawn, in anticipation of White's Nb5 (which would attack the pawn). Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti adds another defender to the d6-pawn, in anticipation of White's Nb5 (which would attack the pawn).'''} 18. Rd3 {Sofort 18.b5 wäre verfrüht wehen 16.-d5. Jetzt aber droht Weiß, diesen Zug nach der Turmverdopplung zu machen, und Schwarz versucht deshalb, sich von dem Druck der weißen  durch Abtausch zu entledigen. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine clears d1 for the second Roook. He plans to double the Rooks on the d-file and put further pressure on the d6-pawn.''Alekhine clears d1 for the second Roook. He plans to double the Rooks on the d-file and put further pressure on the d6-pawn. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Sofort 18.b5 wäre verfrüht wehen 16.-d5. Jetzt aber droht Weiß, diesen Zug nach der Turmverdopplung zu machen, und Schwarz versucht deshalb, sich von dem Druck der weißen  durch Abtausch zu entledigen. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine clears d1 for the second Roook. He plans to double the Rooks on the d-file and put further pressure on the d6-pawn.'''} Ne7 $6 {Darauf gehen die schwarzen  am Damenflügel verloren, aber die schwarze Stellung ist bereits unterminiert. (R) Auf diesem Wege geht es allerdings nicht, und er kommt sofort in materiellen Nachteil. (A) Lopez : 'Reti's thought here is to relieve some of the pressure on his center by swapping off the Queens.''Reti's thought here is to relieve some of the pressure on his center by swapping off the Queens. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '?!' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Darauf gehen die schwarzen  am Damenflügel verloren, aber die schwarze Stellung ist bereits unterminiert. (R) Auf diesem Wege geht es allerdings nicht, und er kommt sofort in materiellen Nachteil. (A) Lopez : 'Reti's thought here is to relieve some of the pressure on his center by swapping off the Queens.'''} (18... Na5 $142 19. Qa3 Bf8 20. Rfd1 {mit zwar schwierigem, aber zunächst noch verteidigungsfähigem Spiel für Schwarz. (A)}) 19. Nb5 $1 {Lopez : 'Alekhine will have none of it. He deftly blocks the Queen swap and adds another attacker to the push against d6.''Alekhine will have none of it. He deftly blocks the Queen swap and adds another attacker to the push against d6. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '!' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine will have none of it. He deftly blocks the Queen swap and adds another attacker to the push against d6.'''} d5 $8 {Lopez : 'Sometimes the best way to defend a threatened pawn is to advance it. Rather than scramble to find another defender for the pawn, Reti advances it to a square already controlled by four of his pieces. Now the pawn is attacked just once and securely overprotected.''Sometimes the best way to defend a threatened pawn is to advance it. Rather than scramble to find another defender for the pawn, Reti advances it to a square already controlled by four of his pieces. Now the pawn is attacked just once and securely overprotected. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Sometimes the best way to defend a threatened pawn is to advance it. Rather than scramble to find another defender for the pawn, Reti advances it to a square already controlled by four of his pieces. Now the pawn is attacked just once and securely overprotected.'''} 20. Nxa7 {Auch diese Wendung ist durch den 17. Zug von Weiß ermöglicht worden. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine begins operations against Black's Queenside pawns, which will quickly melt away.''Alekhine begins operations against Black's Queenside pawns, which will quickly melt away. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Auch diese Wendung ist durch den 17. Zug von Weiß ermöglicht worden. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine begins operations against Black's Queenside pawns, which will quickly melt away.'''} Ra8 {Lopez : 'Pinning the White Knight. Even if the White Queens moves, Black still thrusts at the a2-pawn with an x-ray attack. Unfortunately, the Rook must abandon the open c-file to make this possible.''Pinning the White Knight. Even if the White Queens moves, Black still thrusts at the a2-pawn with an x-ray attack. Unfortunately, the Rook must abandon the open c-file to make this possible. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Pinning the White Knight. Even if the White Queens moves, Black still thrusts at the a2-pawn with an x-ray attack. Unfortunately, the Rook must abandon the open c-file to make this possible.'''} (20... Qxa4 $5 {Swapping the Queens immediately was another possibility (and better than what was actually played).} 21. bxa4 {The obvious recapture.} Rc2 {The Rook slides down the open file to attack the a2-pawn.} 22. Bxb6 {White gobbles the second pawn. Black might play ...Rxa2 here or may try another threat (such as attacking one of White's minor pieces with his d-Rook). Either way, White retains a pawn advantage, the Bishop pair, and a freer position.}) 21. Bxb6 {Lopez : 'White grabs up the last Queenside pawn.''White grabs up the last Queenside pawn. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'White grabs up the last Queenside pawn.'''} Qxa4 {Schwarz hat nichts Besseres. (A) Lopez : 'Reti makes the Queen swap.''Reti makes the Queen swap. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Schwarz hat nichts Besseres. (A) Lopez : 'Reti makes the Queen swap.'''} (21... Rdb8 22. Qxd7 Nxd7 23. Be3 Rb7 24. Bxd5 Nxd5 25. Rxd5 Raxa7 26. Bxa7 Rxa7 27. Rfd1 $18 {(A)}) 22. bxa4 {Lopez : 'Alekhine must recapture. Compare this board position to the one after 22.Bxb6 in the last variation we looked at. The positions are identical save for one Black Rook, which is on a8 here, as opposed to c2 in the variation. The Rook would have better chances of winning a pawn if it was on c2 than it does at its present post. This is why 20...Qxa4 was better.''Alekhine must recapture. Compare this board position to the one after 22.Bxb6 in the last variation we looked at. The positions are identical save for one Black Rook, which is on a8 here, as opposed to c2 in the variation. The Rook would have better chances of winning a pawn if it was on c2 than it does at its present post. This is why 20...Qxa4 was better. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine must recapture. Compare this board position to the one after 22.Bxb6 in the last variation we looked at. The positions are identical save for one Black Rook, which is on a8 here, as opposed to c2 in the variation. The Rook would have better chances of winning a pawn if it was on c2 than it does at its present post. This is why 20...Qxa4 was better.'''} Rd7 {Lopez : 'Reti's plan is 23...Rxa7 24.Bxa7 Rxa7, winning two minor pieces for a Rook.''Reti's plan is 23...Rxa7 24.Bxa7 Rxa7, winning two minor pieces for a Rook. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti's plan is 23...Rxa7 24.Bxa7 Rxa7, winning two minor pieces for a Rook.'''} 23. Nb5 {Lopez : 'Alekhine must retreat the Knight to save his minor pieces...''Alekhine must retreat the Knight to save his minor pieces... Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine must retreat the Knight to save his minor pieces...'''} Rxa4 {Droht auch 24.-b4 25.b3 b3: 26.ab: b7. (A) Lopez : '...but does so at the cost of a pawn.''...but does so at the cost of a pawn. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Droht auch 24.-b4 25.b3 b3: 26.ab: b7. (A) Lopez : '...but does so at the cost of a pawn.'''} 24. Nc3 {Lopez : 'Alekhine attacks the marauding Rook.''Alekhine attacks the marauding Rook. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine attacks the marauding Rook.'''} Ra6 {Lopez : 'Reti retreats the Rook with a threat to the b6-Bishop.''Reti retreats the Rook with a threat to the b6-Bishop. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti retreats the Rook with a threat to the b6-Bishop.'''} (24... Ra3 {Ribli} 25. Bc5) 25. Rb1 {Lopez : 'The Rook defends the threatened Bishop. Alekhine might have retreated the Bishop instead, but chose to leave it at its current post, as it controls a number of squares in the heart of Black's position.''The Rook defends the threatened Bishop. Alekhine might have retreated the Bishop instead, but chose to leave it at its current post, as it controls a number of squares in the heart of Black's position. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'The Rook defends the threatened Bishop. Alekhine might have retreated the Bishop instead, but chose to leave it at its current post, as it controls a number of squares in the heart of Black's position.'''} Rb7 {Lopez : 'Reti strikes at the Bishop a second time...''Reti strikes at the Bishop a second time... Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti strikes at the Bishop a second time...'''} 26. Bc5 {Lopez : '...forcing Alekhine to withdraw it to a safer square.''...forcing Alekhine to withdraw it to a safer square. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : '...forcing Alekhine to withdraw it to a safer square.'''} Rxb1+ {Lopez : 'Reti, concerned about future threats to his isolated d-pawn, decides to do a little board-clearing to head for an endgame.''Reti, concerned about future threats to his isolated d-pawn, decides to do a little board-clearing to head for an endgame. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti, concerned about future threats to his isolated d-pawn, decides to do a little board-clearing to head for an endgame.'''} 27. Nxb1 {Lopez : 'Alekhine completes the trade.''Alekhine completes the trade. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine completes the trade.'''} Nc6 {Die Stellung ist nun abgeklärt - Weiß hat einen Freibauern behauptet, und d5 bleibt noch immer schwach. (A) Lopez : 'Reti is intending to play ...Ra5, so the Knight advances to provide coverage for that square.''Reti is intending to play ...Ra5, so the Knight advances to provide coverage for that square. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Die Stellung ist nun abgeklärt - Weiß hat einen Freibauern behauptet, und d5 bleibt noch immer schwach. (A) Lopez : 'Reti is intending to play ...Ra5, so the Knight advances to provide coverage for that square.'''} 28. Nc3 $1 {Der schnellste Weg zum Gewinn. Indem er auf die Behaltung des a2 verzichtet, erreicht Weiß durch dessen Rückgabe das Eindringen seines  in das feindliche Lager, wodurch der entscheidende Bauernangriff ermöglicht wird. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine replies by putting pressure on the isolated pawn.''Alekhine replies by putting pressure on the isolated pawn. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '!' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Der schnellste Weg zum Gewinn. Indem er auf die Behaltung des a2 verzichtet, erreicht Weiß durch dessen Rückgabe das Eindringen seines  in das feindliche Lager, wodurch der entscheidende Bauernangriff ermöglicht wird. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine replies by putting pressure on the isolated pawn.'''} (28. a3 $6 Ra5 29. Be3 Rb5 {hätte dem Gegner einen zäheren Widerstand gestattet. (A)}) 28... Ra5 {Lopez : 'Reti attacks the hanging Bishop. The idea is to force the Bishop to move so that the a5-Rook will help defend the d-pawn. But this seems a bit awkward.''Reti attacks the hanging Bishop. The idea is to force the Bishop to move so that the a5-Rook will help defend the d-pawn. But this seems a bit awkward. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti attacks the hanging Bishop. The idea is to force the Bishop to move so that the a5-Rook will help defend the d-pawn. But this seems a bit awkward.'''} 29. Bb6 {Zeitgewinn. (A) Lopez : 'The Bishop moves (of course) but to a square from which it threatens the a5-Rook.''The Bishop moves (of course) but to a square from which it threatens the a5-Rook. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Zeitgewinn. (A) Lopez : 'The Bishop moves (of course) but to a square from which it threatens the a5-Rook.'''} Ra6 {Lopez : 'The Rook creates another threat to the Bishop. By keeping White off-balance this way, Reti doesn't give his opponent time to capture the isolated pawn.''The Rook creates another threat to the Bishop. By keeping White off-balance this way, Reti doesn't give his opponent time to capture the isolated pawn. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'The Rook creates another threat to the Bishop. By keeping White off-balance this way, Reti doesn't give his opponent time to capture the isolated pawn.'''} (29... Ra3 {This was another possibility to consider. The Rook pins the Knight to the White Rook.} 30. Bf1 {The Bishop defends the Rook, allowing the Knight to move. But White's pieces seem a bit uncoordinated.}) 30. Bc5 {Lopez : 'Alekhine merely moves the Bishop back to its former post.''Alekhine merely moves the Bishop back to its former post. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine merely moves the Bishop back to its former post.'''} Ra5 {Lopez : 'Reti, a pawn down, is only too happy to repeat the position.''Reti, a pawn down, is only too happy to repeat the position. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti, a pawn down, is only too happy to repeat the position.'''} 31. Be3 $1 {Lopez : 'Alekhine must find another plan, as he is unwilling to settle for a draw. The Bishop now goes to the only other square that makes sense.''Alekhine must find another plan, as he is unwilling to settle for a draw. The Bishop now goes to the only other square that makes sense. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '!' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine must find another plan, as he is unwilling to settle for a draw. The Bishop now goes to the only other square that makes sense.'''} Nb4 {Lopez : 'Reti keeps the pressure up by attacking the d3-Rook.''Reti keeps the pressure up by attacking the d3-Rook. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti keeps the pressure up by attacking the d3-Rook.'''} (31... d4 32. Bxc6 $1 (32. Bxd4 $2 Nxd4 33. Rxd4 Nd5 $1 {mit Remischancen. (A)}) 32... dxc3 33. a4 $18 {und c3 geht verloren. (A, R)}) 32. Rd2 {Lopez : 'The Rook must withdraw.''The Rook must withdraw. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'The Rook must withdraw.'''} h6 {Lopez : 'Having done all he can on the Queenside, Reti now turns his attention to the Kingside.''Having done all he can on the Queenside, Reti now turns his attention to the Kingside. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Having done all he can on the Queenside, Reti now turns his attention to the Kingside.'''} (32... Ne4 $2 33. Nxe4 dxe4 34. Rd8+ Bf8 35. f5 $1 $18 {(A)}) 33. a4 {Droht 34.b6 und erzwingt damit den Gegenzug. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine advances the pawn, taking space away from the a5-Rook (the pawn is guarded by the Knight on c3).''Alekhine advances the pawn, taking space away from the a5-Rook (the pawn is guarded by the Knight on c3). Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Droht 34.b6 und erzwingt damit den Gegenzug. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine advances the pawn, taking space away from the a5-Rook (the pawn is guarded by the Knight on c3).''' Droht 34.b6 und erzwingt damit den Gegenzug. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine advances the pawn, taking space away from the a5-Rook (the pawn is guarded by the Knight on c3).''Alekhine advances the pawn, taking space away from the a5-Rook (the pawn is guarded by the Knight on c3). Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Droht 34.b6 und erzwingt damit den Gegenzug. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine advances the pawn, taking space away from the a5-Rook (the pawn is guarded by the Knight on c3).''' Droht 34.b6 und erzwingt damit den Gegenzug. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine advances the pawn, taking space away from the a5-Rook (the pawn is guarded by the Knight on c3).''Alekhine advances the pawn, taking space away from the a5-Rook (the pawn is guarded by the Knight on c3). Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Droht 34.b6 und erzwingt damit den Gegenzug. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine advances the pawn, taking space away from the a5-Rook (the pawn is guarded by the Knight on c3).''' Ribli: '!'} Ne4 $8 {Lopez : 'Reti sees a way to try to improve his position. He begins by attacking the Rook on d2.''Reti sees a way to try to improve his position. He begins by attacking the Rook on d2. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti sees a way to try to improve his position. He begins by attacking the Rook on d2.'''} 34. Nxe4 {Lopez : 'The Knight swap is forced, as White has no way to save both the Rook and the c3-Knight.''The Knight swap is forced, as White has no way to save both the Rook and the c3-Knight. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'The Knight swap is forced, as White has no way to save both the Rook and the c3-Knight.'''} dxe4 {Lopez : 'The obvious conclusion to the trade.''The obvious conclusion to the trade. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'The obvious conclusion to the trade.'''} 35. Rd8+ {Lopez : 'Alekhine picks up a tempo by attacking the King.''Alekhine picks up a tempo by attacking the King. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine picks up a tempo by attacking the King.'''} Kh7 {Lopez : 'Moving the King to safety is better than ...Bf8 as the latter move just pins the Bishop.''Moving the King to safety is better than ...Bf8 as the latter move just pins the Bishop. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Moving the King to safety is better than ...Bf8 as the latter move just pins the Bishop.'''} 36. Bxe4 {Lopez : 'Alekhine snares the hanging pawn...''Alekhine snares the hanging pawn... Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine snares the hanging pawn...'''} Rxa4 {Lopez : '...and Reti returns the favor. The idea of these exchanges was to eliminate the central and Queenside pawns. Now Reti's Knight will be as valuable as a Bishop in an endgame with pawns on just one side of the board. Now his problem is how to get his Knight back across the board.''...and Reti returns the favor. The idea of these exchanges was to eliminate the central and Queenside pawns. Now Reti's Knight will be as valuable as a Bishop in an endgame with pawns on just one side of the board. Now his problem is how to get his Knight back across the board. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : '...and Reti returns the favor. The idea of these exchanges was to eliminate the central and Queenside pawns. Now Reti's Knight will be as valuable as a Bishop in an endgame with pawns on just one side of the board. Now his problem is how to get his Knight back across the board.'''} (36... f5 37. Rd7 $1 (37. Ra8 {is much simpler (Nunn).}) 37... Kh8 (37... fxe4 38. Bd4 Rd5 39. Rxg7+ Kh8 40. Rd7+ Kg8 41. Rxd5 Nxd5 $18) 38. Bd4 Bxd4 39. Rxd4 fxe4 (39... Rxa4 40. Bb1 $1 Kg7 41. Kg2 {followed by 40.c4 and 41.c2, winning as 41.-a2 can be met by 42.b3. (Nunn)}) 40. Rxb4 $18 {(A)}) 37. f5 $1 {Einleitung zum entscheidenden Bauernsturm. Zunächst droht 38.fg:+ fg: 39.d6. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine wants to play fxg6 fxg6. His pawns will then be undoubled and his 3-2 pawn majority should be capable of promotion.''Alekhine wants to play fxg6 fxg6. His pawns will then be undoubled and his 3-2 pawn majority should be capable of promotion. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '!' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Einleitung zum entscheidenden Bauernsturm. Zunächst droht 38.fg:+ fg: 39.d6. (A) Lopez : 'Alekhine wants to play fxg6 fxg6. His pawns will then be undoubled and his 3-2 pawn majority should be capable of promotion.'''} Ra6 {Lopez : 'Covering c6 so that the Knight can start crossing back over to the Kingside.''Covering c6 so that the Knight can start crossing back over to the Kingside. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Covering c6 so that the Knight can start crossing back over to the Kingside.'''} 38. h4 {Lopez : 'Preventing ...g6-g5.''Preventing ...g6-g5. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Preventing ...g6-g5.'''} h5 {Erzwungen wegen der Drohung 39.h5. (A) Lopez : 'Likewise grabbing space and making it difficult for the White g-pawn to advance.''Likewise grabbing space and making it difficult for the White g-pawn to advance. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Erzwungen wegen der Drohung 39.h5. (A) Lopez : 'Likewise grabbing space and making it difficult for the White g-pawn to advance.'''} 39. g4 $1 {Aljechin führt den Schlußangriff wuchtig und überzeugend. (R) Lopez : 'Surprise! White is unafraid of ...hxg4, as Black will have doubled g-pawns.''Surprise! White is unafraid of ...hxg4, as Black will have doubled g-pawns. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '!' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Aljechin führt den Schlußangriff wuchtig und überzeugend. (R) Lopez : 'Surprise! White is unafraid of ...hxg4, as Black will have doubled g-pawns.'''} Ra5 {Lopez : 'Reti puts flank pressure on the Kingside pawns.''Reti puts flank pressure on the Kingside pawns. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti puts flank pressure on the Kingside pawns.'''} (39... hxg4 40. h5 $18 {(A)} (40. fxg6+ {Ribli} fxg6 41. h5)) 40. fxg6+ {Lopez : 'Alekhine breaks up the Black pawns around the King.''Alekhine breaks up the Black pawns around the King. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine breaks up the Black pawns around the King.'''} fxg6 {Lopez : 'Reti recaptures, but he's in dire straits. His g-pawn is now pinned.''Reti recaptures, but he's in dire straits. His g-pawn is now pinned. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti recaptures, but he's in dire straits. His g-pawn is now pinned.'''} 41. gxh5 {Lopez : 'Alekhine picks at the pawns around the White King. There is now a threat of mate: hxg6!''Alekhine picks at the pawns around the White King. There is now a threat of mate: hxg6! Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Alekhine picks at the pawns around the White King. There is now a threat of mate: hxg6!'''} Rxh5 {Lopez : 'It was either this or the awful ...Bf6.''It was either this or the awful ...Bf6. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'It was either this or the awful ...Bf6.'''} 42. Bg5 $18 {Gewinnt noch zum mindesten die Qualität. (A) Lopez : 'And now the Black Rook is cut off.''And now the Black Rook is cut off. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: '+-' Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Gewinnt noch zum mindesten die Qualität. (A) Lopez : 'And now the Black Rook is cut off.'''} Bc3 {Lopez : 'Reti gives his King a bit of breathing room, but it's a pretty hopeless situation. Black could resign here.''Reti gives his King a bit of breathing room, but it's a pretty hopeless situation. Black could resign here. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'Reti gives his King a bit of breathing room, but it's a pretty hopeless situation. Black could resign here.'''} 43. Rd7+ {Lopez : 'By checking the King, Alekhine forces it to the back rank.''By checking the King, Alekhine forces it to the back rank. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : 'By checking the King, Alekhine forces it to the back rank.'''} Kg8 {Lopez : '...Kh8 was also possible, though iy would hardly make a difference.''...Kh8 was also possible, though iy would hardly make a difference. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Lopez : '...Kh8 was also possible, though iy would hardly make a difference.'''} 44. Bxg6 {Nun gewinnt auf 44.-h8 das Vorgehen des h4 ganz leicht. (A) Lopez : 'With his King cornered and its protection gone, Reti calls it a day and resigns.''With his King cornered and its protection gone, Reti calls it a day and resigns. Kotov: Erbe II, 91: 'Nun gewinnt auf 44.-h8 das Vorgehen des h4 ganz leicht. (A) Lopez : 'With his King cornered and its protection gone, Reti calls it a day and resigns.'''} 1-0


