{Thomas Engqvist: 'The super-tournament in Moscow took place from November 10th to December 8th, 1925. It was organized by Nikolai Krylenko using Soviet state funds, and featured 21 participants from around the world, of whom world champion Capablanca and Emanuel Lasker were regarded as the favourites. So it was a surprise when Efim Bogoljubow, in his greatest ever triumph, took clear first place, scoring 15½ points out of 21. Lasker was second on 14 points, with Capablanca third on 13½. Réti finished two points behind Capablanca and shared 7th place with Peter Romanovsky. The great Russian film director, Vselovod Pudovkin, together with Nikolai Shpikovsky, produced a short silent comedy called 'Chess Fever' (1925), which contains footage from the tournament itself. For a couple of seconds it is possible to see a clear picture of Réti. '} 1. Nf3 {CB 1)WSZ 1925, S.356 [Reti in Shakhmatny Listok] 1)WSZ 1925, S.356 [Reti in Shakhmatny Listok] Stohl 1)WSZ 1925, S.356 [Reti in Shakhmatny Listok]} d5 2. c4 c6 3. b3 Bg4 4. Bb2 ({QUESTION: How would Black respond to} 4. Ne5 {here?} {whereas the tactical trick} dxc4 ({ANSWER: Although it gains time on the g4-bishop, 4 Ne5 has the fundamental drawback that, after} 4... Bh5 {, a timely ...Nd7 or ...f7-f6 will put the aggressively posted knight itself under pressure; while} 5. g4 Bg6 {leaves the white kingside slightly compromised} ({rather than} 5... f6 $6 6. gxh5 fxe5 7. Bh3 {, when White has the initiative on the light squares.})) (4... Bf5 {is fine too, if Black prefers}) 5. Nxg4 Qd4 {is in White's favour after} 6. Nc3 $1 Qxg4 7. h3 ({or even} 7. bxc4 $5 Qxc4 8. Rb1 {, followed by e2-e3 and d2-d4 with more than sufficient compensation for the pawn}) 7... Qd7 8. bxc4 {.}) 4... e6 (4... Bxf3 $5 {Stohl} 5. gxf3 Nd7 (5... e6 $5) 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. d4 e6 8. Nc3 Rc8 $13 {McNab,C-Hodgson,Ju,Bath zt 1987}) 5. e3 (5. d3 Bxf3 6. gxf3 Nf6 $13) 5... Nf6 6. Be2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. h3 Bh5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The natural and best move, keeping options with the bishop as well as the tension on the h5-d1 diagonal. There may be a better moment later in the game for either an exchange on f3 (or e2) or a switch to the h7-b1 diagonal. Perhaps something else is in store for the light-squared bishop, although it is not possible to figure it out at this moment.'} ({The immediate} 8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 {, followed by} Nbd7) ({and} 8... Bf5 9. Nh4 Bg6 ({or} 9... Bxb1 10. Rxb1 Nbd7) 10. Nxg6 hxg6 {might gain some time but relinquish the light-squared bishop, which is not to everyone's taste. After all, the bishop pair may turn out to be of long-term value, showing its teeth in the endgame when some pawns have vanished from the board.}) 9. d3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'One step with the d-pawn is in the hypermodern style. '} (9. d4 {would transpose to a quiet version of the Slav Defence – and a classical game.}) 9... c5 $1 $10 {c6 Thomas Engqvist: '!?' '!?'} ({Either} 9... Nbd7) ({or} 9... a5 {is more in the spirit of Black's set-up, but the text move is typical of Bogoljubow's optimistic style when playing with the black pieces (as exemplified by his famous quote in the introduction to Game 19). It is probably better to be an optimist than a pessimist when playing chess, even if one's judgment can then be slightly biased.}) 10. cxd5 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Since Black is planning to develop his b8-knight to c6, a logical continuation is'} 10. Ne5 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!'} Bxe2 11. Qxe2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'while '} Nbd7 $10 {Thomas Engqvist: 'can be met by '} ({Presumably Réti did not like} 11... Nfd7 $1 {But retreating again with} 12. Nf3 {might give White an edge. For example,} ({when the simplifying} 12. f4 Nxe5 {favours Black, who can now play ...Nc6.} (12... Z0)) 12... Nc6 ({while if Black replies in kind with} 12... Nf6 {, the exchange of light-squared bishops has smoothed White's development, who can play} 13. Rd1 {, followed by Nc3 (or Nbd2) and Rac1 with a harmonious position}) 13. cxd5 exd5 14. d4 {will soon leave Black with an isolated d5-pawn.}) ({when} 11... Nc6 $6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 {saddles him with a weakness at c5} (12... Z0)) 12. f4 $1 {.}) 10... Nxd5 ({White would meet} 10... exd5 {with} 11. d4 {, aiming for another isolated d-pawn position. The wasted tempo on d2-d3-d4 does not really matter.}) 11. Nc3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'White's pawns on b3, d3 and e3 (with bishops on b2 and e2) are nowadays familiar as a Hedgehog. Its latent dynamism was demonstrated (primarily with reversed colours) by Anatoly Karpov and Ulf Andersson in the 1970s.'} (11. Nbd2 $5 Bf6 $10) ({Here} 11. a3 {, followed by Nbd2 and Qc2, would be the thematic development, but of course in Réti's time this set-up was not yet known.}) 11... Nc6 ({Black could oppose White's fianchettoed bishop by playing} 11... Bf6 {. After the natural continuation} 12. Rc1 Nc6 13. Qd2 Rc8 14. Rfd1 Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Bxc3 16. Qxc3 b6 {, the position is about equal.}) 12. Rc1 Rc8 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: How should White proceed? '} 13. Qd2 ({ANSWER: First of all, White should check the variations after} 13. Nxd5 {.} {while} Qxd5 ({For instance,} 13... exd5 $6 14. d4 {gives White a solid edge;} (14. Z0)) 14. d4 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Bxe2 16. Qxe2 {However, Black seems to be fine after something like} Rfd8 {, so it seems White has nothing to gain from forcing the pace and that Réti's natural queen development is a sensible choice} (16... Nxd4 $6 17. Bxd4 a6 18. Rfd1 {also keeps a slight advantage. White's pieces are more active, with his bishop tremendously situated in the centre, whereas the black queen is a little uncomfortable on d5. If Black tries} Rxc1 19. Rxc1 e5 {, White keeps control of the c-file with the amazing} 20. Ba7 $1 {, when} Ra8 21. Qc2 $1 Rxa7 22. Qc8+ Qd8 ({not} 22... Bd8 $4 23. Qb8 {, trapping the rook}) 23. Qxd8+ Bxd8 24. Rc8 Kf8 25. Rxd8+ {leaves White with the better endgame.})) 13... Nxc3 ({Alternatively, Black might play} 13... Ndb4 $5 {, putting some pressure on d3. Considering that Black possesses more space (the c5-pawn!), it is logical to keep as many pieces on the board as possible. If White hits the knight at once with} 14. a3 (14. Rfd1 Bg6 15. a3 {is a quieter continuation.}) {, Black can respond} 14... Bxf3 $1 15. gxf3 Na5 {, intending} 16. axb4 $2 ({White would have to play} 16. Rb1 $1 {, when} Nbc6 17. Ba1 f5 {leads to an interesting and sharp battle}) 16... Nxb3 17. Qd1 Nxc1 18. Bxc1 cxb4 {with a big advantage.}) 14. Bxc3 Qb6 15. Qb2 f6 16. Rfd1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'White has completed his development and managed to provoke a slight weakening on the kingside in the process. '} (16. Kh1 $5 $13 {g4-g5}) 16... Rfd8 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: How should White continue now? ANSWER:'} 17. Ne1 $6 {Thomas Engqvist: '!?' '!?' Thomas Engqvist: 'It is normally in Black's interest to remove the defender of the d3-pawn, which becomes weaker after the equivalent exchange in a Hedgehog, and so also here. One of the main goals is to advance this pawn to the fourth rank, so this is what Réti should have done, objectively speaking. '} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'The drawback with '} 17. d4 $10 {Thomas Engqvist: 'is that it leads to simplification after '} cxd4 18. Nxd4 Bxe2 ({Black can play} 18... Bf7 {if he wants to avoid too many exchanges himself}) 19. Qxe2 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Qa5 {and so forth. Rather than allow his opponent an easy game, Réti presumably wanted to keep more tension in the position, even if this approach means that more is demanded of both players.}) 17... Bxe2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The principled move since, as we have just said, it weakens the d3-pawn further, though Black has little chance of winning it with White's minor pieces where they are at present. Considering that Black has a space advantage, he might consider retreating the bishop to g6, f7 or even e8. This is an interesting case of colliding elements, and it is a matter of taste how one chooses to play. '} 18. Qxe2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'In 'Shakhmatny Listok' (1925), Réti wrote that the position is approximately equal here, whereas the computer is more definite, evaluating it at "0.00". '} Qa6 $5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The queen puts slight pressure against the d3- and a2-pawns, while making way for the black b-pawn to support its colleague on c5, and incidentally pinning the white d-pawn. It is logical that Black has a white-square strategy with his queen after the light-squared bishops have been traded. '} 19. Rc2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'By overprotecting the a2-pawn, Réti frees his queen to roam, while preparing to double rooks on either the c- or d-file. '} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'White could play '} 19. Qg4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'at once, but'} Nb4 (19... e5 20. Qc4+ Qxc4 21. dxc4 Rxd1 ({and} 21... e4 $5 {is worth investigating too}) 22. Rxd1 Rd8 {just leads to equality.}) 20. Bxb4 cxb4 $36 {c} 21. Rxc8 Rxc8 22. d4 {might offer a little something.}) 19... Rd6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The rook looks slightly disharmonious here, considering the temporarily reduced activity of the e7-bishop, though it does at least defend the e6-pawn. '} ({Another way of doubling rooks is} 19... Rc7 {, keeping an eye on the c5-pawn as well as the b4-square behind it.}) ({Note that} 19... Nb4 20. Bxb4 cxb4 21. Rdc1 {leads to a comfortable position for White.}) 20. Qg4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Since Réti does not want to break with d3-d4, his only options for active play are on the flanks, either attacking the king with h3-h4-h5 or trying to open the c-file with b3-b4. Putting the queen on g4 supports both plans. '} ({The tricky} 20. b4 cxb4 ({and Black has a trickier response of his own in} 20... c4 $1 {, no doubt seen by Bogoljubow who had a strong tactical eye}) 21. Bxb4 {does not achieve anything after} Rd7 {.}) 20... Rcd8 21. h4 b6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Defending c5 and clearing a path for his queen to return to the centre.'} 22. h5 $6 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Another idea is to play '} 22. Rdc1 $142 $1 $132 { Thomas Engqvist: 'at once;'} {Thomas Engqvist: 'intending'} Qb7 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' '?!'} ({in this case Black might resort to} 22... e5 {, intending} 23. b4 ({or} 23. h5 Qc8 $1) 23... Qa4 $1 {.}) 23. b4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!'} cxb4 $2 24. Bxb4 Nxb4 25. Rc7 $18 {Thomas Engqvist: 'and wins;'} (25. Z0)) 22... Qb7 23. Rdc1 ({Clarifying the situation on the kingside} 23. h6 $6 g6 {would be in Black's favour, since White is in no position to try and exploit the slightly weakened dark squares.}) 23... Qd7 {Thomas Engqvist: 'The queen continues to centralize. '} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Alternatively, '} 23... a5 $15 {Thomas Engqvist: 'works against an immediate b3-b4 by White, though he could prepare it by playing a2-a3 first.'}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE (calculation): What should White play now? Calculate all necessary variations. '} 24. f4 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' '?!' Thomas Engqvist: 'White concentrates his efforts on the kingside, allowing Black to gain control on the rest of the board.'} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'ANSWER: Perhaps Réti did not fully consider the consequences of '} 24. b4 $142 $1 $132 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!' Thomas Engqvist: '.'} {or} e5 ({The main ideas are seen if Black accepts the pawn sacrifice with} 24... cxb4 {.} {But White can improve this by inserting} 25. h6 $1 ({The obvious} 25. Bxb4 $2 {fails to the intermezzo} f5 $1 26. Qf4 Nxb4 27. Rc7 ({or} 27. Qxb4 Rxd3) 27... Nxd3 $1 {(this is the point of luring the queen to f4)} 28. Nxd3 Qe8 29. Ne1 h6 {, when Black has an extra pawn and a strong bishop.}) 25... g6 {and only then} 26. Bxb4 Nxb4 (26... f5 $2 {does not work here due to the beautiful queen manoeuvre} 27. Qe2 $1 Nxb4 28. Rc7 Qe8 29. Qb2 $1 {and the mate threat at g7 means that White regains the knight with the more active position and good chances}) 27. Rc7 Qe8 28. Qxb4 R6d7 29. Qa4 (29. Qb2 {is also playable}) 29... Rxc7 30. Qxe8+ Rxe8 31. Rxc7 Bf8 32. Rxa7 Rc8 {and White has a minute advantage.}) ({Black is not obliged to go in for this. He might play, for instance,} 24... Rd5 25. bxc5 bxc5 {.}) 25. Qf3 Qe6 (25... cxb4 $6 26. Bd2 $1) 26. bxc5 bxc5 {, when his slightly inferior pawn structure is balanced by his more active pieces. The choice depends on whether a player gives priority to dynamic factors (such as active pieces) or static ones (such as a sound pawn structure).}) 24... e5 ({Another good move is} 24... Qe8 {, preparing ...Qf7; or if White continues with} 25. h6 {, then} Qg6 {kills his slight kingside initiative in one stroke.}) 25. f5 ({Naturally, White does not want to exchange queens, since after} 25. Qxd7 R6xd7 26. f5 a5 $1 {, he is the one with static weaknesses. Black can consider several breaks such as ...a5-a4, ...g7-g6 or ...e5-e4 at the right moment. Note that the white queen on g4 actually controls all those critical breaking squares.}) 25... Bf8 26. Rf2 Qf7 27. Rf3 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'It is no good pushing '} 27. h6 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' '?!' Thomas Engqvist: 'just yet, since '} g5 $17 {Thomas Engqvist: 'then closes the kingside, leaving the h6-pawn as a permanent weakness. Otherwise'} 28. fxg6 $2 Qxg6 {picks it off very quickly.}) 27... a5 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Bogoljubow finally takes time to play this useful move, which helps prevent the b3-b4 break, as well as preparing his own ...a5-a4 when the circumstances seem right. '} 28. Rg3 Ra8 $36 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' '?!' Thomas Engqvist: 'But circumstances are not right yet. '} (28... h6 $5) ({The careful} 28... Kh8 {is the most logical move, when} 29. h6 $6 {can be met by} g6 $1 (29... g5) ({and} 29... gxh6 {are good too}) 30. fxg6 hxg6 {, intending} 31. Qxg6 Qxg6 32. Rxg6 Kh7 {, followed by ...Bxh6, with the advantage due to his superior structure and more active pieces.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: How does White exploit Black's last move? '} 29. Qf3 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' '?!'} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'ANSWER: This is a good moment for '} 29. h6 {Thomas Engqvist: ', with the following possible variations: '} g5 30. fxg6 hxg6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'but not '} 31. Qxg6+ {Thomas Engqvist: '?' '?'} (31. Qe4 f5 $1 ({after} 31... Kh7 32. Nf3 Bxh6 33. Rf1 {, White has enough compensation for the pawn}) 32. h7+ Kxh7 ({of course not} 32... Qxh7 $2 33. Qxf5 {and White is clearly better}) 33. Qh4+ Bh6 34. Rh3 g5 ({not} 34... Qg7 $6 35. Nf3) 35. Qxg5 Rg8 36. Qh4 Rg4 37. Qf2 Kg8 38. Rc2 {and White is still in the game. Note that the e1-knight defends both d3 and g2.}) ({or} 31. Qh4 $5) 31... Qxg6 32. Rxg6+ Kh7 $15 {Thomas Engqvist: 'etc'}) 29... a4 $2 {Thomas Engqvist: '?!' '?!'} (29... h6 {d5,a4}) ({Either} 29... Kh8 {again}) ({or} 29... Ra7 {, breaking the pin on the knight and adding to the defence along the rank, is a better preparation.}) 30. b4 $1 $36 {b5 Thomas Engqvist: '?!' '?!'} ({Réti plays to exploit Black's self-pin directly, but it is more precise to insert} 30. h6 $1 g5 ({note that if Black tries to win a pawn with} 30... axb3 31. hxg7 Bxg7 32. axb3 Qxb3 {, White replies} 33. Bxe5 $1 fxe5 34. f6 Ra7 35. Rc4 $1 {, planning Rcg4, with the upper hand}) 31. fxg6 hxg6 {and only then play} 32. b4 {.}) 30... e4 {Thomas Engqvist: '??' '??' Thomas Engqvist: 'There is no need to give a pawn away.'} (30... Ra7 {defuses the threat of b4-b5, and Black can just ignore h5-h6; for example,} 31. bxc5 bxc5 32. h6 ({or} 32. Qe2 Nb4) 32... Qxa2 $1 {with an edge.}) {Thomas Engqvist: 'EXERCISE: What is the correct response to this unexpected thrust in the centre? ANSWER:'} 31. dxe4 $1 {e5+-} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Bogoljubow was probably hoping for '} 31. Qxe4 $2 Re8 {cb4,a2} 32. Qg4 cxb4 33. Bxb4 Nxb4 34. Qxb4 Rxd3 $1 ({or} 34... Rc6 $5 35. Qb1 Rxc1 36. Qxc1 h6 {and Black's chances are slightly preferable; it is not clear what White's rook and knight are doing and his pawns look rather weak}) 35. Rxg7+ $6 ({or} 35. Qxb6 Rd6) 35... Kxg7 $1 36. Qg4+ Kh8 37. Nxd3 Bh6 {, followed by ...Bxe3+ with decent winning chances. The bishop is huge on e3, whereas the white knight lacks a strong outpost; note that} 38. Nf4 $2 Qxa2 {gives Black a big advantage.}) 31... Rad8 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' '?'} ({Possibly Bogoljubow overlooked that} 31... cxb4 $2 {fails to} 32. e5 $1 fxe5 33. Bxe5 {, winning material since the knight is still pinned.}) ({Taking the other way with} 31... Nxb4 $2 {also leads to a difficult position for Black after} 32. e5 $1 {(this thrust did not exist before)} Rdd8 33. e6 ({not} 33. exf6 $4 Nxa2 34. fxg7 Bd6) 33... Qe7 34. Ba1 $1 {and White is strategically winning:} Nxa2 {is answered by} 35. Rc4 {, followed by Rcg4 and h5-h6, or if} h6 {then} 36. Rg6 {, threatening Bxf6, is very convincing.}) ({Even at this stage} 31... Ra7 $1 {is comparatively best, giving further protection to the g7-square, although} 32. bxc5 bxc5 33. Qe2 {keeps a solid advantage. The text move is a positional mistake; the rook is not doing anything on d8 since it lacks invasion squares on the d-file.}) 32. bxc5 bxc5 33. h6 $40 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!'} Kh8 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Now '} 33... Qxa2 34. hxg7 Bxg7 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'fails to'} (34... Be7 35. Ra1 {gives White a clear advantage.}) 35. e5 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!'} fxe5 36. f6 $18 {Thomas Engqvist: 'again'}) ({Avoiding the capture on g7 by playing} 33... g6 {s little better for Black, in view of} 34. fxg6 ({the funny variation} 34. Qh5 $5 g5 35. Rxg5+ fxg5 36. Qxg5+ Rg6 37. fxg6 Qxg6 38. Qxg6+ hxg6 39. Kf1 {also leads to an advantageous ending for White}) 34... hxg6 35. h7+ Kh8 ({or} 35... Kxh7 36. e5 $1) 36. e5 Re6 37. exf6 {and so on.}) 34. hxg7+ Bxg7 {Thomas Engqvist: 'or'} 35. Qe2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'Other good moves, taking care of the a2-pawn, were also'} ({Both} 35. a3) ({and} 35. Qg4 {also came into consideration.}) 35... Nb4 36. Bxb4 {Thomas Engqvist: '?' '?' Thomas Engqvist: 'The drawback to safeguarding the a2-pawn in this way is that it gives Black an effective majority. '} (36. a3 $2 {is also a mistake, in view of} Na2 $1 37. Rc2 Nxc3 38. Rxc3 Rd1 {, when Black has good counterplay and can be happy with the outcome.}) ({It is understandable that Réti wanted to avoid} 36. Ra1 {, which looks very passive. Nonetheless, this was the right move, intending simply to drive the knight away with a2-a3 and then reactivate the rook. If Black prevents this with} a3 {, White can target the knight in another, unexpected way by bringing his kingside rook (actually the queen's rook) to the fourth rank and slowly preparing e4-e5. Look at the following variation:} 37. Rh3 ({better than} 37. Rg4 Qh5) 37... R6d7 38. Rh4 $1 Qg8 (38... Kg8) ({and} 38... h6 {are met the same way}) 39. Nf3 {, threatening e4-e5, and if Black prevents that with} Nd3 {, White can bring the rook out of the corner, keeping a clear advantage.}) 36... cxb4 37. Nf3 b3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: How should White continue? ANSWER:'} 38. Nd4 $1 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'The obvious move '} 38. axb3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'is well met by '} Qxb3 $132 { Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!' Thomas Engqvist: ', threatening 39...Rd1+ 40 Rxd1 Qxd1+ 41 Kf2 Qxe2+ 42 Kxe2 a3 43 Rh3 Rd1!! and the a-pawn cannot be stopped. White's best try is to move the king. For example,'} {Thomas Engqvist: 'and'} 39. Nd4 $2 {Thomas Engqvist: '??' '??' Thomas Engqvist: 'runs into '} (39. Kh2 Qd3 ({obviously} 39... a3 $2 40. Nd4 {is to White's advantage}) 40. Qxd3 ({or} 40. Qa2 Qb3 {again}) 40... Rxd3 41. Nd4 {leads to a rather forced line:} Bh6 42. Ne6 Rxe3 43. Nxd8 Rxg3 44. Nf7+ Kg7 45. Nxh6 Rg5 46. Rc6 Rh5+ 47. Kg3 Rxh6 48. Rc7+ Kf8 49. Ra7 Rh1 50. Rxa4 {and White has an advantageous rook ending but probably not a win.}) (39. Kf2 {is met by} Rd3 $1 40. Rh3 Qb4 {, threatening ...Qxe4 and ...Rd2}) 39... Rxd4 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'since the g3-rook is undefended'}) ({Note that the tempting} 38. e5 fxe5 39. Ng5 {fails to} Qxf5 40. Rf1 Qxf1+ $1 41. Qxf1 Rd1 {and White has to take the draw with} 42. Nf7+ Kg8 43. Nh6+ {etc.}) 38... bxa2 39. Ra1 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'It is too soon for '} 39. Ne6 $6 {Thomas Engqvist: 'since '} Rxe6 40. fxe6 Qxe6 {e5-+ Thomas Engqvist: 'gives Black sufficient compensation for the exchange. The natural-looking move'} 41. Ra1 $4 {actually loses to} Qe5 42. Qe1 Qb2 {, when ...f6-f5 is in the air with an easy win.}) 39... Bh6 {xe3 Thomas Engqvist: '?!' '?!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Black wants to activate the bishop while threatening the e3-pawn, but this cheapo is very easy to stop. '} ({It looks simpler to activate both rooks with} 39... Rb6 40. Qxa2 Qxa2 41. Rxa2 Ra8 42. Ne6 Rb7 {, when Black has reasonable drawing chances.}) 40. Ne6 $16 Rxe6 $8 {Thomas Engqvist: '!' '!' Thomas Engqvist: 'Here, too, Black's best chance is to sacrifice the exchange and rely on the a-pawn (in this case the back-up pawn on a4). '} (40... Rd2 41. Nxd8) ({His position is more vulnerable with the queens and knight left on the board; for example,} 40... Rg8 $6 41. Rxg8+ Qxg8 42. Rxa2 Qg3 43. Rc2 $1 Bxe3+ (43... Qxe3+ $2 44. Kh1 $1 {is immediately fatal}) 44. Kf1 h6 45. Qh5 $1 Qg8 46. e5 $1 fxe5 47. Qh4 Bg5 48. Qxa4 {and White has excellent winning chances.}) 41. fxe6 Qxe6 42. Rxa2 Qxe4 {Thomas Engqvist: 'QUESTION: What is White's best winning attempt?   ANSWER:'} 43. Qf3 $1 {Thomas Engqvist: 'White has nothing better than to offer the exchange of queens here. This move has the added benefit of setting a little trap, which proves to be remarkably successful. '} Bxe3+ $2 {Thomas Engqvist: '??' '??'} ({Thomas Engqvist: 'In a rush of blood, Bogoljubow sees that he can deflect the white queen first, but this is no good either. He had to play '} 43... Qxf3 44. Rxf3 {Thomas Engqvist: 'or'} Re8 (44... Ra8 45. e4 $16 Bf8 $1 (45... Bc1 $2 {is met by} 46. Rc3 $1 {and 47 Rca3}) 46. Rxf6 a3 47. Kf2 ({the rook vs. bishop ending after} 47. Rf3 Bc5+ 48. Kf1 Ra4 49. Rc3 Be7 50. e5 Re4 51. Rc7 Rxe5 52. Re2 Rxe2 53. Kxe2 Bf6 {is also a draw}) 47... Bg7 48. Rf7 Bb2 {and the endgame of rook and two pawns vs. rook and pawn on the kingside is drawn, whether White gives up his trapped rook for bishop and a-pawn or leaves them all where they are.}) 45. Kf2 {Thomas Engqvist: 'and White wins a pawn after'} Re4 46. Rxf6 Bxe3+ 47. Kf3 Re7 48. Rxa4 $16 {Thomas Engqvist: 'and so forth.'}) ({Obviously not} 43... Qb1+ $4 44. Kh2 Qxa2 $4 45. Qxf6+ {and mates.}) 44. Qxe3 $1 ({Thomas Engqvist: 'Presumably Bogoljubow only realized now that '} 44. Qxe3 Qb1+ 45. Kh2 Qxa2 46. Qe7 $18 {Thomas Engqvist: 'also leads to a quick mate. This was one of only two games Bogoljubow lost in Moscow (the other was to Capablanca). It did not help Réti all that much since he himself lost four games; to Grünfeld, Marshall, Spielmann and Tartakower.'}) 1-0


