1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bf4 Nbd7 4. Nbd2 g6 5. e4 Bg7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. h3 c6 ({Better, as a preparation for ...e7-e5, would have been} 7... Re8 {[%cal Ye7e5]}) 8. O-O Qc7 9. Bh2 {[In order not to be forced to exchange after Black's ...e7-e5, but to keep the center position firm with c2-c3.]} e5 10. c3 Nh5 {[This attempt to retain the attack on the King's wing is thwarted by White's depth of play.]} 11. a4 $1 {[This looks like the beginning of an attack on the Queen's wing, but it is, as we shall soon see, the commencement of counteraction against 10...h5.]} a5 {[White threatened to establish the Knight permanently on c4 and in the long run to exert an intolerable pressure upon the points e5 and d6.]} 12. Nc4 b5 13. axb5 cxb5 14. Ne3 {[This threatens 15.xb5 as well as 15.d5.]} Nb6 {[Black believes White's attack against his Queen's wing has broken down.]} 15. g4 {[This was the point of 11.a4. The Knight was to be conveyed without loss of time via e3 to g2.]} Nf4 16. Bxf4 exf4 17. Ng2 h5 $1 18. gxh5 Bh6 ({If} 18... Bxh3 {then} 19. Ng5 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 {and White obtains a decisive attack along the h- and g-files.}) 19. Nfh4 Bxh3 20. Qf3 Qc8 {[%cal Rh3g4]} ({Threatens 21...g4. We shall soon see why Black did not play} 20... Qd7) 21. Nf5 Bxf5 22. exf5 g5 {[White has now succeeded in reducing Black's Bishop to the position of a pawn. That disadvantage Black can only get rid of if he can set his pawns in motion on the King's wing by means of ...g5-g4. To this effect he will bring his Knight at b6 by way of d7 to f6. With that in view he moved the Queen (on move 20) not to d7 but to c8.]} 23. Rfe1 {[This is no mere developing move in the old style, but the necessary introduction to counterplay against Black's plan as above outlined.]} Nd7 24. Qd5 Qb8 ({Naturally not} 24... Qc7 {because of} 25. Re7) 25. f6 $1 {[A species of problem combination which White has prepared with both of this last moves.]} ({White dare not win a pawn with} 25. Qc6 {because the sequel would be} Rc8 26. Qxd7 $2 Ra7) 25... Nxf6 26. Qf5 Qd8 ({Black certainly dare not play} 26... Kg7 {on account of} 27. Re6 {But he thought after the text to be able to continue with 27...g7 in order to enforce the exchange of Queens by 28...c8 or 28...d7 maintaining his preponderance in pawns.}) 27. f3 $3 Kg7 28. Kf2 $1 Qc8 29. Nh4 ({After} 29. Nh4 {we see how White's combination was calculated to a nicety. Black is lost. If he exchanges Queens by} Qxf5 ({He dare not take the Knight with} 29... gxh4 {because of} 30. Rg1+) ({and if Black moves his Queen from c8, e.g.} 29... Qd8 {then} 30. Rg1 {decides the game.}) 30. Nxf5+ {and White wins easily following} Kh7 31. Nxd6+ Kg7 32. Nf5+ Kh7 33. Re7) 1-0


