{White to move. This position is approximately equal, with both sides being able to point to certain advantages which more or less balance one another. White can be happy with his actively placed knights and rook on the open d-file, while Black's main asset is the monster knight on c3, which prevents White from doubling rooks on the open file. While strictly speaking neither side can claim an advantage, the burden is more on White to play accurately since Black's knight is firmly entrenched on an excellent square, while White's advantages are of a more temporary nature.} 24. Rd6 $6 ({Reti immediately makes a slip. White's rook was under attack and since the immediate 24.Rd7 could be met by 24...Ra7, Reti preferred to gain time by attacking Black's queen. However, he needed to play more energetically to counter the influence of Black's knight and the clearest way to maintain equality was to offer the exchange to dispose of the menacing piece:} 24. Nd7 $1 Nxd1 25. Rxd1 Rd8 ({after} 25... Rxc4 26. Nxf6+ gxf6 27. bxc4 {Black's advantage on the queenside is balanced by White's play against the exposed king}) 26. Rd6 Qa7 27. Nxf6+ gxf6 28. Qxf6 Rxd6 29. Nxd6 {and White will give perpetual check. The exchange sacrifice may seem a drastic solution to the position, but it's an example of the importance of anticipating problems in sufficient time to take preventative measures.}) (24. Rd7 Ra7) 24... Qb7 {[Diagram]} 25. Re1 {White has to take time out to defend the important e4-pawn, but now he threatens 26.Rb6 Qc7 27.Nc6, when his knights severely constrict Black's position. 25...} Bxe5 {It's correct to exchange one of White's menacing minor pieces.} ({White threatens} 25... Z0 26. Rb6 Qc7 27. Nc6) 26. Nxe5 Qc7 $1 {Lasker finds the most dangerous move, exploiting the uncomfortable position of White's pieces to force the enemy knight to return to c4.} ({The alternative} 26... Rd8 27. Nc4 e5 28. Rxd8+ Rxd8 {only leads to equality after} 29. Nxa5 ({or} 29. Nxe5 Qc7 30. Nd3 Qd6 31. Re3 Qe6 32. Nc5 Qe5 33. Nd3 Qe6 {, when a repetition is very likely.}) 29... Qc7 30. Nc4 Nxa4) 27. Nc4 {[Diagram]} e5 $2 ({But now Lasker fails to capitalize on his earlier careful play. He isconcerned that White will play e5 himself, creating an outpost on d6 which can be occupied by either rook or knight. However, this outpost is less dangerous than he imagined and it would have been better simply to grab the pawn by} 27... Nxa4 $1 28. Z0 (28. Red1 Rf8 29. Rd7 Nc5 {is very good for Black}) ({but after} 28. e5 {White threatens to win immediately by} Z0 29. Red1 {with} Z0 30. Rd7 ({or} 30. bxa4 Qxc4 31. Qxa8 $1 {to come})) (28. e5 Ra7 $1 29. Rd4 Nc3 30. Nd6 Rf8 {and White has trouble proving sufficient compensation.})) 28. Qf5 $1 {Reti at once exploits Black's mistake. Now not only is the e5-pawn attacked, but White also threatens an immediate win by 29.Rd7 28...} Ne2+ $5 {[Diagram] A typical Lasker move. Seeing that there is no really satisfactory continuation, Lasker chooses a move which at least creates complications and gives White the chance to go wrong. This is also a good example of how to create chances without taking excessive risks. Black has a poor position in any case and it turns out that even if White finds the best response to the move played, he is by no means guaranteed a win. Therefore Black is not losing anything by trying the knight check, especially as the correct reply is far from obvious.} ({Most players would have been content to accept the modest disadvantage that arises after} 28... Ra7 29. h4 Re8 30. h5 h6 {, although in this case} 31. Re3 {creates unpleasant pressure against Black's kingside.}) (28... g6 $2 29. Qxe5 Nxa4 {is worse, as although it maintains material equality it is positionally disastrous after} 30. h4 {, when Black is doomed by the lack of kingside defenders.}) 29. Kf1 $2 {Chess intuition screams for Kf1 to be played, since on f1 there is no danger of a back-rank mate and the king moves closer to the centre in case an endgame arises. There is no danger to the king along the a6-f1 diagonal, so this seems a far more natural choice than moving the king into the corner. Intuition is a valuable tool in many areas of life, but one should be aware that intuition can lead one badly astray in situations which do not fit standard patterns. That's the case here, since the king turns out to be poorly placed on f1 for the unlikely-looking reason that it allows a knight check on d2 later on. Concrete analysis of the position is the only real defence against being deceived like this.} ({After} 29. Rxe2 $2 Qxd6 30. Qxf7+ Kh8 31. Qd5 Qf6 32. Re1 Rd8 33. Qxe5 Qxe5 34. Nxe5 Kg8 {it may well be that the position is a draw but only Black can be better.}) (29. Kh1 $1 {was the best move and after 29...} Rd8 ({here} 29... Nd4 30. Qxe5 Nxb3 31. Nb6 {is winning for White as there is no check on d2}) 30. Qxe5 Rxd6 31. Qxd6 Qxd6 32. Nxd6 Nd4 33. Re3 Rd8 34. Nb7 Rd7 35. Rd3 Rxb7 36. Rxd4 Kf8 37. Rd5 Rc7 38. g4 Rc3 39. Rxa5 Rxb3 40. Rb5 {the queenside pawns will at some stage be exchanged, leaving an ending with four pawns against three on the kingside. Such endings can be drawn fairly easily if Black is able to set up a chain of pawns f7-g6-h5, but that is not possible here. According to theory, it should be a draw in any case, but the practical difficulties facing the defender are considerable. Perhaps the main point is that White has no simple win and therefore Black's 28th move was perfectly justified.}) 29... Nd4 30. Qxe5 Nxb3 31. Nb6 {With the king on f1, this is no longer effective as Black can transfer his knight to c4 with gain of tempo. 31...} Nd2+ $1 32. Kg1 (32. Ke2 $4 Nxe4 {and Black wins.}) 32... Nc4 33. Nxc4 Qxc4 {[Diagram] The upshot of the complications is very favourable for Black since he now has a powerful passed pawn on the queenside, while White has little counterplay on the opposite flank.} 34. Qf5 $2 {This is a mistake which should lose immediately. The alternatives offered a few drawing chances:} (34. h4 Rab8 $1 35. Qxa5 b3 36. Rb1 b2 37. Qe1 Qxa4 38. Rd2 Qa2 39. Kh2 Rb4 {is very good for Black although not a clear win.}) ({Defending passively by} 34. Rd7 Rab8 35. Rb1 b3 36. g3 {allows Black a large advantage; for example, after 36...} h6 37. Kg2 Re8 38. Qd4 Qe2 39. Rb2 Qxe4+ 40. Qxe4 Rxe4 41. Rd3 Reb4 {Black is a clear pawn ahead in the ending although it's true that it won't be so easy to win this position.}) (34. Qd5 Qxd5 35. exd5 Kf8 {is an unpleasant ending for White as Black's protected outside passed pawn is much stronger than White's isolated pawn in the centre of the board}) 34... Rab8 $2 ({Instead of this cautious move (34... Rab8?), Black could have won straight away by} 34... b3 $1 35. e5 (35. Rb6 Qxa4 {gives Black two connected passed pawns}) 35... b2 36. e6 {(White's only chance is to aim for kingside counterplay) 36...} fxe6 37. Rdxe6 Rab8 38. Re7 b1=Q $1 39. Rxb1 g6 {and White faces heavy material loss.}) 35. e5 $2 {[Diagram] Now Black is once again on track to win.} ({White should have tried} 35. Qd5 Qc3 36. Qd2 Qxd2 37. Rxd2 b3 38. Rb2 Rc4 39. Ra1 Rxe4 40. Kf1 g6 41. Rab1 Reb4 42. Ke2 {, when although Black is a pawn ahead, the win is not guaranteed.}) 35... b3 {The b-pawn is unstoppable so White's only hope is to aim for counterplay on the kingside.} 36. e6 fxe6 37. Rdxe6 Rf8 {This wins, but} ({it would have been simpler to continue} 37... b2 38. Re7 b1=Q $1 39. Rxb1 g6 {, as in the note to Black's 34th move.}) 38. Qe5 Qc2 39. f4 b2 40. Re7 Qg6 {For the moment Black has to fall back to defend against the threatened mate, but the b-pawn is simply too strong} 41. f5 {[Diagram]} Qf6 $2 {Lasker unexpectedly makes a serious mistake which could easily have cost him half a point.} ({There was a clear win by} 41... Qh6 $1 42. Qd4 (42. Rb1 Qc1+ 43. Qe1 Rfc8) 42... Kh8 43. Rb1 Rfc8 44. Ree1 Rc1 {and White's position is hopeless.}) 42. Qd5+ $2 {After this Black wins easily.} ({The best line was} 42. Rb1 $1 Qxe5 43. Rxe5 Rfc8 44. Kf2 Rc1 45. Re1 Rc4 46. Re2 Rcb4 47. Ke1 {and White has some chances to save the game although Black retains a large advantage}) 42... Kh8 {Now it's all over.} 43. Rb7 Qc3 (43... Qc3 {After} 44. Rf1 {, one way to win is 44...} Rxb7 45. Qxb7 Qe5 46. Rd1 Rb8 {followed by ...h6 and the b-pawn decides the game.}) 0-1


