1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. Bd3 {White has a large range of alternatives to the innocuous text move, including 7.cxd5, 7.c1 and 7.c2.} (7. cxd5 {allows White to develop his forces on either flank without fearing central counterplay, but the stabilised central situation also allows Black to deploy his pieces more freely; for example, the path for the queen bishop has been opened. The motivation behind 7.c1 and 7.c2 is more subtle. White expects that Black will want to play 7...dxc4}) 7... Re8 ({7.d3 does not follow this strategy and allows Black to play} 7... dxc4 $1 8. Bxc4 c5 {, a line which should lead to equality.}) 8. O-O Nf8 {Black is hoping for 9.cxd5 when the game will transpose into a standard exchange variation with Black's pieces on the usual squares. However, if white refrains from committing himself to definite actions, Black is sure to remain cramped and find his pieces misplaced.} 9. Ne5 c6 $6 {The '?!' could have gone to any of Black's last three moves. Black's position has become terribly passive and he soon realises his plan to strongpoint ...d5 will merely leave White with a free hand on the kingside.} ({Black should hit out with} 9... c5 {and hope for the best - the isolated QP which might result after exchanges in the centre would be a small price to pay for a little space.}) 10. f4 dxc4 {Black surrenders the centre and commits himself to a permanent inferiority.} (10... c5 {was still worth a try.}) 11. Bxc4 Nd5 {Correctly aiming to exchange pieces to ease his cramped position.} (11... c5 {is no longer feasible as} 12. Bb5 $1 {ties Black in knots.}) 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Qf3 f6 {It is hard to condemn a move which dislodges White's powerful knight even though it entails a slight weakening of Black's pawn structure.} ({Note that} 13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 {would only be helping White strengthen his centre. Black's main hope must be that when White plays e4 White's queen's pawn will prove weak - a slightly backward queen's pawn on a semi-open file is easier to attack that a backward queen's bishop pawn on a closed file (as would be the case after 13...xc3).}) 14. Nd3 Bd7 15. e4 Nb6 16. Bb3 Rad8 17. Rad1 Bc8 18. Nc5 Kh8 19. Qf2 Qc7 20. h3 {White prepares for play on the kingside.} ({This is certainly a powerful plan but my personal preference would be to interpolate the move} 20. a4 {to soften Black up on the queenside. If Black replied} a5 {the unprotected state of the Black queen's knight could later prevent Black's queen coming to the resuce on the kingside. Wheels within wheels. One should, however, consider the tournament situation when analysing this game. Reti, one of the strongest players in the world, had effortlessly achieved an imposing position against a little known player by the name of Watson (hardly the most chessic of names - compare Dunkelblum or the unpronounceable Euwe). Quite possibly Reti had already earmarked Watson as a tailender for the tournament (he was not wrong). Psychologically it would have been easy for Reti to assume that the remainder of the game would be just as easy as the first twenty moves and therefore Reti might have considered that a good move would do just as well as the best move. Watson sets about correcting that misconception in dogged fashion.}) 20... Re7 (20... e5 {is still not good:} 21. dxe5 fxe5 (21... Rxd1 22. Nxd1 $1 fxe5 23. fxe5) 22. Rxd8 Qxd8 23. fxe5 {and again White's extra pawn is stronger than it looks.}) 21. Kh1 Nbd7 22. Nxd7 $6 ({Normally one would expect White to avoid exchanges and leave Black's pieces in a tangle by playing} 22. Nd3 {. Reti was no doubt attracted by the bind which he obtains through his next few moves but logic should have suggested that unless Black could play ...e5 or ...c5, the plan would be even stronger with an extra pair of knights on the board.}) 22... Rexd7 23. e5 $1 {White closes the centre to facilitate his forthcomning kingside attack. Black's next is virtually forced as he cannot allow the White knight to reach d6. White has conceded an outpost on d5 in return for his on d6 but the Black minor pieces have little hope of being able to utilize it in the near future.} f5 24. g4 $1 g6 25. Rg1 Rg7 26. Qh4 Qe7 27. Qh6 (27. Qf6 $5 {was an interesting try. If Black exchanges queens, White will be left with a protected passed pawn in the endgame but without an exchange Black's forces remain severely restricted.}) 27... b6 28. Kh2 Bb7 29. Rg3 c5 {Black decides to try for activity at last.} ({Objectively} 29... Rd7 {might have been more sound but Reti was becoming short of time.}) 30. gxf5 {Initiating exchanges which dissipate a large part of White's advantage.} ({The correct line, as Maroczy pointed out in the tournament book, was} 30. Nb5 $1 cxd4 31. Nd6 {. White probably feared} Rxd6 32. exd6 Qxd6 {but Black lacks sufficient compensation for the exchange if White finds} 33. Qg5 $1) 30... gxf5 31. Rxg7 Qxg7 32. Qxg7+ Kxg7 33. Nb5 {Better late than never, White may have thought.} ({However, the d6 outpost means less with so few pieces on the board and White should have preferred} 33. dxc5 {which at least gives Black a few isolated pawns to worry about.}) 33... cxd4 34. Nd6 Rd7 35. Rxd4 Re7 {Another trick seen and avoided. How easy it would have been to overlook 36.xe6 xe6 36.xf5+ etc.} 36. Kg3 {A slight inaccuracy which allows Black to activate his rook.} ({Since} 36. Ra4 Bc6 $1 {leads nowhere,}) ({White should aim to infiltrate on the c or g file by playing} 36. Rd1 $1 {However, despite a number of second best moves, the position must still be assessed as favourable to White due to the permanent nature of his space advantage. Black lacks scope, so White can try a plan and later abandon it without risking much. Unles White becomes grossly overambitious there is no way he can lose whilst Black has to prepare for a long struggle to obtain the meagre return of a draw.}) 36... Kh6 37. Kf2 Rg7 38. Ke3 Ba8 $6 39. Kd2 $2 {A surprising double oversight which leaves Black closer to a draw as he now liquidates rooks.} ({Presumably Reti's mind was set on a king march, for both players have overlooked} 39. Nxf5+ exf5 40. Rd8 {when White regains the piece while his e pawn becomes a tower of strength. Black's best defence is probably} Rg3+ {but} 41. Kf2 {leaves Black in trouble, e.g.} Rf3+ 42. Ke2 Ng6 43. Rxa8 Rxf4 44. e6 {with a clear advantage.}) 39... Rg2+ 40. Kc3 Rg3+ 41. Rd3 Rxd3+ 42. Kxd3 Bg2 43. Nf7+ Kg7 44. Nd8 $1 {The only move to maintain winning chances.} (44. Ng5 h6 $1 45. Nxe6+ Nxe6 46. Bxe6 Bxh3 {is certainly not worse for Black.}) 44... Bxh3 45. Bxe6 Ng6 46. Ke3 Ne7 {Black has achieved a solid defensive setup and Watson was probably expecting a draw offer reasonable soon. Reti, however, plugs away and goes close to creating serious winning chances. His advantage lies in the fact that Black cannot afford to exchange all the minor pieces as then White's protected passed pawn will be a decisive factor in the pawn ending. Not a great deal to work with, I agree, but the need to avoid exchanges is certainly an inhibiting factor on Black.} 47. Kf2 Bg4 48. Kg3 Be2 49. Nb7 Kg6 50. Nd6 Bd3 51. a3 Be2 52. b4 Bd3 {White's pieces and pawns have reached their optimum squares and he must now find a plan. White's next few moves indicate either time trouble or a singular lack of ideas.} 53. Bf7+ Kg7 54. Be8 h6 {Perhaps not immediately necessary, but White was about to force ...h6 by playing h4-g5. The Black pawn is a little more exposed on h6 than on its original square as the game continuation demonstrates.} 55. Kf3 Bf1 56. Kf2 Bd3 57. Ke3 Bf1 58. Kf2 Bd3 59. Ke3 Bf1 60. Bd7 $1 ({White could of course claim a draw by threatening to play} 60. Kf2 {but he is not giving up his winning attempt so readily.}) 60... Kg6 61. Be6 $1 {Black is running short of moves. His king and knight are tied to the f pawn, his bishop is on its best diagonal (preventing b5) and his queenside pawns are at their best, vulnerable. That leaves the h pawn, yet if Black plays ...h4 White simply returns his bishop to e8 and his knight to the kingside and infiltrates through the newly weakened g5 square. Black is forced to make a concession and he succeeds in finding the least evil.} Bg2 62. Nb5 Bd5 $1 {White is permitted to get closer to his hoped for pawn ending but only on Black's terms.} 63. Bd7 ({Now} 63. Bxd5 Nxd5+ 64. Kf3 a5 65. bxa5 {offers no realistic winning chances for White.}) 63... Bc6 $1 64. Bxc6 Nxc6 65. Nd4 $1 Ne7 ({A summary of White's winning process after} 65... Nxd4 66. Kxd4 {would be as follows: (a) White fixes the Q-side pawns  (b) White plays his king to h4 or h5 (c) White plays e6 and play will continue ...f6 2.h5 xe6 3. xh6 d5 4.g6! e4 5.g5 and wins. The only way Black can cut across this winning play would be to play} b5 {in order to conclude part (c) with a6 and Black wins! However, after (mhb: Rogers variation's analysis ends here. I complete this by the following:)} 67. Kd5 {and the e pawn is too fast. If} Kf7 68. Kd6 Ke8 69. Ke6 {wins.}) 66. b5 Nd5+ {There is little choice as White threatened 67.c6+} 67. Kf3 Nc3 68. Kg3 Ne4+ 69. Kh4 Nc3 70. Nc6 $5 {The final winning attempt. White sacrifices a pawn to procure connected passed pawns.} Nxb5 71. Ne7+ Kf7 $1 {Watson realises the value of the king as a blockader and the worthlessness of his h pawn.} (71... Kh7 {would leave Black struggling to draw.}) 72. Nxf5 Nxa3 73. Nd6+ $1 {Again correctly disregarding the h pawn.} (73. Nxh6+ Ke6 {is possibly winning for Black. The white king would find it very difficult to halt the black pawns whilst the black king was efficiently blockading the more advances white pawns. The irrelevance of the white king would be a key factor in Black's favour.}) 73... Ke6 74. Kh5 Nc2 75. Kg6 $2 ({It was high time to grab a draw and eliminate a remote Black queenside pawn with} 75. Nc8 $1 {. Reti probably still cherished hopes for a win, but with so few White pawns remaining, such hopes are rather unrealistic.}) 75... Ne3 $2 (75... Nd4 {is much stronger as White's} 76. Nc8 {can be met by} b5 77. Nxa7 b4 {with a win due to the offside white knight. Fortunately for Australian chess, Watson is given a second chance.}) 76. Ne8 $2 ({White cannot afford} 76. f5+ Nxf5 77. Nxf5 a5 {when the remote passed pawns should win,}) ({but} 76. Nb5 $1 {offered good winning chances. The threats of 77.c7+ and 77.d5+ would be very nasty e.g.} a5 77. Nc7+ Kd7 78. e6+ Kxc7 (78... Ke7 79. f5) 79. e7 {and White queens.}) ({Black's only good defence to} 76. Nb5 $1 {would be} Ng2 $3 77. Nc7+ $140 Ke7 78. f5 Nh4+) ({so after} 76. Nb5 $1 Ng2 $3 {White should probably be content with the forced draw resulting from} 77. Nxa7 Nxf4+ 78. Kxh6 Kxe5 79. Nc8 b5 80. Na7 b4 81. Nc6+ {draw. Reti's choice does not give White the option of playing this drawing line if his winning attempt fails.}) 76... Ke7 $1 77. Ng7 Ng2 $1 78. Kf5 $2 ({White misses his last chance to draw with} 78. f5 $1 Nh4+ 79. Kxh6 Nxf5+ 80. Nxf5+ Ke6 81. Nd4+ Kxe5 82. Nc6+ {. If 78.f5 was a further attempt to play for a win it was a very misguided one.}) 78... a5 79. Ke4 a4 80. Nf5+ Kf8 81. Nd4 Nxf4 $3 {Absolutely decisive.} 82. Nb5 ({If White captures the knight with} 82. Kxf4 {, Black plays} a3 {a2, exchanges his h pawn for White's passed pawn and walks over to the the Q-side, capturing the hapless white knight.}) 82... Ng6 83. Kf5 Kg7 84. e6 Ne7+ 85. Ke5 h5 86. Ke4 Kf6 {Reti could resign with a clear conscience here. He plays on, probably unable to believe he could have lost a game which he dominated for the first 75 moves.} 87. Nc3 a3 88. Kd4 h4 89. Kc4 Kxe6 90. Kb3 h3 91. Ne4 h2 92. Nf2 Kf5 0-1


