1. d4 {1)Kalendovsky:Richard Reti.1989.Praha. p.10. 2)Di Felice: Chess Results 1901-1920. p.98.3)Matsukevitch: Рихард Рети.2005.Moskau  The Championship with 15 players was won by Leo Fleischmann, (later Leo Forgacs) with 11/14 points (2.-3.) Abonyi and Szekely 10/14 (4).Barasz 9/14 (5.-6.)Foldes and Gajdos 8,5/14 (7.-8.) Exner and Reti 7,5/14.  Reti was 18 years old at the time this game was played, so we can't expect the hypermodern play...} d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 4. c4 e6 5. Bd3 Nbd7 6. O-O Bd6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. e4 dxe4 (8... dxc4 {is an alternative.}) 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 f5 {the game move is also played nowadays.} ({Though it is considered that better is} 10... h6) ({or} 10... Nf6) 11. Bc2 Nf6 ({Black is not developed enough for opening up the play} 11... e5 12. Bg5 Be7 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Re1 Rd8 (15... Qb4 {loses} 16. Rxe5 Qxb2 17. Rb1 Qa3 18. c5 $18 {Black has serious problems due to his undeveloped queenside}) 16. Rxe5 Qxe5 17. dxe5 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 $16 {White is a pawn up and so he has a good winning chances.}) 12. b3 Qc7 13. Qe2 Re8 14. Ne5 $2 ({White plays naturally but not good. After} 14. c5 $1 {White has a clear advantage} Be7 15. b4 $16 (15. Bd2 $16 {is also good enough for getting an advantage.})) 14... b6 (14... c5 $11 {was a good alternative for equal play.}) 15. f4 ({More natural was:} 15. Bb2 $11) 15... Bb7 16. Bb2 Rad8 (16... c5 {is a good alternative.}) 17. Rad1 c5 18. Qe1 $6 {[%cal Ye1g3,Yg3h4] In his youth, Reti was an attacker.The idea behind this move is Qh4 though it is not visible how he could continue the attack.} ({Better was} 18. h3) ({or} 18. d5 {In both cases, the position is close to equal.}) 18... Be4 ({Better was:} 18... cxd4 19. Bxd4 Be4 $15 {Black has a small advantage.}) 19. Bxe4 Nxe4 20. d5 $11 exd5 21. Rxd5 Nf6 ({This is simplest. It is more complicated to get an equal play by} 21... Bxe5 22. fxe5 (22. Bxe5 $6 Qf7 {gives Black small advantage.}) 22... Rxd5 23. cxd5 c4 (23... Rxe5 $5 24. Bxe5 Qxe5 25. Qd1 g6 $13) 24. bxc4 Qc5+ 25. Kh1 g6 26. Qe2 b5 27. cxb5 Qxd5 $13 {leads to an irrational position in which Black's chances are not inferior.}) 22. Rd2 Ng4 (22... Ne4 {leads to completely equal play.}) 23. Qg3 ({Equal play also gives} 23. h3 Nf6 24. Qe3 $11) (23. Re2 $5 {also leads to equal position} Nf6 $11) 23... Bxe5 (23... Nf6 $11 {led to equal play simpler than the game move.}) 24. Rxd8 Qxd8 25. fxe5 g6 26. h3 ({Better was} 26. Qf4 Qc7 (26... Qd3 27. Re1 Qc2 28. Ba1 $14) 27. Bc3 $14 {White has a small advantage.}) (26. Re1 $5 {is also an interesting possibility.}) 26... Qd2 $1 {Excellent move which gives Black equal play.} 27. Bc3 Qe3+ 28. Qxe3 Nxe3 29. Rf3 Nc2 (29... Nd1 {also leads to equal play though it creates a complicated position unnecessarily.} 30. Bd2 Rxe5 31. Rd3 Re4 32. Kf1 f4 $11) 30. Rd3 Kf7 ({To equal play, also leads} 30... Nd4 31. Bxd4 Rd8 32. Kf2 cxd4 $11) 31. Kf2 Nd4 32. Bxd4 cxd4 33. Rxd4 Rxe5 {The rook ending is completely equal.} 34. Rd7+ Re7 35. Rxe7+ Kxe7 {Also pawn ending is completely equal. Old books give a small advantage to White though it's not clear why.} 36. Ke3 g5 37. b4 {Both sides prepare for pushing their passed pawns.} Kd6 38. Kd4 a5 39. a3 ({In his book, "Richard Reti" by Matcukevich, Moscow 2005, the following variation is given as a draw} 39. bxa5 bxa5 40. a4 $4 ({To draw leads only} 40. c5+ $1 Kc6 41. Ke5 f4 42. Kf6 Kxc5 43. Kxg5 Kb4 44. Kxf4 Ka3 45. g4 $11) {In fact, White is lost here after} 40... f4 41. Kd3 Kc5 42. Kc3 h5 $19) 39... a4 40. g3 h5 $5 ({In the above mentioned book, it is considered that this move is a decisive mistake and that to draw leads only} 40... h6 41. h4 Ke6 42. hxg5 ({ili} 42. h5 Kd6 43. c5+ bxc5+ 44. bxc5+ Kc6 45. Ke5 f4 46. gxf4 gxf4 47. Kxf4 Kxc5 $11) 42... hxg5 43. c5 b5 (43... bxc5+ {also leads to draw} 44. Kxc5 f4 45. gxf4 gxf4 46. Kd4 Kf5 $11) 44. c6 Kd6 45. c7 Kxc7 46. Ke5 f4 47. gxf4 gxf4 48. Kxf4 Kd6 $11) ({In fact, neither after the game move Black loses, and to draw also leads} 40... Ke6 41. h4 h6 42. c5 bxc5+ 43. bxc5 f4 44. gxf4 gxh4 $11) 41. h4 gxh4 $4 ({This move leads to defeat. After} 41... g4 {the position is draw, for instance:} 42. Kd3 Ke6 $1 43. Kd2 Kf6 44. Ke2 Ke6 $1 45. Kd3 Kd6 46. Kd4 Ke6 $11) 42. gxh4 $18 Ke6 43. c5 bxc5+ 44. Kxc5 $1 f4 (44... Ke5 {loses after} 45. b5 f4 46. b6 f3 47. b7 f2 48. b8=Q+ $18 {[%csl Re5][%cal Rb8e5]}) 45. Kd4 Kf5 46. b5 {now everything is clear and no comment is needed.} f3 47. Ke3 f2 48. Kxf2 Ke5 49. Kf3 Kd5 50. Kf4 Kc5 51. Kg5 Kxb5 52. Kxh5 Kc4 53. Kg4 Kb3 54. h5 Kxa3 55. h6 Kb2 56. h7 a3 57. h8=Q+ Kb1 58. Qb8+ Ka1 59. Qe5+ Kb1 60. Qe1+ Kb2 61. Qb4+ 1-0


