1. e4 {Zenón Franco} c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 ({QUESTION: The main line today is} 5. Nxd5 {Zenón Franco} exd5 6. d4 {. What can you tell me about Réti's move? ANSWER: Yes, the main line is as you say, but let's remember that this game was played in the early days of the 2...Nf6 variation, and while it does not have a good reputation, it is certainly playable. The bishop on g2 and the b-file (which will probably be opened after ...Nxc3) often combine well in similar positions, although admittedly it requires precise play by White, in view of the fact that his pawn structure will be damaged.}) 5... Nc6 6. Bg2 Nxc3 7. bxc3 d6 8. exd6 Bxd6 9. O-O O-O 10. d3 ({Rubinstein also faced the more incisive move} 10. d4 {(Zenón Franco) . F.Yates-A.Rubinstein, The Hague 1921, continued} Be7 ({controlling g5 with} 10... h6 {was another possibility}) 11. Qd3 Bd7 $6 (11... Qa5 {, followed by ...Rd8, is interesting}) 12. Rb1 $1 Na5 13. Ne5 Be8 14. Be4 h6 15. Rd1 Qc7 16. Bf4 ({here} 16. Nc4 $1 {is rather unpleasant for Black}) 16... Bd6 17. Qe2 cxd4 18. cxd4 Rc8 19. Bd3 Nc6 {with equal chances, although Rubinstein outplayed his opponent in a major-piece ending after} 20. Qe4 f5 21. Qe3 Nxe5 22. Bxe5 Bxe5 23. dxe5 b5 24. Bxb5 Bxb5 25. Rxb5 Qxc2 {and won in 59 moves.}) 10... Be7 {'Zenón Franco: 'This move is now more attractive, in view of the possibility of ...Bf6. ''} 11. Be3 Bd7 12. Qd2 $6 {'Zenón Franco: 'A strange decision; the d2-square is needed for the knight, on its way to c4, so the queen will soon need to move again.''} ({It was more natural to play} 12. Rb1 {(Zenón Franco) , as Yates did, supporting the efforts of the g2-bishop, although here Black can fearlessly reply} b6 $1 {Possibly it would be better to play} 13. Nd2 {instead.} ({since} 13. d4 {can be answered by} cxd4 14. Nxd4 (14. cxd4 Rc8 {leads to a position where White will need to justify his hanging pawns}) 14... Nxd4 $1 15. Bxa8 Bb5 $1 {, regaining the exchange (if} 16. Re1 {then} Ne2+ $1 {).})) 12... Qc7 {'Zenón Franco: 'QUESTION: Wasn't 12...Qa5 more active?''} ({ANSWER: The more modest text move defends b7 in advance. White's idea in playing 12 Qd2 would become clearer after your suggestion of} 12... Qa5 {(Zenón Franco) ; he could then play} 13. Rfb1 {, answering} b6 {with} 14. d4 {in better circumstances than on the previous move.}) 13. Rfe1 Rad8 14. Bf4 {'Zenón Franco: 'QUESTION: Hmm, with a weakened pawn structure, is it such a good idea to exchange pieces? ANSWER: It's true that one always has to choose carefully which piece to exchange and which to keep, especially if, as you pointed out, White has doubled pawns. In this particular case White probably chose the text move because he had gained nothing from the opening and could see that Black was planning to seize more of the centre with 14...e5, after which the white pieces would lack coordination. ''} Bd6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Qe3 {'Zenón Franco: 'White clears the d2-square for his knight.''} ({Razuvaev suggested another idea, occupying the centre with} 16. c4 {(Zenón Franco) , something that could also be played later in the game. But Réti wanted to post his knight there, which is a typical idea if followed by a4-a5.}) 16... b6 17. Nd2 {'Zenón Franco: 'EXERCISE: White is seeking to improve the position of his pieces. Which piece do you think Rubinstein in turn chose to improve? ANSWER:''} Ne7 $1 {'Zenón Franco: 'Since Black no longer needs to control the e5-square, he sends his knight in search of better prospects on d5 or f5. If White opts for c3-c4, Black can now respond with ...Bc6, when an exchange of bishops would leave more weaknesses in the white position. ''} 18. Nc4 Qc7 19. Qe5 $2 {'Zenón Franco: 'A surprising decision; White decides voluntarily to enter an endgame which will definitely not be a pleasant one for him.''} ({Instead, the most logical continuation was} 19. a4 {(Zenón Franco) , planning to advance to a5 at an opportune moment; nevertheless, Black would have a good position after} Bc6 {.}) 19... Qxe5 20. Nxe5 {'Zenón Franco: 'EXERCISE (easy): Black has a slightly better endgame. What do you think he played in this position? ANSWER:''} Ba4 $1 {'Zenón Franco: 'A good strategy, and not only in the endgame, is to restrict the mobility of the enemy pieces, in this case by putting pressure on his weaknesses. ''} 21. Re2 Nd5 22. Bxd5 $6 {'Zenón Franco: 'QUESTION: Why? Is this a good exchange? Or did White simply have nothing better? ANSWER: You're right; this is not a pleasant exchange for White to make, as Black is left with the superior minor piece.''} ({The problem is that it is not easy defend the c3-pawn. If} 22. c4 $6 {(Zenón Franco) then} Nb4 23. Rc1 f6 $1 24. Nf3 {and now, instead of} Kf7 {with just a slight advantage,} ({Black has the much stronger} 24... Bxc2 $1 25. Rcxc2 Nxc2 26. Rxc2 Rxd3 {with a rook and two pawns for the two minor pieces, and the d-file opened in his favour.})) ({Perhaps the best practical chances lay in entering tactical complications after} 22. Re4 $5 {(Zenón Franco) . Black can accept the challenge with} Bxc2 ({possibly Rubinstein would have maintained the tension with} 22... Be8) 23. Rc1 Nxc3 24. Ree1 Nxa2 25. Rxc2 Nb4 {, when he has the more pleasant position with three pawns (two of them passed) for the piece, and there is a weakness at d3. However, this line is neither forced nor completely clear.}) 22... exd5 {'Zenón Franco: 'QUESTION: With the pawn, closing the d-file? Why? ANSWER: Because it opens the e-file instead, and Rubinstein is seeking to simply the position down to the bare bones of his advantage. With the e-file open it should be easier for him to exchange the rooks, in order to reach a favourable endgame of bishop against knight. ''} 23. Rae1 Rfe8 24. f4 f6 25. Nf3 Kf7 26. Kf2 Rxe2+ 27. Rxe2 Re8 28. Rxe8 Kxe8 29. Ne1 {'Zenón Franco: 'Black has made progress; White is passive, tied to the defence of the c2-pawn. As we know, on its own this is unlikely to be sufficient for Black to win; at least two weaknesses are required, or some other sort of advantage... ''} Ke7 30. Ke3 Ke6 {'Zenón Franco: 'And the advantage that Rubinstein seeks is to infiltrate with his king on the kingside. ''} 31. g4 $2 {'Zenón Franco: 'This prevents infiltration via f5 and g4, but at the cost of weakening his pawn structure. Black now has important extra options for probing the white kingside, with either ...h7-h5 or ...g7-g5, and White will be unable to maintain his pawn chain.''} ({Instead,} 31. d4 $1 {(Zenón Franco) has been suggested, and this would indeed increase White's chances of a draw.} {Euwe examined} Kd6 (31... Kf5 {can be answered with} 32. Kf3 {, planning Ng2-e3+, and White would also have the possibility of playing d4xc5, followed by Nd3.} (32. Z0)) 32. Kd2 Kc6 {, but then White can continue with the main idea behind 31 d4, which is to improve the position of his knight, by playing} 33. Ng2 {and Ne3, where it would be ideally situated, defending the weakness on c2 and controlling the entry points of the black king on both wings: c4, f5 and g4.}) 31... Kd6 32. h3 ({If immediately} 32. Kd2 {(Zenón Franco) , Black can play} Bd7 33. h3 h5 $1 {and the white position collapses; for example,} 34. f5 Ke5 35. Ke3 d4+ 36. cxd4+ cxd4+ 37. Kf3 Bc6+ 38. Kg3 b5 {and White is lost, since after} 39. Nf3+ ({or} 39. gxh5 Kxf5 40. Nf3 Bxf3 41. Kxf3 b4 $1) 39... Bxf3 40. Kxf3 h4 {, he is in zugzwang.}) 32... g6 33. Kd2 {'Zenón Franco: 'EXERCISE: How did Rubinstein proceed in this position? ANSWER:''} Bd7 $1 {'Zenón Franco: 'Seeking to open lines with ...h7-h5. ''} 34. Nf3 Ke7 $1 {'Zenón Franco: 'There is no hurry;''} ({although the immediate} 34... h5 {(Zenón Franco) was playable, as after} 35. g5 $5 fxg5 36. Nxg5 Ke7 {, followed by ...Kf6-f5, it is not possible for White to defend his pawns, and he now has two definite weaknesses, f4 and c2. If, for example,} 37. h4 Kf6 38. Nf3 ({or} 38. Ke3 Ba4) 38... Kf5 39. Ne5 Be8 40. Ke3 Ba4 41. Kd2 d4 {, White can no longer protect the f4-pawn with Ke3, so Black wins after ...Be8 (to guard g6) and ...Kxf4.}) 35. Ke3 h5 $1 36. Nh2 ({In the event of} 36. gxh5 {Zenón Franco} gxh5 37. h4 {, Black gains access to the g4-square and wins after} Ke6 {and ...Kf5 etc, always with the resource of ...Ba4 to deflect the white king if necessary.}) 36... Kd6 $1 {'Zenón Franco: 'White has prevented the black king from breaking into the kingside, but at the cost of becoming very passive, so Rubinstein now probes for an entry on the other wing, via c6-b5. ''} 37. Ke2 {'Zenón Franco: 'EXERCISE: How did Rubinstein proceed? ANSWER:''} d4 $1 {'Zenón Franco: 'Opening the long diagonal to the bishop's advantage, while giving greater force to a future ...g6-g5. ''} 38. cxd4 {'Zenón Franco: '?!''} ({It was more tenacious to keep the position closed with} 38. c4 {Zenón Franco} hxg4 39. hxg4 ({not} 39. Nxg4 Ke6 40. Nh6 $2 f5 {and the knight is trapped}) {. After} 39... g5 $1 40. fxg5 fxg5 {, White would have to defend the weaknesses at g4 and c2, in addition to preventing ...Ke5-f4; but in that case Black's win would not be trivial, and a great deal of manoeuvring would still be required; for example, after} 41. Kf2 {(forced)} Ba4 42. Nf3 Bxc2 43. Ke2 Ba4 44. Nxg5 Ke7 {and so on.}) 38... cxd4 39. Kd2 hxg4 40. hxg4 ({In the event of} 40. Nxg4 {(Zenón Franco) , the simplest way is} Bxg4 $1 41. hxg4 g5 {, as the pawn endgame is won for Black; for example,} 42. fxg5 fxg5 43. Ke2 Kc5 44. Kf3 {However,} Kd5 $1 {is much easier, followed by ...b7-b5, ...a7-a5-a4, and only then ...Kc5-b4-c3xc2, after which ...b5-b4-b3 etc promotes the b-pawn much faster.} ({and now} 44... Kb4 45. Ke4 Kc3 46. Kf5 Kxc2 47. Kxg5 Kxd3 {leads to a winning queen ending after} 48. Kf4 Kc3 49. g5 d3 50. g6 d2 51. g7 d1=Q 52. g8=Q a5 {, since the white a-pawn will soon drop off.} (52... Z0))) 40... Bc6 $1 41. Ke2 ({If White tries} 41. c3 {(Zenón Franco) , Bogoljubow pointed out a way to win:} dxc3+ 42. Kxc3 Bg2 $1 {, when White will soon be in zugzwang and will have to allow the black king to advance to support his outside pawn majority on the queenside; for example,} 43. Kd4 b5 44. Ke3 a5 45. a3 ({or} 45. Kf2 Bd5 46. a3 b4) 45... Kc5 46. Kf2 Bd5 47. Nf1 b4 {and so on.}) {'Zenón Franco: 'EXERCISE: How can Black extract maximum benefit from the pawn structure? ANSWER:''} 41... Bd5 $1 {'Zenón Franco: 'Once the a2-pawn is forced to advance, Black can easily create a passed pawn. ''} 42. a3 b5 43. Nf1 a5 44. Nd2 {'Zenón Franco: 'EXERCISE: How can Black show that provoking 42 a3 was decisive? ANSWER:''} a4 {'Zenón Franco: '!' Zenón Franco: 'So that, after ...b5-b4, a passed pawn will inevitably result. ''} 45. Ne4+ ({If} 45. Kd1 {(Zenón Franco) , Black can throw in} g5 $1 {, returning to the plan of infiltrating with the king at f4.}) {'Zenón Franco: 'EXERCISE (easy): What is the quickest way to win now? ANSWER:''} 45... Bxe4 {'Zenón Franco: '!' Zenón Franco: 'This exchange concludes the plan started with 44...a4. ''} 46. dxe4 b4 $1 47. Kd2 bxa3 48. Kc1 {'Zenón Franco: 'EXERCISE (easy): How does the black monarch force a way in? ANSWER:''} g5 {'Zenón Franco: '!''} 0-1


