[EventCountry "GER"]

{Besides playing 1.Nf3 Reti adopted both the English Opening and 1.g3 as White. Here we see him venturing the latter move against no less a player than Alexander Alekhine.} 1. g3 e5 2. Nf3 {A kind of Alekhine's Defence with colours reversed. The move ...g7-g6 is often useful for Black in the Alekhine so g2-g3 will be similarly useful for White.} e4 3. Nd4 d5 4. d3 exd3 5. Qxd3 (5. cxd3 {would be more in keeping with lines of the Alekhine Defence. But Reti wants to play a later c2-c4 and then play along the open d- and c-files.}) 5... Nf6 6. Bg2 Bb4+ (6... c5 {should be considered here.}) 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8. Nxd2 O-O 9. c4 Na6 (9... c5 {is well worth considering here, for example} 10. N4b3 Na6 11. O-O Nb4 {is more or less equal.}) 10. cxd5 Nb4 11. Qc4 Nbxd5 12. N2b3 c6 13. O-O Re8 14. Rfd1 {Once again Reti has achieved an excellent position with play along the open c- and d-files and a useful kingside pawn majority. What's fascinating to see in this game is Alekhine stirring up massive complications. And this all goes to show that the opening is not enough.} Bg4 15. Rd2 Qc8 16. Nc5 Bh3 17. Bf3 Bg4 18. Bg2 Bh3 19. Bf3 Bg4 20. Bh1 (20. Bg2 {would repeat the position. The text indicates that White is getting ambitious.}) 20... h5 21. b4 a6 22. Rc1 h4 23. a4 (23. e4 Nb6 24. Qc3 {is also very nice for White.}) 23... hxg3 24. hxg3 Qc7 25. b5 (25. e4 Ne7 26. a5 {would strengthen the position of the knight on c5 but Reti wanted to attack c6. In retrospect this was a fateful decision.}) 25... axb5 26. axb5 Re3 $1 {Just when it was starting to look as if Black's strategy was not succeeding Black launches this stunning combinative blow. The position is unclear after this but Alekhine succeeds in confusing his opponent.} 27. Nf3 $4 (27. fxe3 $4 Qxg3+ {obviously leads to mate}) ({but} 27. Bf3 {deserved attention. After} Rea3 28. bxc6 bxc6 29. Kg2 {White's position looks pretty good.}) 27... cxb5 $1 28. Qxb5 Nc3 {Black's pieces are swarming into the attack but with so many things en prise this hangs by a thread.} 29. Qxb7 Qxb7 30. Nxb7 Nxe2+ 31. Kh2 (31. Kf1 {is also hopeless after} Nxg3+ 32. fxg3 Bxf3 33. Bxf3 Rxf3+ 34. Kg2 Raa3 {etc.}) 31... Ne4 $3 {A fantastic move from Alekhine, wasting no time in closing in on White's position.} ({After} 31... Nxc1 32. fxe3 Ra3 33. Ng5) ({and} 31... Rxf3 32. Rxe2 Rf5 33. Rb2 {White would save the draw.}) 32. Rc4 {Reti is trying to exchange some pieces via tactical means.} (32. Rd8+ Rxd8 33. fxe3 Rd5 $1 {and}) ({and} 32. fxe3 $2 Nxd2 33. Nxd2 Nxc1 {are good for Black.}) 32... Nxf2 $1 ({After} 32... Bxf3 {White can play} 33. Rxe4 $1 Bxe4 34. fxe3 Bxh1 35. Kxh1 Nxg3+ 36. Kg2 {with good drawing chances.}) ({And} 32... Nxd2 {doesn't work because of} 33. Nxd2 Rd3 34. Nc5 $1 {.}) 33. Bg2 (33. Nc5 {was a slightly better chance but is still winning for Black after} Rae8 34. Ng5 Nxh1 35. Kxh1 Nxg3+ {etc.}) 33... Be6 $1 34. Rcc2 $2 (34. Rb4 Ng4+ 35. Kh3 {would have been the best chance.}) 34... Ng4+ 35. Kh3 Ne5+ 36. Kh2 Rxf3 $1 (36... Nxf3+ $6 37. Bxf3 Rxf3 38. Rxe2 {is also better for Black but much less clear than the game.}) 37. Rxe2 Ng4+ 38. Kh3 {Neither now nor before could the white king move to the first rank because of the deadly check on a1} Ne3+ 39. Kh2 Nxc2 40. Bxf3 Nd4 41. Rf2 Nxf3+ 42. Rxf3 Bd5 {Either the knight or rook will be lost.} 0-1


