{This game was played a year after Capablanca's stunning defeat by Reti in the New York 1924 tournament. This time he plays a set-up that would become recognised as one of the most solid and reliable defences to the Reti.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 c6 3. b3 ({Of course} 3. d4 {would bring about a Slav Defence which Black must also be prepared for.}) ({If, on the other hand, White wants to fianchetto his king's bishop then he should do this now with} 3. g3 {. But in this case White has to reckon with} dxc4 {.}) 3... Bg4 4. Bb2 Nf6 5. Ne5 ({One of the advantages of Capablanca's early ...Bc8-g4 is that after} 5. g3 {he can mangle White's pawn structure with} Bxf3 {.}) 5... Bh5 6. g3 e6 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O Nbd7 {Exchanging off White's advanced knight. It could go back of course, but that would represent a loss of two tempi.} 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. d3 O-O 11. Nd2 Qc7 12. Rc1 Rfd8 13. Nf3 Ne8 {Preparing to exchange more pieces with .. .Be7-f6. This time round it's evident that Capablanca is treating his opponent with far more caution.} 14. Rc2 Bf6 15. Qa1 $5 {Reti really loved putting his queen on this square!} Bxb2 16. Qxb2 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Qe7 18. Rd1 a6 {There's not much in it now.} 19. Bg2 g6 20. e3 h5 21. cxd5 exd5 22. b4 h4 23. a4 Nd6 24. e4 dxe4 25. dxe4 Ne8 (25... Nxe4 26. Re1 f5 27. f3 {would win the knight.}) 26. Rcd2 hxg3 27. hxg3 Rxd2 28. Qxd2 Nf6 29. Qd4 Re8 30. Qb6 Kg7 31. e5 Qxe5 32. Qxb7 Ng4 33. Qb6 ({And not} 33. Qxc6 {because of} Nxf2 34. Kxf2 Qe2+ 35. Kg1 Qxd1+ {etc.}) ({whilst} 33. Bxc6 $2 {is bad because of} Qh5 34. Bg2 ({Or} 34. Qa7 Re2) 34... Re2 {etc.}) 33... Qh5 (33... Qh5 34. Qd4+ Kg8 35. Qd2 Re5 {gives Black adequate counterplay.}) 1/2-1/2


[Event "New York"]
