[EventCountry "USA"]

{A famous game in which Reti put his opening on the map. I quite like this method of play against Black's King's Indian style set-up and have often played something similar in my own games (1.Nf3 Nf6 2.g3 g6 3.b4). White takes space on the queenside and this often leads to an undermining of any centre Black tries to set up.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. b4 Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O 5. g3 b6 6. Bg2 Bb7 7. O-O d6 8. d3 Nbd7 9. Nbd2 e5 ({Black can also consider} 9... c5 {but after} 10. a3 {White's space gives him slightly the better chances.}) 10. Qc2 Re8 11. Rfd1 ({Another plan would be to play} 11. e4 {with the aim of preparing f2-f4. This would probably have been my preference in fact.}) 11... a5 12. a3 h6 13. Nf1 c5 (13... e4 14. dxe4 Bxe4 {would have been fine for Black, though perhaps Capablanca was concerned that the position might become drawish.}) 14. b5 $6 {White should not close the queenside like this.} (14. Ne3 {looks like a much better idea, keeping open possibilities of play along the b-file.}) 14... Nf8 15. e3 Qc7 16. d4 Be4 17. Qc3 exd4 18. exd4 N6d7 (18... Ne6 {looks like a superior alternative. After} 19. Qd2 cxd4 20. Nxd4 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Qb7+ 22. f3 (22. Nc6 Nd8) {Black can play} 22... Ne4 $1 23. fxe4 Nxd4 24. Bxd4 Rxe4 {etc.}) 19. Qd2 cxd4 20. Bxd4 Qxc4 21. Bxg7 Kxg7 22. Qb2+ Kg8 23. Rxd6 Qc5 $6 {Leaving the queen exposed.} (23... Qc7 {would have been better.}) 24. Rad1 Ra7 ({And here} 24... Re7 {was better.}) 25. Ne3 Qh5 $2 {This could have lost on the spot.} (25... Rc7 {was better.}) 26. Nd4 $6 ({Missing an even stronger move in} 26. R1d5 $1 Bxd5 27. g4 Bxf3 28. gxh5 Bxh5 29. Bc6 {etc.}) 26... Bxg2 27. Kxg2 Qe5 $6 (27... Rxe3 28. fxe3 Qxd1 $4 {loses to} 29. Nf5 $1 {, threatening both mate on g7 and Black's queen. But 27...Rxe3 might have been a better chance in conjunction with 28...Ne5.}) 28. Nc4 Qc5 29. Nc6 Rc7 30. Ne3 Ne5 $2 (30... Rxe3 {was the last chance to keep fighting.}) 31. R1d5 (31. R1d5 Nc4 32. Rxc5 Nxb2 33. Rc2 {threatening both the knight on b2 and 34.Nd5 is deadly. It rather looked as if both players were affected by nerves in this game, and certainly Capablanca looked far from at ease when facing Reti's indirect opening.}) 1-0


