[EventCountry "USA"]

{Black's 5...Ne4 makes little sense before White has played d2-d4 as the knight gets driven away with d2-d3. But this is typical of the way people played against Flank Openings when they first started being played in strong tournaments. Players were used to 'doing something' so just did it anyway.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c6 4. b3 Nf6 5. Bg2 Ne4 $6 6. Qc2 Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. O-O Nd7 9. d3 Ng5 10. Nbd2 Nxf3+ 11. Nxf3 Bf6 {Attempting to ease his game via simplification, but White can avoid this easily enough.} 12. d4 {Now Black would like his knight on f6 so as to fight against White's central expansion with e2-e4.} Re8 13. e4 Nb6 {'Fast development' was still highly prized at this time in chess history, but now we have a greater focus on quality rather than just speed.} ({Black's knight does nothing on b6 so it would have better to play} 13... b6 {instead.}) 14. Ne5 Bd7 15. Ng4 Rc8 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. a4 Red8 (17... a5 18. c5 Na8 19. e5 Qf5 20. Qd2 {would win the a5 pawn.}) 18. a5 Na8 19. e5 Qg6 20. Qe2 Nc7 21. Ba3 Na6 22. Rfe1 Be8 23. Bd6 f5 24. f4 Qh6 25. Bf3 {Preventing 25...Bh5 and getting ready for eventual kingside action with g3-g4. Black 'strikes' first in order to effect some exchanges but the problem with his position continue into the endgame.} g5 26. Ra2 (26. fxg5 Qxg5 27. Kh1 {looks very strong here.}) 26... gxf4 27. gxf4 Rd7 ({After} 27... Qxf4 {White would obviously have compensation for the pawn along the open files on the kingside but with nothing clear this might have been a good swindling chance for Black.}) 28. Qe3 Rg7+ 29. Rg2 Rxg2+ 30. Kxg2 {Reti has a certain endgame in mind in which Black's knight on a6 will spell his doom. But the exchanges also weaken his king position so he needs to be careful.} Bh5 31. Bxh5 Qxh5 32. Rg1 Kf7 33. Kh1 Rg8 34. Rxg8 Kxg8 35. cxd5 cxd5 36. b4 {The point behind White's recent moves. What does the knight do?} Kf7 37. Qd3 Qh4 38. Qf1 Qd8 39. Qh3 Kg8 ({Or} 39... Kg6 40. Qg3+ Kf7 41. Qg5 {etc.}) 40. Qg3+ Kf7 41. Qg5 Qc8 (41... Qxg5 42. fxg5 Kg6 43. b5 {also wins Black's knight.}) 42. b5 Qc1+ ({Or} 42... Nb8 43. Bxb8 Qxb8 44. Qf6+ {etc.}) 43. Kg2 Qd2+ 44. Kh3 Qe3+ 45. Kh4 Qe1+ 46. Kh5 Qe2+ 47. Kh6 Qxh2+ 48. Qh5+ Qxh5+ 49. Kxh5 Kg7 50. bxa6 bxa6 51. Bc5 Kf7 52. Kh6 Kg8 53. Bxa7 Kh8 54. Bb6 Kg8 55. Bd8 Kh8 56. Bh4 {Not a great game but interesting nonetheless.} 1-0


[Event "Karlsbad"]
[Site "Karlstad"]
[Date "1923.05.04"]
[Round "5"]
[White "Reti, Richard"]
[Black "Rubinstein, Akiba"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "A09"]
[Annotator "Nigel Davies"]
[PlyCount "99"]
[EventDate "1923.04.28"]
[EventType "tourn"]
[EventRounds "17"]
[EventCountry "SWE"]

{Rubinstein's 4...d4 is not a move that many modern players would venture. But at the time this game was played Benoni type positions were thought to confer a huge advantage on the player taking the space.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 d4 ({In my own games I've noticed that} 4... c6 {tends to be the most popular reply when I've played either 5.b3 or 5.Qa4.}) 5. d3 Bg7 6. b4 O-O 7. Nbd2 {I've always liked the smooth harmony that you find in Reti's games by delaying the development of his queen's bishop White has extra options available, such as the a3 square.} ({After the more forceful} 7. Bb2 {Black can play} a5 (7... c5 8. bxc5 Nc6 9. Nbd2 Nd7 10. Nb3 Nxc5 11. Nxc5 Qa5+ 12. Nd2 Qxc5 13. O-O Qh5 14. Re1 Bh3 15. Bh1 Rab8 16. Rb1 {was very pleasant for White in Geller, E-Novopashin, A, Kiev 1963.}) {, for example} 8. b5 c5 9. bxc6 Nxc6 10. Na3 e5 11. Nb5 Re8 12. O-O Bf8 13. Nd2 Bf5 14. Rc1 Qd7 15. c5 Bh3 {was not bad for Black in Larsen, B (2625)-Pfleger, H (2540), Manila 1975.}) 7... c5 8. Nb3 (8. bxc5 {is also better for White, for example} Nfd7 9. Nb3 Nxc5 10. Nxc5 Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Qxc5 12. Rb1 {gives definite pressure. But Reti may have preferred to avoid this because of the resultant simplification.}) 8... cxb4 9. Bb2 Nc6 10. Nbxd4 {Gaining a central pawn for a flank one is one of the major themes of the Reti Opening. Now it will be White who gains a major share of the centre, despite the fact that he did not stake an early claim to this part of the board.} Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b6 {Contesting the h1-a8 diagonal.} 12. a3 {Getting rid of the annoying b4 pawn and setting up a position in which White has a single pawn island (c4 to h2) against Black's two.} ({Note that} 12. Nd2 $2 {is bad because of} Qxd4 13. Bxa8 Ng4 14. O-O Nxf2 $1 {etc.}) 12... Bb7 {Threatening 13...Bxf3.} 13. Bb2 bxa3 14. Rxa3 Qc7 15. Qa1 $1 {These days there is nothing strange about this development of the queen. But in Reti's time it was highly original and raised more than a few eyebrows.} Ne8 16. Bxg7 Nxg7 17. O-O Ne6 18. Rb1 ({And not} 18. Rxa7 $4 Rxa7 19. Qxa7 Ra8 {, winning the queen.}) 18... Bc6 19. d4 {So now it is White who gains control of the centre. And this spatial control will allow White to put his pieces on big squares.} Be4 20. Rd1 a5 ({And not} 20... Qxc4 $2 {because of} 21. Nd2 {.}) 21. d5 Nc5 22. Nd4 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 Rfd8 24. Nc6 Rd6 25. Re3 Re8 26. Qe5 f6 ({On} 26... Rd7 {there follows} 27. Nxe7+ Rexe7 28. Qxc7 Rxc7 29. d6 {as after} Rxe3 30. dxc7 Re8 31. Rd8 {the passed c-pawn will promote.}) 27. Qb2 {With the mission accomplished (creation of further weaknesses in Black's camp) the queen latches on to a new target, the weak pawn on b6.} (27. Nxe7+ $2 {is bad because of} Kf7 {by the way.}) 27... e5 28. Qb5 Kf7 29. Rb1 Nd7 30. f3 Rc8 31. Rd3 e4 {With his position held in a vice like grip, Rubinstein makes a desperate bid for some counterplay.} 32. fxe4 Ne5 33. Qxb6 Nxc6 (33... Nxd3 34. exd3 {would be hopeless for Black because of White powerful clump of pawns.}) 34. c5 Rd7 35. dxc6 Rxd3 36. Qxc7+ Rxc7 37. exd3 Rxc6 38. Rb7+ Ke8 39. d4 Ra6 {Getting his rook behind the passed pawn. But this rook endgame proves to be too much for even Rubinstein.} 40. Rb6 ({And not} 40. Rxh7 $6 {because of} a4 {.}) 40... Ra8 41. Rxf6 a4 42. Rf2 a3 43. Ra2 Kd7 44. d5 g5 45. Kf3 Ra4 46. Ke3 h5 47. h4 gxh4 48. gxh4 Ke7 49. Kf4 Kd7 50. Kf5 1-0


[Event "British Empire Club Masters"]
