[EventCountry "ENG"]

{5...Nbd7 is generally viewed as a more reliable line these days. Vidmar's 5... Bd7 aims to put the bishop on c6 from where it will neutralise the one on g2. But the problem is that it blocks Black's c-pawn. This makes it difficult for Black to challenge White's centre.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxc4 Bc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Qc2 ({White can also leave the queen on c4, for example} 8. Nc3 a6 9. d4 O-O 10. Bg5 Nbd7 11. Rfe1 Rb8 12. a4 Nd5 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. e4 {was better for White in Vaganian, R (2615)-Smagin, S (2520), Germany 1993.}) 8... O-O 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. Rd1 {Still keeping all the options open with his pawns.} (10. d4 {looks natural but after} Bb4 {Black gets some kind of hold on the d5 and e4 squares.}) 10... e5 11. d4 exd4 12. Nxd4 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 c6 14. Nf5 {Already this looks very good for White. Perhaps Black should have played 13...g6 last move.} Re8 15. Bg5 Qc7 16. Bf4 Qa5 17. Bd6 Bf8 18. Rd2 g6 19. Bxf8 Nxf8 ({It might have been better to play} 19... Qxf5 {whereupon} 20. Qxf5 gxf5 21. Bd6 {must be better for White though Black's weak pawns may not be as weak as they seem.}) 20. Nd6 Re7 21. Rad1 Ne8 22. Nce4 Nxd6 23. Rxd6 Qe5 24. Nf6+ Kg7 25. Kf1 Re6 26. Rxe6 Qxe6 27. Ne4 Re8 28. Qc3+ Qe5 29. Nd6 Re6 $2 (29... Re7 {was better when} 30. Qxe5+ Rxe5 31. Nxb7 Rb5 {gets the pawn back with a good game.}) 30. Nxb7 Qxc3 31. bxc3 Re5 32. Rd4 Ne6 33. Ra4 Rd5 34. Na5 (34. Rxa7 Rd7 {puts White in a nasty pin.}) 34... Rd6 35. Nb3 Rd7 36. Nd4 Nxd4 37. cxd4 Rb7 38. Ra6 Rc7 39. e3 Kf8 40. Ke2 Ke7 41. Kd3 Kd7 42. Ra3 f6 43. Kc4 f5 44. Kc5 {Black is doomed though there hasn't been a particularly good reason for him to resign as yet.} Ke7 45. Rb3 g5 46. a4 f4 47. gxf4 gxf4 48. e4 Kf6 49. Rb8 Kg5 50. f3 h5 51. Rf8 Rb7 52. Rf5+ Kg6 53. Rxf4 Rb2 54. h4 Ra2 55. e5 Rxa4 56. e6 1-0



